<SLUG> BC-METLIFE-BANKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN LIFE SAYS IT AIMS TO START A FULL-SERVICE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time since Congress eliminated
Depression-era barriers last fall that prevented banks and
insurance companies from intermingling their businesses, a major
insurance company, Metropolitan Life, said Thursday that it was
taking steps to go into full-service banking.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life, a unit of MetLife Inc. and one of the
nation's largest insurers, said it had not decided whether to buy a
bank or to get a charter and develop one from the ground up. It did
say, however, that it expected to make ``the best use of both
traditional banking services and online capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   To work out the new banking strategy, Met Life has selected Judy
Weiss, a 27-year veteran of Met Life who is the company's chief
actuary and one of a handful of executive vice presidents. She is
to report to Robert H. Benmosche, Met Life's chief executive and a
former investment banker at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Met Life's decision was likely to set off a chain
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Met Life is such a powerful force in the industry,'' said Tom
Burnett, president of Merger Insight, a Manhattan financial
research company. ``They are telegraphing that a large insurance
company cannot afford to remain solely in their own industry and
that you have to diversify to take advantage of the changed
regulatory environment.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, under the new financial services laws, no banks have
bought major insurance companies, said Ken Reynolds, executive
director of the Association of Banks in Insurance, an organization
in Washington. But Larry Mayewski, a senior vice president at A.M.
Best Co., the insurance rating agency, said a handful of banks had
begun ``looking for insurance properties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot going on behind the scenes,'' Mayewski said.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 insurance companies have obtained thrift charters and
are offering checking and other banking services through agents and
on the Internet. But analysts said they expected the Met Life
operation to be far larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be a more broad-based, aggressive push into the
banking area,'' Mayewski said.
</P>
<P>
   With a thrift charter, banks are expected to offer at least some
mortgage loans and most of their commercial lending is to small
businesses, which limits their prospects for growth. In 1998,
Travelers, another big insurer, merged with Citicorp to form
Citigroup. That merger anticipated the regulatory change and
increased pressure on Congress to bring it about.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that Met Life's move into banking was
inevitable. ``A couple of years ago,'' said Colin Devine, a Salomon
Smith Barney analyst, ``you would have said their competitors were
the other major insurers. Now their competitors are the big
financial services companies like Fidelity, Schwab and Merrill
Lynch. They had to do something to keep pace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
