<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-SOCCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TURKS, TIME TO SHOUT `HELLO, EUROPE!' 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Early Thursday morning, after the Istanbul
soccer team Galatasaray won the first major European championship
ever by a Turkish team, the coach, Fatih Terim, said he had one
more wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope our country follows up on this,'' Terim said during the
jubilation, ``not just in soccer but in every field.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people in this soccer-crazed country spent Thursday both
proud and ecstatic. In a century of competition, no Turkish team
has even come close to such a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   But Galatasaray's 4-1 victory in a penalty shootout over the
British team, Arsenal, has an importance far beyond sports. It
spoke of this country's growing self-confidence and encouraged the
increasing number of Turks who say that Turkey can succeed at any
level if it disciplines itself and embraces European rules.
</P>
<P>
   Terim is an ideal symbol of the transition Turkey hopes to make.
Once a young tough who got into fights in bars, he has blossomed
into an articulate leader who plays by Europe's rules and comes out
a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much bigger than football,'' said Serif Erol, a radio
commentator who spent much of his Thursday morning show discussing
the big victory in the Ufea Cup, given by the Union of European
Football Associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey has been missing success for much too long,'' Erol
said. ``We started to wonder if we could ever compete with Europe.
Now we're losing some of that inferiority complex. It's a sign of
the reversal in our psychology. If we can beat so many great
European teams on the soccer field, that makes us think we can be
as good as the rest of Europe in democracy, in human rights, in
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's game, which was played in Copenhagen, gave
Galatasaray the right to call itself the best soccer club in
Europe. On its way to the championship, it defeated top teams not
just from Britain but also from Germany, Italy and other longtime
soccer powers.
</P>
<P>
   The victory came at a remarkable moment in Turkish history.
During the last year this country has seen the apparent end of a
long civil war, has been invited to apply for membership in the
European Union, and has begun making peace with Greece, its
longtime rival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
