<SLUG> BC-JDS-APPOINT-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEO OF FIBER OPTIC LEADER JDS UNIPHASE RETIRES, CITING EXHAUSTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ontario)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ JDS Uniphase, the largest component manufacturer
for fiber optic equipment, said Thursday that Kevin Kalkhoven had
retired as co-chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Kalkhoven, 55, is succeeded by Jozef Straus, 53, who has been
co-chairman, president and chief operating officer since the
company was formed 18 months ago through the merger of JDS Fitel,
of Nepean, Ontario, and Uniphase, of San Jose, Calif. Kalkhoven
said he was leaving because of exhaustion after several years of
100-hour weeks and that he would start a venture capital fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been nine years of extreme high-intensity activity,''
Kalkhoven said in a conference call with securities analysts.
``It's been a wonderful time; it's been the pinnacle of my career.
But it's also been a very stressful environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have today,'' he added, ``is only a transition. It's a
relatively seamless transition in a company that is going to be a
major player for many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that confidence in the company remained high
despite Kalkhoven's departure because of the steps he and Straus
had taken to deepen the management team. JDS has been an aggressive
acquirer of smaller components companies, and in addition to
broadening its product line through these deals it has typically
retained senior management.
</P>
<P>
   ``When JDS and Uniphase got together, they really did create an
industry,'' said Chris Crespi, a BancAmerica Securities analyst.
``People realized you had to put together a lot of product lines''
to compete across the breadth of the fiber optic market, he said.
At JDS Uniphase, he added, ``even without the acquisitions, the
internal growth sequentially is very good.''
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase also reported earnings for its third fiscal quarter
Thursday. Excluding acquisition-related charges, it had earnings of
$85.8 million, or 11 cents a diluted share, up 158 percent from
$33.2 million, or 5 cents a share, in the period a year earlier.
Revenue rose 155 percent, to $394.6 million from $154.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase shares fell $5.75, to $86.75, in heavy Nasdaq
trading. The shares have surged 345-fold since Uniphase went public
in 1993 and have more than quadrupled since the merger with JDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago we were a $200 million company,'' Straus said in
a telephone interview. ``Now we are a $1 billion company, and we
want to be a $4 billion company very soon. So we have a
considerable task in front of us, but I think our agility and
flexibility will continue to be the driving force.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Straus, a refugee from Soviet-era Czechoslovakia, co-founded JDS
Fitel in 1981 and served as its president and chief executive from
1993 until its merger with Uniphase. Bringing the two companies
together joined JDS Fitel's leadership in passive optical
components, like attenuators and distribution devices, with
Uniphase's expertise in active components, like semiconductor
lasers.
</P>
<P>
   With customers like Nortel Networks and Lucent Technologies, JDS
Uniphase has been well positioned to ride the commercial explosion
of fiber optics. ``We have a natural transition from electrical to
optical in the core parts of the network,'' Crespi of BancAmerica
said. ``The volumes are humongous.''
</P>
<P>
   Straus has been in charge of production since the merger, while
Kalkhoven focused on strategic acquisitions. Straus will be
succeeded as president and chief operating officer by Charles J.
Abbe. Abbe joined JDS Uniphase as part of the February acquisition
of Optical Coating Laboratory of Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
