<SLUG> BC-USANETWORKS-DIGITAL-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USA NETWORKS BUYS 2 DIGITAL CABLE TV CHANNELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   USA Networks Inc. has acquired two digital cable television
channels for approximately $100 million, company executives said
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Diller, the USA Networks chairman, said his company had
purchased North American Television Inc., a Canadian concern that
owns the Trio network, and News World International.
</P>
<P>
   Those networks are only available through digital television
services offered by providers like DirecTV and Time Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   Trio, an arts and entertainment network, can be viewed in 7
million homes. News World International, which shows newscasts from
around the world, is available in 6 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the continued growth of digital TV, Diller said he expected
the networks' distribution to grow significantly during the next
couple of years and predicted that they would eventually become a
significant part of his cable TV empire.
</P>
<P>
   Diller said he would spend ``hundreds of millions of dollars''
over the course of the next few years to produce new programming
for the two networks, which do not currently have very high
production values.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Diller said, he would like News World
International to run first-rate documentaries and to feature
in-depth discussions of issues. Trio, he said, will delve even
deeper into the popular arts, including jazz and the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got big, big aspirations and we're willing to invest
what I think anybody would call serious money to get there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks does not own other TV networks that strictly
feature nonfiction programming. Its USA network runs entertainment
shows like ``La Femme Nikita'' and ``Walker, Texas Ranger.'' Its
Sci-Fi Channel is geared to science-fiction enthusiasts with shows
like ``Sliders'' and ``Farscape.'' USA Networks also owns two
shopping networks.
</P>
<P>
   Since America Online announced that it was buying Time Warner
Inc., industry observers have said that they expected Diller to
announce a major deal of his own.
</P>
<P>
   This latest acquisition marks but another small, calculated step
on his part to expand his businesses.
</P>
<P>
   However, he recently said that he was interested in buying more
traditional media properties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
