<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-H.S.-MILER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL STAR ON TARGET TO JOIN SUB-4-MINUTE MILERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Va., Kan.)  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Marty Liquori became the third high school miler to break
four minutes in the 1960s, he remembers calling his coach and
saying, ``This is great and all that, but I wonder who will do it
next year?''
</P>
<P>
   To which Fred Dwyer, who coached him at Essex Catholic in
Newark, replied, ``No, this is going to be very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   How unusual, Dwyer could not have known. Liquori ran 3 minutes
59.8 seconds on June 23, 1967, in Bakersfield, Calif., carried
along by the world-record pace of Jim Ryun. In the 33 years since
then, not a single schoolboy miler has breached four minutes, a
particular lapse that symbolizes the general decline of U.S.
distance running.
</P>
<P>
   The next serious mile challenge will come Saturday night in
Charlotte, N.C., when Alan Webb, a junior from South Lakes High in
Reston, Va., attempts to accomplish what only Ryun, Liquori and Tim
Danielson have done in their pre-college careers _ run four times
around a track with a pace below one minute a lap.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six years after Roger Bannister became the first runner to
go under four minutes, the mile retains a certain magic. It is
seldom run anymore, but it remains the last holdout against the
metric onslaught, with its familiar measurement of yards and feet
and its requirement of enervating resourcefulness. The 1,500 meters
at least retains Olympic familiarity as the metric mile, but the
distance run frequently in high school is the 1,600. While the
1,600 is closer in length to the mile _ just slightly less _ it is
a distance with no emotional resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mile is that combination of speed and endurance for a long
enough period of time that, if you happen to blink, you won't miss
the race, as you would in a short sprint,'' said Ryun, now a
Republican member of the House of Representatives from Kansas.
``It's a distance people can identify with. One of the things that
has hurt us is, we felt we had to go to the metric system. It
confuses people about distance. The 1,600 meters is not a mile.
Just what is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Living in suburban Washington, the 5-foot-8-inch, 140-pound Webb
has twice met Ryun, who ran the mile under four minutes five times
while in high school in Wichita, Kan. His national schoolboy record
of 3:55.3 still stands after 35 years. Last year, Webb broke Ryun's
sophomore record with a time of 4:06.94. Last month at the Penn
Relays, the 17-year-old Webb ran a 1,600-meter leg of the sprint
medley relay in 3:59.9, which converts to a 4:01.03 mile.
</P>
<P>
   Ryun advised Webb to stick to his own training program and told
him to surround himself with people who will help him facilitate
his dream instead of telling him it will be impossible to achieve.
He also cautioned that the ability to handle mental pressures will
be as challenging as the physical requirements to run under four
minutes. Webb's workouts indicate that he is on target. He has
recently run 800 meters eight times in descending order from 2:14
to 1:55 on 2-3 minutes' rest, and 400 meters 12 times in 58-59
seconds, with 30-45 seconds' rest between each lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If you think you can do it, don't hesitate,''' Webb
said of Ryun. ``He said when he was younger, some people said, `You
should wait until you're older to really push.' He told me not to
hold back. I think I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Why hasn't a high schooler broken four minutes in three decades?
There are many theories: training has evolved from high mileage to
long, slow distance. (``Some coaches feel it is child abuse to make
guys run 80 miles a week,'' Liquori said.) Compulsory physical
education has lapsed, while increased opportunities to compete in
other sports such as soccer and lacrosse have siphoned potential
distance stars. The awarding of college scholarships to foreign
runners has diminished the motivation of U.S. high schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the '60s, there was a different work ethic in which
young athletes recognized that you had to invest a certain amount
of time to arrive at a destination,'' Ryun said. ``Today, it's more
like, `I want it now.' Instant gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb appears to have two things in his favor, aside from immense
talent. First, his coach, Scott Raczko, is a former runner at
American University, and not a football coach who works with track
in the spring. He has Webb training between 40 and 55 miles a week
and is careful not to overrace him and to allow for sufficient rest
and recovery. Second, Webb appears not to be obsessed with four
minutes as a barrier. His ambition this season is to run even
faster, breaking Ryun's junior national record of 3:59, and
achieving the 3:58.14 he would need to qualify for the Olympic
trials at 1,500 meters in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what has hurt some of the kids who tried in the '90s
was just that, the four-minute mile,'' Raczko said. ``It's a mental
thing. If you're driven just to get to four minutes, you're in
trouble. Four minutes is not a barrier for Alan. He is shooting for
3:58, so he's confident about 4:00.''
</P>
<P>
   So confident and determined that he is skipping his high school
prom Friday night to rest for Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 46 years ago, they were saying it was physically
impossible for humans to run under four minutes,'' Webb said.
``That's the coolest thing about all this. It's why I get excited.
It's the only thing that makes 3:59 anything more than taking five
seconds off my best time. It wasn't that long ago that they thought
no one could do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
