<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WIZARDS-JARVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO JOB OFFERED, JARVIS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Jarvis, the St. John's basketball coach,
acknowledged Thursday that his agent had spoken with the Washington
Wizards. But Jarvis said there was no offer on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said his lawyer, Robert Ades, met with the Wizards'
Michael Jordan, the head of basketball operations, Thursday but
characterized the discussions as informational. He was careful not
to say he was Jordan's top candidate; that was a mantle that former
Atlanta Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens assumed prematurely last week. He
also cautioned that if he received an offer, it was not a foregone
conclusion that he would accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talking and listening,'' said Jarvis of the discussions
between Ades and Jordan. ``He's gathering information. Negotiations
would not be the right word. People are talking. I have to be
prepared before an offer is or is not made. Once I make a decision,
I've got to be comfortable with it. You can't go into anything
blindly. I have the world's greatest respect for Michael Jordan,
but he will be just one factor in the decision. You make a list.
You list pros and cons. Reasons why you would and wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Jordan was in no hurry to make a decision even
though the former Bulls star has indicated that he would like a
head coach in place before Sunday's league lottery draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody knows Michael Jordan, Michael Jordan is not
stupid,'' Jarvis said. ``Michael Jordan is not going to offer a job
unless he is absolutely sure I'm going to take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the process, Jarvis said: ``This is a great
educational opportunity for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis also said he would not be intimidated working for Jordan
and handling pro players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If and when the time comes that I'm offered the job, I would
not be any more worried about that than when people said I couldn't
go from high school to college,'' he said. ``In any business, you
make sure you surround yourself with a great staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said he planned to attend the Big East meetings in
Florida, which begin Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
