<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TEQUILA-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN IN JALISCO: LIVING OUT A TEQUILA DREAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, N.J.)  (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By ALICE FEIRING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entrepreneurial challenge is not a new concept to W. Park Kerr.
After all, he and his mother had started the El Paso Chile Co. by
selling chile ristras, or garlands of red-hot chiles, on a roadside
in El Paso, their hometown. Now, 20 years later, the close-knit
family business _ which includes his mother, Norma; sister, Monica;
and brother-in-law, Sean _ makes a line of salsas, hot sauces, dips
and chips that brings in more than $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Though business was great, Kerr hit a self-proclaimed midlife
crisis a few years ago and was itching for a new cross-border
thrill. ``In our company, any family member with a really good idea
can pitch it,'' he said. ``So, I said: `I want to make tequila. Are
you guys in?' They gave me $30,000 and a credit card to explore the
venture with their blessing.'' (So far, he has spent about a
half-million dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   His decision to enter an already crowded market and take on
another country's national obsession raised eyebrows in the spirits
industry. Those who know the Mexican tequila world had their doubts
that Kerr could accomplish his goal of making a custom-distilled
premium product. After all, the non-Mexican companies in the
business were just distributors, buying ready-made tequila and
slapping private labels on it, like Don Eduardo, from Brown Forman,
or Porfidio from Martin Gassl.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Emmons, an industry consultant who wrote ``The Book of
Tequila,'' said: ``The Mexicans jealously guard their tequila. It's
highly unlikely that any outsider could pull this off.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Denton, who imports two premium tequilas, El Tesoro and
Chinaco, was also skeptical. ``No one rents out their distilleries
for an American to come and make their tequila, believe me,'' he
said.''
</P>
<P>
   But the charismatic Kerr was able to convince a distiller to
make a tequila the way he wanted it. After almost three years in
development, the El Paso Chile Co.'s new offering, Tequila Nacional
Silver, has hit the United States market 6,000 bottles strong. The
tequila, already available in Texas, will reach stores in New
Jersey this week, with New York and several other states to follow
in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy, Kerr said recently over a perfectly chilled
margarita (with salt). But perseverance and connections helped.
</P>
<P>
   Learning all he could about the tequila process went smoothly
enough. He hired a Mexican bottle manufacturer that, in turn,
introduced Kerr to its distillery clients. Such links were crucial.
``These people are very traditional,'' Kerr said. ``It's probably
only because of the personal nature of my introduction, and that I
speak Spanish, that I eventually won their trust.'' He learned
about growing, harvesting and distilling the spiky agave plant's
fruit, the pina, which looks something like a pineapple on steroids
and can weigh 100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   By last winter, Park was ready to contract with a distillery,
though he had a laundry list of criteria. It had to be midsized _
small enough so an extra $500,000 in annual income would make a
difference, yet large enough to handle the planned volume. It could
not have competing brands in the United States. It should be in Los
Altos, in the state of Jalisco, where, Kerr said, ``the earth is
red and the agave grow sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not all: The tequila would have none of the ammonia
nitrate, flavoring or urea often used in commercial tequila. The
pinas were to be roasted before fermentation in the traditional
adobe ovens called hornos, and the distiller had to agree to roast
the fruit slowly and to let it cool for a full 24 hours before
distillation, to improve taste. Kerr wanted to supply his own yeast
and yeast food. He insisted on potstills made of stainless steel
instead of copper, for a purer flavor. To ensure purity, all
production had to be above ground, in an immaculately clean plant
free of chemical contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I tell you my favorite story?'' he asked. ``I visited one
distiller who was very proud of how clean his plant was, because
every day he scrubbed the machinery and floors down with Pine-Sol.
What do you think his tequila tasted like?''
</P>
<P>
   Distillers he visited told him to be a good boy, buy ready-made
tequila and put his own label on it. Who would know the difference?
Once the distillers understood that Kerr, an American businessman,
was seeking control over how his tequila was made, none would play;
they did not return his phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   As despair was setting in, Kerr met Thomas Fernandez, the owner
of Coca-Cola bottlers in five Mexican regions, at a cocktail party.
``I play in two worlds _ America and Mexico,'' he said he told
Fernandez in frustration. ``I live on the border. I speak Spanish.
I love everything about this culture and its food. Yet no one
understands me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez thought that one of his sons might be able to help.
When Kerr got together with Miguel Fernandez, a man of American and
Mexican parentage who attended schools on both sides of the border,
he knew he had found an ideal ally.
</P>
<P>
   With the younger Fernandez at his side, Kerr found, distillers
were willing to talk about the project, and he could begin choosing
instead of begging. ``Out of 20, five were out because they were
too big, five others because they were too small,'' Kerr said.
``Seven didn't make the cut because of integrity and cleanliness
issues _ which, believe me, is a big deal down there. We finally
came down to a list of three distillers. One guy at the last minute
balked at our bringing our own yeast and distillation techniques
in, and then it came down to price. One guy wanted to charge us $10
a liter of tequila, which is a huge amount of money. In April we
finally went with Destileria San Isidreo, who agreed to all of the
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   As in-country coordinator for Tequila Nacional, Fernandez
interprets the intricate Mexican culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about strategic partnering with someone in Mexico with
fluency on both sides of the border, who can understand American
urgency and Mexican politics,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Destileria San Isidreo agreed to use Kerr's recipe,
Fernandez is on hand to oversee it personally. He springs surprise
distillery visits, makes sure no rotten or blighted agaves get into
the mix and reminds the distiller why the pinas have to be washed
before they are split and thrown into the hornos.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said the distiller, whose own approach to planning and
organization was very different from Kerr's, was ``finally open to
our advice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The project has gone relatively smoothly, though the Mexican
government paperwork has been a bureaucratic nightmare,'' Fernandez
said. ``If a word is misspelled or an `i' not dotted, the document
is returned for correction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said he admired some aspects of the Mexican system. ``Here,
we got our trademark in three months,'' he said, ``way shorter than
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the task is to make Tequila Nacional stand out on crowded
retail shelves. Kerr made a point of thinking about this early and
often, and he had an established company with related products in
his corner. Leveraging and capitalizing on El Paso Chile's current
market position _ it is the industry leader in the highest-priced
tier of the salsa market _ the company started guerrilla marketing
before there was anything to sell.
</P>
<P>
   It introduced a line of salsas called Borracho (``drunk,'' in
Spanish) with the words ``made with Tequila Nacional'' displayed on
the labels, as well as a margarita mix and margarita salt. ``The El
Paso Chile Co. Margarita Cookbook,'' published last May, included a
full-color reproduction of the Tequila Nacional label. Kerr is
banking on niche marketing and brand allegiance for the tequila,
which will have a retail price of about $35 to $40, midpriced for a
premium brand.
</P>
<P>
   Denton, the importer who thought it was impossible, conceded
that Park Kerr appears to have beaten the odds by bringing a
custom-distilled tequila to market. But like Kerr's Mexican
distiller, he does not see why Kerr insists on having the agaves
washed before roasting. ``Nothing can live through distillation,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr's response: ``I'm a little obsessive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
