<SLUG> BC-NY-CONDO-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE OF AVERAGE MANHATTAN APARTMENT TOPS $700,000 IN SURVEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing a seemingly inexorable climb, the average
price for apartments in much of Manhattan jumped by nearly a third
over the last year, breaking the $700,000 mark for the first time,
according to one of the real estate industry's most comprehensive
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The average price for an apartment south of West 116th Street
and East 96th Street rose to $733,860 during the first quarter of
2000, a 31 percent rise from the $559,204 average recorded in the
first quarter of 1999, according to the study, the Douglas Elliman
Manhattan Market Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time ever that the average has exceeded
$700,000,'' said Jonathan Miller, president of Miller Samuel, the
appraisal company that prepares the quarterly report. Miller said a
major contributor to the jump in the overall average price was an
increased proportion of larger apartments in the quarter's sales.
</P>
<P>
   The $733,860 figure represents a 77 percent increase over the
average price of $414,187 recorded in 1995 _ during the
bottoming-out of the last real estate recession _ and 62 percent
over the $453,909 average in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are crazy, but it's still not the 80s in terms of
percentage,'' Miller said, pointing out that between the fourth
quarters of 1985 and 1986, the overall average price rose 49.1
percent, to $580,282 from $389,170. Adjusted for inflation, that
1986 average of $580,282 would be $906,458 today.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James W. Hughes, dean of the Edward J. Bloustein School of
Planning and Public Policy at Rutgers University, put the current
increases in perspective. ``We're in an era of setting economic
records,'' Hughes said. ``Each month, we break the record for the
longest economic expansion in history. Manhattan has become one of
the major locomotives of this record-setting, and it would be
shocking if this were not reflected in surging housing prices in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This now rivals the boom of the 1980s in terms of a single
year,'' Hughes said. ``The difference in the 80s was that the price
surge was sustained over a seven-year period. This current boom has
really only taken off the last two years. As long as the national
economy keeps expanding, the price momentum in Manhattan will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan is not the only place in the country where price rises
have been breathtaking. In Santa Clara County, Calif., which
includes most of Silicon Valley, the local association of Realtors
reported in April that the average price for a single-family home
hit $702,165, a 37 percent increase from $513,085 in April 1999,
and that the average price of condominiums and town houses had
jumped 30 percent over the same period, to $341,167 from $262,139.
</P>
<P>
   The Elliman first-quarter report was based on 2,313 closed deals
for both co-op and condominium apartments, representing about 75
percent of the market's volume. It does not include sales of less
than $75,000, Miller said, because there are so few transactions
below that mark ``that they are insignificant to the overall
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Beck, executive vice president of the Real Estate Board
of New York, expressing concern that the Elliman numbers might
scare off potential buyers, pointed out that the report did not
cover northern Manhattan and that prices for smaller apartments
throughout the borough, while increasing significantly, were more
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Placing the Manhattan numbers in geographical context, Kevin
Thorpe, an economist with the National Association of Realtors,
cited the median price for an existing single-family home in the
Greater New York Region, which the association defines as the city
and certain suburban areas. The median was $221,500 in the first
quarter of 2000 _ a rise of 14.3 percent from the $193,800 median
in the first quarter of 1999, and 6.5 percent above the median of
$207,900 at the end of last year. The median price is the point at
which half the sales were above that figure and half were below it.
</P>
<P>
   The Elliman Manhattan survey found that the average price for
condominiums had increased 40 percent in a year, from $682,094 in
the first quarter of 1999 to $952,761 this quarter. ``That's a
staggering increase, since we have never seen the quarterly average
for condos exceed $700,000,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking down the condominium category by apartment size, the
average price for a studio in the first quarter of 2000 was
$243,667, up 38 percent from $175,986 in the first quarter of 1999.
For one-bedrooms, the average was $387,961, a 7 percent increase
from $361,397 a year ago. The two-bedroom average this year was
$958,202, up 8 percent from $888,093.
</P>
<P>
   For three-bedrooms, the average price was $1,997,053, a 75
percent jump from $1,140,600 in the first quarter of '99. (Miller
attributed that increase to great demand for the few available
properties.) For condos with four or more bedrooms, the average
price in the first quarter of 2000 was $4,118,750, a 7 percent
increase from $3,836,414 in the first quarter of '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory for the change in the overall average is that there
has been a shift to larger units; a significant increase in the
number of two-bedroom sales relative to the rest of the market,''
Miller said. ``The two-bedroom apartment is becoming a
first-purchase preference.''
</P>
<P>
   In the co-op category, the Elliman survey reported the average
price increased 24 percent over the year, to $576,596 from
$464,692. ``That's the highest average ever recorded for co-ops in
our study,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   For co-ops, by apartment size, the average price for a studio
was $142,060 in the first quarter of this year, up 19 percent from
$119,444 in the first quarter of 1999. For one-bedrooms, the
average was $291,675, a 28 percent increase over $227,229 in 1999.
In the two-bedroom category, the average this year was $760,578, up
39 percent from $547,407. For three-bedrooms, it was $1,858,576, up
44 percent from $1,294,840. And for those with four or more
bedrooms, the average price in the first quarter of 2000 was
$3,565,625, a decrease of 24 percent from $4,690,833 last year.
There are relatively few sales of apartments with four or more
bedrooms, so prices in that category are particularly volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about wary buyers, Beck of the real estate board noted
that the board's report covered all of Manhattan, ``so that our
figures aren't quite as euphoric, although they are wonderful.''
The median price for co-ops in all of Manhattan during the first
quarter of this year was $397,500, the real estate board reported,
up 14 percent from $350,000 in the first quarter of 1999.
Condominium prices were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Beck pointed out that more than 80 percent of all apartments in
Manhattan were studios, one-bedrooms or two-bedrooms. The median
price for those apartments, taken together, was $342,500 in the
first quarter of this year, up 12 percent from $306,000 a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
