<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTING FRAUD, CHALLENGER DROPS OUT OF PERU RUNOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf for clarifications; adds new 9th graf with updating
on decision of National Elections Commission to go ahead with
election)  By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ The outspoken challenger in Peru's presidential
race said on Thursday that he was pulling out of the runoff
election scheduled for later this month because he believed the
vote would be a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger, Alejandro Toledo, asked President Alberto K.
Fujimori to delay the vote to mid-June so international election
monitors could test computer systems to ensure a clean vote. Even
then, Toledo did not promise to participate unless he received
equal time on the main television stations.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori rejected such an idea before Toledo made the
request. For several days, Toledo had threatened to back out of the
race, and earlier on Thursday, Fujimori told campaign audiences
that he would not change the election day.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's withdrawal leaves Fujimori open to win a third
five-year term when balloting begins May 28. But it could prove to
be a Pyrrhic victory, capping a campaign tainted by international
observers' complaints of dirty tricks and tampering in the first
round of voting, on April 9. In that vote, the president fell just
shy of an absolute majority, forcing a runoff with Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Should Toledo and Fujimori hold firm, the Clinton administration
and the Organization of American States would be put in the
difficult position of having to validate an uncontested re-election
victory or reject it because of irregularities. A decision to
reject the election could lead the U.S. Congress and the OAS to
apply economic and political sanctions to Peru that would be
damaging not only to the country's weak economy but to its alliance
with Washington in the fight against cocaine trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope President Fujimori will not push the country over the
cliff,'' Toledo said at a brief news conference on Thursday
evening. ``We are firm. We will not participate in a fraudulent
election process like the one of the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   If history is any guide, Fujimori is not one to be pressured in
public. Over the last several days he has publicly pledged in no
uncertain terms that he would not change the election date no
matter what Toledo or the OAS' election observation team said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who say we should postpone the elections,''
Fujimori told a rally in the city of Chiclay on Wednesday night,
``but we just won't do it.'' He ridiculed Toledo, saying he was
trying to destabilize the country by traveling to Washington and
Buenos Aires, Argentina, in recent weeks to complain that the
election process had been so corrupted that it was probably
impossible for him to win.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the National Elections Commission, the final
authority on elections, announced that it would not change the
election date. Upon hearing the news, at a rally in Lima, Toledo
said: ``The dictatorship has taken the cruel decision of staying in
power. We will not allow five more years.'' He then called on
students to take to the streets in peaceful demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   In the April round of voting, ballots were counted over three
days amid calls by the Clinton administration and the OAS that a
second round was necessary to assure a fair result.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a 54-year-old, American-educated business professor, has
been threatening to drop out of the race ever since he came in
second in that vote, a tactic that has sometimes made him look
indecisive and like a sore loser. But on Thursday he was able to
use a new report by the OAS observation team calling for a delay in
the election as a buffer, as he claimed only to be following the
recommendations of a nonpartisan body invited by the Fujimori
government to monitor the election.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released on Thursday, the organization's team
sharply criticized the election authorities for choosing an
entirely new computer software program for the May vote without
consulting foreign or Peruvian opposition monitors. The report
called on the government to postpone the election, in order to
avert a series of irregularities that plagued the initial round of
voting.
</P>
<P>
   OAS monitors said there had been tampering with ballots, but
most important, it said that the disappearance of ballots and tally
sheets for hours at a time when they were supposedly being counted
made it impossible to verify the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This second round of the presidential election has to choose a
winner with a clear and transparent result,'' the report concluded.
``But confidence continues to be lacking and the calendar conspires
against recuperating that confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the new computer software, the report continued:
``When did they initiate the development of this new application
and why did the National Office of Election Processes not share
this information?'' It added that ``the election calendar makes it
impossible to do a complete test'' of the new software to assure
that it would give the opposition access to the final count as the
votes are being counted.
</P>
<P>
   In another press conference on Thursday, officials at the
National Office of Election Process disputed the OAS report. They
said they needed to change the computer program because unlike the
first round of voting the May 28 ballot would not include
congressional races. It also said that all of the software was
being properly shared with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In endorsing the findings of the report, Toledo said that even
if the vote was postponed, he would only participate if the main
television channels also gave him equal coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dirty war against my candidacy must end,'' Toledo said,
referring to a campaign by several tabloid newspapers and several
television stations of either not covering his campaign or filling
its coverage with stories about his marriage, allegations that he
has an illegitimate daughter and claims that he has a drinking
problem.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aides to Toledo said they concluded that they needed to take
dramatic action to prevent fraud after they completed their own
study that showed that in scores of voting sites in remote
provinces Fujimori had inexplicably high vote counts last month. In
some vote tables, Toledo received no votes.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's aides again demanded on Thursday that the April
poll-watchers, who were chosen by lottery and used in the first
round to guarantee the vote, be replaced by new monitors in the
second round. But Fujimori's allies in Congress have refused to
change a law that requires that the same poll-watchers who worked
in the first round be used in the second.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday night, Fujimori denied that there
would be any fraud or problems in the vote May 28. ``At this moment
there are no more irregularities,'' he said. ``They have been
overcome since the first round and now we are in the runoff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
