<HEADER>
A9571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-N     05-19 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS TRIES AGAIN AND, THIS TIME, SUCCEEDS
</HEADLINE>
  By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernard Arnault is not a man who makes the same
mistake twice. Ever since LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton bought
Phillips Auctioneers in October, Arnault, its chairman, has been
determined to make the house _ a distant third to Sotheby's and
Christie's _ a major player in the art world. Last week, Phillips'
first evening sale of important Impressionist and modern art was
something of a disaster: about 40 percent of the works went unsold.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Phillips tried again, this time with 39 works of
contemporary art. But this time Phillips was smart: estimates were
low, or at least at market prices. As a result, the sale totaled
$11 million, just under its high estimate of $11.2 million. Of the
39 works up, two failed to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for contemporary art was great, as it had been
earlier this week at Sotheby's and Christie's, and buyers were
willing to pay mightily. Records have been set all week, and
Thursday night several more could be added to the list, for Agnes
Martin and Damien Hirst, among other artists.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' sale included modern masters like Andy Warhol and
Martin, as well as trendier artists like Hirst and Robert Gober,
who has just been named to represent the United States at next
year's Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   In the American Craft Museum on West 53rd Street _ a space LVMH
has rented and spent more than $1 million to renovate for these
sales _ major dealers bid avidly, some for stock, others for
clients.
</P>
<P>
   But drawing a crowd must have cost LVMH a considerable sum. Of
the lots offered Thursday night, 30 came with some form of
financing from Phillips: a guarantee (an undisclosed minimum price
promised to the seller regardless of a sale's outcome), an advance,
a loan or a combination of the three. Often, competitors said,
Arnault had paid more for the works than their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But the sensible estimates encouraged bidding. Among the star
works was ``Apple Orchard,'' a 1987 landscape by Gerhard Richter
that had recently been on view at an art fair in Munich. Lucy
Mitchell-Innes, the Manhattan dealer, won her battle against
another bidder, paying $1.6 million, nicely above the painting's
high estimate of $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another sought-after painting was Martin's ``Drift of Summer''
(1965), a white abstract grid. Estimated at $800,000 to $1 million,
it sold to an unidentified telephone bidder for $1.4 million after
five people competed for it. The price more than doubled the
artist's previous record, $525,000 for ``The Tree,'' a 1964 grid
painting sold at Sotheby's in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A record was also set for Hirst. ``Out of Sight, Out of Mind,''
a 1991 work consisting of two cow heads preserved in formaldehyde,
sold to an unidentified buyer for $552,500, far above its $400,000
high estimate. It eclipsed Hirst's previous record, set last year
when ``My Way,'' one of his pharmaceutical cabinet assemblages,
sold for $354,500.
</P>
<P>
   A salesroom announcement made before bidding was opened on the
piece explained that it was in London and had been cleared by
British customs. If the purchaser was in either Britain or the
European Union, the work could be picked up immediately, the
announcement said, ``but if purchased by a client in the United
States, U.S. Customs will require the new owner to sign an
affidavit stating that they will not use the medium in any way
other than for the purpose of an art exhibition, as to prevent the
potential threat of mad cow disease or any other hazardous epidemic
that can be associated with the natural decay of dead animal
tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Another work by Hirst was up for sale: the photograph ``With
Dead Head,'' part of an edition of 15 made from 1981 to 1991.
Estimated at $30,000 to $40,000, it went to an unidentified
telephone bidder for $74,000, the same price another print brought
at Christie's last year.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include Phillips' commission, 15 percent of the
first $50,000 and 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not reflect
commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Sherman's ``Untitled Film Still No. 13'' (1978), a
photograph of a blonde reaching for a book, was estimated at
$80,000 to $120,000. It sold to an unidentified telephone bidder
for $167,500. Christie's sold another print last May for $156,500.
A self-portrait of Sherman posed as an Old Master sold Thursday
night to an unidentified bidder for $79,500, just under its low
estimate of $80,000. On Tuesday night, a similar Sherman work sold
at Sotheby's for $269,750.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
