<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI KEEPS AGONIZING, AND SO DO REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said at a nationally televised
town hall meeting in Manhattan on Thursday night that he still had
not reached a decision about his treatment for prostate cancer or
whether he would remain in the race for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers now say the decision could come this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor told Andrea Mitchell of MSNBC, who was moderating the
meeting at the 92nd Street Y, that the decision about his treatment
had turned out to be more difficult than he ever imagined.
</P>
<P>
   When he discovered he had prostate cancer, the mayor said, ``I
put a whole process into place'' for making a decision. ``I kind of
approached it as if this was a big case, or a budget decision.''
But he learned, he said, that ``this is a different kind of
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It involves thinking about your life, mortality, the quality
of your life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hourlong program, Mitchell frequently asked the
mayor if he regretted some of his most controversial actions of the
last year, including his verbal attacks on Patrick Dorismond, the
unarmed black man who was shot dead by police in March.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Giuliani said he regretted not having been
more sympathetic to Dorismond's family. ``In doing that I made a
mistake,'' he said, adding, ``I should have also conveyed the human
feeling that I had, the compassion, the loss of the mother. I think
if I could do it over again, I would have tried to balance it
more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani did not say he regretted releasing Dorismond's
juvenile police record, a decision for which he was criticized.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As Giuliani spoke, the state Republican Party continued with
plans to nominate him as its Senate candidate 11 days from now in
Buffalo. The party, which is operating on the assumption that the
mayor will run, has already spent tens of thousands of dollars on
``Rudy'' posters to be festooned all over the convention site. The
state Democratic Party nominated Hillary Rodham Clinton as its
Senate candidate on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans moved Thursday to turn up the pressure on Giuliani
to make a decision. A senior state Republican official said that
party leaders had contacted one of Giuliani's senior advisers to
warn him that the mayor's political future with the state party
would be in ruins if he dropped out of the race now _ unless it
turned out, the official said, that the mayor had additional
medical complications.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani's cautious deliberations are driving
Republicans, his campaign staff and the media to high levels of
irritation and anxiety, several prostate cancer specialists said
Thursday that the mayor was taking no longer to determine his
treatment than many other men. Many patients, doctors said, can
take months to decide. The delay is not a problem, they added,
because most prostate cancers are slow to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going through a process that lots of people go through,''
said Dr. Michael J. Droller, the chairman of the urology section at
Mount Sinai Medical Center, who is not directly involved in
Giuliani's case.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's two main choices are radiation or surgical removal of
the prostate. He said Monday that he had wavered between the
options, and said Thursday that he was not leaning in either
direction. He also said that the possible side effects were
complicating his decision.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``You find that that does sort of overlap into the thinking,''
Giuliani said, speaking at a new Steuben glass store on Madison
Avenue after a ribbon cutting. He added that ``it makes it more
complicated than it would be if I were making this decision
privately.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most men of Giuliani's age, 56, choose surgery, which doctors
say can have a cure rate as high as 95 percent. But side effects
include both incontinence and impotence. Doctors say the rates of
incontinence and impotence vary widely, depending on the patient's
age, his functioning before surgery and the skill of his doctor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a report in the Journal of the American Medical Association
last year, a team of scientists led by Dr. Janet L. Stanford of the
Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle found that almost
60 percent of patients were impotent after prostate surgery. But
Dr. Patrick C. Walsh, a specialist at Johns Hopkins Medical Center
in Baltimore who developed the ``nerve-sparing'' prostate operation
designed to preserve sexual function, said that 75 to 90 per cent
of patients under the age of 60 _ provided they were in the hands
of experienced surgeons _ recovered sexual function a year and a
half after the operation.
</P>
<P>
   A mayoral adviser said that Giuliani had spoken to at least a
dozen experts around the country and had recently traveled to
Baltimore to meet with Walsh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
