<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT ALL TOO AWARE OF WHAT LURKS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Tim Hardaway looked around the locker room in the
afterglow of the Miami Heat's victory in Game 5 on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no smiling,'' he said. ``Everybody is dead serious.
Check it out. We're going to New York to end it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, which leads the playoff series against the New York
Knicks three games to two, is passionately mindful that the Knicks
have ended the team's season with first-round knockouts the last
two seasons, particularly last season when Allan Houston's winning
shot bounced off the glass and tantalizingly off the rim before
falling through the net with 0.8 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory of that shot is still there, big-time,'' P.J. Brown
said Thursday at American Airlines Arena before the Heat flew to
New York for Game 6 on Friday night. ``A lot of heartache and pain
went with it. Now we have a chance to close them out at the Garden.
To say the least, it would be a real good feeling to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Riley put it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time,'' he said. ``We've been through a lot. There's not
going to be any real words by me or videos. It's going to be
straight up and straight down. It's time for us to step up and move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning wants his teammates to go into the Garden with a
feeling of desperation, to play as if the Heat trailed in the
series. He tried that approach in Game 2 after the Heat won Game 1,
and it failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have a cushion we tend to relax and kind of exhale,''
Mourning said. ``I think if we go in with an attitude that it's a
must-win situation, we'll be able to finish it out. It's a matter
of carrying that mentality over from Wednesday's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning is aware that the Heat has won six of the nine games
played between the teams this season, including three of four in
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found ways to beat this team throughout the course of
the year,'' he said. ``But we have to learn to play better on the
road. That is our challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat seems to also feel that the team must prove it can end
the Knicks' season at the Garden _ with all the hostility and
history it represents _ in order to be a serious contender for the
National Basketball Association championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our chance to show we can close a series with
championship quality,'' Brown said. ``And I think we're ready to go
out and play our best game of this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the Knicks win Friday, the decisive game would be Sunday
at Miami. The Heat has had too many disappointing finishes against
the Knicks to want to risk a Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a security blanket to us because it hasn't proven
successful,'' Dan Majerle said. ``We have to go to New York with
the mindset that we want to end it there and not leave it to one
game.''
</P>
<P>
   A season ago, the Knicks had a 24-rebound advantage in
eliminating the Heat in five games. This time, the Heat has 40 more
rebounds than the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our No. 1 priority going into the series,'' Riley
said. ``I think that's what got us beat last year. The difference
is simply big muscle. It's concentration. It's blocking out.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riley is particularly happy that the Knicks' offensive
rebounding has been minimized. They have been held to fewer than 20
second-chance points in each of the Heat's three victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time,'' the coach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
