<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-SIXERS-NYT &LR;      05-19 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 76ers FACING VACATION OR FINAL SHOWDOWN  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Allen Iverson was late for Thursday's practice,
but once the game begins, he is often a step ahead of everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Iverson, their enigmatic and electrifying guard, the
Philadelphia 76ers are trying to write a playoff run to remember.
</P>
<P>
   No National Basketball Association team has ever recovered from
a 3-0 deficit to win a four-of-seven game series. But the Sixers,
who lost the first three games of their series against the Indiana
Pacers, have reduced that margin to 3-2 heading into Friday night's
Game 6 in Philadelphia. If the Sixers win Friday in the energized
First Union Center, the decisive Game 7 will be Sunday in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, facing elimination no longer alarms the Sixers.
They have somehow turned the pressure into a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this is the third time we'll be playing a game we have
to win,'' said Toni Kukoc, a Sixers backup forward who has
championship experience from his days with the Chicago Bulls. ``You
don't think about that anymore. You just play.''
</P>
<P>
   Few play the game with more zest than Iverson, who has averaged
28.2 points a game in the series to lead all scorers. Despite being
only 6 feet 1 inch, Iverson can dominate a game, either by making
long-range jumpers or by driving to the basket with an array of
moves and alarming quickness. His talent and his toughness have
made Iverson one of the league's special players, an All-Star who
has become the cornerstone of a franchise on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   But Iverson's penchant for lateness to practice, and several
disagreements during the season with coach Larry Brown, have also
been part of the package. Iverson joined his teammates on the floor
Thursday as practice was about to begin, but he was nowhere in
sight during the half-hour media session that preceded the workout.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Croce, the Sixers' owner, said Iverson would be fined for
his tardiness, but around the Sixers, Iverson's being late was
almost business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fined and I'll talk to him,'' said Croce, wearing the
wry smile of someone who knew that neither a talk nor a fine would
probably change the situation. ``I've talked to him before about
leadership, about the importance of timeliness. But believe me, his
teammates won't show any angst about it. They know him. They know
when he gets out on the floor during a game, he gives everything he
has.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers squeaked out a 2-point victory in Game 4, then
dominated Game 5. But Game 6 will mark the return of Reggie Miller,
Indiana's All-Star guard who served a one-game suspension in Game 5
for throwing a punch at Matt Geiger, Philadelphia's center.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger was suspended two games for his flagrant foul against
Miller, so he will miss Friday night's action as well.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has been magnificent in the playoffs, averaging 25 points
over all and 26 points against Philadelphia. After sitting out a
game, expect Miller to be even more eager to end this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers were well aware of Miller's penchant for rising to
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie can be quiet for three quarters, then hit three
3-pointers in a row,'' said Aaron McKie, a Philadelphia guard and
one of the players who will guard Miller. ``He's going to come out
and try to kill us. He's a showboat. He'll play to the crowd,
whatever. It's all fun to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the series was more fun for the Pacers when they were making
more outside shots. In the first three games, Indiana was 28 for 62
from 3-point range, but in the last two games, Indiana made just 10
of 41 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jalen Rose, Indiana's second-leading scorer, has
become ineffective at an inopportune time. After averaging 35
points in the first two games of the series, Rose scored just 12
points in Game 3, 16 points in Game 4 and 13 points in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pacers make their outside shots Friday night and spread
Philadelphia's defense, Indiana has an excellent chance to prevail
and go on to face the winner of the Knicks-Heat series. But the
Sixers are the better rebounding team, and they have momentum. So
if the Pacers don't shoot well, Philadelphia could move closer to a
historic comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown our maturity by fighting back,'' said Theo
Ratliff, Philadelphia's leading shot-blocker, who has also averaged
15 points a game in the series. ``We're looking forward to another
game. We know we have a chance to do something that no team has
ever done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
