u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-19 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BECOMING AN UNRAVELED TEAM ON AND OFF THE COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ In one 72-hour mood swing, the same good-time
New York Knicks who were dizzy in the afterglow of their Sunday
victory began bickering on the floor by the second quarter of
Wednesday night's Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   That discord set the tone for the team's mental unraveling on
defense minutes before the final buzzer of their miserable loss in
Miami, a dispiriting defeat that left last year's Eastern
Conference champions one game from elimination as Friday's Game 6
at Madison Square Garden approaches.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was unsettling enough before another calamity
unfolded around 3 a.m. Thursday morning when the Knicks' team plane
landed in Westchester County. In a freakish incident, a large
amount of thrust was emitted from one engine as the plane neared
the team's parking area. The blast lifted coach Jeff Van Gundy's
Honda Civic and tossed it like a tumbleweed rolling over several
staff and player cars, including the Mercedes of Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say?'' Latrell Sprewell said. ``Things were
already bad and then to have that happen, it was the cap for the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time this season such destructive forces _
whether on the court or off it _ have existed in the midst of a
team that has generally been a dysfunction-free zone. With almost
everyone healthy and well fed by their contracts, with nearly
everyone safe and snug in their job security, the Knicks are
missing the kind of desperate air the Miami Heat has fed off to
take a three games-to-two lead in this four-of-seven-game,
second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   The less-talented Heat understands that if it is eliminated,
coach Pat Riley might dismantle the team and start over. And the
Heat is dead set on slaying the Knick demons that have dogged them
for two early offseasons. The Knicks, the year-long favorite to
reach the finals again, have been missing that little something
extra this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just hunger,'' Houston said. `'Just that feeling of us
against the world. We don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a sign of that glorious, motivational
dysfunction sprouting in the cracks of the Knicks. Now, the Knicks
either win or get humiliated by the Heat. Now, Marcus Camby either
finishes strong with an offensive rebound or he could return to the
same fragile label he fought so hard to peel off last year. Now,
the vanishing Houston either shakes the crusty, throw-back defense
of Dan Majerle or he could find his All-Star status second-guessed.
Now, Patrick Ewing either puts a body on Alonzo Mourning or he
could end up mocked for his ``I'm Still Great'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of tension to galvanize the adversity-starved
Knicks. And it all was laid out before them in the team's film
session Thursday. ``It was like watching a horror flick,'' said
Houston, who noted that he has to assert himself more than he did
in Game 5, when he was 1 of 2 in the second half. ``It was hard to
watch. You wanted to say, Jeff, that's enough. We don't want to
watch this, but we have to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the moment Mourning missed two free throws and the
Heat won the wrestling match for the rebound in the first quarter,
and the time when Ewing called for the ball and Chris Childs
angrily directed him to set a pick in the second quarter. Both
snarled at each other for several minutes as the Heat overtook the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be together when things aren't going our way,''
Camby said. ``We can't have guys wanting the ball and then rolling
their eyes and not getting back on defense. It should be a group
effort and the ego and stuff should be put aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Van Gundy address the infighting during a
second-quarter timeout, he added a few more words about the issue
in the locker room after Game 5. ``You're fighting an opponent you
shouldn't be fighting which is yourself,'' Van Gundy said. ``Any
time the pressure is up more you have time to fall prey to that. I
think that obviously the more time you spend fighting amongst
yourself, the less time you spend fighting the opponent you should
be fighting. I just wish we could move on past it quicker. Say what
you've got to say and then go to the next play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks talked about moving forward Thursday by learning from
all of the mistakes they've made so far in this series. There was
plenty of material. Through the five games, the most glaring
breakdowns have occurred in the fourth quarter. In Game 5, the
defense was confused in its rotations and gave up three 3-pointers
in the last 2 minutes 30 seconds of the game. In Game 3, it was 8
costly turnovers during a fourth quarter, plus overtime. In Game 1,
there were 5 pivotal turnovers down the stretch. But in each game,
one common thread that needs attention has been rebounding,
particularly on the offensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Heat poke at the Knicks every time. And since
rebounding is borne out of effort, this is the area that gnaws at
Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the ball,'' Van Gundy said. ``It's very simple. Hit
someone and go get the ball. Anthony Carter has 26 rebounds, more
than most of our big guys. If he can get the ball, you can get the
ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
