<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEH-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI MEMO DETAILS FREEH WARNING TO RENO
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Director Louis Freeh of the FBI warned in 1996 that
Attorney General Janet Reno and one of her top deputies should
remove themselves from an investigation into Democratic fund
raising after the aide was quoted as saying that Reno could lose
her job if the inquiry proceeded, government officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's warning, they said, was in a memorandum that the FBI
provided this week to Senate investigators who are reviewing the
Justice Department's investigation of campaign fund-raising
improprieties by Democrats in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum could cast new light on Reno's early decision
making in the investigation and her later decision to turn aside
the advice of Freeh and her own chief campaign finance prosecutor
and close an investigation into Vice President Al Gore. That
decision greatly eased Gore's burden as he prepared to open his bid
for the White House, but it embroiled Reno in harsh criticism that
she was seeking to protect her superiors. She has insisted that her
decision not to seek an independent counsel in the case was
motivated by a lack of evidence, not by any sort of political
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum is additional evidence of the deep, longstanding
split between Freeh and Reno, and its existence became known as
Reno received an internal report this week that faulted both the
Justice Department and the FBI for failures to cooperate in the
investigation of the nuclear scientist Wen Ho Lee. Officials said
the report was especially tough on the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Dec. 9, 1996, memorandum on the campaign
fund-raising investigation, Freeh recounted remarks attributed to
Lee Radek, the Justice Department's chief of public integrity, in
which Radek was said to have claimed that he was under considerable
pressure to scrap the investigation because Reno's job ``might hang
in the balance,'' the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had been widely quoted at the time as
suggesting that Reno might be asked to step aside and allow the
appointment of a new attorney general in President Clinton's second
term. The existence of the memorandum was first reported by The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's memorandum, which was addressed to the bureau's deputy
director, William Esposito, recounted remarks made to Esposito by
Radek, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Radek was traveling in Europe Thursday and was not immediately
available for comment. But in a prepared statement released to The
Associated Press, he said he did not recall making such statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no recollection of ever saying I was under pressure
because the attorney general's job hung in the balance,'' Radek
said. ``Nor is it something I would have said because it has no
basis in fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Myron Marlin, the Justice Department spokesman, said Reno's
actions were based on the law, not on personal or political
considerations. ``This attorney general has never let her own
self-interest color her decision making,'' he said. ``She proceeds
by the book, based on the facts and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Rallying to Reno's defense, Justice Department officials noted
that the attorney general sent nine separate matters to independent
counsels for investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a year after Freeh's memorandum, the officials noted,
Reno expanded the jurisdiction of Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel whose inquiry into the Monica Lewinsky matter led to the
president's impeachment in 1998. In Freeh's memorandum, which is
being studied by the House and Senate judiciary committees, he told
Esposito that he had confronted the attorney general and Radek and
urged them both to step down from the investigation, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno apparently refused, and the rift between her and Freeh has
widened considerably during Clinton's second term.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Democratic fund raising began in the midst
of Clinton's re-election campaign in 1996, when Justice Department
prosecutors reviewed several instances of questionable fund raising
by senior Democrats, including Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president came under intensive scrutiny by prosecutors
over his activities at what was later described as a fund-raising
event at a Buddhist temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif., in April
1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter on Nov. 1, 1996, to a top federal prosecutor in Los
Angeles, Radek said the local investigation of the incident had to
be brought to a halt and turned over to the Justice Department in
Washington because of the potential for appointment of an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your office should take no steps to investigate these matters
at this time,'' Radek wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The temple inquiry eventually exonerated Gore, although it led
to an conviction of a California fund-raiser, Maria Hsia, who
helped organize Gore's visit to the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said initially that he did not know that the temple event
was a fund-raiser, although he later acknowledged that he knew it
was ``finance-related.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsia's conviction earlier this year has kept alive the political
embarrassment that the event caused for the vice president, the
putative Democratic presidential nominee this year. His opponent,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, has vowed to make Gore's role in
campaign fund raising in 1996 a major issue in the campaign this
fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
