<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REJECTED-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS REJECTION OF GUILTY PLEA IN KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York state's highest court ruled Thursday that a man accused
of strangling eight women in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., cannot avoid the
death penalty by pleading guilty.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, the suspect, Kendall L. Francois, tried to
plead guilty to murder before prosecutors had decided whether to
charge him with capital murder and seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dutchess County district attorney, William V. Grady,
refused to accept the plea, saying that Francois did not have the
right to do so during the 120 days prosecutors are allowed after an
arraignment to decide whether to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve, the day after Francois tried to plead guilty,
Grady announced that he would seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Francois appealed, saying their client could plead
guilty at any time.
</P>
<P>
   But the argument was rejected in July by the Appellate Division
of the state Supreme Court, and Thursday, the State Court of
Appeals upheld that ruling. The unanimous decision by the
seven-member appeals court, written by Judge Howard Levine, found
that the state's 1995 death penalty law did not give capital murder
defendants the right to sidestep a district attorney's period of
deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   Until completion of that deliberation, Levine wrote, ``a capital
defendant does not have an unqualified right to plead guilty to the
entire indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Francois, Mark Harris of the state's Capital
Defender Office, said there were still several issues to be
resolved in the case but the matter of the guilty plea ``is sort of
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices noted that if the decision had been otherwise, ``it
would inevitably result, in the most heinous or high profile cases,
in an unseemly race to the courthouse between the defense and
prosecution to see whether a guilty plea or notice of intent to
seek the death penalty will be filed first.'' The murder trial is
expected to start this fall in Dutchess County.
</P>
<P>
   Francois is accused of strangling eight women and stashing their
bodies in the Poughkeepsie house that he shared with his family in
a 22-month killing spree. He was arrested in September 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
