<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9601 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-19 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ENTERTAINMENT, RICKEY'S A STEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's not often a newly acquired player helps two
sports teams in town.
</P>
<P>
   But think about it: Now that the Mariners have acquired Rickey
Henderson, the Sonics' Gary Payton is no longer Seattle sports'
only wild hair.
</P>
<P>
   Payton now can hurl all the TV remote controls at all the
teammates he wants. Few sports fans will notice.
</P>
<P>
   With Henderson, baseball's designated distraction, so much will
be happening that even the Experience Music Project building falls
to second in the public peeves.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get me wrong. Having Henderson around is wonderful.
Hey, I'm a sports columnist.
</P>
<P>
   He is to my job what hooker roles are to actresses: Disturbing,
yet exotic, and necessary to experience just to display range.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Mariners get out of this decision is secondary, and
can be explained in two numbers: $150,000 and .184.
</P>
<P>
   If Henderson is a complete bust as a player and more toxic in
the clubhouse than a paternity-suit rumor, the Mariners can cut him
for a cost of about $150,000 in salary _ almost exactly the wages
of the pool boy for Mariners CEO Howard Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   And .184 is the average of Mariners hitters in the leadoff
position this season. To give an idea how bad that is, well, it's
worse than Ken Griffey Jr.'s average in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the horror. Oh, the humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Though Henderson is old, he's not THAT old _ contrary to reports
elsewhere, he was a mere child, not an adult, when the Crusades
began _ and even on baseball fumes he can hit better than .184.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he was hitting .219 this season with two stolen bases with
the New York Mets. But if the Mariners had that nearly 40-point
improvement all season leading off in front of Alex Rodriguez, John
Olerud and Edgar Martinez, we'd be talking magic numbers already.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, at 40, Henderson led the National League in on-base
percentage at .429. Even if age has caught up with him, he's not
too old to crouch his strike zone down to a pinhole. Camels have
better relationships with eyes of needles than pitchers do with
Henderson's strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Once he's walked, just the threat of a theft by the greatest
base stealer in history has to shake up pitchers. In that way, he's
like Payton: Just standing there, he's annoying to opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Henderson is a liability in the outfield. He's
always had a mediocre arm, and watching him break on a fly ball the
past few years has been a little like watching a teenage driver's
first attempt to parallel park.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, for $155,000, what can be expected? If Henderson just
throws back whatever hits off the left-field wall, the problem is
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   The issue with Henderson has always been his attitude and its
impact on the several dozen clubhouses he's been in.
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, chemistry as a baseball virtue is vastly
overrrated. Compared to most other team sports, there is very
little teamwork involved, unless it involves passing notes to the
dugouts from the halter tops circling the bullpens.
</P>
<P>
   Little in baseball has changed. Casey Stengel once observed that
his major task as a manager was to keep ``the half of the team that
hates me from the half that hasn't made up their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the little picture, Henderson's litany of troubles rarely
involve teammates. Many of his former teammates say he's usually
been helpful, and almost never confrontational. And he's a media
magnet, saving many a postgame clubhouse when there wasn't much to
be said about a particular contest.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in sports is better at saying nothing in an amusing
fashion than Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   His conflicts lie almost exclusively with managers and
management. It's possible that in his 21 years as a major league
player, Henderson has never been played enough or paid enough, in
his own humble estimation.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of perpetual yap was probably at the heart of the
debate among Mariners bosses. There's no way that either general
manager Pat Gillick or club president Chuck Armstrong can look
forward to Henderson's complaints, laments, suspicions and
paranoias. They just finished with Griffey, fergawdsakes.
</P>
<P>
   Merely getting ahold of the guy is a major franchise task. After
Henderson failed to show on the day expected at spring training,
Mets officials had 11 different phone numbers for Henderson. None
worked. Nor did his family or agents have a location.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Lou Piniella, who handled Henderson somewhat
successfully when the Mariners manager skippered the Yankees in the
late 1980s, is persuaded that he can deal with any player, as long
as he is not a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing to understand about Henderson is that he is
almost exclusively about himself. He is eager to become baseball's
career leader in runs scored and walks. As long as those goals
match team goals, things can work. If not ...
</P>
<P>
   Will he crash into a wall for a catch? No.
</P>
<P>
   If his often delicate hamstrings so much as twitch, will he go
from first to third on a single to right? No.
</P>
<P>
   Will he be accepting when he loses an at-bat to a defensive
substitution? No.
</P>
<P>
   But is he entertaining, eccentric and incorrigible? Oh my. Those
Hall of Fame skills are nowhere near gone.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
