<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-ASSEMBLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEMOCRATIC STIRRINGS IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, May 19:
</P>
<P>
   The attempted coup in the New York state Assembly this week had
a healthy feel to it at first, like a blast of oxygen that aroused
hope of energy and independence among the Assembly's Democratic
majority. Then, within a few hours, the attempt to overthrow
Speaker Sheldon Silver began to look less like an effort to change
the state Legislature's claustrophobic system than a plot to
replace one autocrat with another.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bragman, the second-ranking Democrat in the Assembly,
announced Wednesday that he would try to oust Silver in a showdown
vote next Monday. By the standards of normal combat, announcing
plans to storm the castle five days in advance would seem the
height of folly. Since the first word of the revolt, Silver has
unleashed an army of powerful backers to coax or threaten his
troops to support him, especially those teetering on the fence. The
speaker has also stripped Bragman of his position as majority
leader and demoted two of his close allies. Some old Albany hands
were predicting that by Monday Bragman would be lucky if his office
still had state furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The dream of swapping the secretive and lethargic Silver for a
lively consensus builder is understandable. Over the last six years
Silver's methods have encouraged one of the worst traditions in
Albany _ the coalescing of legislative power in the hands of three
people: the governor, the Senate majority leader and the speaker.
Efforts to open budget sessions or simply to spread legislative
power have often been either rebuffed or simply ignored by the
speaker. Bragman's strength so far has been that he is promising a
``member-driven house,'' an innovation that is already decades late
in coming to Albany's insular and outdated legislative culture.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether Bragman's promises of openness are
sincere or simply a means to grab power. If the latter, the key
difference between Bragman and Silver could be a devastating loss
of clout in Albany for New York City. At present Silver, whatever
his shortcomings, is the city's sole voice in negotiations with the
governor and Senate leader.
</P>
<P>
   In his six years running the Assembly, Silver has sometimes
pushed for education funding, new transit money and other issues
that have aided city residents. On other occasions, however, he has
worried so much about re-electing Democrats in upstate districts
and the suburbs that he has misserved his urban constituents,
agreeing for example to end even the modest tax that commuters pay
for their use of facilities in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, who lives near Syracuse, generally has a political
agenda that is more suburban and conservative than Silver's, and
Bragman's views on abortion, campaign finance reform and gun
control raise troubling questions for traditional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   If Silver manages to quell this revolt, as most Democrats still
believe he will, he does not deserve to celebrate a victory and go
around the State Capitol methodically punishing the vanquished.
Instead the speaker needs to register this uprising as a dire
warning that there is trouble in his house and a hunger for
democratic reform among legislators who would like to do the work
for which they were elected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
