<SLUG> BC-NCAA-UCLA-SOFTBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA RUNS PAST CANISIUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If playing UCLA _ one of the most storied programs
in college softball history _ didn't make Canisius dizzy, watching
the Bruins run the bases Thursday afternoon certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   The defending national champion Bruins set a NCAA Tournament
record with 10 stolen bases and beat the Golden Griffins 8-0 in
five innings in the first game of a double-elimination regional
tournament at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Natasha Watley also set a single-game tournament record
with four steals and tied, in just her second year, the school's
career stolen-base record of 31. The Bruins' total bettered the
seven steals by Kansas last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know UCLA has a reputation of not being a running team, but
look what we have here,'' Bruins coach Sue Enquist said. UCLA,
ranked No.1 in the region, advanced to face No.3 Long Beach State
at 12:30 p.m. (PDT) today.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins executed three double steals and generally ran at
will against the No.6-seeded Golden Griffins. UCLA took advantage
of three Canisius errors, and Amanda Freed pitched a two-hitter,
walked none and struck out six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were a little bit in awe about playing UCLA,''
Canisius coach Mike Rappl said. ``We were taking pictures in the
dugout. I try to stress the importance of playing ball, but I want
them to have fun, too.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had all the fun Thursday. Freed led off the game with a
double and Watley followed with a walk. A double steal put runners
on second and third, and Freed scored on Julie Marshall's groundout
to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins added a run in the second and broke the game open in
the fourth. With the bases loaded and no outs, UCLA's Tairia Mims
hit a fly ball to right. Outfielder Nicole Guadagna first went in
but couldn't recover in time. The ball glanced off her glove, and
all three runners scored.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndsey Klein went 2 for 2 with two RBI and three runs scored.
Watley walked twice and reached on an error once. She stole second
base each time and stole third in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's other games, Leslie Malerich pitched a
three-hitter as Florida State beat Long Beach State 2-0, and No.2
Iowa beat No.5 Bethune-Cookman 9-1 in five innings. Today,
Bethune-Cookman and Canisius meet in an elimination game at 10 a.m.
(PDT), and Iowa plays Florida State at 3 p.m. (PDT). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
