<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLACE AD HERE' TAKES ON NEW MEANING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A half-page newspaper ad adorned with a palm tree ran in
Sunday's sports editions of the Hartford Courant and New Haven
Register. It said in part:
</P>
<P>
   (ital)Work in a cold environment? In a dead-end opportunity?
Want to heat up your career? Come join us in Los Angeles. ... Drive
your career forward and put your current situation in the rear-view
mirror. Send us your resume.(endital)
</P>
<P>
   The equal-opportunity employer who placed the ad, trying to
spread a little sunshine, was L.A.-based Fox Sports Net. So who in
Hartford, Conn., and New Haven, Conn., might happen to be the
target audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it's graduation time, we just wanted to make sure people
at the University of Connecticut School of Broadcasting know where
to find us,'' said Scott Ackerson, the executive producer of Fox's
``National Sports Report,'' well aware that rival ESPN is in nearby
Bristol, Conn. _ since he used to work there himself as a producer
on ``SportsCenter'' with an anchor named Keith Olbermann.
</P>
<P>
   And what current anchor, producer, assignment editor, director,
key grip or coffee-go-getter who once upon a time worked at ESPN
with that supposed anchor-monster would want to come west to work
in the same building with him again?
</P>
<P>
   Says Olbermann of the ads: ``For those ESPN employees who can
afford to buy a newspaper, it's a godsend.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE FOX 'TUDE: Ackerson, a Midwesterner and East Coaster who's
been living in Southern California for the last six years, has been
on the cutting edge of the Internet-friendly, analyst-loaded
reshaping of the nightly hour-long highlights show that was
formerly called ``Fox Sports News.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, the ``National Sports Report'' has taken the
typical ``SportsCenter'' format to new high-tech heights.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good, says Ackerson, who was put in the executive
position for the show at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've taken a good first step,'' he said. ``We find
some people driving it more than others, but one thing we do like
is a lot people really trying hard (to make it work).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a decent amount of time to get it right.
We're taking a look at all aspects now and we're in the process of
filtering it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the people I've talked to _ not in TV _ the most
universal thing they like is the analysts getting involved in the
highlights. Now we've got to get better at picking the right things
to show. We've lacked a bit in that and the reason is we're all not
used to cutting highlights this way. We're in a process of having a
`highlights seminar' to get everyone working (on the same page).
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of sharing what works, ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' has
already borrowed the live news-flash across the bottom of the
screen that Fox began using on its major highlights show.
</P>
<P>
   Which it borrowed from ESPN2's nightly practice. And didn't CNN
Headline News actually start it?
</P>
<P>
   ``What it shows me, despite what you'll hear from our neighbors
to the north, is they do notice what we're doing, they care about
it,'' said Ackerson. ``It's up to us to push forward and after a
certain point, they'll say instead of Fox Sports Net is copying
from ESPN, ESPN is copying what Fox Sports Net does. Hopefully we
can get viewers to realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   RABBIT PUNCHES: ``Friday Night Fights'' (6 p.m. PDT) originates
tonight from the Playboy Mansion in Holmby Hills before an
invitation-only crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first live sporting event ever telecast from the
mansion. (Provide your own punchline here).
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC L.A.: The latest push to get ESPN Classic in every home
with cable is to address particular major cities with theme-based
programming. L.A.'s the place this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup Saturday (all times PDT):
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.: The Dodgers' Sandy Koufax shuts out Minnesota on a
3-hitter in Game 7 of the 1965 World Series. In stunning
black-and-white.
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m.: USC's Charles White, rushing 39 times for 247 yards,
scores a 1-yard TD with 1:32 left to give a Trojans a 17-16 win
over Ohio State in the 1980 Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m.: UCLA's Tyus Edney drives the length of the court and
hits the game-winning layup at the buzzer to beat Missouri in the
second round of the 1995 NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m.: The Kings' Wayne Gretzky becomes the NHL's all-time
scoring leader when he sets up the game-tying goal against his
former team, Edmonton, with 53 seconds left in regulation in 1989
(then scores the game-winning goal in OT).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's lineup:
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m.: L.A. Raiders 1983 Yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   6:30 a.m.: L.A. Rams 1979 Yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   7 a.m.: 1973 Final Four Highlights (ending with Bill Walton's
21-for-22 shooting in the title game for UCLA against Memphis
State).
</P>
<P>
   7:30-9 a.m.: Roy Firestone's ``Up Close'' shows with John
Wooden, Don Drysdale and Tommy Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.: Kirk Gibson's 1988 World Series Game 1 home run contest.
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m.: The 45-42 USC football win over UCLA in 1990 featuring
Todd Marinovich vs. Tommy Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE: In addition to Marion Jones' interesting ads out for
Nike _ she's on a radio show calling for athletes to become more of
a role model _ she and husband/shot-putter C.J. Hunter did ads for
NBC's Olympic coverage, strategically placed in the network's
season-ending episode of ``E.R.'' on Thursday night. ...
</P>
<P>
   Time-Warner Cable systems reached an agreement with NBC to carry
the two cable channels _ MSNBC and CNBC _ through 2008, just in
time for their Olympic coverage this fall. ...
</P>
<P>
   CNN/SI's Peter King reports that the reason former Jets coach
Bill Parcells didn't sign a $1.5 million deal with ESPN is the
all-sports network wanted to ``tie up Parcells' Internet rights.''
Parcells is supposedly ready to sign a seven-figure deal with
another Internet company. ...
</P>
<P>
   CourtTV begins live coverage of the murder trial of Baltimore
Ravens standout Ray Lewis on Monday, if jury selection is finished
this week. ...
</P>
<P>
   In response to a viewer's letter, ESPN and ESPN2 have started to
use Spanish accent marks and the Spanish alphabet when using names
of Hispanic major-league baseball players in graphics. ``It is a
very simple addition which shows our dedication to detail and our
respect for the Hispanic players and their heritage,'' said Tim
Scanlan, ESPN coordinating producer for baseball. ...
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's ``NFL Prime Time'' will return to a one-hour format this
fall (4:30 to 5:30 p.m.) as the kickoff for the cable network's
Sunday Night Football telecast will be pushed back from 5:15 to
5:30 p.m. PDT. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writer Tom Hoffarth's media column appears Fridays. He can be
reached at (818) 713-3661 or at sptmediaaol.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
