<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE WILL GET HIS RING NO MATTER WHAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Let the heartbreaks commence. Kobe Bryant,
the Lakers' 21-year-old wunderkind, is getting hitched.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of female teeny-boppers everywhere, Bryant
confirmed Thursday he has become engaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' young shooting guard would not reveal the identity
of his betrothed, reportedly an 18-year-old senior at Marina High
School in Huntington Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about it, I walked behind Kobe and took a look at
him,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``He started wondering what
I was doing, and I asked him if he wasn't still wet behind the
ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Aren't you a little young to get married?' And he
said, `Nah, I do everything young.' He's quite convinced he can
carry this out, and I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said she was not a Hollywood starlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not a movie star, she's my star,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a date had not been set, though the marriage would come
after The Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who signed a seven-year deal for $70.85 million before
last season, said he knew his life was about to undergo a
significant change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``In the past, I've been pretty much
all basketball, stressing myself out with that. She'll provide
balance in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   GET IT GOING: Glen Rice is supposed to be the outside threat
that helps to take pressure off Shaquille O'Neal inside, but thus
far in the postseason, the career .449-percent field-goal shooter
has hit on just 43 of 111 field goals (.387).
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have gotten past Sacramento and Phoenix with Rice off
his game, but if he doesn't return to form in the Western
Conference Finals, they can't expect to have the same success
against the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a series Glen is going to have to be a key,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, however, isn't inclined to call plays to get Rice
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't do anything so extraordinary that takes us out of
what we do well,'' he said. ``We'll expect Glen to have the ability
to find his own game at some level in our offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get a rhythm (against the Suns), and rhythm is
important. Now that Rick (Fox) is back playing a good role, I think
we can shorten Glen's minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S A MIND GAME: Portland forward Scottie Pippen acted like a
guy who knew Jackson all too well when he heard Jackson's comments
that if Pippen didn't lead the Blazers in the Western Conference
Finals, no one would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah?'' Pippen said. ``He's just trying to get into my
head. We're not going to buy into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Jackson wouldn't respond to Blazers coach Mike
Dunleavy's early cry for more fouls to be called on O'Neal. Said
Dunleavy on Wednesday: ``If Shaq is allowed to zone up like he was
doing in the Phoenix series _ I think I counted 57 times _ and if
he is allowed to push guys out of the way and gain his position,
it's going to be tough for anybody to beat them. But if it's called
the way it needs to be called, then we're going to have a good
shot.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
