 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, May 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STRESS-WOMEN (Undated) _ For more than a half century,
scientific gospel has held that animals, including humans, respond
to stress by preparing to do battle or to flee, a physiological
syndrome commonly known as ``fight or flight.'' But in a newly
published report, a group of researchers asserts that females often
show a very different reaction to stress, one that revolves around
nurturing and seeking the support of others rather than aggression
or escape. This ``tend and befriend'' response, seen both in humans
and in animal species, may be based in hormonal differences between
the sexes, the researchers argue. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTRONOMY-AGENDA (Undated) _ A panel of astronomers, whose
recommendations are often followed, unveils its 10 year plan for
astronomy, which includes construction of a new giant telescope
that would be twice as big as Hubble. The priorties for the next 10
years include looking for earth-sized planets around other suns and
launching a fleet of new xray satellites to search for black holes.
By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIPPER-GORE (Washington) _ More than a decade after she became
the very public face of parental outrage over the content of rock
lyrics, Tipper Gore is struggling with how much of a public face
she should be in the presidential campaign of her husband. In some
ways she seems to want to be the anti-Hillary, standing back in the
crowd as other women led the Million Moms March last weekend, or
avoiding altogether important campaign events of her husband. By
Katharine Q. Seeley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT3,11) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
