   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-EXPLAIN _ An explainer on Social Security, with
particular attention to these questions: How did the pension
program get into trouble? Why is everyone talking about fixes? Will
separate accounts work? What are other ways to put the program back
on track? By Richard W. Stevesnon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-TECH-TALENT (Manila, Philippines) _ Maybe it was a
couple of 20-something Filipinos who created the rogue e-mail
program that disabled computer systems on May 4. Maybe it wasn't.
But there is no doubt that a couple of young Filipinos played a big
part in rubbing the bug out. They are part of a growing pool of
high-technology Philippine talent that has become attractive to
employers in Europe and the United States. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT-WORLDCOM (Washington) _ The staff of the Justice
Department's antitrust division recently recommended that the
government block the proposed $115 billion merger of WorldCom Inc.
and Sprint, people involved in the review said Thursday. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPKORN-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Stanley Shopkorn has been a
masterful stock trader for longer than many of today's money
managers have been alive. Now he is sailing away from the stock
market. But you can bet he'll be back. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is increasingly common for
marketers to focus advertising on teenagers and 20-something
consumers in the hope of developing shopping patterns that become
lifelong buying habits. Now the ABC television network is joining
the ranks of advertisers like Kraft Foods and Procter &AMP; Gamble with
an ambitious campaign intended to stimulate demand among consumers
16 to 24 for four of its own ``products'': daytime soap operas. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
