<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FOOD FLOWS FREELY AT DOT-COMS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One more reason why you're sadly missing the
boat if you're not working for a dot-com: Eats.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned Thursday that companies traditionally supply their
employees with coffee, free or cheap, and that's it.
</P>
<P>
   I forgot that there is a whole new world of new-age companies
where the workers work at such a frenetic hummingbird pace that
they require constant snackage.
</P>
<P>
   So these stupendously rich companies supply the food and drink,
free. Eric Dew, an engineer at Fire-Drop Inc. in Redwood Shores,
says the bosses there provide free coffee and tea, and every kind
of pop, sport drink and fruit juice you could dream of.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even some beer, which can be imbibed during work hours.
And they cater lunch. And they cater dinner Monday through
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday evening employees don't need a free dinner because
they've made enough that week in salary and stock options to retire
and hire live-in chefs.
</P>
<P>
   WE NEED a name for the genetic mutants who don't drink coffee,
other than ``Mormons.''
</P>
<P>
   We need the no-coffee equivalent of ``vegetarians'' or
``teetotalers.'' Michael Conkin suggests: 1. Antimochans. 2. The
differently hot-beveraged. 3. Nojoes.
</P>
<P>
   WE BUILT this city on rock 'n' roll. Now pack up your guitar and
get outta town.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message being sent to more than 100 local bands and
artists who rent rehearsal space in the Art Explosion building,
17th and Potrero.
</P>
<P>
   The owner leases the building to two guys who invented the Art
Explosion, a nonprofit, and they in turn rent spaces at
below-market rates to starving artists and bands.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? It's eviction time. And the Art Explosion and their
tenants are fighting it, raising money for the legal battle with a
concert at the Paradise Lounge a week from Sunday, 2 to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When they were all served their 30-day notices, someone slapped
a sign on the building's front door that reads simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``evicted.com''
</P>
<P>
   A FELLOW named Ryan Brooks was hired as the city's new director
of administrative affairs. He was hired by phone, and word spread
around City Hall of the new Irish chief.
</P>
<P>
   When the mayor met Brooks at a staff meeting, Brown said, ``You
can't be Ryan Brooks, you're supposed to be Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks happens to be African American.
</P>
<P>
   And when Brooks, whose duties include supervision of City Hall
janitors, introduced himself to two of the janitors, one said to
the other in Spanish, ``He's the new `Irish' boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks also speaks fluent Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   LEAFING THROUGH a home-listings magazine, ``Harmon Homes,'' Anne
Sawyer-Scharf came upon a beauty of a Victorian in Placerville.
</P>
<P>
   Among the home's features: ``double butler panties.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what that means, so I'll check with the experts at
Victorian's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   WE'RE NO. 1 ... In croquet. Phoenix teenage croquet phenom
Jacques Fournier defends his world title Saturday morning against
27 other wicked wrist-flicking wicket slickers at the World Croquet
Championship at Sonoma-Cutrer Vineyards cq &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Fournier of Phoenix has only a slight edge over local hero Jerry
Stark of the Meadowood Resort.
</P>
<P>
   It could get rowdy because festivities include wine tasting, a
wine auction, dancing, etc., all to benefit kids' charities.
</P>
<P>
   Fun fact: Croquet was so hot in old Hollywood that Harpo Marx
built a $50,000 temperature-controlled room to store his mallets.
Imagine how he must have pampered his balls.
</P>
<P>
   A THIEF crept into the 1,2,3 Wash &AMP; Dry on Hyde and Pacific and
made off with a dryer full of Gwyneth Borden's colored clothes,
ignoring her two loads of whites.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has probably watched too many cop TV shows would
do, Gwyneth called the police. They were nice enough to come out
and take a report, though they decided against having a sketch
artist draw a composite of the missing laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the theft may be the work of the same person who
for years has been sneaking into Laundromats and homes throughout
the Bay Area stealing single socks.
</P>
<P>
   MEMO TO Muni driver Ted Helman, who found and returned a wallet
with $1,300 in cash:
</P>
<P>
   Several of this paper's readers kicked in a few bucks as a
thank-you for your honesty, so please call to collect your reward.
If you don't _ this not being a dot-com _ I'll blow the loot in the
hallway candy machine.
</P>
<P>
   COSMETIC SURGERY on animals may soon be forbidden in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Abney wonders: ``Have they talked to the animals? My
cat has been begging me for years for a boob job. My daughter's
hamster is getting hormone treatments to become a beaver. I am just
my bulldog's guardian, and it should be his call if he wants to
have liposuction on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   HE COULDN'T resist the sales pitch of the Street Sheet hawker,
so Rad Dewey bought a copy from the guy who was calling out:
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy the Sheet! We're the only paper that didn't bribe
Willie!''
</P>
</TEXT>
