<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-SOCSEC-SENATORS-SFCHR     05-19 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-SENATORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA'S SENATORS ASSAIL BUSH'S PLAN FOR SOCIAL SECURITY  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer
entered the election-year war over Social Security Thursday,
calling Texas Gov. George W. Bush's plan for personal retirement
accounts a ``riverboat gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the phrases Vice President Al Gore frequently uses to
attack Bush, his GOP opponent in the presidential race, Boxer and
Feinstein called the proposed accounts ``a risky scheme'' that
would hurt women.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein and Boxer argued that private accounts would reduce
benefits, and that women are particularly vulnerable because they
tend to live longer than men, earn less and rely more on Social
Security as their sole source of income.
</P>
<P>
   The two Californians led their female Democratic colleagues in
the Senate in praising Gore's alternative, which calls for
buttressing Social Security with general tax revenues when it
starts to run short of money in about 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Social Security proposal, announced Monday, would allow
people to invest an undetermined amount of their 12.4 percent
Social Security payroll tax in personal retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when your investment goes bad?'' Boxer asked.
``Who pays? If it's the retirees, they will be ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   If the government pays, she said, ``we'll all be ruined because
we'll see an S&AMP;L-like bailout.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, who noted that she used to be a stockbroker, said Social
Security was always intended as a foundation for people's
retirement, and one should ``never mess with the foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Both Parties Aim at the Issue
</P>
<P>
   The entry of Boxer and Feinstein into the campaign &LR; 
 &LR; election-year debate over Social Security highlights the emphasis
both parties are putting on the issue, with Bush and Gore
coordinating their efforts with allies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer called Gore's plan ``safe and sensible.'' ``Vice President
Gore's plan keeps Social Security solvent and thriving for the next
50 years, in contrast to George Bush's risky scheme,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Barbara Mikulski of Maryland declared, ``This is
the first in a series of press conferences that will go from now to
November, where Democratic women will stand up for what's right and
stand up for truth.'' Mikulski urged voters to elect Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein and Boxer, both first elected to the Senate in the
1992 ``Year of the Woman,'' led the attack on the Bush plan, saying
it would endanger women's financial security.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said that if personal Social Security accounts are
allowed, ``the big, big losers are women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply believe that it is not necessary to privatize Social
Security at this time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization _ the shifting of a government program to the
private sector _ has become a loaded term in the debate, brandished
by opponents and avoided by supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has been short on the details of his plan, it
would allow individuals to privatize a portion of their Social
Security accounts. He has said that anyone who wanted to stay with
the existing system could, and the expectation is that many would
opt for the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advocates private accounts as a way to help people earn
more from their payroll taxes than Social Security's current 1.88
percent. Bush says the accounts would especially help minorities
and young workers build wealth and pass it on to their children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not release enough specifics to determine to what
extent, if any, private accounts might remedy Social Security's
projected funding shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein and Boxer argued that private accounts would reduce
benefits, and that women are particularly vulnerable because they
tend to live longer than men, earn less, and rely more on Social
Security as their sole source of income.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if or how Bush's plan would reduce benefits for
younger workers, since much would depend on how the accounts were
structured.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Rassell, an economist from the Economic Policy Institute
who joined the press conference, said women caring for children
``have less time to watch the stock market'' and so would see
little benefit from personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tanner, who heads the Social Security privatization
project for the libertarian Cato Institute, argued that Feinstein
and Boxer have it wrong. Tanner said many women lose under the
current system.
</P>
<P>
   That's because widows are entitled to half of their husband's
Social Security benefits. If that turns out to be more than the
benefits due them from their own work, the widows' own
contributions to Social Security are erased.
</P>
<P>
   ``About one-third of all women end up having their taxes go for
naught under that formula,'' Tanner said.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner also charged that it is Gore's plan that is risky,
because it would only shift more bonds to the Social Security trust
fund without adding any cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a promise that when the debt comes due, taxpayers
pick up the bill,'' Tanner said, ``but there is absolutely no
guarantee of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Current projections indicate that Social Security benefit
payments will begin to exceed revenue in about 15 years, and that
by 2037, the program will be able to pay just two-thirds to
three-quarters of promised benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal is modeled on a plan put forth by President
Clinton about a year ago. The Congressional Budget Office, the
General Accounting Office and other budget experts described the
proposal as an accounting maneuver that had no effect on the
government's ability to pay promised benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore contends, however, that his plan would pay down the
national debt and transfer any future interest savings to Social
Security. If the debt is paid down, then it will be easier for the
government to pay benefits in the future, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is in any way a risk,'' Boxer said. ``It is
a very prudent plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
