<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-CHAMPIONSHIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD DAY FOR PAC-10 AT NCAA TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Another women's tennis match, another gut check
for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Bruins get to play another day against yet
another opponent they have faced.
</P>
<P>
   To simplify: Ninth-ranked UCLA defeated No.8 Texas 5-2 on
Thursday in the NCAA championships to earn a quarterfinal match
with No.1 Stanford at 2 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great day for the Pacific-10 Conference, as all five
teams reached today's quarterfinals. In addition to UCLA and
Stanford (a 5-1 winner over No.14 Northwestern), other winners
included 12th-ranked USC, which beat No.32 LSU 5-2; 11th-ranked
Arizona State, which beat No.6 Duke 5-2; and No.5 Cal, which beat
No.10 Vanderbilt 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, USC faces No.2 Georgia at 11 a.m., Cal faces No.3
Wake Forest at 5 p.m. and ASU plays No.4 Florida at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity breeds more familiarity at the NCAAs. Fifteen of the
top 18 ranked teams are here, including UCLA and Texas, who already
have faced each other once this season and two other times at the
NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, the Bruins were asked to look inside and find that
extra drive to overcome the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, the Bruins failed, losing in the third round
and quarterfinals. On March 4, UCLA trailed 4-2 after singles and
swept doubles for a 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, senior Elizabeth Schmidt at fifth singles showed
the most intestinal fortitude in helping UCLA end Texas' 17-match
win streak. She lost 6-3 to Kaysie Smashey before rebounding to
take the match 6-3, 6-0. Then Schmidt teamed with freshman Abigail
Spears and won the one doubles match 8-5 needed after leading 7-2.
Matches end after a team wins five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing the first set, I could have gotten down,'' Schmidt said
of her singles win, ``but I thought to myself, `This is my senior
year. I don't want this to be my last match. Every match could be
my last match.' I had to dig deep. I got confidence in the second
set, and that carried over in the third.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of gut-check tennis that UCLA (17-8) has played
all season, starting with a home loss to Arizona to having to deal
with the loss of top singles player Sara Walker _ who missed a
sizable portion to mourn the death of her mother _ to adjusting to
Walker's return.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it has prepared the Bruins for the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Catherine Hawley and Spears' easy wins, Texas (24-6)
pushed the Bruins in every match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone fought hard,'' Schmidt said. ``That's UCLA tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of pride and we're playing with a lot of
heart,'' said UCLA coach Stella Sampras. ``We're playing our best
tennis now. This is the best we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (18-8) didn't have to fight as hard, but the Trojans got key
wins from second singles Veronika Safarova and third singles Jewel
Peterson. Safarova, a senior, lost the first set to Ana Paula Mores
6-3 before rallying for a 6-2, 6-1 decision. Peterson, a freshman
ranked 17th, won a first-set tiebreaker over unranked Fernanda
Tsucamoto and then breezed in the second set 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that stage, the match was extremely close,'' USC coach
Richard Gallien said. ``The momentum shifted our way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans and Bruins hope it stays their way in today's
quarterfinals. UCLA has two 7-2 losses to the Cardinal; USC lost
5-4 to Georgia in the NCAA Indoors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
