r s BC-TEN-NCAA-NOTEBOOK-LAD     05-19 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO (FOOT) FAULTING THIS FAMILY RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Karen Huebner doesn't doubt her parents love
her, but she put them to the test when she took a job as USC
assistant women's tennis coach.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is a family steeped in UCLA tradition, so much so that her
mother, Gretchen, a UCLA song girl in the 1950s, owns nothing
cardinal and gold and still performs the pompon routines whenever
she watches UCLA score a touchdown on television. She also was
among the many who painted Tommy Trojan blue and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Huebner's father, Larry, was UCLA's tennis captain and led the
Bruins to the 1953 national tennis championship.
</P>
<P>
   Huebner herself captained UCLA for three years and led them to
the 1981 Association of Intercollegiate Athletics for Women
national title.
</P>
<P>
   When she landed the USC post, Larry was thrilled _ he turned on
his pro-USC family to become a Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom said, `Are you sure?''' Huebner said. ``She couldn't
understand me rooting for a Trojan team.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Larry and Gretchen started going to USC tennis functions
and rooting (gulp) for USC tennis. They even drive from their
Fresno home to watch. Every other sport, however, is off limits.
Gretchen is of the ``My favorite teams are UCLA and anyone playing
USC'' mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood is thicker than water,'' Huebner said. ``I learned the
depth of the love my parents have for me.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ADVANTAGE: One reason Southern schools have won six of the
last eight national titles is the players spend countless hours
practicing and competing in great humidity. At these NCAA
championships, nine of the final 16 schools are from below the
Mason-Dixon Line.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the first day, just three won. Of these, only Florida
didn't beat another Southern team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams from the South play tough,'' USC coach Richard Gallien
said. ``With the weather and humidity, it's no place for the
weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, however, there is no humidity. Instead, there are winds
and aggressive teams that come to the net instead of staying on the
baseline to outlast an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Staying back is what Duke, LSU and Vanderbilt did against
Arizona State, USC and Cal. That's why the three Pac-10 teams are
playing today.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pressure situations, we tend to sit back and wait for our
opponent to make a mistake,'' said Duke coach Jamie Ashworth, whose
team lost 5-2 to ASU. ``People need to see we need to be more
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashworth said the Pac-10 and Southeastern conferences are the
two strongest. Which is stronger could be determined today. USC
faces Georgia and ASU meets Florida. Cal already beat an SEC team
and now plays Wake Forest of the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   NOT NERVES OF STEEL: The ASU-Duke match was closer than the
score indicated. Although the Sun Devils led 4-2 after the singles
matches, Duke led 7-6 in one doubles set and trailed 7-6 in
another.
</P>
<P>
   ASU coach Sheila McInerney couldn't take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to win the lottery or marry a millionaire so I don't
have to go through this,'' she said after her team won. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9624 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-19 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT sits on a bookshelf, inside a souvenir glass from the Nagano
Olympics in the room I use for an office.
</P>
<P>
   And it could have been Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   A pingpong ball, bright red and bearing the words ``Houston
Rockets'' in white block letters, is a link to the past of the NBA
draft lottery and to the story of a franchise that has benefited as
much from good fortune as from hard work.
</P>
<P>
   How many careers and championships would have been changed if on
May 17, 1992, that one ball could have jumped out of the hopper and
sent Shaq to Houston?
</P>
<P>
   Would there even be a debate about a downtown arena? Would the
words Kelvin Cato and $42 million ever be mentioned in the same
sentence?
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Sunday's televised schmaltz, where the only thing
missing is Regis Philbin, it is the Rockets' sole appearance in the
draft lottery and the only time luck failed them.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Patterson, by that time club president emeritus and a kind
of 6-3 rabbit's foot, was the Rockets' official witness to the
actual lottery prior to the TV show to announce the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we were the only team with red, I figured our ball would
be pretty easy to pick out,'' Patterson said that day. ``But when I
looked into the container, all I could see was blue from Orlando,
Charlotte and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept looking and looking, and I couldn't find it. That
little SOB was buried all the way down there at the bottom of the
pile, gasping for air. It couldn't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   So Shaq went to Disney World, the Rockets chose Robert Horry
with the 11th pick in the draft, and since then the lottery
procedure has evolved into something slightly more complicated than
the genetic code for DNA.
</P>
<P>
   But back in another century, before computer combinations and
weighted odds and even pingpong balls, in a simpler age, there was
just a coin flip.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly 17 years ago today in New York that the late NBA
commissioner Larry O'Brien tossed a silver dollar and it plopped
onto the carpet, giving the Rockets the draft rights to Ralph
Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie, it's heads,'' O'Brien said calmly to then-club owner
Charlie Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson raced across the room to plant a kiss on the owner's
cheek. Thomas embraced his youngest daughter Tracy, who had told
him to make the call of ``heads,'' and in the back of the room Jim
Foley, then the club's media relations director, let out a whoop,
danced an Irish jig and tore away his coat, tie and shirt
Superman-style to reveal a blue T-shirt with orange letters that
read: RALPH!
</P>
<P>
   It was the payoff after a franchise-worst 14-68 season and the
heady culmination of hours of ritual and superstition. The Rockets'
New York traveling party had spent the night before the coin flip
in Jimmy Weston's Pub on 54th Street getting ready.
</P>
<P>
   Foley had brought a ``lucky'' Irish coin, and the group took
turns dipping it in a glass of Irish whiskey. Foley noticed a clock
of Ireland _ with a dozen coins designating the hours _ fixed to
one wall by a heavy chain and mused that it might work well as a
charm. Weston sent out for bolt cutters and had the clock taken
down, and Foley carried it under one arm the next day to the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   The group returned to Weston's to celebrate, toasting with
bottles of Dom Perignon champagne that were being charged by phone
from many of Thomas' friends in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never imagine ever doing this again,'' said a
jubiliant Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, he was back. This time for a coin tossed by
new commissioner David Stern, with a young Akeem Olajuwon as the
plum in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The traveling party had grown. But all of the charms were back _
the coin, the whiskey, the clock, Foley and Patterson, who as GM in
Milwaukee also had won the flip that sent Kareem Abdul-Jabbar to
the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   This time Portland owner Larry Weinberg made the call:
``tails.'' It came up heads.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas beamed again. Patterson pumped his fist again. Foley
stripped again. The T-shirt said: AKEEM! Though he also was wearing
another one that said: MICHAEL! As in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it again next year!'' Foley shouted.
</P>
<P>
   But they changed the rules, replaced the coin toss with the
lottery, brought in envelopes, computers and a game show.
</P>
<P>
   On that day in Secaucus, N.J., Patterson reached into his
pocket, pulled out the red pingpong ball and tossed it to me.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how what might have been history came to sit on a
bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the no-good little SOB,'' he said. ``But I'm still
unbeaten in coin flips.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
