<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HERSKOW     05-19 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
BALTIMORE _ This is a city famed for its crab cakes and black-eyed
Susans, as the birthplace of Babe Ruth and the home of the National
Museum of Dentistry. This week it becomes the showplace for
America's sporting gentry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That is, seven of the eight horses in the field for the
Preakness Stakes will be competing for place and show as Fusaichi
Pegasus romps away with the second gem in the Triple Crown. The
handicappers do not see a contestant who can match the tools of the
Kentucky Derby champion. His price _ 3-5 on Thursday _ could drop
to a dollar by race time. This is no way to make an honest living,
betting five bucks to make six.
</P>
<P>
   If Fusaichi Pegasus can weave his way through a wall of 19 in
the Derby, not once needing the sting of the whip to urge him on,
what can the Sieve Seven possibly do to stop him? The best hope is
the smallness of the field itself. Maybe he'll get lonely and bored
and distracted.
</P>
<P>
   Those searching for a weakness may have to be content with this
one: He may be Superhorse, and the favorite to end the Triple Crown
famine, but he didn't get here on his own wings. He needed an
airplane, unlike the Pegasus of Greek mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the ground, Saturday's coming attraction seemed less a
horse race than a fox hunt. In this chase, Neil Drysdale, the Hall
of Fame trainer, is the fox, pursued by writers who want him to
regale them with Bob Baffert-type quips and fence with them like D.
Wayne Lukas. The tall, frosty Englishman does neither. This time
the fox is winning.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were still peeved Thursday after Drysdale had avoided
a mob scene at Pimlico, ordering a van to Barn 7 and standing on
the running board as he gave the driver directions. The maneuver
enabled his colt to walk down a ramp directly into his stall. A
public ceremony planned by track officials went begging in the
process. Casual fans may take the position that if you've seen one
barn you have seen them all. But at Pimlico, Barn 40, on the
eastern side, is reserved for the winner of the Kentucky Derby, and
the area in front had been paved to accommodate the crowd waiting
for this year's champ.
</P>
<P>
   When the unflappable Brit was asked, with obvious sarcasm, if
barricades would be used to keep the media and tourists away, he
didn't bat an eye. ``Not that I know of.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that he had not deliberately stiffed the press.
When the van pulled up to the stable area, a race had just started.
``I didn't want to unload and have him walk by the track,''
explained the 52-year-old trainer. Fusaichi Pegasus has his quirky
side, and there seemed to be no reason to tempt fate.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale's decision to pick a site on the backside, almost as
far from the other entries as possible, was criticized by the media
and some insiders as undemocratic, even unrepublican. In a nice
counterpoint, Baffert moved Captain Steve, who finished eighth in
the Derby, into Barn 40. He had qualified for that location before
with Silver Charm and Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast was too tempting to resist, so reporters asked the
playful Baffert what he thought of Drysdale's isolation. ``Neil's
got his own agenda,'' he said. ``I'm not getting into that.'' But
Bob clearly misses the spotlight. ``It's lonely at the bottom,'' he
confided.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much room left on the bandwagon, but a handful of
dissenters insist that the Japanese-owned colt can be beaten, among
them Lukas, whose High Yield finished 15th in the Derby. ``I don't
think we should anoint him yet,'' said Lukas, referring to the
Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The second choice, Red Bullet, one of three entries who skipped
the Kentucky Derby, is fresh and rested and earned respect by
finishing second to the Big Horse in the Wood Memorial. The others
are Hugh Hefner, owned by a friend of the publisher of Playboy, and
Snuck In, the runner-up in the Arkansas Derby and owned by
Houston's Ackerley brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no colt has skipped the Derby and won the Preakness since
1983, and 71 have tried. Ed Nahem, Hefner's pal, couldn't care
less. His sights are on the place or show money and the prestige
such a finish would bring his breeding operation. What this
achievement would do for the original Hugh Hefner, a prominent
figure himself in the breeding culture, isn't clear.
</P>
<P>
   Hef's namesake is starting on the pole, with Hal's Hope on the
outside, the two longest shots at 20-1. Which brings us to another
example of the optimism so dear to this sport. Hal's Hope is also
named after his owner and trainer, the 88-year-old Harold Rose, who
was not discouraged when his horse finished 16th in the Derby. Nor
is he disturbed by the fact that Hal's Hope has a new cut on his
left hind leg to go with the ones he picked up in the Derby. He
also has developed an unsightly skin rash and at midweek
accidentally conked his head on a beam in his stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insignificant,'' said Rose. ``He's feeling so good he doesn't
know what to do with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
