<HEADER>
A9626 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PAPER-NOSALE-LADN     05-19 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-NOSALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAILY NEWS OWNER SAYS PAPER ISN'T UP FOR SALE
</HEADLINE>
 (Resending to correct typo in lede.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Daily News of Los Angeles is not for sale and
there are no plans to sell it to the rival Los Angeles Times now or
in the future, the newspaper's owner said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Some media reports Thursday suggested that the Times was likely
to buy the paper in the future because of an option it holds,
despite antitrust laws that would forbid such a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion arose after the Times published a story pointing
out that its parent, the Times Mirror Co., holds a two-year-old
option to buy the Daily News if it's put up for sale by
Denver-based MediaNews Group, owner of the San Fernando
Valley-based paper.
</P>
<P>
   William Dean Singleton, president and chief executive officer of
MediaNews Group, said that the option, part of a complex financial
deal, could be exercised only if he agreed to sell the paper, which
he doesn't plan to do.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that federal officials have said they would
not approve such a sale to the Times because of antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said the $2.4 million option provision was part of a
$50 million loan package from Times Mirror, which was used to
finance the Daily News' purchase for $130 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have to be willing to sell and the Justice Department
would have to agree,'' Singleton said of the option, which was
disclosed in Securities and Exchange Commission documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I wanted to sell the Daily News to the Times _ which I
don't _ it would be legally impossible. So there is no exposure,''
Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Times Mirror could not sell the option without first
offering it to MediaNews, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither executives with Times Mirror nor its new ownership, the
Chicago-based Tribune Co., returned calls for comments.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company issued a statement: ``There is an option to
buy the Daily News that was part of a broad financial agreement
reached in 1998 between Times Mirror and Garden State Newspapers.
The earliest it would be exercisable would be 2003 at which time it
would be subject to all necessary government approvals.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal centered on the loan, and the papers later purchased
California Independent Postal Service, which distributes
pre-printed ads in the papers and to the homes of nonsubscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror and MediaNews have a long history of working
together. Times Mirror helped finance MediaNews' 1986 acquisition
of the Dallas Times Herald with a $60 million loan and the 1987
purchase of The Denver Post with a $70 million loan. Both papers
were owned by Times Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   If Singleton decides to sell the Daily News between 2003 and
2010, the option allows Times Mirror first right to buy it at a
fair market value. But Singleton said Justice Department officials
investigated the two companies' financial partnership and objected
only to the option provision allowing Times Mirror to buy the Daily
News, saying it would violate antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department did a one-year investigation, and they
blessed everything we were doing, but they said they would not
entertain the Times exercising the option,'' Singleton said.
``We've been told it couldn't be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department antitrust officials could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ike Massey, Daily News president, chief executive officer and
publisher, said the deal between Times Mirror and MediaNews'
predecessor company, Garden State Newspapers, requires both parties
to agree to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times Mirror can't force the sale of the Daily News; there
must be a willing buyer and a willing seller,'' Massey said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms, Times Mirror could sell the option back to
MediaNews at any time during the seven-year option window. If it's
still in force by 2010, MediaNews would have to repurchase it.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said he will buy the option back at the first
opportunity, noting its payback value is tied to the paper's value.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to buy it back today,'' Singleton said, citing the
Daily News' overall appreciation and steadily climbing performance.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton predicted Times Mirror will make an ``outstanding
return'' on its investment in the Daily News as the loan, including
the option, is retired.
</P>
<P>
   For the six-month period ending March 31, the Daily News had
average daily circulation of 200,798 and Sunday circulation of
212,434. Singleton has solidified his Southern California position
by creating the Los Angeles Newspapers Group, MediaNews Group's
largest operating division.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Daily News, the group includes the San Gabriel
Valley Tribune, Long Beach Press-Telegram, Pasadena Star-News,
Whittier Daily News, Inland Valley Daily Bulletin, San Bernardino
County Sun, Redlands Daily Facts and Lompoc Record.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said that while he has no immediate plans for more
acquisitions in the area, he continues to be interested in
expanding his operations, now the seventh-largest newspaper group
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Massey said Times Mirror and the Times have no control of nor
influence on the operations or contents of the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Daily News has outperformed expectations at the time
of its purchase. ``For every circulation reporting period since the
purchase, the Daily News' circulation has grown both daily and on
Sunday,'' Massey said. ``The Daily News will remain the voice of
the San Fernando Valley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9629 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r v BC-COUNCIL-POWERGRAB-LAD     05-19 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNCIL-POWERGRAB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR ACCUSES COUNCIL OF UNDERMINING CHARTER REFORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the sharpest clash yet over the new City
Charter, Mayor Richard Riordan's office accused the City Council on
Thursday of subverting the will of voters by trying to strip the
mayor of lobbying responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   With millions of dollars in state and federal funding at stake,
the council is set to consider an ordinance today that would
restore lobbying responsibility to Chief Legislative Analyst Ron
Deaton, titularly the council's top bureaucrat but widely regarded
as the most powerful figure in City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The new voter-approved charter that goes into effect July 1
stripped Deaton of his state and federal lobbying role, but the
proposed ordinance _ which officials say he crafted _ would restore
it and expand his power in some ways.
</P>
<P>
   An outside legal analysis commissioned by Riordan and released
Thursday found the proposal is ``constitutionally suspect'' and
undermines the new charter's goal of making the council primarily a
legislative body and giving the mayor expanded authority to manage
city departments.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Glushon, a member of the city's elected Charter Reform
Commission, said the proposal was a power grab since the reform
commission felt it was important that the mayor be the city's main
representative at the state and federal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council needs to listen to the will of the voters,''
Glushon said. ``When someone in Sacramento or Washington wants to
hear from the city of Los Angeles, they look to the Mayor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politics. The mayor wants more authority and the council
doesn't want to give any mayor more authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Kelly Martin said the council was attempting to
usurp the mayor's authority to preserve Deaton's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of millions of dollars each year come to us from the
state and federal government,'' Martin said. ``Making sure we get
our fair share is very crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Deaton was out of town and unavailable to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a six-page analysis, attorney Dale E. Bonner of Hogan &AMP;
Hartson said that instead of developing a broad set of state and
federal legislative policies annually, the proposal would include
other local government bodies as part of the council's authority.
</P>
<P>
   It also states that Deaton, the council's top adviser, would be
empowered to shape guidelines for the council to take positions on
almost any issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Charter ... prohibits the Council having any
administrative control over the various functions of City
government,'' Bonner wrote. ``The ordinance is constitutionally
suspect and would be subject to legal challenge if adopted by the
Council and signed into law in its present form.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's opinion states that the ordinance expands Deaton's role
in intergovernmental relations and violates the mandatory
separation of powers mandated by the new charter.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The charter) vests in the Mayor the exclusive power and duty
to represent the City in intergovernmental relations in accordance
with city policy and supervise the City's intergovernmental
relations function,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The report angered some council members who sit on a charter
reform committee that already approved the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It troubles me that the mayor went to some outside source when
the legal adviser for the city is the city attorney,'' said
Councilwoman Laura Chick, chairwoman of the council's Charter
Implementation Committee. ``The city attorney has carefully
contemplated this and advised the council during a variety of
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Qualls, a spokesman for the City Attorney's Office, said
the proposal is being reviewed but declined comment on the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The latest sparring match is just one in a string of tense
debates between the mayor and council over how to implement the new
City Charter, approved by voters to try to make local government
more responsive and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, Deaton represents the city in
Sacramento and Washington on a regular basis. Under the new
charter, the mayor would become the city's chief representative
when lobbying for state and federal funds for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Feuer, a member of the Charter Implementation
Committee, said he will support postponing the vote on the matter
until further review by the city attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be sure that we have all the facts before us,''
Feuer said.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said, however, that she is comfortable with the ordinance
as it stands and that the city attorney already reviewed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can ask three or four different people, if you look around
for them, and get three or four different opinions on what the
charter says. That's why we rely on our city attorney,'' Chick
said.
</P>
<P>
   George Kieffer, chairman of the city's appointed Charter Reform
Commission, said the ordinance is ``in a very gray area'' and that
he plans to review the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may or may not be good policy, but it doesn't necessarily
mean it's inconsistent with the charter,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
