<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 04:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9639 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ALARM-`E'-TERROR-IHT-     05-19 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALARM-`E'-TERROR-IHT-RESEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BE VERY FRIGHTENED,' EXPERTS SAY OF E-TERRORISM POTENTIAL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from May 16)   (This compelling 975-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By LEE DEMBART  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PARIS -- This month's ``love bug'' and last year's ``Melissa''
computer virus were child's play compared with the damage that
could be done with existing technologies, many experts say.
</P>
<P>
   A rogue state, terrorist or other malefactor could wreak havoc,
not with a nuclear or biological weapon but with a computer virus
that could cause massive disruptions or worse throughout the world,
these experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maliciousness of a virus is not limited by technical
obstructions but by the inventiveness of the perpetrator,'' said
Leonard Adleman, Henry Salvatori professor of computer science at
the University of Southern California, who has been studying
computer viruses for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would predict that we haven't seen the worst possible of
them,'' Adleman said by telephone from Los Angeles. ``I don't see
any obstructions to a really bad virus coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he said, ``The Internet has no perfect defense, and
it can never have a perfect defense.'' In other words, anti-virus
programs can only protect against known viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world should be very frightened,'' said Adleman, who in
the 1970s was one of the inventors of RSA cryptography, which has
become the world's leading computer encryption system.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, at least, it appears that the world's most
critical computers _ those that run electricity generators and the
banking system, for example _ are immune to e-mail-borne viruses
such as Melissa and the love bug, which was sent as an attachment
to an electronic-mail message with the subject line ``ILOVEYOU.''
</P>
<P>
   The computers that perform such key functions are almost all
based on the Unix operating system rather than on Windows, and they
have a much higher degree of security protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people being affected are the users of the systems rather
than the basic infrastructure,'' said Chris Goggans, director of
operations at Security Design International in Annandale, Va., and
London. As a result, he said, the computer virus attacks so far
have been ``annoying but not catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed, however, that they could have been a lot worse. If
the person who had released the ``love'' virus had been ``more
malicious,'' he said, ``It could have caused real problems. There
are certainly ways to cause real nastiness to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While all of the attacks to date have been ``perpetrated by
amateurs,'' Goggans said, the speed and scope of the love virus
were eye-opening. ``I don't know of a single place that that virus
didn't arrive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone can write 50 lines of Visual Basic code and make
that happen _ someone with a dedicated target and lots of resources
_ what can they accomplish?'' he asked. ``Given the fact that the
vandals can do so much, it stands to reason that if you have high
motivation and a powerful tool, you can do much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Goggans said it would difficult to imagine a successful virus
attack against a basic-infrastructure computer. But in the ongoing
cat-and-mouse game between computer systems on the one hand and
hackers and vandals on the other, he said, the attackers have
consistently done things that had been considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Goggans added that, in testing the computer security of its
clients, Security Design International had broken into supposedly
secure computers of banking systems, power plants, hospitals and
major car companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the successful viruses so far have been delivered by
e-mail and required the recipient to open an attachment. The
``ILOVEYOU'' virus exploited a feature of the widely used Microsoft
Outlook e-mail program that is not available in other e-mail
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ways to send viruses over the Internet besides
e-mail, Goggans said. For example, it might be possible to hide a
malicious program in a Web-site link so that when someone clicked
on the link, a virus would infect the person's computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not that hard to do,'' he said. ``It would be very
conceivable to hide something in there. In terms of what's going to
happen next, that might be the next delivery mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Until late last year, it had been thought that for an e-mail
virus to infect a computer, the user had to open an attachment. But
then a virus called ``Bubbleboy'' spread, and all that it required
was that the user highlight the e-mail on the computer screen. No
attachment was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of damage that viruses can inflict was demonstrated in
April 1999, when the ``Chernobyl'' virus destroyed the contents of
an infected computer's hard drive. By comparison, the love virus
only tampered with picture and music files.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the genie is out of the bottle. The world knows how
vulnerable computers are, and some people are talking about it,
even if they are not actually doing anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can bring the entire West to its knees,'' Vladimir
Zhirinovsky, the Russian ultranationalist, said recently, according
to the newspaper Kommersant. ``Let us put viruses into their secret
programs like we did recently, and they will not be able to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A global assault of this kind would not require a sophisticated
and expensive delivery system. It could take just one computer
connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Given the periodic and increasingly destructive computer viruses
that the world has seen in the past decade, the question now
appears to be not whether but when this kind of attack will occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any reasonable terrorist organization worth its salt should be
able to do this,'' said a leading computer security expert who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the only foolproof way to protect a computer from
new viruses on the Internet was to disconnect it completely from
networks. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 975-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
