<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9779 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-CROOKS-HN     05-19 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CROOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANOTHER SMALL TIME FLICK FROM WOODY ALLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the more revealing bits in the new Woody Allen movie _
which, incidentally, is comprised of bits, as most Woody Allen
movies are anymore _ involves Allen digging a tunnel. Behind him is
Michael Rapaport, urging him to wear his miner's hat backward. And
Allen, as dim lowlife Ray, complies, flipping the hat around so
that light on his head shines the wrong way. He's entirely
indifferent as to how ridiculous he looks, because as Rapaport's
Denny tells him, it's fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks'' is populated with the thickest collection
of stooges ever assembled in one of Allen's comedies, as if he has
finally capitulated to the pervasive notion that, from the Farrelly
brothers to the Dogma 95 guys, there's comedy inherent in violent,
stupid people.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Allen is out of his league, or that he's
as culturally lost as he was in, say, ``Celebrity.'' But his movies
lately are aching for conceptual wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   In its false embrace of stupidity, the film is already a distant
cousin to Lars von Trier's ``The Idiots,'' also just out.
</P>
<P>
   With a cast that includes Tracey Ullman (as Frenchy), Jon
Lovitz, Tony Darrow and a tearfully funny Elaine May, ``Small Time
Crooks'' takes us on a basic route back to Allen's halcyon days,
when his quickie farces refused to let you come up for air. For the
first half of ``Small Time Crooks,'' the jokes, physical shtick and
sight gags _ as cheap or impolite as some of them are _ are
breathlessly funny transports to that era. What's missing is any
discernible trace of a mission beyond getting easy laughs, which
evaporate in the final act, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that Allen was aspiring to do something more
than entertain on a mass scale _ it's odd that his most widely
distributed and, DreamWorks thinks, his most potentially mainstream
film happens to be one about the bliss of ignorance. An ex-con
exasperated with his gig as a dishwasher, Ray restlessly hatches a
plan to rob a bank by buying the storefront across the street,
where Frenchy will bake cookies while the boys dig a tunnel leading
to the bank. The early sequences have the insouciant, whimsical
snap of Allen's stronger one-act plays and short stories. But it's
difficult to see Ray's scheme as fodder for anything more
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   After the boys do things like strike a water main and mistakenly
dig their way into the boutique next door, it would take divine
intervention for the film to rise to creative higher ground.
Twenty-five years ago, that dank, birth-canal-like tunnel would
have led straight to Elliott Gould's brain. Instead, Frenchy the
ex-stripper and Ray the ex-con become the tasteless, gaudy
multimillionaire owners of Sunset Farms Cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Frenchy dreams of being a respectable New York socialite instead
of the flamboyant Noo Yawk holdover from Ullman's ``Tracey Takes On
. . .'' sketch show that she is. The decision to recruit Hugh Grant
as the urbane British art dealer to whom Frenchy turns for culture
(not to mention the decision to have him wear a scarf) further
illustrates the uninspired territory ``Small Time Crooks'' has
waded into.
</P>
<P>
   In the best role she's had in years (as Frenchy's dim cousin,
Mae), Elaine May plays what should be dubbed the Woody Allen
half-wit, a woman whose obtuseness is a hysterical matter of fact.
He's been writing these women for about 10 years, women whose
vapidity begs a surreal hypothetical. But May's enlightened dryness
rescues the part from being an insulting half-wit redux, despite
the cruelty fueling the comedy behind it.
</P>
<P>
   The best lines here are the meanest ones _ hurled at Ullman and
May. ``I'm gonna slam your head off,'' Ray tells Frenchy with the
sort of contempt held over from ``Deconstructing Harry,'' but with
a Ralph Kramden growl. A line like that is funny because it just
sounds pathetic and impossible _ screwball banter as a delightful,
empty threat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
