<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CORPORATE-VOLUNTEERS0     05-19 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-VOLUNTEERS0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corporate good works
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne McCollors, stylishly dressed in a red and blue
plaid polo shirt, navy blue pleated pants and brown dress shoes,
knew that volunteering could be dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   A process analyst with Andersen Consulting in Atlanta, McCollors
joined with 30 colleagues this spring to renovate a portion of
Piedmont Park. He spent the afternoon spreading mulch with a
pitchfork around the park's playground area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I would get dirty, but I had to go back to work
afterwards,'' says McCollors, 24. ``I had to shake mulch out of my
shoes and cuffs, but it was a fun-filled day.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of corporate volunteerism is changing.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, company brass view community service projects as a
way to raise employee morale, foster diversity, build teamwork, and
bolster the corporation's community image.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really see a different side of the people you work with,''
says McCollors.
</P>
<P>
   And, hopefully, consumers see a different side of big business,
suggests Suzanne Apple, vice president of community affairs for
Atlanta-based Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteering . . . extends our customer service into the
community, and contributes to building our reputation,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteerism has become so ingrained in the country's corporate
fabric that many organizations now use the theme of helping others
as part of their marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In television and print advertisements today we are told that to
BellSouth, ``Community Matters,'' that Coca-Cola is ``Reaching
Out,'' that ``AT&AMP;T Cares,'' and Philip Morris is ``Working to Make
a Difference.''
</P>
<P>
   What adds weight to these slogans are the hundreds of volunteer
projects these companies sponsor, helping to feed the hungry, house
the homeless and beautify neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers detailing such efforts can be staggering. Andersen
Consulting, for instance, holds 50 volunteer projects a year in
metro Atlanta, some involving as many as 600 of its 1,800 local
employees. A third of all BellSouth employees in metro Atlanta _
about 7,000 people _ belong to the Pioneers volunteer program,
averaging 38 hours a year in various projects. And half of Rich's
4,200 local employees volunteer annually, contributing 9,400 hours
of service.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers reveal a dramatic shift in corporate thinking that
began about a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   PROFESSIONAL APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that companies saw volunteerism as something
nice to do,'' says Jeffrey Hough, vice president of corporate
affairs for the Points of Light Foundation, a Washington,
D.C.-based volunteer advocacy organization. ``The company's
volunteer projects might have been focused on a pet cause of the
president. But now companies are becoming much more professional in
their approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, a company's community involvement related
directly to the conscience of the company's leadership, says Tom
Smith, a newly retired IBM executive of 30 years and a board member
and past chairman of United Way of Metropolitan Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate volunteerism, he argues, was analogous to people who
helped rebuild a neighbor's barn when it burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it for one another, (being) fairly confident that one
day their own barn would burn down,'' says Smith. ``They wanted
their social dues paid in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   But as companies became larger, more impersonal and less in
touch with their communities, community involvement declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies couldn't see any return,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 study conducted by the Points of Light Foundation, 31
percent of the corporations surveyed said they connected
volunteerism to company business. In a similar survey last year, 81
percent of the companies polled connected volunteerism with
business strategies, including all those companies with more than
100,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Every company in the new survey reported that supporting
volunteer programs improved its public image, and 97 percent felt
volunteerism built teamwork skills.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that companies consciously use their
volunteer programs to strengthen specific business goals:
</P>
<P>
   _ 83 percent connect volunteer programs to their company's
public relations activities;
</P>
<P>
   _ 64 percent to their marketing and communications efforts;
</P>
<P>
   _ 60 percent to developing employee skills;
</P>
<P>
   _ 58 percent to job recruiting and retention.
</P>
<P>
   While there's nothing wrong with companies using volunteerism to
make them stronger, Smith thinks that real change and growth didn't
come until corporate leaders realized their companies had to
reflect the needs, interests and diversity of their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteerism is very personal,'' says Smith. ``It's about
people and their own hearts, what they feel is really valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollors says he didn't understand Andersen Consulting's
emphasis on community service when he joined the company a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doubtful and suspicious'' of Andersen's motives, he
says. But after volunteering on a few projects, he changed his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteering . . . has been of tremendous value to me. I
realized that I wanted to be part of something bigger than just my
job, and that by becoming a better person I became a better
employee.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot officials also recognize the impact volunteerism has
on its employees _ and its bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   A highly decentralized company with 971 stores in North and
South America, Home Depot stays in touch with local community
concerns by having one employee at each store responsible for
targeting areas of need and pulling together volunteer projects
that offer solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made giving back and community values one of our core
values,'' says Home Depot's Apple.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC LEAP FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   The growth of corporate volunteerism mushroomed across the
country in the early '90s. In Atlanta, it took the formation of two
volunteer agencies and one mega-event to ignite an explosion of
corporate altruism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Hands On Atlanta, an umbrella organization offering
companies a variety of ways to connect with service projects, was
formed. Then, in 1992, the Metro Atlanta Corporate Volunteerism
Council was created to help companies develop volunteer programs.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Atlanta Olympics that ultimately pulled the
corporate and volunteer communities together. ``The Olympics
spurred a lot of companies forward,'' says Linda Parrish, president
of the corporate volunteerism council. Olympic organizers ``turned
to corporations to be the backbone of their volunteerism efforts.
That galvanized companies.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympics ended, many of those companies redirected
their volunteer forces elsewhere. The impact on the metro area's
nonprofits has been immense.
</P>
<P>
   At Hands On Atlanta, corporate volunteers now contribute 100,000
hours of service at 400 agencies annually, doing everything from
tutoring children to providing meals for the homeless. The
organization depends on companies for a quarter of its 25,000
volunteers. In 1999, 425 companies volunteered with Hands On
Atlanta. In 1991, there were fewer than 10.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, many business leaders recognize today that creating
a better community through volunteerism feeds the bottom line. It's
a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is a business, not a charity, and what we do, we do
because it helps our business,'' says David Arneke, with AT&AMP;T in
Georgia. ``And the better off the community, the better off our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
