<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DEEPAK-CHOPRA0520-COX     05-19 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEPAK-CHOPRA0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chopra hopes to give up the limelight and seek spiritual growth
in obscurity
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Deepak Chopra is an industry: books, videos,
greeting cards, retreats, enlightenment, relaxation, focus, money,
success, weight loss, weight gain, more enlightenment. The author
of more than 25 books _ a half-dozen bestsellers _ and a denizen of
America's popular consciousness, Chopra was named one of the
century's 100 icons and heroes last year by Time magazine. Indeed,
the globe-trotting San Diego-based guru has risen to one-name
status. Forget the Chopra. For millions he is simply Deepak.
</P>
<P>
   But the show is coming to an end. Chopra, 53, an Indian-born
physician who left a successful career in endocrinology in the
1980s to pitch the benefits of Transcendental Meditation before
creating his own particular brand of self-awareness, says he wants
to trade it all for a search for serenity. In a few more years, he
says, he's off to obscurity _ giving up his reported $15 million a
year in earnings to seek spiritual growth somewhere away from the
public eye. ``I hope by the time I die, I will already have sunk
into anonymity,'' Chopra says.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting barefoot in a hotel room in Portland and speaking by
phone in his soothing Indian accent, Chopra says 90 percent of any
newspaper article is about the writer writing, not the speaker
speaking. ``Objectivity,'' he says ``is a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   So in deference to the man _ and the industry _ here then is
Deepak Chopra in his own words:
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post: You have said, seek the company of those
who are looking for the truth but run from those who believe they
have found it. A lot of people believe you have found it. What
would you say to them?
</P>
<P>
   Deepak Chopra: If I'd found it I would be by now sunk in
oblivion and anonymity and wouldn't be writing. I write what I
explore.
</P>
<P>
   PBP: You write a lot about exploring the magical and the
miraculous. There is a culture that believes that this can be
explored with hallucinogenic drugs. Do hallucinogenic drugs help in
this exploration?
</P>
<P>
   DC: They do. They have had a place traditionally in many
cultures as a means to initiatory rites and they have been part of
ritual and so on, so there is no question that hallucinogens and
mind-altering drugs can give somebody a genuine spiritual
experience. The problem is they lead to dependency and sometimes to
psychosis and they're dangerous. And when they're not part of a
ritual and part of a tradition they lead to lack of integration.
There is a thin line sometimes between a genuine spiritual
experience that can be integrated with everyday reality and a very
flashy spiritual experience that cannot be integrated into a
reality . . . so while I believe that, yes, hallucinogens have had
a role in traditional cultures and continue to have a role, in the
more fashionable parts of America that's an excuse more than
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   PBP: You have said that you are looking for God and that once in
a while you get glimpses of her. When was the last time you saw
her?
</P>
<P>
   DC: I get glimpses of God almost every day these days, my
attention is so much into that experience and I'm taking more and
more time in silence. I just returned from a retreat in Thailand,
and every three months I take a week of silence. I do have more and
more of the experience of . . . silence.
</P>
<P>
   PBP: Who are you voting for for President?
</P>
<P>
   DC: It's tough choice but I'm certainly not voting for Mr.
George Bush Jr. (laughs). I probably will vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   PBP: Can you get a sense of their spiritual development?
</P>
<P>
   DC: I have a sense of their development, yes. I think Gore, is,
from what I know of him . . . a very avid reader and the very fact
that he has championed ecology for a long time means he has a sense
of the web of life. He's more eclectic, he's more international.
Bush called the Greeks Grecians the other day and people of East
Timor East Timorians. That doesn't say much. He couldn't name the
most important heads of states of many countries.
</P>
<P>
   PBP: You've said that poverty is a reflection of an impoverished
spirit. Is that always the case?
</P>
<P>
   DC: Unless it's voluntarily sought. But if it isn't voluntarily
sought, you know, as Mr. Oscar Wilde once said, there is only one
category of people that think more about money than the rich, and
that's the poor. In fact, the poor can think of nothing else. In my
view wealth is a state of consciousness as is poverty, and poverty
is the lack of creativity. I also believe that it's a shame that it
exists today, with all the resources that we have and all the
technology and all the creativity. As we evolve into a more
spiritual society, then we will take the collective responsibility
to eliminate it. I have personal plans for tackling this, which I
can't share with you right now because I'm still developing them.
But I have a very personal desire to participate in the elimination
of poverty in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
