<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JUPITER-SETTLEMENT052     05-19 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUPITER-SETTLEMENT0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida coast dig reveals centuries old settlement
 &HT;    By Joe Brogan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Archeologists who dug around the Jupiter
Lighthouse during its recent renovation say they have uncovered the
first physical evidence of a 1700s English settlement previously
mentioned only in historical records. The findings, they say, are
the oldest evidence ever of an English presence in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ''It provides proof that the site is more historical than
previously believed,'' said Conservancy Director Bob Carr, who held
a news conference on the site Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Recovered were a fragment of a tobacco pipe made from Jackfield
Ware, a British lead pottery, and a piece of tabby, a plaster-like
substance commonly used as building material in English colonies,
said field archeologist James Pepe of the Architectural and
Historical Conservancy in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Both finds, dug up near the mound on which the lighthouse sits,
were carbon-dated to the 1734-1800 period, Pepe said.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts were linked to the Grenville settlement described
in archival records. They will be displayed at the Florida History
Center and Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are scant records of the area known as Grenville,
Carr and Pepe said records do show an English settlement in the
Jupiter Inlet area in the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   Archival records show that in 1770, Dutch mapmaker William
Gerard De Brahm created the first well-known map of the area and
referred to the Jupiter Inlet area as the Grenville Inlet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1773, English geographer Bernard Romans travelled to the
Jupiter Inlet to map the Florida coast and wrote that the area was
called Grenville. The Grenvilles were most likely an English family
given a grant to the land when Florida was owned by England
(1763-1783).
</P>
<P>
   In 1815, with Florida under Spanish rule, Spaniard Eusebio Gomez
asked the king of Spain for land that included an English
settlement. The area he received was 12,000 acres in the Grenville
(Jupiter Inlet) area. Pepe says that a land grant application was
given to Gomez which included the Grenville area.
</P>
<P>
   Carr says the detailed history of the English settlement is
probably somewhere in England. ``Nobody's ever dug for it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists also carbon dated oyster shells at the lighthouse
site that are believed to have been placed there by Native
Americans in the period 925 to 950 A.D., Carr said. Carr said this
is a significant find because they are the first artifacts taken
from the north side of the inlet. Carr said there are probably many
English artifacts, including structures, that could be found with a
more comprehensive dig _ one that would cost about $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before the discoveries at the Jupiter Lighthouse, the only other
finds of British artifacts in South Florida were in Miami, Carr
said. He said they were dated from 1790 to 1810 and discovered in
the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Any future excavations on the federal property would depend on
Coast Guard permission and getting the money to do it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservancy was hired to do a surface excavation required by
the federal government as part of the grant that paid for
lighthouse renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
