</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yet another great man is gone
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ When I heard of Jerry Flemmons' death back in
September, I found that I couldn't write about it. This surprised
even me since I had been able to write about my father only a few
hours after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmons and my father are interconnected in my life in many
ways, though they barely knew one another.
</P>
<P>
   But I could not write about Flemmons. Perhaps it was because he
was a writer himself. Actually, it is a sacrilege that I even talk
of us both being writers in the same paragraph. I hack. Flemmons
wrote. Not that Flemmons would be offended by the comparison. He
was as unassuming a man as I have ever met.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, you don't know Flemmons and have never read any of
his work. I'm sorry for you because you have missed something
special. Look in Texas bookstores for any of his several books.
</P>
<P>
   For more than three decades Flemmons wrote for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He was a reporter, then a travel writer and a
columnist of such excellence as to put the rest of us to shame.
Really. This is not false modesty and I'm not the only writer who
would say it.
</P>
<P>
   It is Flemmons' fault that I am a journalist today, but don't
hold it against his memory. There is no way to know how many people
he inspired with his prose.
</P>
<P>
   I met Flemmons before I ever read the first word of his work
though. He came to my house to interview my father, the war hero.
</P>
<P>
   How Flemmons found out my father was a war hero I'll never know.
Certainly, I didn't know it at the time and neither did my brother
or sister. Like many of those who served in World War II, my father
refused to talk about his experience.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, my father the medic drove an ambulance through
``heavy'' enemy fire to rescue a single soldier trapped in the
middle of a battlefield and drove him out again, getting shot in
the process. That is what it says on his presidential citation. Not
that I found out about that
</P>
<P>
   Flemmons in his quiet, folksy manner got my father to talk about
it all _ not that I overheard the interview and not that my father
ever spoke about it to his children. I read it in Flemmons'
multi-part story ``War+25,'' one of the many articles and series he
wrote which won writing awards.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, maybe ever, my father revealed those
horrible and bloody days. The 30 minutes that earned him a few
medals was only a part of the story. There were the two weeks he
was missing in action that we had never heard about. My mother
received a terrible telegrams that he was MIA-presumed dead. He was
found in a foxhole two weeks later, delirious with pneumonia,
unable to tell anyone how he had managed to survive behind enemy
lines.
</P>
<P>
   It was from Flemmons' article that I first understood the power
and meaning of journalism. It was from Flemmons' article that I
first understood my father. You know which was most important.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know it as a young boy, but I was hooked from that
moment. I never admitted wanting to be a journalist until I went to
college _ mostly because I didn't think I could do it _ but I never
forgot Flemmons and how he went about his business and the
craftsmanship of his work.
</P>
<P>
   I was privileged to get to meet him again years later as a
journalist and got to tell him that he was my inspiration. He
smiled slightly and changed the subject. But later he came back to
me and told me that he remembered my father well and said with all
sincerity that he was a great man.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was. And so was Jerry Flemmons.
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas)
News Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
