<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '60s generation won
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _My wife keeps up with fashion news. ``Did you read the
story about the new dress code at that big Atlanta law firm?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered. ``Is it in the paper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right here in the Living section,'' she answered. I figured
the law firm had cracked down on some yuppie lawyer for not wearing
a necktie to work.
</P>
<P>
   Was I in for a shock! Powell Goldstein Frazer &AMP; Murphy, one of
Atlanta's biggest and most prestigious law firms, is doing away
with coat and tie except for courtroom appearances! I couldn't
believe it. The last wall breached! A staid silk-stocking law firm
going from Brooks Brothers to Wal-Mart!
</P>
<P>
   ``The newspaper really messed up on that story,'' I said. ``What
do you mean?'' she asked. ``They put it in what used to be the
women's section. It should have been the top story on Page 1 with a
big black headline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should they have done that?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's the biggest story we've had so far in this
century,'' I explained. ``You must be crazy,'' she replied. ``It's
not bigger than Janet Reno kidnapping Elian at gunpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand,'' I said. ``Powell Goldstein Frazer &AMP;
Murphy lawyers dressing in garden clothes ranks right up there with
V-E Day and General MacArthur making the Japanese sign in Tokyo
Bay. ``You're off on one of your tangents,'' she said. ``This means
total and unconditional surrender,'' I said. ``We've lost and
they've won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't making any sense,'' she said. ``Who lost and who
won?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The '60s generation has won,'' I continued. ``They've invaded
and subdued one of the last bastions of traditional values. Now
everything will fall like dominoes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know you were such a stickler for formal dress,'' she
said. ``I have a hard time getting you to wear clothes that aren't
muddy and sweaty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Garden clothes are one thing,'' I said. ``Work clothes are
something else, unless your work happens to be cutting pulpwood or
collecting garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The story says the firm had to make their lawyers start
dressing down because of their clients,'' she said. ``All those
kids who've made millions in new technology wear yard clothes to
work. They're turned off when their lawyer shows up in pinstripes
and lace-up shoes. They say it's good business to dress like their
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee,'' I said. ``What happens if they represent a nudist
colony?''
</P>
<P>
   The new dress code at Powell Goldstein Frazer &AMP; Murphy is
mandatory, which shocked me. When I was trying to enforce a
modified dress code (socks, shirts and occasional haircuts) at the
newspapers in the '70s, the liberals argued that dress codes in the
workplace constitute cruel and unusual punishment and therefore are
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that what one wears on the job has nothing to do
with job performance. Oddly, when one of the strongest objectors
got a job with The New York Times he promptly shed his bellbottoms
and headed for Brooks Brothers. I thought a reporter or
photographer out meeting the public ought to dress at least as well
as a clerk at the local department store.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon I got a call from an acquaintance, a weekly
newspaper editor who had gone to Athens to do some shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you ought to know,'' he said. ``Two hippies are
going around Athens posing as a reporter and a photographer for the
Constitution. I think they're on drugs or something. They stopped
me on the street and tried to ask me some questions, but before
they could rob me I ran away and hid in a department store. Then I
called the police. I thought you ought to know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have anybody in Athens?'' I asked our city editor after
I hung up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do,'' he said. ``We have a reporter and a photographer
doing a street poll.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the new dress code at that law firm belonged on the
front page of the newspaper is that it's a trend story,'' I
explained to my wife, ``and you have to spot trends early. If
silk-stocking lawyers don't buy pinstripe suits and lace-up shoes
anymore, nobody else will either. Brooks Brothers will go out of
business. People will be wearing blue jeans and tank tops to
funerals. Wall Street will panic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are young people so fond of ugly clothes?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' I said, ``it's the uniform of a revolution. You
ever see Fidel Castro in a coat and tie?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
