<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At war with roaches
 &HT;    Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Early in the morning I flipped on the kitchen
light and caught a movement of something large in my peripheral
vision.
</P>
<P>
   My home invader turned out to be a fearless tree roach about the
size of the Taco Bell dog.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mind an occasional ant, spider, scorpion, gecko or wasp.
Roaches, however, are intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   My aversion to roaches extends to these big, flying tree roaches
that don't actually live indoors. They just wander in once in a
while to see if you have anything that can be pawned.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago when I was stationed in Florida, the natives there
referred to the same creatures as palmetto bugs. That's a nicer
name, but a roach is a roach whether it lives in trees or in
palmetto bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people like roaches. Nevertheless, some people appear
to tolerate the pests.
</P>
<P>
   If I couldn't rid my house of roaches, I'd move. Sleeping under
bridges and eating worms would be better than living in a
roach-infested house, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   That's harsh, I know. But we are shaped by our experiences. I
once had an experience with roaches that gave me nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   After I was discharged from the military, I worked for a few
years as a firefighter in a metropolitan city's busiest fire
station. Our district covered the city's worst slums.
</P>
<P>
   One day I was using a lath hook to open a hole in a ceiling so
my colleagues could put water on a fire. Suddenly, the entire
ceiling collapsed on my head.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK CLOUD OF ROACHES
</P>
<P>
   When the ceiling gave way, a black cloud of cockroaches came
down with the plaster. A jillion or so cockroaches fell inside my
fire coat and down inside my pants and boots. I was covered in
scurrying cockroaches.
</P>
<P>
   The usual crowd of spectators and my firefighting buddies were
entertained when I burst out of the burning building performing my
new cockroach dance, a free-style frenetic creation that included
stripping out of my clothes.
</P>
<P>
   I expressed the need for a new parking lot to my amused
co-workers who ignored me and put out the fire. After that, I often
thought many of the fires we fought were started by citizens
desperate to win a battle with their cockroach adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   This particular morning I was locked in a stare-down with the
big tree roach as I slowly slipped one hand under the sink for the
bug killer. I grabbed the wasp-and-hornet can and hit the intruder
with a powerful blast.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because my chemical weapon was not species-specific, it
took a lot of juice to best my opponent.
</P>
<P>
   I felt good about my victory despite a recent symposium in
London organized by the Universities Federation for Animal Welfare
where studies were presented that claim cockroaches can feel pain
and have the capacity to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   These people evidently are trying to get humans to stop
torturing cockroaches.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies presented at the symposium announced discoveries
that slugs, snails and flies also feel pain. Cows, they say, can
react emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   If an animal feels and reacts to pain similar to the human
reactions, then that animal deserves special protection, according
to many supporters of animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of giving special protection to cockroaches doesn't sit
well with me. I'm not terribly concerned whether a cockroach is
discomfited when I kill it.
</P>
<P>
   What if these people find that pathogenic staph bacteria also
feel pain? What if the AIDS virus feels pain? Do we protect their
lives are the expense of our own?
</P>
<P>
   I say that if an animal dares intrude itself into my house or my
body, then it deserves what it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, I'd treat a human intruder the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
