<HEADER>
A9800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-REFORM-JUDAISM0520-CO     05-19 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-JUDAISM0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman on a mission
 &HT;    By Pamela Smith McCall
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The rapid click click click of heels on the
linoleum floor Temple Beth Or announced the arrival of Rabbi Judy
Chessin _ a sound followed by her expansive smile and rich, deep
voice.
</P>
<P>
   The smile radiates confidence, of the sort needed to juggle
hectic life and job: She's the 42-year-old mother of two sons, the
wife of a professor of Judeo-Christian Studies at Hebrew Union
College in Cincinnati, and is also known as a forceful preacher.
She's also a woman on a mission _ that of carrying her faith,
Reform Judaism, out into a world that knows relatively little about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Chessin became a rabbi 15 years ago in a religion that has only
accepted women in that role since the early 1970s. She was among
the first 100 ordained women in the Reform Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make her a feminist?
</P>
<P>
   She does refrain from using the masculine gender when speaking
of God. But she sees her role as more a ``teacher and guide than a
commander and presider.'' She said this helps open the door to
Judaism _ particularly for women who have been abused by their
fathers, and who are therefore ``never going to relate to a father
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Chessin is equally dedicated to her role as mother,
being a rabbi is ``an ideal job _ so much of temple life is
family-oriented.'' She has been rabbi at Temple Beth Or, with a
congregation of about 200 families, for 15 years. Chessin said her
mission as rabbi is ``to help carry forth Judaism into the world.''
She wants to make Judaism ``accessible, positive and joyful'' _
especially for young people. That way, she says, her children and
others will want to pass the faith along.
</P>
<P>
   The most rewarding part of being a rabbi, said Chessin, is
``sharing intimate moments _ times of rejoicing and tragedy.'' She
also loves being in a position to ``facilitate community through
religious observances.''
</P>
<P>
   Chessin says one of the hardest parts of her job is ``keeping it
all going when finances are tight. Everyone is struggling.'' The
synagogue sets a fee for each family membership, and Chessin said,
``It's high.''
</P>
<P>
   But the business of managing the synagogue, while important,
isn't what gets her words flowing. She wants to talk about her
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Judaism is a relatively liberal movement within Judaism
with respect to interpretation of Torah, the Jewish Bible.
</P>
<P>
   She draws upon a well-known story. ``The miracle of, say, the
parting of the Red Sea was not so much what happened to the sea as
the miracle of an oppressed people finding freedom, collecting
themselves together, and creating this amazing nation that has
continued to this day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we look to God to do Red Sea miracles then we are
disappointed; and (today) we ask why God didn't do it at Auschwitz.
But if the miracle is that the Jewish people survived, that's where
we can see God's miraculous actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Chessin thinks all people need some help and inspiration from
God, though, ``We do not have the concept of original sin or the
sinfulness of humanity. Judaism says we have the good inclination
and the evil inclination which are constantly at war. We need to
give as much fuel as possible to the good inclination.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she went on to say, evil is necessary _ if only to balance
out and contrast the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also our inclination to consume, to build, to grow. It's
our power. If we have no hunger for power, we won't produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Chessin said there is a story written by rabbis that tells how
the evil inclination was found and put in jail. ``All of a sudden
no one had any more babies, no one went to work, no one had any
ambition, no one built houses and nothing happened because everyone
was sitting around being pure and good,'' she said with a laugh.
``So it's a little of the spice and leavening of life. What they
did is this: They blinded the evil inclination and let it back into
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of this concession, she said, is that we continue our
struggle between both sides. ``I love that view, because I think it
is a realistic view of humanity. It puts the choice and
responsibility within ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And she has no illusions about human nature. ``We live in a
secular society, a humanistic society, where anything goes.'' To
counteract this, she said, ``if there were a sense that there
actually is something out there that cares, and that makes demands
upon us, it's a better world.''
</P>
<P>
   Chessin's response to living in a predominantly Christian
culture is: ``I love Christians. I feel that if our world were all
(genuinely) Christian, we'd be in a safer place.''
</P>
<P>
   Then who is this God of modern-day Judaism? Maimonides, a major
Jewish theologian of the 12th century, said you can't define God
because our words are inadequate. ``You had to say God is not
whatever we are. God is not kind in what we think of kindness, but
something far beyond what we could ever define.''
</P>
<P>
   As God said in the Book of Exodus, ``I am what I am.'' According
to Chessin, this is God saying, ``You'll never get it. So let's
just get on with it!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
