<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-ROADTRIP-     05-19 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ROADTRIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RIDING ON HORMONES IN `ROAD TRIP' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until the last 20 minutes, not-as-lewd-as-you-think ``Road
Trip'' is a gangbusters adolescent comedy with one eye on
unglamorous undergraduate realism _ an old Ford Taurus, a sexually
frustrated teaching assistant and virtual pennilessness are among
the supporting characters.
</P>
<P>
   The other eye, meanwhile, is on the possibility of doing
something (anything, really) to spin the fantastic from the
mundane. This includes, but is not limited to, a character named
E.L. (Sean William Scott) stealing a van from the school for the
blind; Kyle (DJ Qualls) the gangly shut-in stepping with brothers
at a black fraternity in Alabama; and a strangely exhilarating
four-man sing-along to Twisted Sister's ``I Wanna Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   At its most superficial, ``Road Trip'' is one of those
laws-of-cheating essays meant to make young men nod in agreement.
But the film, co-written with Scot Armstrong and directed by Todd
Phillips, who co-directed the hazing documentary ``Frat House,'' is
also about the liberty of experiencing the world _ or, as much of
it as you can see driving from Ithaca, N.Y., to Austin, Texas, in
two days.
</P>
<P>
   It's a feat Phillips and Armstrong accomplish without asking any
of its four stars to hump an apple pie. The difference between
``Road Trip'' and last summer's now iconic ``American Pie'' is that
this new film, with its similar preoccupations, doesn't punish
curiosity with humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   What the two films share is a fascination with the absurdity of
the emotional-sexual evolution of boys. But what some mistook for a
poignant/raunchy coming-of-age comedy, so to speak, was executed
like an achingly inept horror film, carried to glory by its four
endearing young explorers and a killer dismount. Slightly more
mature and better assembled, ``Road Trip'' goes one better on
``American Pie'' by teasing out the idiosyncrasies in four guys
existing in a personality grab bag. The film also boasts an actual
narrative, however standard, as well as selfless MTV jester Tom
Green, for a second ply of comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   Set on the campus of the ``fictitious'' University of Ithaca,
the film is loosely the story of Josh and Tiffany, and, in the
limited parlance of campus tour guide Barry (Green), ``their most
challenging challenge ever'': the long-distance relationship.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a few days since Josh (Breckin Meyer) has heard from
Tiffany (Rachel Blanchard), who goes to school 1,800 miles away in
Austin. He's afraid she's cheating on him, but he's having trouble
reconciling monogamy with his attraction to Beth (Amy Smart), a
cute girl being hounded by Josh's Ancient Philosophy T.A. (Anthony
Rapp).
</P>
<P>
   One night after a party, apparently tipsy on ``sex lies and
videotape'' and Zima, Beth quizzes Josh with his camcorder about
what he likes in a girl. That just devolves into toplessness and
sex caught on a tape that's accidentally mailed to Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to save a relationship the average freshman would have
allowed to evaporate after a month apart, but without the cash to
fly to Austin, Josh decides to drive. He and his revved-up slacker
buddy E.L., played by Scott, the embarrassed jock from ``American
Pie,'' talk a taciturn, traumatized-looking virgin named Kyle, who
has Emo Phillips' demeanor and the face of Snoop Dogg, into letting
them borrow his dad's Taurus and credit card. Because he has
nothing else to do but study, Josh's pothead-genius roommate Rubin
(Paulo Constanzo) tags along, leaving the feeding of his pet boa to
Barry, who can't wait to see it eat a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   They have the weekend to get to Austin and back in time for a
philosophy exam that Josh needs to pass. The journey is raucous,
with the guys doling out male dating rules as though they were on
``Sex and the Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Things go disastrously wrong with the Taurus, Kyle's hotheaded
sheriff father (Fred Ward, the funniest he's been since ``Tremors
2'') gets involved and the film threatens to get haywire, taking a
detour into unnecessary grossness featuring a violent slice of
French toast.
</P>
<P>
   But once it gets to Austin, the film _ with its whiplash pacing,
dizzying energy and plausible, inspired grasp of girls _ feels
truncated, solving problems with anticlimactic terseness. It's as
though, just as Josh had to get back to Ithaca in time for his
philosophy exam, the film had to clock in at 90 minutes to make
that 11:35 multiplex late show possible.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its petered-out story, the ideas about young men are
shockingly progressive: sexual stimulation of the prostate turns
out to be a good thing, as does losing it to a full-figured woman,
which Kyle does with a sister named Rhonda.
</P>
<P>
   Staggeringly in-tune with his black and Hispanic cousins, Kyle
may be the only man in Hollywood who knows what to do with a
42-35-48 and truly espouse the passions in Sir Mix-A-Lot's ``Baby
Got Back.'' The Kyle-Rhonda tryst is used as a joke but, like a lot
of the action in ``Road Trip,'' it's rendered sincerely. Even
Green, whose sick humor resists cynicism and irony even at the risk
of plain stupidity, has an exterior charm that belies his
sociopathic behavior, which for my money, is a cry for help.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his coolness resides in the fact that he plays dumb so
you don't have to. Just as bracing is the movie's innocence, which
is banking on Josh and Beth's passion surviving the remaining years
of college. Try two semesters, tops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
