<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DESTRUCTIVE COMPUTER VIRUS SURFACES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN VAMES   
 c. 2000 N.Y. Times.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just weeks after the insidious ``love bug'' email virus crippled
computer systems with its evil message of love, a new variant of
the virus known to be even more destructive and less loving is
making its way around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The latest email-based virus, known to rapidly change its form
and cause more severe damage than the now-infamous love bug, was
reported at several large companies late Thursday. But it does not
appear to be spreading quite as fast as its amorous predecessor,
largely because firms have been beefing up security in recent
weeks, computer experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the trademark ``ILOVEYOU'' subject line that accompanied
the earlier virus, the new virus changes subject lines each time it
is spread, and obliterates key files on the computers it infects.
It generates a not-as-loving subject line which starts ``FW:'', and
the body of the email contains an attachment similar in name to one
recently sent from the infected computer, except that the file
extension, for example ``.doc'' or ``.exe'' is switched to
``.vbs''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any email attachments with the VBS extension should be deleted
immediately and should not be opened,'' warned Internet security
firm Computer Associates. If the attachment is opened, the virus
has the ability to randomly rename files on the computer's hard
drive, giving the computer the equivalent of a lobotomy. But before
it renders its host useless, the virus will send itself to all
other users in the victim's address book. Its ability to slither
its way into networks in that way puts it in the ``worm'' category
of viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Like the love bug and last year's Melissa worms, the latest
virus is isolated to the Microsoft Outlook email system, according
to antivirus software maker Trend Micro.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say that the size of the data attachment in infected
emails is significantly larger than recent viruses, which might
actually help to prevent its spreading because heavy traffic in
large attachments often cause email systems to get clogged or
outright crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worm grows in size as it spreads and can therefore clog a
network with a large amount of email traffic and will likely bring
down mail servers,'' said Computer Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The burden of large attachment size, plus recent efforts by many
companies to update their Internet security systems, may render the
virus less destructive than the love bug.
</P>
<P>
   The recent virus activity has heightened awareness of the
vulnerabilities of new information technology. The love bug virus
spread like wildfire earlier this month in such high-security
places as the Pentagon and at many large corporations, and damages
are estimated to be in the billions.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
