<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a PM-NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS     05-19 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S MAYOR TO QUIT SENATE RACE AGAINST MRS. CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 PM-NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS-685&AMP;ADD-NYT   (Eds, story will be updated after the formal announcement)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has decided to drop out of the
race for U.S. Senate, and will call a news conference later Friday
to detail his decision, two aides to the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani informed his staff about the decision Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's decision to drop out of his contest with Hillary
Rodham Clinton comes after a tumultuous three week period for the
mayor. Giuliani first announced that he had been diagnosed with the
early stages of prostate cancer, and than said he was seeking a
separation of his wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover. At the same
time, Giuliani has increasingly been seen in public with an Upper
East Side woman he described as a ``very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement jolted a political career that began with
Giuliani's stint as a sharply aggressive and high-profile federal
prosecutor in New York in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue as mayor, while facing treatment for prostate
cancer and dealing with his separation from Hanover, his wife of 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   His current second term as mayor ends on Dec. 31, 2001, and term
limit laws prevent him from seeking another term.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has often said how much he has enjoyed his job running
the city, where he has been credited with bringing a drop in crime,
cleaner streets and with other improvements in the quality of life.
And he has frequently made it clear that his major political
interest is to be executive.
</P>
<P>
   The only statewide job that would appear to be appealing to
Giuliani, who never formally announced his Senate candidacy but was
clearly the front runner, is the governorship. But that job is
currently held by George Pataki, a popular Republican whose second
term does not expire until 2002. Pataki, who has ruled out a run
for the Senate seat as a replacement to Giuliani, has told
reporters that in all likelihood he would run for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has shown his openness to an eventual gubernatorial
run, telling a radio show caller who made the suggestion, ``What
you say is certainly a reasonable, rational analysis and people
have privately offered me the same analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   He will have a ready-made war chest, $9.2 million which federal
campaign financing laws allow him to keep for a future run. But
holding on to the money could alienate donors and Republican
leaders. Federal law bars him from transferring the dollars to a
replacement candidate. But Giuliani could pass on the money to a
state or national Republican Party committee, which in turn could
spend it on behalf of another candidate. Other options are to
return the money to donors, or give it to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's departure also puts the state Republicans on the
spot. As the mayor decided on the course of his treatment, and then
whether to run, the days ticked by ahead of the state Republican
convention in Buffalo on May 30, when the party formally names its
candidate. Republican leaders fretted over who would take up the
banner. Without Pataki, who is the strongest possible candidate,
Republican leaders have given the most attention to Rep. Rick A.
Lazio of Long Island. A survey from the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute that was released May 16 had Mrs. Clinton leading Lazio
by 50 percent to 31 percent. The survey's margin of error was plus
or minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible contender is Rep. Peter T. King, also of Long
Island. Pataki, as the state's leading Republican, will have the
strongest voice in making the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Both are less known than Giuliani, lack his campaign war chest
and would face in Mrs. Clinton a candidate who has been campaigning
for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Many questioned just how much Giuliani wanted the Senate job. At
times he seemed less than enthusiastic about campaigning. Some
political observers wondered how attractive he found the prospect
of being a junior member of a legislature rather than a political
leader.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The announcement came after a remarkably rapid series of events.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of two weeks, the personal life of a politician who
so often demanded his privacy was splayed open to all. First came
his disclosure at a news conference on April 27 that he had an
early, treatable form of prostate cancer. Two weeks later, after
tabloid reports and whispers about his relationship with another
women accelerated, a visibly shaken Giuliani announced _ again to
reporters _ that he was separating from Hanover. In the same news
conference, Giuliani, 55, emphasized that he would rely even more
now on his ``very good friend,'' Judith Nathan, an executive who
lives on the Upper East Side with her teenage daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The public disclosure caught Hanover by surprise. She responded
with her own public statement, a tearful one, in which she blamed
her husband's past relationship ``with one staff member'' as one of
the reasons from their marital problems. A spokeswoman for Hanover
identified that staff member as the mayor's former communications
director, Cristyne Lategano. Both Lategano, who is now married to
Nicholas Nicholas, and Giuliani denied having a romantic
relationship. The former aide later became the president of NYC &AMP;
Co., the city's visitor and convention bureau, with backing from
Giuliani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
