<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9831 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-TEX     05-19 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN COMIC STRIPS HAVE THEIR PITFALLS OF TASTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LANCE MURRAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last place in a newspaper that one would expect readers to
be offended would be the comics pages.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past few years, words and images have shown up in the
comic strips that have sent some readers running to their phones,
typewriters or e-mail software.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about the seven dirty words pointed out years
ago by comedian George Carlin, because those words would never show
up in daily newspaper comics. But other words that many parents
don't want their children to use have. And cartoonists have used
images that have shocked some of our readers.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to offend anyone, so I'll use descriptive phrases
instead of the words themselves. Bear with me.
</P>
<P>
   The first word, one that I've probably gotten more phone calls
about than any other, is ... well, it rhymes with ``Jabba the
Hutt'' and is something that Han Solo likes to kick. This word has
appeared several times in the past year in comic strips, and each
time readers have called to say that the word is inappropriate for
a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   I agree. It is unseemly, and the callers are correct: It doesn't
belong in family-oriented comics.
</P>
<P>
   Another word that appeared recently in a ``Non Sequitur'' strip
is the word used for the escape of gases from the human body. The
comic strip used the word in the context of aging men being ``old
__,'' but that doesn't lessen the objectionable nature of the word
to some readers.
</P>
<P>
   Other words that are common vulgar exclamations have appeared in
the comics pages in the past couple years. These words are often
part of a phrase, preceded by the word, ``Oh, ...'' Get the
picture?
</P>
<P>
   The complaints usually come from parents who don't want their
children exposed to objectionable material and from older readers
who are sensitive to what they perceive to be bad language.
</P>
<P>
   Several readers also called recently about a story line in
``Gasoline Alley'' that had a couple of its characters lost in the
woods with no clothes on. The readers thought that nudity, even if
it was cartoon nudity, was inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   A man called several years ago to vociferously complain when
Sally Forth was shown getting dressed and her bra was visible.
</P>
<P>
   I take every complaint about taste seriously because these
readers would not contact the newspaper unless they were upset by
the comics' contents.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a couple of times when I told readers that I
thought they were being overly sensitive and to just let a joke be
a joke. But I also have agreed with other readers that some words
cross the line between acceptable language and poor taste.
</P>
<P>
   These readers have wondered why we don't edit out the words in
question or alter the comic in some way. Why didn't I draw clothes
on those characters?
</P>
<P>
   Because the comics are copyrighted works of original art, we
can't change them. I could pull that day's strip completely, and we
would do so if one of Carlin's famous seven words appeared.
</P>
<P>
   But that is an extreme measure. Some might call it censorship,
and at the least it would deny fans of that strip who might not be
offended the access to that comic. We would probably run a
substitute strip instead.
</P>
<P>
   The words we are dealing with are common in everyday
conversation these days. You hear them _ and even worse ones _ on
prime-time TV nearly every night. I've heard the word that rhymes
with ``Jabba the Hutt'' on children's cartoon shows often.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that they are in common use, though, doesn't lessen a
newspaper's obligation to use intelligent, decent language. So to
that end, when readers complain about objectionable words in
comics, I take the time to write the syndicates or talk with their
representatives in person to let them know what my readers think.
</P>
<P>
   I know some people will look at all this as silly, but I've been
a cartoonist, and I know there are plenty of ways to get a laugh
without being offensive. This is an issue of concern to many
newspaper readers.
</P>
<P>
   If it's important to them, it's important to me.
</P>
<P>
   (Lance Murray is reader advocate for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at (817) 390-7692 or
lancem(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
