<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT DOESN'T MISS THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Bob Baffert has been relaxed this week, as befits
the trainer of an 8-1 shot in Saturday's Preakness at Pimlico. All
the pressure is on Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and his
trainer, Neil Drysdale, while little is expected of Baffert's
charge, Captain Steve, who ran eighth in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help if they would load him backward,'' quipped
Baffert, when asked how Fusaichi Pegasus could be beaten. ``Maybe
we could beat him with a head start, or if he ran into the Stanford
band.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert won the Preakness with Silver Charm in 1997, and Real
Quiet in '98, after they had also won the Derby. Their Triple Crown
bids came up short in the Belmont Stakes. No longer the focus of
attention, Baffert claims to be enjoying his secondary role.
Meanwhile, Drysdale is running around trying to make sure
everything is perfect for the sometimes temperamental Fusaichi
Pegasus. The 3-5 morning-line favorite is stabled on the
backstretch, instead of in the stakes barn, and can be viewed only
with security clearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil's a very private person,'' said Baffert. ``He knows other
people will be deflecting the cameras. He knows (being stabled on)
the front side is a distraction to a horse. It doesn't take much to
get his horse going. Most of the horses I have brought here are
like me, laid-back. Everybody has their own style. I like to share
my horses with everybody. But I don't blame him for keeping his
horse separate because the media hordes can really bug a horse.
Neil's got his own agenda, and I'm not going to get involved in
that deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhausting trying to win a Triple Crown. I went through
that for two years, and I came out of it exhausted. The media wants
you to give them a lot of time, and this is when you want to
promote your sport. You only get two chances _ the Triple Crown and
the Breeders' Cup. Neil said this wasn't going to change his life,
but they're already asking him for autographs. It got so bad for me
that I had to work on my handwriting so people could read it. And
it's still terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fusaichi Pegasus appears to be the headline-grabbing
superstar the sport has long hoped for, Captain Steve has a chance.
Owned by Mike Pegram, who also owned Real Quiet, Captain Steve got
blasted in the Derby just after he took over the lead turning for
home. Wheelaway, who is being held out of the Preakness for the
Belmont June 10, came over sharply under Richard Migliore and wiped
out Captain Steve and Robbie Albarado. Wheelaway finished fifth,
and the Derby only awards purse money to the top four finishers, so
there was no inquiry or foul claim at the time. The Churchill Downs
stewards subsequently gave Migliore a five-day suspension for
careless riding.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought Captain Steve had been run too hard chasing a
furious Derby pace (:45 4/5, 1:09 4/5, 1:35 2/5), and would have
stopped even if he wasn't bothered. It is expected that Albarado
will take a firm hold of Captain Steve in the early-going and find
a position behind the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie rode the horse to my instructions,'' said Baffert. ``I
wanted him to ride him early, and get the jump on them. I told him
to ride him hard from the three-eighths pole to the eighth-pole,
and maybe we could stagger in from there. But Wheelaway came over
and that was it. Even if he was clear, he wasn't going to win. He
may have been fourth, or so, but he only got to run a mile and
one-16th before that horse came over on him. Plus, he had to chase
a fast pace.''
</P>
<P>
   With Captain Steve finishing far back, Baffert, once a target,
is now just a member of the Preakness pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come here at 8-1, it's different,'' he said. ``When
you win the Derby, you come in flying high. When you get beat in
the Derby, you're just looking to get a piece of the pie. I'm
getting off at this stop. I'm going to take one more shot. I'm not
going to the Belmont. Captain Steve has run so well for us
(12-4-0-5 career record), and he's just short of being a
millionaire ($960,256 in earnings). He's worked great this week and
he really looks happy. That's all you can ask for at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm keeping my fingers crossed. I'm hoping to get a good
break, and we'll see what happens. Fusaichi Pegasus is a very good
horse, but it's my job to make him earn it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
