<HEADLINE>
NBC NOT PLAYING GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give NBC some credit for telling viewers right up front that its
coverage of the summer Olympics _ all 437 1/2 hours _ will be via
tape delay.
</P>
<P>
   The only live telecasts outside of unforeseen breaking news will
be of studio host Bob Costas, who will tell viewers that all events
were taped but present the day-old events as if they were currently
unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is hoping that viewers won't mind, but the network is
expected to face stiff competition from pro football and the
baseball playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will be airing more than three times the coverage it showed
during the Games in Atlanta, and it will be spread over NBC and its
sister cable stations, CNBC and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   NBC itself will have a total of 164 1/2 hours of coverage, while
MSNBC will supplement 10 a.m.-5 p.m. during the week and 10 a.m.-4
p.m. on the weekend. CNBC will have Olympic programming 5-9 p.m.
during the week and 4-9 p.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Using tape-delay makes sense. There is a 15-hour time difference
between Sydney and the East Coast and 18 hours from the West. The
finals of most Olympic events will occur between 4-7 a.m. EST, not
exactly the time most Americans are watching television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we paid $705 million for the rights
and it would be a good idea to broadcast the games when people are
watching,'' said NBC spokesman Kevin Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   The taped coverage is nothing new. Ninety-six percent of the
1992 Olympic Games in Barcelona was taped, and 60 percent of NBC's
coverage from Atlanta was taped.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of live and taped coverage caused some confusion among
viewers, but NBC hoped to reduce that by announcing their plans
early. ``The results are not unimportant,'' Sullivan said, noting
that instantaneous scores and results will be found on
NBCOlympics.com. ``Most people watch for the story lines, the
patriotism and human drama.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sullivan, NBC Sports chairman Dick Ebersol did not
ask the International Olympic Committee to change the events
schedule in Sydney to accommodate American viewers, as NBC did
before the 1988 Summer Games in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Play ball
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This Week in Baseball'' returns on national television May 27
before the Red Sox-Yankees game. The 30-minute show starts at 12:30
p.m. on Fox25 and features will include guest hosts providing
inside looks at the ballparks. Derek Jeter is the first guest host.
Mel Allen was the original host in 1977, and Ozzie Smith is the
regular one now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jump ball
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is talking with New York's Rucker summer basketball
league about televising its playground games on the NBA's 24-hour
satellite and digital cable channel. The Rucker league was the
subject of a recent Turner Network documentary _ ``On Hallowed
Ground: Streetball Champions of Rucker Park.'' Former players at
the Harlem playground include Wilt Chamberlain, Connie Hawkins,
Juluis Erving, Allen Iverson, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Mark Jackson,
Vince Carter and Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fit to be teed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS will be airing the third and fourth rounds of the
``MasterCard Colonial'' 3-6 p.m. Saturday and Sunday. CBS's Gary
McCord told reporters that the pressure is building on Davis Love
to win a tournament. ``He is in desperate need of a win to get back
in the flow,'' McCord said. ``There are some dastardly things in
the back of his mind, and one of those is Tiger Woods. Davis
acknowledged that he is trying to keep up with, and ward off,
Woods. In this game, you have to worry about yourself. It takes too
much time and energy to worry about other players.'' McCord was
equally frank about Jesper Parnevik. ``He is great for the Tour
because he brings that much needed fanatical fringe,'' said McCord.
``He's eccentric, he's different and he's good. His pink pants, his
turned up hat, eating volcanic ash _ all that is good.'' McCord
also said that Parnevik has another side to him. ``Jesper is
actually very quiet and introspective,'' he said. ``He is a
world-champion chess player, which shows you that he has some
depth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
