<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR LINE DEFINES SOUTH AFRICAN OPINION ON MUGABE'S ACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Midway through the political turmoil in Zimbabwe,
a South African paper asked two of its reporters covering the story
to debate in its pages whether the media were being fair to
President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   One of the journalists is black, the other white.
</P>
<P>
   The black journalist, arguing that the press had diminished
Zimbabwe's independence leader by accusing Mugabe in recent weeks
of formenting violence against his own people, wrote: ``Zimbabweans
deserve acknowledgment of their history.''
</P>
<P>
   The white reporter, taking an opposing view, countered: ``A
leader should be judged and condemned or praised on the present.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Zimbabwe, where more than 20 people have been
killed in a violent campaign season ahead of what is widely
regarded as the country's most important elections in two decades,
has sparked a vigorous and emotional debate in newsrooms across
South Africa. Black and white journalists, viewing Zimbabwe's
crisis from divergent historical perspectives, tend to agree that
after 20 years in power, Mugabe should go.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't agree why.
</P>
<P>
   ``You carry your baggage about Africa, that it is all wars and
famines and dictators,'' said Abbey Makoe, a reporter and columnist
for the Sunday Independent. ``I cannot ignore the contribution
Mugabe made. When I say he should go, it is not because he is
barbaric, but because he should go into history with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Already facing its worst economic slump in at least a decade,
Zimbabwe has become increasingly violent since late February, when
government supporters began seizing white-owned commercial farms.
The invaders, orchestrated by veterans of the 1970s war for
liberation, claim they are only taking back land stolen from their
ancestors by colonial settlers. While most rural blacks eke out
meager lives on modest communal plots, 4,500 whites own more than
30 million acres of prime farmland. Blacks fought for independence
to correct that imbalance, but it endures 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Politics precipitated the land grab. In February, voters
rejected a new constitution sponsored by Mugabe, handing the ruling
party its first defeat in two decades and giving momentum to
growing opposition movement ahead of parliamentary elections,
scheduled for June 24-25. The draft would have allowed the
government to seize land without compensation. When it failed,
Mugabe encouraged the war veterans to invade white farms.
</P>
<P>
   While the farms have been the primary targets, violence has
spread. Farm workers and businessmen thought to support the
opposition, as well as opposition candidates themselves, have come
under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the crisis in Zimbabwe is fundamentally about land or
politics, race fundamentally shapes the way people respond to it.
Black journalists in South Africa complain that their white
counterparts have focused too much on violence against whites.
</P>
<P>
   When the first white farmer was killed, for example, the media
gave the man's name, age, background, interviewed his widow, told
how many children he left behind, and covered his funeral. They
gave mere mention of a black policeman killed the same night in a
similar attack. It wasn't until late April before the mainstream
South African press noticed that black farmworkers bore the brunt
of most of the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``British papers and the BBC have covered Zimbabwe as if whites
were all that mattered,'' said John Battersby, editor of the Sunday
Independent. ``But the story is about a black opposition movement
being crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many white reporters now see Mugabe fomenting violence to save
his political career. For them, the issue seems clear cut. The
president has presided over a corrupt government, ruined the
economy, and terrorized his people. For many black journalists,
Zimbabwe has many shades of gray. Even if Mugabe has mishandled
land reform, the issue needs to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe was a great hero in 1980, but people see through him
now,'' said Xolela Mangcu, a newspaper columnist. ``But because
whites are against Mugabe, blacks take the other side. That's
ironic. Even now, we continue to base our reactions on the actions
of whites. That makes us perpetual victims of whites _ prisoners of
our own history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
