<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONCOMPETE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 KEEPING A LOCK ON INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Robert L. Johnson, president and founder of Vermont-based
Omega Optical Inc., asked his hourly employees to sign
noncompetition and nondisclosure agreements nine years ago, few
firms were requesting lower-level employees to sign such covenants.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, most companies reserved those contracts for top
executives who were privy to the kind of confidential or
proprietary information that, if revealed, could cost a firm its
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   But as intellectual property has developed into a primary
economic engine, US employers are no longer restricting these
agreements to the top tier of the corporate hierarchy. In some
cases, technicians, analysts, programmers _ even clerks _ are being
asked to sign on the dotted line.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, companies are seeking to protect more material than
ever before. Business plans, customer lists, pricing data,
investors' names, marketing and sales strategies, and just about
anything deemed valuable but not necessarily covered under standard
copyright or patent laws may be considered proprietary or a trade
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Old notions of corporate loyalty and retention have given way to
a job-hopping frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   That Rolodex on your desk, those policy guides and address
books, the contact list you keep in your computer file at work,
even the creative ideas you come up with in the middle of the night
_ they're all fair game in the war against the misappropriation of
trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is a great deal of tension over what an
employee can take when he or she leaves,'' especially at high-tech
firms where talent is hard to keep, said Ariel D. Cudkowicz,
general counsel at Seyfarth Shaw in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information in your head is information you may have
gathered over the years and it may appear to be yours,'' he added,
``but the courts could ask whether you had the information when you
started or if you acquired it because the company invested in you,
trained you, and showed you how to build up a customer base. As
long as companies take action to protect it, employees cannot walk
away with that kind of information.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question remains: Do rank-and-file employees really
know that much about their bosses' strategic plans? Legal experts
say the answer depends on the worker and the case.
</P>
<P>
   Take Adrian Lofton, 28, of Baltimore. He was a laser eye
technician at TLC Laser Eye Center when he was fired last February.
Lofton found new work at another firm, but his lawyer maintains
that the company shied away from hiring him after TLC told the
prospective employer about the noncompete agreement Lofton had
signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, Adrian received another offer from a company TLC
considers a competitor and TLC threatened my client and the
competing firm in a letter stating that the noncompete agreement is
legally binding,'' said Lofton's attorney, John Vecchione of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the agreement bars Lofton from working at any other
laser center within 60 miles of TLC's numerous regional offices.
Vecchione declined to reveal the length of the restriction. In a
related case, however, a former TLC technician signed an agreement
that bars her from working for any TLC rivals for one year. A TLC
spokesperson said the company could not comment on pending
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adrian Lofton did not solicit clients and he was not privy to
any trade secrets,'' said Vecchione. ``In fact, I don't really
think there is anything about this business that would be
considered a trade secret. Usually, these agreements are for people
with specialized knowledge about the way a corporation works.''
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions on who owns certain information are not limited to
workplace agreements. In a recent decision, the Second District
Court of Appeals in Los Angeles adopted a legal premise widely
known as the inevitable disclosure doctrine. It assumes that
employees who leave one job for the same position at a competing
firm are likely to divulge business strategies or certain trade
secrets simply because the new job is so much like the old one.
Under such circumstances, said the court, giving away trade secrets
may be unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   The doctrine is being invoked on a case-by-case basis by
management-side lawyers who say it is a valuable weapon in the
pursuit of court injunctions to prevent former employees from
sharing trade secrets with rival firms.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' lawyers argue that restrictive covenants and temporary
injunctions are actually being used by employers seeking to stymie
competition by preventing ex-workers from joining a competitor's
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management lawyers will say these kind of agreements protect
trade secrets,'' said San Francisco attorney Cliff Palefsky. ``What
they really do is prevent other employers from stealing their
rivals' employees, and they prevent employees from going to
competing firms. They can also have a chilling affect on start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the employees' standpoint,'' he added, ``these agreements
are terrible. Why? Because there really isn't any job security in
this economy. So, you really need to have a skill that you can take
from place to place. The idea that someone who is no longer paying
you, and might have even laid you off, can now turn around and
prevent you from working somewhere else is harmful.''
</P>
<P>
   Omega founder Robert L. Johnson doesn't see it quite that way.
He maintains that in 1991, when he asked his hourly workers to sign
noncompetition and nondisclosure agreements, he was simply trying
to protect trade secrets. The company is among a handful in the
country that manufacture optical interference filters, the glass
filters that help certain microscopes and telescopes filter light,
and provided filters for the Hubble space telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the noncompetition agreements raised a ruckus among some
of Omega's employees. Lee Madden, then an $11-an-hour accounts
receivable and data-entry clerk, refused to sign the agreement and
was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the noncompetition part was out of line,'' said Madden,
47. ``I did not take the job with that provision. Plus, I was not a
scientist, so to restrict my employment after I left made no
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   When Madden left Omega, he joined nine other ex-Omega workers
who had either been fired or had quit. They launched an
employee-owned company called Chroma Technology Corp., now one of
the fastest-growing high-tech firms in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, five years later, Johnson sued the start-up and its
founders, alleging unfair competition and breach of the duty of
loyalty. The suit, which sought an estimated $15 million in
damages, argued trade secrets were used to launch the rival firm.
</P>
<P>
   Filed in Windham County Superior Court, the suit goes to the
heart of the current debate revolving around information and what
is secret, says Vermont lawyer Bernie Lambek, who represents
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, you cannot take trade secrets acquired in the
course of employment and use them if they do not belong to you,''
he said. ``The knowledge those employees had wasn't general
knowledge. It involved the creation of extremely specialized
filters, the really high-tech end of the optical interference
filter industry. Nobody else could replicate what Omega was doing.
These were key research and engineering design people who left to
start Chroma. These weren't auto mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The company environment was intentionally located in
Brattleboro because openness has never been an issue here,'' said
Johnson, a 52-year-old physicist. ``Unlike Boston or Silicon
Valley, where people can easily walk across the street and get a
job at a competitor, the people who work for me have always been
local. They aren't bringing information when they come. They learn
it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Kabbel, 52, a plant manager and co-owner of Chroma, said
the information he gleaned while working for Omega was public
knowledge. Kabbel was a $12-an-hour technician who operated and
repaired machinery. He said most of what he learned was available
in scientific journals and was routinely taught at a
company-sponsored apprenticeship program. And, he says, Chroma's
current manufacturing technology and processes, which rely on
robotics and other high-tech methods, are now dramatically
different from Omega's.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Judge Robert Grussing III ruled in favor of Chroma.
The judge also found that ``the defendants did not start the new
company by taking equipment or documents from Omega.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has appealed. ``Just before the workers left Omega, the
company was drawing up noncompete and confidentiality agreements,''
said Lambek, his lawyer. ``So when they left, they knew the
information they took was considered confidential and proprietary.
That should be enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
