<HEADLINE>
US ACQUISITION SCENE TAKES ON A FOREIGN FLAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !Bienvenidos a los Estados Unidos! Did you bring cash?
</P>
<P>
   The language keeps changing, but the story is being repeated
with striking frequency. Foreign acquirers are buying American
companies and, more often than not, paying big premiums to make the
deals work.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about an American company selling to a
foreign corporation. New England's supermakets are already owned by
British, Dutch, and Belgian giants. But it's time to get a
multilingual scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   This has already been a busy week: first, Pioneer Group of
Boston struck a $1.2 billion deal to sell to Italy's third largest
bank, Unicredito Italiano SpA, only to be eclipsed the next day by
the $12.5 billion sale of Lycos Inc. of Waltham, Mass. to Terra
Networks SA of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the prices were eyepopping even though the
sellers faced problems. Lycos was struggling to break out of its
second-tier Internet status and Pioneer was faring much worse,
reeling from serious business setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   It's been so busy barely anyone recalled that Primark Corp. sold
Boston's Yankee Group to British financial media giant Reuters
Group PLC for $72.5 million in cash just last week.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, 558 American companies have announced plans
to sell to foreign buyers through the first four months of this
year, according to Thomson Financial Securities Data. That's up
more than 35 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of reasons that foreigners, principally
European companies, are aggressivley buying American businesses.
Most important: mergers and acquisition activity within Europe has
grown dramatically and America's investment bankers have set up
shop overseas to scour the globe for sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see how many billions of dollars are available in the
foreign marketplace, I think investment bankers are quick to
realize there is a market ready, willing and able to acquire
companies around the world, including in the United States,'' said
Allen Michel, a Boston University professor who specializes in
mergers and acquisition research.
</P>
<P>
   Some industries in particular are lending themselves to foreign
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service deals become more attractive as America
relaxes regulations, and Europeans are paying huge premiums for
typically second-tier targets.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans, especially British companies, have moved in on
American utilities, in part because they have already gone though
the complex deregulation now taking place here, according to Linda
Varoli, a senior analyst at Merger Insight.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid Group PLC's $3.2 billion agreement to purchase New
England Electric System last year was only one deal among many.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stickiest issues in the foreign purchase of an
American company: how to pay. Cash deals create instant tax bills
for sellers, but stock swaps are not particularly welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very true US investors prefer cash over foreign
equities,'' said Boston money manager Bernie Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the two deals announced this week. Pioneer's rich
cash agreement has even silenced the company's griping dissident
shareholders. Lycos, though it commanded a high price on paper, has
watched the value of the Terra Networks shares to be used in the
stock swap sink 21 percent since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The stock swap problem: poor liquidity. Like many foreign
stocks, their American Depositary Receipts traded in the United
States are thin in numbers (ADRs are traded securities representing
actual foreign shares that have been deposited with a trustee).
</P>
<P>
   Terra's problem was especially acute because its parent company
owns 67 percent of all the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Anderson took cash the first time his Yankee Group was
sold, to Waltham-based Primark, and didn't have to consider the
option of getting paid in foreign stock. We think we know what he
would have decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Depositary Receipts sound pretty good to us if it's
Sony, but if it's some company that's thinly traded, there's
questions of liquidity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's not always the case, said Varoli at Merger
Insight. A handful of stock-swaps have involved foreign buyers that
did not even have US-traded securities at the time of the
agreement, like the pending acquisition of Snyder Communicatins
Inc., a Maryland advertising company, by Havas Advertising of
France. Buyers simply agree to create depositary receipts before
the deal closes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these companies are starting to realize they're going
to have a (US stock market) listing here to be more competitive
bidders,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   You can count on it. Ciao.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
