<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS-BOS &LR;      05-19 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPING IN FOR EVERETT, LEWIS FUELS SOX' SURGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Red Sox made their move to first place, he was
everything you could ask for in a center fielder. He caught every
ball hit his way. He hit for average, he hit with power, he stole
bases, he scored runs and drove in others. And by the end of the
day, his uniform usually required a second washing.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett?
</P>
<P>
   No, although Everett almost certainly will be back in the Sox
outfield during the three-game weekend series against the Detroit
Tigers, with the Toronto Blue Jays arriving Tuesday for another
three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   But until Wednesday, when he returned from a sore right
quadriceps injury with three hits as the Sox DH, Everett was on the
bench while the Sox won six of seven in Baltimore and Toronto. He
was a spectator while the Sox engineered a 4 1/2-game swing in the
standings _ from second place, 3 1/2 games behind the Yankees _ to
first place and a one-game edge entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the center of the diamond was Darren Lewis, the same
man who was supposed to be relegated to the shadows when the Sox
acquired Everett from Houston last December, then signed him to a
four-year, $30 million deal a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lewis, the Sox' center fielder on each of the last two
wild-card winning teams, stepped in for Everett and responded with
the greatest offensive splurge of a big-league career that began in
Oakland in 1990, when he was summoned from the minors when Hendu,
Dave Henderson, went down with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who was batting .167 when the trip began last Thursday in
Baltimore, singled in the ninth inning of that first game, when
Everett first pulled up lame. He then reeled off four three-hit
games over the next five games, and singled in his last at-bat
Wednesday before feeling a tug in his left hamstring, which caused
him to leave in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who hit only .160 last September and just .215 after the
All-Star break _ in part because of the jammed wrist he suffered on
a headfirst slide into second base in Toronto last June _ hit .583
on the trip, going 14 for 24. The four three-hit games eclipsed
anything he has done before in a five-game span. He scored eight
runs, drove in four, and stole four bases. He beat out a push bunt
for a hit Friday night in Baltimore, then two days later took
Orioles ace Mike Mussina deep for a home run, his first in 315
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis takes a .352 average into the weekend. More important, the
32-year-old Lewis created a renewed awareness of his value to a
winning ballclub, even if he is now serving in a secondary role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect timing,'' said Jeff Frye, another forgotten veteran
who was part of a group effort by the Sox reserves that enabled the
Sox to thrive despite the absence of the sore-legged Everett, the
disabled Nomar Garciaparra, and the ailing Jason Varitek
(bronchitis).
</P>
<P>
   ``But even though he's had success in the role,'' Frye said,
``that still doesn't mean it's easy. It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rice, the Sox hitting coach, said he doesn't really know
what it's like to come off the bench cold and play infrequently,
because he was never in that role. ``But when you're not playing
every day and you get the chance, you've got to turn it up a
notch,'' Rice said. ``And you've got to be ready. You've got to do
a little extra to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis needs no prompting to do the extra labor required.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works hard,'' first base coach Tommy Harper said. ``Darren
Lewis is a professional. You never have to worry about him. He's
ready to play center field, right field, pinch run, pinch hit. He
stays ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got some hits, but he deserved them. He worked his butt off
to get those hits. The guy practices everything. He practices like
he's going to play. He takes extra hitting, he practices getting
good jumps, he practices base stealing. In spring training, he
asked me a million questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis came to spring training knowing he would have a reduced
role. During the spring, he said that the time might come where he
would think about asking for a trade, if he felt he couldn't
tolerate the lack of playing time. But that time hasn't come. If
anything, Lewis now takes exception to any suggestion he'd rather
be elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be here,'' he said recently. ``I want to win. I want
that ring. I'm a part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   There's always the potential for trouble, Harper said, when a
starter loses his job. ``But he doesn't complain,'' Harper said.
``He just goes to work. Sure, it could have been a disruption to
the team, but that's not him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quiet, but he's a very intense guy, Darren Lewis. You
have to know him. Darren Lewis is Darren Lewis. Once he starts
doing something, as a coach you have to back off and let him do his
thing. He'll discuss any subject on the field, and he'll listen,
but once he starts putting it into practice, he goes full-bore. He
doesn't like anything to disrupt him.''
</P>
<P>
   You look at Darren Lewis before a game, headphones on, listening
to his favorite rap music, and you could mistake him for just
another player killing time until the action starts. Some guys play
cards, or do crosswords, or watch videos.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis? Look at the eyes. He's already in full battle
mode. He carries a chip on his shoulder the size of Wendell Kim.
``It's nothing personal,'' Harper said. ``It's just Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he gives to you, you can't put in the paper. It just
shows up in wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Lewis gave himself up with a daring headfirst
slide into home to break a tie score. ``You know I'm going to do
that,'' he said. ``I'm a ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``Old school,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
