<HEADLINE>
BRUSH THE SEALER OR STAIN ON DECK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 21, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. If I do my own deck, cleaning it and applying sealer or
stain, what is the best way to apply the sealer or stain? Roller or
brush?
</P>
<P>
   RICH HADJIAN, North Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Brushing is best because brushing will get the sealer or
stain deeper into the wood, providing better adhesion. Some pros
first roll it on, then brush it in. To me that is double work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My seasonal cottage is open only in summer. This year when I
opened it for the summer, it was terrible, with mold growing on the
walls. How can I remove the mold, and keep it from coming back next
year when I close the cottage up again?
</P>
<P>
   STEVE DERBOGHOSIAN, Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The secret is not to close the cottage. That is, when you are
ready to close it for the winter next fall, keep the windows open
by an inch or so, making sure they are secure. You may have to
invest in burglar bars if you are to keep the windows open. Oh, you
have casement windows, that open like doors. Then leaving them open
is not practical. In that case, cut some vents in the walls, high
up near the ceiling. They can be any size, and being high up will
allow air to circulate well, releasing excess water vapor or
keeping it from building up in the first place, which was the cause
of the mold.
</P>
<P>
   For the mold there now, apply a mix of one part bleach and three
to five parts water. Paint it on and let it dry. Wear skin and eye
protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The tank in one of my toilets is dripping water; it is very
rusty, and is staining the floor. The water in the tank is clear,
so the water must be picking up rust from some other source. How
can I prevent it?
</P>
<P>
   S. S., Westborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. One of two things is happening.
</P>
<P>
   1. The tank drain (the opening where the water goes into the
bowl when the toilet is flushed) is leaking a bit, and the clear
water in the tank is running past rusting metal, picking it up as
it drips. The solution there is to tighten that drain connection;
there is a bolt on the bottom of the tank that you can turn.
</P>
<P>
   2. Water vapor is condensing on the cold tank and turning into
water; it gathers on the bottom of the tank and may be running into
a rusy bolt or other metal before it drips. The trick here is to
stop the condensation. You can have the tank lined with 1/4-inch
Styrofoam insulation. Or, wrap the tank with a terry cloth cover.
Some people have had good luck installing a mixing valve to bring a
bit of hot water into the tank. Ventilate the bathroom, using the
exhaust fan more often if you have one, or keeping a window and
door open, releasing a lot of water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your recipe of hydrogen peroxide and cream of tartar on the
stained bathtub worked beautifully. The bottom of the tub is
pristine again. But only the bottom. Your recipe required
sprinkling cream of tartar on the surface wetted with hydrogen
peroxide, but it does not stick to the sides and other vertical
surfaces. How can I treat them?
</P>
<P>
   PAT McNAMARA, Haverhill, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Vertical surfaces usually don't need treatment because they
are not dirty. But if yours does, make a paste of the hydrogen
peroxide and cream of tartar and smear this on the surface, leave
for an hour, scrub and rinse.
</P>
<P>
   Or smear on Ivory Shampoo, or Soft Scrub, let stand for an hour,
scrub and rinse. Someone called to tell us that Ivory Shampoo is
nowhere to be found. So, use any kind of shampoo. When you see what
it does to a stained bathtub, it boggles one's mind to consider
what it does to our hair and our scalps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My cedar deck is several years old and sound, but with a
rather bad finish on the floorboards. I had it sanded and it has
weathered a bit. A Sherwin-Williams representative told me to put a
sealer on it immediately. Is this necessary, now or ever?
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT PHELPS, Lincoln, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Not really. Cedar naturally resists decay, so there is no
need to preserve it. A sealer will make it more water resistant,
but if it is beginning to weather, it may turn the deck even
darker. Besides, a sealer is required every year, adding to the
chores you have to do for a so-called maintenance-free structure.
Weathering is what cedar does best, so why not let it? If you don't
think much of the sealer, or of weathering, apply one coat of a
semitransparent stain. You have a choice of earth colors, and in
three to five years you can do it again, with one coat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought a seasonal house. The dryer in that house vented
into the vertical plumbing stack. Can I do that with the dryer?
</P>
<P>
   CURIOUS
</P>
<P>
   A. No, no, a thousand times no. A dryer should be vented to the
outdoors. A gas dryer must be vented to the outdoors. Venting
anything other than the sewer system into a stack like that will
probably not hurt anything, but it is illegal to do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
