<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-19 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTIC PIECE TAKES A SWIPE AT HARVARD PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the current issue of The Atlantic Monthly, Christina Hoff
Sommers levels a withering accusation at Harvard professor Carol
Gilligan: Sommers says she tried four times to access the research
materials Gilligan used for her best-selling 1982 book, ``In a
Different Voice,'' and was rebuffed. The research that launched
Gilligan's career and won her tenure at Harvard, Sommers suggests,
is either too flawed to be shared with scholars, or does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishing, if true. But more astonishing is the fact that
neither Sommers nor the Atlantic ever contacted Gilligan to verify
their claim. A claim that proved to be, as we say in journalism,
too good to check. ``I was amazed they didn't call me,'' says
Gilligan. ``The research is all there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommers and Gilligan occupy the antipodes of the proto-academic
discipline known as gender studies. Gilligan's ``Voice,'' which
advances the unremarkable premise that women and men have different
moral sensibilities, has sold 600,000 copies and won her a $250,000
Heinz award for ``transform(ing) the paradigm for what it means to
be human.'' In 1994, Sommers, then at Clark University, set herself
up as the anti-Gilligan, with her own bestseller, ``Who Stole
Feminism?'' Sommers argued, convincingly, that the liberal
intelligentsia had hijacked gender studies, and she won a large
following among conservative women.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of her Atlantic article on the status of boy vs.
girl achievement studies, Sommers interrupts the narrative for an
attempted drive-by character assassination of Gilligan. She calls
Gilligan's research data ``tantalizingly inaccessible,'' and offers
two examples of her assistants asking Gilligan's own assistant for
the data. ``I made four attempts to reach Gilligan,'' Sommers told
me. But in fact she made none. All of the attempts were made by
factota who didn't reveal they were working on a book for Sommers.
The one example Sommers gave me is simply duplicitous: ``Dear
Professor Gilligan, I am a student at Harvard College and I'm doing
research involving your book . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly surprising, Gilligan says, that her assistant didn't
offer up her research transcripts to a purportedly interested
undergraduate. ``We signed confidentiality agreements with the
subjects of these interviews,'' Gilligan says. ``I'm not running a
secret operation, but we're not going to hand out raw data just
because some student calls up and asks for it.''
</P>
<P>
   By way of defending herself, Sommers says other scholars have
questioned Gilligan's research. (So what?) Her assistants would
have identified themselves, if asked, she says. But she fears that
the mere mention of her name would have tipped off Gilligan to
Sommers's intentions. (So what?) ``Did Woodward and Bernstein tell
Nixon what stories they were working on?'' Sommers asks. She seemed
startled to learn that yes, Woodward and Bernstein often checked in
with Nixon's press spokesman Ronald Ziegler.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't the Atlantic find it strange that Gilligan isn't quoted
defending herself against Sommers's dramatic accusation? ``Sommers
said to me that she tried unsuccessfully to reach Gilligan,''
reports story editor Michael Curtis. He says Sommers's article
wasn't subjected to the usual fact-checking scrutiny because it was
a book excerpt, not an assigned article. Gilligan will have to
defend herself in a letter to the editor, which won't attract quite
as much attention as Sommers's cover story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free plug
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life is much too short for me to read my friend Bob Cullen's new
book, ``Why Golf? The Mystery of the Game Revisited.'' Why golf?
Who cares? In his book, Bob purports to examine the intellectual
underpinnings of the sport, which are about as solid as the
intellectual underpinnings of gender studies, if you gather my
drift. Inevitably, a book like this will end up quoting John Updike
a lot, as he's one of the few bogeymen, other than Cullen himself,
who can string two coherent sentences together.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen also quotes liberally from Arnold Haultain's 1908 classic
``The Mystery of Golf,'' which has just been republished by
Houghton Mifflin. ``Mystery'' is a lovely book, written in a clear,
simple prose that any writer would envy. The inevitable afterword
by the aforementioned Updike shows how the language has suffered in
the past century. When the Bard of Beverly extols ``the fluid,
multiform, neo-Platonic complexity of golf,'' I think we can all
agree it's time to head for the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
