<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 CHRYSLER HAS A HIT WITH A CRUISE BACK IN TIME  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They seem to appear by the decade: cars that capture American
drivers and their current lifestyles. The Ford Mustang, the
Volkswagen Beetle, the Chrysler minivan, the Mazda Miata, and as
the millennium ended, Volkswagen's New Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive cults spring up around them. We wait in line to buy
them, often paying more to dealers than the manufacturers
recommend.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the Chrysler PT Cruiser, part truck, part minivan,
part Beetle. Today's hot car looking like the car that yesterday
might have sat idling outside a bank job.
</P>
<P>
   Drive the PT Cruiser in creeping morning traffic along the
avenue and a remarkable thing happens: other drivers motion for you
to lower your window because they want to talk about your car, even
as you roll along.
</P>
<P>
   Park it on a city street and a crowd gathers, extolling its look
with words they might use to describe the aura of that street
itself: hip and hot, sassy and sharp, funky and fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their idea was to get attention, they got attention,''
Kevin Kelly, a retail design and marketing man, says as he checks
out the Cruiser on Newbury Street in Boston this week. ``Look at
the cars along the street here. This one stands out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does, as people stop to run their hands along its
lines, pop the hood, open the trunk, sit inside and grab the wheel.
Nearby Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz and BMW autos go unnoticed, as does a
glistening Norton motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhere between a truck and a minivan,'' says Carolyn
Talley, a building supply store manager. ``I love this car.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler had hoped to sell 50,000 PT Cruisers annually. They
sold more than 8,000 last month, the first sales period, and
already there are six month-waiting lists to buy more. The company
is ramping up for annual sales that could reach 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   All this in the age of the thundering SUV, for a car that has a
modest four-cylinder engine, is not very big (though surprisingly
roomy), and has dealers adding $2,000 and more to the
manufacturer's suggested retail price, which ranges from $16,000 to
$20,000.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the low price surprised most people who stopped by in
Boston, where the Cruiser was parked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what, $30,000, $35,000?'' Talley asks when challenged to
guess the price for a Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Many were surprised by the size _ about that of a Beetle, though
with a higher, longer roofline. They had seen pictures of the
Cruiser in magazines, looking like a big four-door sedan out of the
1940s, and assumed it would be as big as those old cars _ or
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be the size of one of those monstrous SUVs,
which I hate,'' says Alan Fincke, a realty agent. ``It's compact.
It's really a sharp car.''
</P>
<P>
   What the PT Cruiser is, in fact, is a front-wheel drive vehicle
with moderate power and distinct styling, from its retro outer
shell down to its black on white gauges and Art Deco interior door
handles.
</P>
<P>
   It seats five adults _ four comfortably _ and its back seat
folds down, leaving van-like cargo space all the way into the
trunk. Its appeal crosses generations and demographics, from
students looking to hop into something hip to older couples looking
to recapture some essence of their automotive past.
</P>
<P>
   It is function in a form that seems to dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got that retro look,'' says Tom Zbruz, a graphic design
student. ``That's what got me.''
</P>
<P>
   His pal and fellow student, Luis Taforo, adds, ``It's hot. It's
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back in time in this thing,'' says Nick Raportoru, a
heating and air conditioning technician.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a PT Cruiser Web site _ ptcruiserclub.org _ has been
launched. Cruiser paraphernalia _ models, accessories, key chains _
abounds. On the Web site, owners and aficionados chat about the
car, swap customizing tips, information about Cruiser-related
events, and share pictures of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   All this over a car which is only now hitting the streets, a
modern phenomenon that Diane Peterson, a district manager for the
Pottery Barn, says, ``Looks most like a '40s gangster car.''
</P>
<P>
   Retro or modernist; minivan, truck or car; gangster wagon or
London taxi clone, the PT Cruiser has captured America's motoring
fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Luis Taforo as he runs his hands along a front fender in
tactile assessment of the styling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta catch me one of these,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0091 </DOCNO>
