<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SMALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CROOKS' A FUN TRIP BACK TO ALLEN'S EARLY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SMALL TIME CROOKS 
Written and directed by: Woody Allen 
Starring: Allen, Tracey Ullman, Elaine May, Hugh Grant, Jon Lovitz,
Michael Rappaport, Tony Darrow, George Grizzard, Elaine Stritch 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: PG (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks'' finds Woody Allen back in a comfortable
comic groove. It's probably the kind of movie people have in mind
when they wish he'd make movies like the ones he used to make.
Allen swears that ``Small Time Crooks'' is a very different
proposition than ``Take the Money and Run,'' that his new comedy
about criminal dimwits trying to engineer a bank job is
character-driven while the earlier one was gag-driven. True, you
don't expect Allen's nebbishy ex-con dishwasher named Ray to hand a
note to a bank teller, only to have the latter respond,
incredulously, ``This is a gub?'' Still, Ray isn't exactly light
years away from the earlier schlep, and neither is ``Small Time
Crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that makes it a lot funnier are the bookending
presences of Tracey Ullman as Ray's wife, Frenchy, an ex-stripper
turned manicurist, and Elaine May as her dim-bulb cousin, May.
Allen says he was worried about holding his own between these two
comic artists. It's not false modesty. May doesn't need gags. She's
hilarious just being a beat or two behind the rest of the world.
It's as if she hung an Out to Lunch sign around her neck years ago
and has never had reason to remove it. She's the queen of
obliviousness. Ullman's Frenchy is the patron saint of pushiness.
She's always putting in her two cents' worth. The joke here is that
her two cents' worth is worth millions.
</P>
<P>
   When Ray and his associates plan to rob a bank by renting the
store next door and tunnelling in through the basement, we think
we're in for a reworking of ``Big Deal on Madonna Street.'' And we
are, but only for five minutes. To cover the basement excavation,
Frenchy starts running a cookie shop out of the store above. The
bank job is literally a washout when Ray and the other diggers
encounter an unexpected outcome right out of silent comedy.
Meanwhile, the cookie boutique upstairs, intended as the merest of
fronts for the bank job, is a wild success. A cop too smart to be
bothered writing a report on the nonsense in the basement looks at
the customers lining up for Frenchy's cookies and gives Ray a word
of advice: ``Franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes its time achieving liftoff. And it's really two
films _ the first dealing with the bank caper, the second about
what happens to Ray and Frenchy after they strike it rich. Here,
too, the pace and energy levels aren't unflagging. ``Small Time
Crooks'' lasts maybe 10 minutes too long. But it's mostly pretty
funny, especially after Frenchy meets an art dealer and smooth
operator played by Hugh Grant and decides that a little social
climbing is in order. The mere sound of her pitch-perfect New
Yorkese was enough to set me laughing, and it's fun to watch Grant
oil his way through the role of the art-dealing shark, which
includes keeping a straight face when Frenchy's pronunciation of
crudites rhymes with Luddites.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a recapturing of the wistful appeal in some of
Allen's earlier films in Ray's rueful resignation to the
inevitability of at least a certain percentage of his life going
spectacularly wrong. Allen hasn't always played resignation; here
he plays it with throwaway charm, sometimes in surprisingly
delicate ways. When he's showing a visitor around his and Frenchy's
amusingly vulgar new digs, stuffed with antiques, he can't quite
get straight whether it's Louis XIV or Louis XV and wriggles out by
describing it as ``top Louis.'' ``Small Time Crooks'' may in the
end be small time Woody Allen, but it's the kind of movie you can
settle into, secure in the expectation that you can steal from it
more than a little vintage Allen fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9859 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      05-19 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYPRESS HILL STAYS REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cypress Hill has a warning for all those wannabes who think
they're going to find instant success in the rock and/or hip-hop
fields: ``It's a fun job, but it's still a job. And save your
money, too. . . . There's gonna be another cat coming out next year
sounding just like you.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning appears in the dual Cypress Hill hits, ``(Rap)
Superstar'' and ``(Rock) Superstar.'' They are actually the same
song with a different arrangement tailored for each market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving you a dose of reality,'' says Cypress Hill's
B-Real. ``We're talking about the hardships of the business,''
B-Real says of the double ``Superstar'' tunes _ the rap version of
which features guests Eminem and Noriega, while the rock version
has a guest cameo from Everlast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rewarding job and I wouldn't trade it, but you've
got to love what you do,'' says B-Real. ``You've got to deal with
the fact you might have a single the record label doesn't think
radio is going to play. And if radio won't play the single, then
the record label won't get behind your video.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've also got critics who are always going to bash you, so
you've got to be a strong-minded person. You've also got to be on
time with your interviews and your studio sessions, and keep a
rapport with your fans. When you're hot, you're hot. And when
you're not, this business lets you die a slow death.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Superstar'' tracks are on Cypress Hill's new double-CD,
``Skull and Bones,'' which were produced by DJ Muggs, another
founding member along with B-Real and Sen Dog. And not only are the
singles tailored for double markets, but so are the two CDs _ one a
pure hip-hip CD, the other a rap/rock hybrid (with screaming guitar
solos) along the lines of what's hot today with acts like Korn,
Limp Bizkit, and Rage Against the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never pursued (rock) very much before,'' says B-Real.
``We felt we needed to keep our roots firm in hip-hop. Some hip-hop
fans are not going to understand what we're doing. But maybe, with
time, they'll accept it or at least have that (rock) CD as a
collector's item. And some fans prefer the rock CD to the hip-hop
CD. But we're giving them the power of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cypress Hill was actually on the tip of the rap/rock crossover
trend when it recorded with Sonic Youth and Pearl Jam on the
``Judgment Night'' CD back in 1993, before Korn and Bizkit took
off. And let it be said that Rage Against the Machine also once
opened a tour for Cypress Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if these groups owe us anything,'' says B-Real.
``Maybe we were a source of some inspiration for them, just as when
we came up, Public Enemy and the Beasties were sources for our
inspiration. Now they all got to be on top of the game, because
it's competitive out there. But I like Limp Bizkit. I think their
stuff is pretty dope. And I like Korn and Rage Against the Machine.
Rage really perfected (rap/rock) and knocked the door wide open.
They made it possible for acts like Bizkit and Reveille to come
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' B-Real says of these crossovers. ``You
have to realize that rock and hip-hop are two musics that people
didn't think would be around for long. Both are rebellious musics
and people spoke out against them. Now you have them cross-mixing.
When you cross-mix two forms of music that people counted out from
day one, it can get interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wailing on: Although reggae pioneer Bob Marley died 19 years
ago, his band the Wailers continues to keep his legacy alive. Four
Wailers from that era _ Aston (Family Man) Barrett, Marcia
Griffiths, Al Andersen, and Earl Lindo _ are still singing his
songs of ``redemption, freedom, and roots,'' says Barrett, the
band's bassist who is in a fight to gain royalties from some of the
songs he says he co-wrote with Marley, including ``Easy Skankin',''
``War,'' and ``Survival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd write together after having a few joints to get the
inspiration going,'' says Barrett, whose group plays the Roxy
Thursday in a command-performance event with Gregory Isaacs and the
Skatalites. It's the strongest reggae bill of the season, now that
there's no more Reggae Sunsplash.
</P>
<P>
   The Wailers' latest album is a live disc, ``The Wailers,''
recorded in Negril, Jamaica. It's a fine, roots-flavored disc
blending new songs with versions of Marley's ``Lively Up Yourself''
and ``Buffalo Soldier,'' among others. It's available through the
group's Web site at www.wailers.com.
</P>
<P>
   As for his royalty battle, Barrett says he's trying to recoup
royalties from the Marley family (now headed by Bob's widow, Rita),
which won the rights to Marley's estate after a long court battle
with his record label. ``We just want something out of the
settlement,'' says Barrett, speaking for the Wailers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Wailers are touring six to eight months a year
``and carrying the music around internationally,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering in 2000: Jefferson Airplane's ``Volunteers'' album
from 1968 was one of the monumental records of the late 1960s. It
was the focal point of the band's appearance at Woodstock _ and is
being revived by surviving members Paul Kantner and Marty Balin
(who are now with the Jefferson Starship) at the House of Blues on
May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Volunteers' era was a year after the Summer of Love,''
says Kantner from his Bay Area home. ``It was when the flower
children grew thorns.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea to reprise ``Volunteers'' just ``bubbled up one day,''
notes Kantner, who says the band will do most of the album,
including the songs ``We Can Be Together,'' ``Good Shepherd,''
``The Farm,'' and ``Wooden Ships,'' written by Kantner with David
Crosby and Stephen Stills. The music will be ``semiacoustic,''
accenting vocal harmonies and 12-string guitar. ``I call it
gangster folk,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a misconception Kantner wants to clear up about the
record. ``People thought of it as a political album, but it was
really nonpolitical,'' he says. ``We felt there was no real point
of dealing with politics any more than dealing with nuns in a
Catholic school head-on, or dealing with the Hells Angels or the
police head-on. . . . We were just saying, `Look what's happening
in the streets,' not `Go burn something down.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
