<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ROAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T GO OUT OF YOUR WAY FOR `ROAD TRIP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ROAD TRIP 
Directed by: Todd Phillips 
Screenplay by: Phillips, Scot Armstrong 
Starring: Breckin Meyer, Seann William Scott, Amy Smart, Paolo
Costanzo, DJ Qualls, Rachel Blanchard, Anthony Rapp, Fred Ward, Tom
Green 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: R (strong sexual content, crude humor, language and drug
use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Road Trip'' wastes no time lowering the summer movie bar.
Aimed at the ``American Pie'' audience, it works hard and no less
brainlessly to top that film's juxtaposition of pie and
masturbation. Before its four college buddies frantically drive
from Ithaca to Austin to retrieve a sexually compromising video, it
ups the gross-out ante with humor tied to anal probes, toe-sucking,
sperm banks, the eating of live mice, and, in its piece de
resistance, a kind of intimacy between a nasty short-order cook and
a couple of pieces of French toast.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``American Pie,'' it's actually quite innocent beneath its
eruptions of biological and other uproar. In fact, if the gross-out
bits are the ones you're curious about, you can get most of those
from the trailer, including the car explosion scene. Even that's
part of the masturbatory fantasy that ``Road Trip'' represents. It
begins when Breckin Meyer's emotionally insecure wrestler and even
more academically insecure freshman, Josh, worries that his
girlfriend since childhood, now attending college in Texas, has
dumped him after he doesn't hear from her for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on his own campus he meets Amy Smart's blond,
uninhibited beauty. She, it soon develops, lives only to have sex
with him when he tells her he's available. The complications begin
when it turns out that she also likes to videotape her sex life.
Thanks to the wrestler's wacko friend, MTV's Tom Green, whose main
interest in life is watching a pet snake eat mice, the video gets
sent to the Austin girlfriend. Not that Josh altogether minded.
He's interested in the new girl and, with the help of his pals,
rationalizes that it isn't cheating if you're in different area
codes or were too wasted to remember the details.
</P>
<P>
   But when the lifelong girlfriend calls from Texas and says she
was away attending a relative's funeral, Josh hits the road. Along
for the ride are `American Pie'' veteran Seann William Scott, as
the loudmouth know-it-all; Paulo Costanzo's pothead, and DJ Qualls'
nerd, who's invited only because he has the use of his father's car
and the others have no alternative transporation. The airheads
trying to persuade one another they're party animals can drive the
film only so far before signs of strain deepen into fault lines
into which the film plunges, never to be seen again, except
repeatedly on video at frat mixers.
</P>
<P>
   It's all totally predictable, filled with manufactured raunch
posing as anarchy. Trying to be hip, it makes the quartet the butt
of a few jokes after they stop at a black frat house in Tennessee.
There, in an episode combining racism and sexism, the nerd
undergoes his long-awaited sexual initiation. A little later on,
the loudmouth becomes the butt of an unexpected experience with a
nurse. Before it's over, ``Road Trip'' falls back on Viagra jokes
and tidy resolutions, proving that you can miss just as easily when
you aim low as when you aim high. ``Road Trip'' occasionally wills
itself to rude, crude life. But most of the time it's pretty limp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1337EDT &QL; 
