<HEADER>
A9862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-STORM-BOS &LR;      05-19 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSE OF PLACE ENLIVENS MURDER TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
STORM TRACK 
By Margaret Maron 
Mysterious Press, 260 pp., $22.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the strong allures of mystery fiction is its generally
rich sense of place. Among its better practitioners, setting rises
to the level of character. It's my contention that well-chosen
mysteries are better than Baedeker's as guides for the adventurous
traveler. Just think of James Lee Burke's tangy, humid New Orleans
or Robert Parker's or William Tapply's gritty and romantic profiles
of Boston, Sara Paretsky's spiky Chicago, or John Straley's raw
Alaskan cityscapes. Such locales shape and shadow the lives of
their denizens while seeming fully alive themselves.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is relevant to ``Storm Track,'' by Margaret Maron.
Although this is the author's seventh Deborah Knott mystery, the
series is new to me, and a very nice surprise, too. It's set in the
flat land of central North Carolina in fictional Colleton County,
an earthy realm where the Old and New South overlap. Knott herself,
a former lawyer and now a district judge, is a hybrid, part of a
fairly prosperous professional circle but rooted in rustic
heritage. Her father was once a moonshiner, maybe still is, and the
pull of the land and the power of a specifically Southern sense of
family are among Maron's strongest attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Knott has 11 brothers, many of whom live nearby, leading to
sweetly chaotic get-togethers featuring a herd of pickup trucks,
the consumption of cold beer and fried chicken, and the percussion
of screen doors banging as close-knit people come and go.
</P>
<P>
   It is to her credit that Maron made me homesick for a place I
knew mainly as a child: I was born in the Tarheel State not far
from Maron's fictional locale, with its truck farms, barbecue
joints, and combination of simmering, longstanding racial tensions
and a widespread familiarity between blacks and whites uncommon in
much of the north.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Maron's characters seem to spring to life
with immediacy _ and this should be read as praise _ is their
provinciality. She connects them indelibly to conventions of place
and specific folksy forms of speech. People say ``though''
(pronounced thew) for through, use the double-conditional ``might
could,'' savor the vinegar in their pork barbecue, and load
coleslaw onto their hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good reason I haven't mentioned the plot of ``Storm
Track'' yet. Suspense and helpings of nasty violence are indeed a
part of Maron's arsenal, and she has a decent sense of story. But
that doesn't seem to hold the primacy it does for many, if not
most, other writers of successful mystery fiction. In fact, it's
not until a quarter of the way through the novel that we hear about
the murder of Lynn Bullock, a local nurse and notoriously cheating
wife, found strangled with her own black lingerie in the Orchid
Motel.
</P>
<P>
   The crime elicits concern, of course, but in small-town Southern
communities like this, such events are typically treated as macabre
shared distractions and fuel for wildfire gossip and moralizing.
</P>
<P>
   Says one suspect in the murder, a young lawyer and one of
Bullock's many lovers, ``I swear to God, she must've spent her
formative years studying `Dynasty' as if it were a documentary on
tasteful dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   More violence ensues when Bullock's elusive killer pursues a
black woman he believes witnessed him leaving the room of the
murder victim. By mistake, he ends up stalking Clara Freeman, the
wife of the new minister of Balm of Gilead. But typically, even
more engrossing than the suspense of the pursuit itself is Maron's
masterful treatment of the characters involved. And no two
characters in the populous ``Storm Track'' are more dynamically
drawn than this pious, God-fearing woman and her well-meaning,
guilt-riven husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Storm Track'' moves forward at a leisurely pace, in keeping
with the late-summer rhythms of the rural South. Yes, a storm is
bearing down on the state as the novel's action gradually
intensifies, a hurricane called Fran very much like the real Fran
of 1996. But while the people of Colleton County eventually buy
some bottled water and flashlight batteries, there's little of the
frantic energy and TV-induced panic familiar to storm-freaked New
Englanders.
</P>
<P>
   Maron seems more interested in the mysteries of character and
nature than the workings of crime and detection. She reverses the
usual formulation, exploiting the conventions of crime fiction to
dissect human relationships and celebrate the world that her fully
fleshed-out characters occupies.
</P>
<P>
   Although she does this extremely well, I recommend Maron with
one notable reservation (that may, admittedly, have something to do
with knowing only this one book in the series). ``Storm Track''
teems with characters _ brothers and countless cousins and
colleagues and numerous other folk, too. It's impossible to keep
track of them all _ even when they sport Southern-fried names like
Kidd and Kezzie and Tater and Skeeter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
