<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HAMLET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAMLET IN THE IMAGE OF KURT COBAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HAMLET 
Directed and adapted by: Michael Almereyda 
Starring: Ethan Hawke, Diane Venora, Liev Schreiber, Julia Stiles,
Bill Murray, Karl Geary, Steve Zahn, Dechen Thurman, Sam Shepard 
Running time: 111 minutes 
Rated: R (some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually, the plunking of Shakespeare into a contemporary setting
just means a lazy director trying to look hip while covering for
the vocal inadequacies of an insufficiently trained cast. But
Michael Almereyda's ``Hamlet'' is a refreshing exception. He not
only solves the problem of throwing an arresting ``Hamlet'' onto
the big screen with a tiny budget. He and his cast, with a suitably
brooding, recessive Ethan Hawke in the title role, persuasively
connect with the energies in Shakespeare's tragedy. Literally, they
pick the play up and run with it. Working fast and rough, like a
pavement artist furiously trying to finish a chalk drawing before
looming rain clouds wash everything away, Almereyda's ``Hamlet'' is
a restless, urgent encounter with this protean text.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a hurtling series of images, racing to keep up with
what's being detonated by the language. Although the text is
trimmed, few filmed versions of ``Hamlet'' seem as alive to the
words. Never does this version unfold as the usual series of set
pieces. This is a situational ``Hamlet,'' hung on a viable conceit
in a Manhattan divided between midtown suits _ career-agenda types
preening and puffing through their sterile glass-and-steel citadels
of power _ and downtown grunge. Hawke, in a pond-scum goatee and
chic pointy knit wool patterned hat from the politically correct
side of the Arctic Circle, is, naturally enough, a filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Which, in the contemporary world of this ``Hamlet,'' means he
has two problems. The first, of course, is Hamlet's usual disgust
at his newlywed mother and uncle, both too in love with advancement
to be in love with each other. They married before the body of
Hamlet's father was cold, and in fact were the ones who chilled the
dead king. Hamlet's second problem is image overload and sensory
bombardment pounding his head. At one point, an overhead jet drowns
out a speech. MovieFone eclipses another. The ``Oh what a piece of
work is man'' soliloquy comes from a laptop. And the
videocam-toting Hamlet ironically delivers ``To be or not to be''
from a Blockbuster Video's action film aisle.
</P>
<P>
   He lives downtown in a cozy underlit book and image-strewn grad
student's apartment. He has little use for the film's Elsinore
Hotel or Denmark Corporation _ in an office slab where Sam
Shepard's Ghost, spotted by a security guard, inhabits a backstairs
Pepsi machine. Hamlet is tortured because he really doesn't want to
kill his mother and uncle, although he enjoys unnerving them when
he doubles as Player King and makes them sit through his accusatory
video. This malaise-ridden Hamlet convinces us he knows from weary,
stale, flat and unprofitable. Hawke has said he grew up admiring
Olivier's Hamlet. But he doesn't regenerate Olivier's febrile
intensity. He's conflicted, but imploded _ a Hamlet in the image of
Kurt Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Almereyda's devices and transpositions work. But he
catches you up in a chase after the play's existential core. His
casting is a plus, too. Diane Venora, who may be the only Gertrude
to also have played Hamlet (and, less remarkably, Ophelia), easily
sketches the queen's uneasy suspension between ambition and
conscience. Kyle MacLachlan, with his Nutcracker profile, sleekly
conveys Claudius' strongest emotion, namely, annoyance at the
perpetual grad student taking the fun out of his corporate
takeover. Julia Stiles' pasty-faced, sullen Ophelia, trying to hide
her upper-crust status under an East Village wardrobe, seems the
one who's really trapped. And Bill Murray surpasses Polonius' usual
addled interference to project a sleazy insider's arrogance, unable
to see that he's in over his head when he sends his daughter to
Hamlet wearing a wire. Almereyda snatches surprising amounts of
sponetaneity from the film's world of media overkill. This is a
sizzling, invigorating ``Hamlet.'' Even when its conceits only play
like conceits, it's alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9867 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-MATCHBOX-BOS &LR;      05-19 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MATCHBOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHBOX TWENTY SWIMS THE MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mr. Grammy Man.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Rob Thomas's mates in Matchbox Twenty now kiddingly
call him after he won three Grammys for his collaboration with
Carlos Santana on ``Smooth,'' including song of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is now a celebrity, but a reluctant one whose band
members are merciless in their rib-tickling abuse. As Thomas
observes, ``Whenever I'll say to our drummer, Paul (Doucette), that
I think you're rushing that drum fill, he'll answer, `Oh, I'm
sorry, Grammy-O. Excuse me.' But it's all in fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is our friend and this gives us something to use against
him,'' says Doucette, laughing. ``Throughout all of this, Rob has
been like that wild-eyed kid who is thrown into his favorite toy
store.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grammy focus, while on singer Thomas rather than on the
band, has actually been a way for Matchbox Twenty (whose new album
``Mad Season'' comes out Tuesday) to grow closer.
</P>
<P>
   That became clear when Thomas, who dropped out of high school
and hitchhiked around the South before the Orlando-based Matchbox
was formed, turned down the cover of Rolling Stone because the
editors wanted him on the front without the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know who we are. And I know that without one member of this
band, we wouldn't be Matchbox Twenty,'' Thomas says of the
musicians formerly known as Matchbox 20. They now like the number
written out because that was the original spelling before Atlantic
Records asked to change it. That was before they sold 10 million
copies of their 1996 debut album, ``Yourself or Someone Like You,''
which spun off the hits ``Real World,'' ``3 a.m.,'' and ``Push,''
while giving the band the freedom to do what it wanted this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Such freedom, coupled with a larger studio budget that enabled
the band to hire orchestral string players on several tracks, led
to more studio experimentation and caused some of ``the big,
catchy, poppy numbers to get left off the record this time. They
just didn't fit what we were trying to say with this album,'' says
Thomas, whose group plays Avalon next Thursday during a
get-reacquainted tour.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Matchbox Twenty has too much of a pop sensibility to
suddenly make an esoteric album. The new disc gambles with some
arrangements _ lovers of the first record may not like everything
here, especially the gushy ``Last Beautiful Girl'' and moody ``Rest
Stop'' _ but there remain enough radio-friendly pop hooks to assure
maximum mainstream appeal, as on the midtempo ``Bed of Lies'' (``I
don't want to be somewhere I don't belong'') and the ballad ``If
You're Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   And the mainstream is right where Matchbox Twenty wants to be.
They don't fit in with manufactured teen idols like Britney,
Christina, and the Backstreet Boys, nor do they fit with the
opposite extreme _ the aggressive bad boys from Korn to Kid Rock.
But they've got their own niche.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world needs a left and a right _ and a right down the
middle,'' says Thomas. ``And we're right down that middle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wanted to make the same record again, though,'' he
adds. ``When we sat down this time, we said, `Wow, we sold a lot of
records. Let's pat overselves on the back, and let's move on and
see who we are now.' We had to start all over. Because in the end,
you look around and you see so many great bands who aren't selling
records. It puts a perspective on what selling records means. You
realize that that was then, and this is now and that you're
starting over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not to make myself a place in the celebrity world, and
it's not for us to try to get on the top of the heap. It's all
about being able to stand up proud and say `Listen to my record, I
like my record.' Because in the end, I think when musicians make
records, what they're really thinking about is that other musicians
and songwriters are going to listen to that record. I want to know
that the people I respect would listen to this and say, `This is a
good record.' Nothing more. That's the reason you do it. I think
you have to have a little bit of an ego just to have the audacity
to think that people want to hear what you're doing. The ego's not
a bad thing at all _ everyone has it. It's what you do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Matchbox did was to increase, not diminish, the democracy
of the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go in and just jam. We would take a song and start
playing it and everybody would throw in ideas on the direction they
thought it should take,'' Thomas says. ``Let each person do what
they do. That's why you're in a band.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also why he's not interested in making a solo record,
despite industry pressure to do so after his Grammy success.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, I can't imagine playing music without these
guys,'' he says. ``It's an unbelievable thing if you have five guys
that you trust and it works like a machine. Everybody takes care of
different things and everybody is watching each other's back. It's
good to have that security, to know you're not in this alone.''
</P>
<P>
   However, don't look for Matchbox Twenty to play 200-plus gigs a
year anymore _ a pace the group set while becoming successful.
Lifestyle changes have occurred since the first record _ Thomas has
gotten married and guitarist Kyle Cook has a new baby _ so Matchbox
won't be quite the same road warriors of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do something that makes everyone happy and
comfortable,'' says Mr. Grammy Man. ``We're a family band and all
of us are in this together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
