<HEADER>
A9868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-DINOSAUR-BOS &LR;      05-19 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DINOSAUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF TO SEE THE LIZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
DINOSAUR 
Directed by: Ralph Zondag, Eric Layton 
Screenplay by: John Harrison, Robert Nelson Jacobs 
With the voices of: D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard, Ossie Davis, Max
Casella, Hayden Panettiere, Samuel E. Wright, Julianna Marguiles,
Peter Siragusa, Joan Plowright, Della Reese 
Running time: 82 minutes 
Rated: PG (intense images) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dinosaurs are natural movie stars. To paraphrase Al Franken,
they're big enough, they're reptilian enough, and, doggone it,
people like them. In Disney's new ``Dinosaur,'' they've got
virtually everything. For its first two-thirds, the film is a small
miracle of freshness in an image-overloaded world, hitting our eyes
with a sense that it's moving movies forward a step, like
``Jurassic Park,'' like ``The Matrix,'' like ``Toy Story.'' The
ever-advancing world of computer graphics renders the awesome
beasts with hitherto unknown degrees of subtlety and detail. When a
gigantic brachiosaur trudges forward, its flesh, suspended from a
massive backbone, sways slowly. When other dinosaurs open their
mouths and bellow, the skin stretched between their upper and lower
jaws vibrates.
</P>
<P>
   What's also new is the way the keyboard wizards blend the
computerized dinos with actual landscapes. These backgrounds are in
some cases computer-enhanced _ a sky or a river may be painted in
or touched up. But Disney's cameras roamed the world for locations
_ Samoa, Australia, Venezuela, Hawaii, and Jordan as well as
Florida and California. It makes for a certain grandeur. The cattle
drive in ``Red River'' never had the spaciousness of this herd of
dinosaurs trekking across a vast desert on their way back to their
nesting grounds after a meteor shower decimates them _ and nearly
kills this film's protagonist, an iguanosaur named Aladar (voiced
by D.B. Sweeney).
</P>
<P>
   Disney being Disney, the film anthropomorphizes the dinosaurs.
They speak. They also scramble time lines by coexisting with
mammals. But at least they don't sing. And they're not made
insufferably cute. The film echoes previous Disney animations, most
notably ``Bambi'' and ``Tarzan,'' when Aladar's mother is killed by
a toothy carnosaur before he's even hatched from his egg. After the
egg is borne on a dizzying journey by a prehistoric bird, and
Aladar emerges, he's raised by a family of furry lemurs. He's Bambi
with scales. Cute, but, like Bambi, not insulated from cruel forces
of nature. When flaming meteors torch the lemurs' island, the
adolescent Aladar is big enough to carry his adoptive family on his
back while he swims to the next landfall.
</P>
<P>
   Before he joins a migrating tribe of his own kind, he must
outrun a colony of vicious little raptors nipping at his
hindquarters. Bringing up the rear of the trek, he's put in his
place by the leader of the pack, Kron, a dinosaur in the figurative
sense as well as the literal one, and Kron's right-hand man,
Bruton. Ironically, considering the limited future of the
dinosaurs, hard-liner Kron takes a Darwinian view, pushing ahead
with a survival-of-the-fittest policy, not unreasonable considering
the world he lives in, and the fact that he must stay ahead of
carnosaurs. Samuel E. Wright brings the right tonal weight and
crustiness to Kron, while Peter Siragusa's voice convinces us that
Bruton is anchored in Kron's perspective, but concedes possible
merit to Aladar's. Bruton's sister (voiced by Julianna Margulies)
feels the young dinosaur may be the one to lead the herd to the
future, that his patience with weaker, slower dinosaurs and his
openness to teamwork may be the way to go as the film heads into
``Lion King'' territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur'' is a fable, and a hugely and sometimes wondrously
watchable one, even if its emotions retreat to certain levels of
programmed predictability as the film proceeds. Amid the splendors
of its dinosaur's-eye view of the world, ``Dinosaur'' throws some
violent images at kids, but they're justifiable; the film would be
dishonestly saccharined without them. One thing that's certain is
that Disney is not just releasing its usual summer animation with
``Dinosaur.'' It's a bold leap, but a necessary one, to an entirely
new level of animation and a new kind of artifice. Otherwise,
Disney would itself risk becoming an entertainment dinosaur. But
Disney's new animation studio, kept under wraps for six years,
emphatically passes the test with ``Dinosaur.'' Throughout the
history of film, nothing turns campier faster than dinosaur movies.
This one will have a much longer shelf life than most.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
