<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES AT THE MARCH: MOTHERS AND POLICE OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The deafening roar had nothing to do with the
Million Mom March. The timing was still perfect.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks away from the main stage on the Mall, scores
of people milled around the National Gallery of Art, waiting for
friends and relatives to arrive at the rally. Just before noon,
just as the first speakers began railing about gun violence, a
quaking rumble and piercing sirens compelled the throng around the
National Gallery to turn their heads away from the Mall and walk
back out onto where Constitution Avenue meets Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The stir was caused by 2,500 police officers on motorcycles,
riding in pairs. They came from Cincinnati, Dayton, and Chelsea.
They came from places as wealthy as Greenwich, Conn., and as
riddled with poverty as Washington, D.C., itself.
</P>
<P>
   The officers were of all colors. They smiled and waved at the
crowd of all colors, which waved back. Their motorcade held up
people trying to get to the Million Mom March for 15 minutes. No
one seemed to care. Rare are the moments that police and masses of
people are relaxed enough to enjoy each other.
</P>
<P>
   The procession was part of National Police Week, to remember the
14,000 American cops who have been shot and killed since 1792. As
the police headed to their own sober festivities, it was fitting
how they skirted so close to the Million Mom March.
</P>
<P>
   One of the speakers at the march was Mary Ann Viverette, a vice
president of the International Association of Chiefs of Police and
police chief in Gaithersburg, Md. Unlike Rosie O'Donnell, Sarah
Brady or even children's singer Raffi, Viverette received no
mention in the next day's news. The media may have missed on of the
march's most powerful allies. It must be a sad day for the National
Rifle Association when mothers who have lost their children and
cops who have lost their colleagues to gun violence get together.
</P>
<P>
   Viverette said the IACP wants thorough background checks on gun
purchasers, and that shorter ones, as desired by the gun lobby,
sacrifice ``the safety of our communities and potentially
jeopardizes the people we are sworn to serve. The police chiefs of
this country want the violence to stop. The Million Mom March has
the same goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Williams, former police director of Newark, N.J., and
president of the Police Foundation, a law enforcement research
group, said several staff members went to the rally. He has argued
for fewer guns on the streets, saying they are regulated less than
cars, children's pajamas, and teddy bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that the NRA and other organizations that have
been standing up for gun rights with no restrictions can withstand
this tidal wave that will spring up in the future,'' Williams said.
``If I were running for president, I would now have to really think
hard about my position on guns. There's no safe haven now for
legislators on unfettered rights to weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no safe haven particularly if the organizers of
the Million Mom March can exploit their common ground with the
police at election time. If they organize right, they can do what
few people have been able to do, to force politicians to choose
between the NRA and the people and the police.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians, particularly law and order conservatives, love
photo-ops with the police at the same time they take money from the
NRA.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the IACP, the Police Foundation, and the Police Executive
Research Forum support gun measures supported by the vast majority
of Americans, but blocked by the conservatives who have kept
Congress from enacting any gun legislation since the massacre at
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   The police organizations support serious background checks,
waiting periods and closing the loop hole where firearms can be
purchased at gun shows without such checks. They also support
trigger locks and measures to get firearms out of the hands of
juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the march as 750,000 people who came to speak for
victims who no longer can speak for themselves,'' said Mary Malina,
communications director of the Police Foundation, who attended the
Million Mom March. ``We all have a stake. We all are affected by
gun violence. Ask an emergency room physician. Ask a cop who never
knows if someone has a gun. There's a natural symbiosis not just
between cops and mothers, but with public health officials, all of
us. Maybe there a real silent majority on the issue of gun
control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
