<HEADER>
A9870 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-REFUGEE-SCHOLARSHIPS-     05-19 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-SCHOLARSHIPS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FORMER JAPANESE INTENREES CARRY ON WITH SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Few of the sons and daughters of Asian immigrants who
will pick up $1,000 scholarships in a ceremony at the University of
Massachusetts in Boston this weekend any idea where the money is
coming from, or why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about Southeast Asian kids _ Lao, Vietnamese, Hmong,''
said Xeng Her, whose Hmong people fled the hill country between
Vietnam and Laos after the Vietnam War. ``It's like niss-eye or
something. I can't really pronounce it. Probably some Asian
organization helping students.''
</P>
<P>
   Her, 17, who will use his award to study science at Bridgewater
State College, is mostly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The people behind his scholarship, and 29 other scholarships
being awarded to children of immigrant families throughout eastern
Massachusetts are in fact nisei (pronounced knee-say) _
second-generation Japanese-Americans. And the awards, the
recipients, and the donors, all are part of a story that is
profoundly American.
</P>
<P>
   The nisei were among 120,000 Japanese-Americans yanked from
their homes, businesses, and campuses on the West Coast during
World War II and confined in barbed-wire-encircled camps by a US
government doubtful of their loyalty. In response, religious and
academic leaders appalled at the racist injustice were forming a
group to get the young men and women whose educations had been
interrupted back to school.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Fumio Robert Naka went from being a UCLA sophomore,
to internee, to degrees at universities in Missouri, Minnesota, and
Massachusetts. He also went from being classified as of doubtful
loyalty to earning a top security clearance, helping develop
stealth avionics and ending his government career as chief
scientist for the US Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in America,'' said Naka, who now lives in semiretirement
in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 nisei were able to continue their educations as a
result of volunteers who helped them get FBI clearances, money for
living expenses, and scholarships from universities that still were
willing to accept people of Japanese heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is payback for us,'' said Glenn Kumekawa, who
attended Bates College in Lewiston, Maine, through the efforts of
volunteers who organized as the National Japanese American Student
Relocation Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time we are helped, we often don't appreciate the
opportunity that is given to us,'' said Kumekawa, who became an
urban planner, a University of Rhode Island professor, and director
of the Coalition of Northeast Governors. ``Only much later did we
understand, at a time of tremendous anti-Japanese, anti-Asian
feeling, the effort that had to be exerted'' to get the students
out of camps and back to campus.
</P>
<P>
   That effort ``was an affirmation of decency and fair play,'' he
said. ``I am stunned when I go back and look at the efforts that
were made.''
</P>
<P>
   The deep connection to that effort is shared by John W. Nason,
who during World War II was president of Swarthmore College, near
Philadelphia, and chairman of the volunteer effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look back over a kind of varied career,'' said Nason, who
is 95, ``I think of what I did in the student relocation council as
the one most-significant thing I've done in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nason is particularly pleased that the Japanese-Americans _ whom
he still calls ``the students'' _ now are helping Southeast Asian
students. ``It demonstrates what we hoped to accomplish,'' he said.
Rather than feel angry and hostile, ``as they have every right to
feel. . . they feel so much a part of the country and so concerned
about those less privileged than themselves. . .''
</P>
<P>
   To the nisei, the decision to focus on Southeast Asians was an
easy one, having little to do with race, and a lot to do with need.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were uprooted from their homes, they were sent to camps,
they were resettled far away and had to adjust to their
resettlement,'' Kamekawa said. ``There is a parallel.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of doing something as payback for the support given the
nisei arose in the early 1980s, at a picnic 15 nisei attended on
the blueberry farm of Lafayette H. Noda, a professor of
biochemistry at Dartmouth College. It became a favorite project of
Kamekawa's sister, Nobu Hibino, who completed her undergraduate
degree at Boston University after she was forced to leave the
University of California at Berkeley. Soon afterward, she helped
start the Nisei Student Relocation Commemorative Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, the nisei were involved in a tense debate
over a new movement to press the US government for an apology and
compensation for the wartime internments, which enabled whites in
the West to buy up Japanese homes, farms, and businesses for
pennies on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Many nisei wanted not to stir up the past; others thought an
apology would be enough. Harvard Law School Professor Alan M.
Dershowitz, whom they consulted, persuaded them to insist on
compensation because, as Dershowitz put it this week, ``if no sense
of pain felt by those who do these things, the apologies are
hollow.''
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz recalled meeting with a big group of people concerned
about the issue, and applauded the actions of the well-to-do nisei
who, when $20,000 per person compensation began to be paid, donated
theirs to the relocation commemoration fund. He said he is urging
Holocaust survivors who have become prosperous to put compensation
paid to them into a fund for victims of contemporary holocausts.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, Naka, the internee who became a defense
intelligence specialist, had dinner with former Secretary of the
Air Force John McLucas, a friend of nearly 30 years with whom Naka
had worked on top-secret projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Bob, were you ever evacuated?' and I said
`yeah,' '' Naka recalled. ``He said, `all these years we worked
together, I never had the nerve to ask.' Then he said, `Only in
America. Anywhere else, you'd have been blackballed for the rest of
your life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I think too,'' Naka said. ``Only in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1346EDT &QL; 
