<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9874 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-PROFILE-IRISH-HN     05-19 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PROFILE-IRISH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AUTHOR MAKES WAVES WITH BOOK ON IRISH HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was an idle Thursday afternoon at the Albany
Ancient Order of Hibernians hall. The drink was Guinness Extra
Stout. The food was corned beef sandwiches. The crowd was cops and
politicos. The talk was Irish history.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Golway, author of a new book celebrating 1,000 years of
Ireland's heroes, was preaching to the choir.
</P>
<P>
   Golway invoked the names of Wolfe Tone, Padraig Pearse and other
iconic figures in what he called ``the trauma, the triumph and the
tragedy of Irish history.''
</P>
<P>
   Golway's ``For the Cause of Liberty'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26),
for which he received a six-figure advance after three publishing
houses engaged in a bidding war, is meant as unabashedly
revisionist history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Irish history is told by academic or British
journalists,'' said Golway, himself a journalist with the New York
Observer, an edgy and irreverent Manhattan weekly. ``Readers get
the idea that the Irish were either crazed or terrorists. Guys in
trenchcoats and ski masks. Anything but heroic.''
</P>
<P>
   Golway said the book has received a negative reaction in
England. ``I was trying to shed the same light on Ireland as
historians do on American freedom fighters like George
Washington,'' Golway said.
</P>
<P>
   He made several trips to Ireland to research the book, including
an interview with Nobel Prize-winning Irish poet Seamus Heaney.
They met in a pub and drank whiskey. Golway's entree came by way of
delivering the poet some Cuban cigars _ ``perfectly legal in
Ireland,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three and maybe four whiskeys,'' Golway, at least in
this telling, was sufficiently lubricated to attempt to edit a line
from a Heaney poem into more grammatical usage.
</P>
<P>
   Golway suffers the copy editor's curse. The 44-year-old Staten
Island native worked as a sports reporter at the Staten Island
Advance, as a sports copy editor at the New York Post, editor at
the Empire State Report and, for the past 10 years, as city editor
and political columnist at the New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   He interprets the political machinations of New York City in
810-word columns under the inherited title ``Wise Guys.'' ``It's
dangerous for a blowhard columnist to go much more than 810
words,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One hot topic of the moment for his Albany crowd was the recent
breakthrough in the negotiations for peace in Northern Ireland
following the Irish Republican Army's historic promise to ``put IRA
arms beyond use'' and to allow independent observers to inspect the
IRA's hidden arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's unprecedented pledge appeared to clear the way for a
resumption of the aborted power-sharing government. Britain took
back self-rule after implementation of the 1998 Good Friday peace
accord derailed. The troubled six-county northern province of
Ulster has been decimated by decades of sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I end my book on the positive note of the Good Friday peace
accord, which may be the first book of Irish history with a happy
ending,'' Golway said. ``I think Gerry Adams has done an
unbelievable thing to convince an unbeaten guerrilla army to put
the guns away and try politics. He put his own life on the line for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Golway credited the economic surge of the Republic of Ireland,
nicknamed ``The Celtic Tiger,'' with helping to lay the groundwork
for the peace process. ``The shipyards in Belfast are rotting away,
unemployment in Northern Ireland is around 18 percent and being a
privileged Protestant there has gotten young people nowhere,''
Golway said.
</P>
<P>
   He has observed Protestant youths riding a train named the
Enterprise from Belfast to Dublin to shop. ``They see these young
computer programmers in the Republic driving BMWs and living in
mansions and seeing everything they don't have in the north,''
Golway said. ``There will come a time when that border won't mean
anything to the young generation. Brittania doesn't rule the waves
anymore. The European Union is changing the landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   After publishing three books of Irish history, in the past five
years, Golway is taking a break from the long form. ``I want to
relax with my family this summer and not worry about working on a
book,'' said Golway. His wife, Eileen Duggan, stays at home with
their two children, Kate, 6, and Conor, 5. They live in Maplewood,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Both Golway and his wife grew up on Staten Island. Both their
fathers were firefighters, but they worked in different precincts
and didn't know each other. Neither did Golway and Duggan, who met
as adults in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscences about favorite pubs peppered the afternoon's talk.
Golway occasionally joins at a Manhattan watering hole the First
Friday Club, an informal gathering of Irish-American writers and
others that includes Frank and Malachy McCourt, Peter Quinn, Dennis
Smith and William Kennedy when he's in the Big Apple. They used to
meet at Eamon Doran's pub, but that closed. So did Tommy Makem's
place. Even the group's dynamic has changed. ``I'd say business
people now outnumber writers three to one,'' Golway said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCourt was an integral member in pre-``Angela's Ashes''
days, when he was simply a retired New York City high school
teacher. ``We knew Frank was working on a memoir, but who knew what
it would become?'' Golway recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Golway and McCourt shared a reality check at this year's St.
Patrick's Day party at the White House, hosted by President
Clinton. ``We both just couldn't believe where we were,'' Golway
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0102 </DOCNO>
