<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-KATHY-MATTEA-HNS &LR;      05-19 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KATHY-MATTEA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AFTER HIATUS, COUNTRY SINGER RETURNS WITH `INNOCENT YEARS' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GOODSPEED  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If fans of country singer Kathy Mattea are upset that it's been
more than three years since her last album, they won't be when they
hear why.
</P>
<P>
   They also won't be disappointed when they hear what she learned
from her ordeals on ``The Innocent Years,'' released earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   First, her mother, Ruth, was gravely ill. Then her father, John,
was diagnosed with terminal colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. Her record company, Mercury, got a new
owner, which always casts doubt on an artist's future. Capping the
long, emotional roller-coaster ride, last June she turned 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those things combined made me reassess my life,''
Mattea said in a phone interview from her home in Nashville, Tenn.
``When you are helping one of the people you love most in the world
re-evaluate their life and death, you can't help but re-evaluate
your own.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting album took on a life of its own as she threw out
songs she had been planning to include, added others and began
writing for the first time in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an album about getting to the essence of what life's
about and living as a grownup in the real world with your eyes
open,'' said Mattea, who has earned two Grammys, five Country Music
Association awards and four Academy of Country Music awards plus 16
Top 10 singles since signing with Mercury in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Topics of the 11 songs on ``The Innocent Years'' include the
loss of youth on the title cut; surviving the Depression on ``Why
Can't We''; finding lasting, true love on ``I Have Always Loved
You''; and that love guiding a couple through death's final embrace
on ``That's the Deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way the album hangs together thematically and looks
at a common theme from many points of view,'' Mattea said. ``That
is something I was able to accomplish on this record that was a
rare thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that the CD is a mournful look at morbid
topics. Musically, it's Mattea's blend of country, folk, bluegrass
and Celtic influences. And Mattea's solid vocal interpretations and
ever-present positive outlook permeate, as on the first single, the
uptempo, melodic ``Trouble With Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bounce around to it and everything but if you really
listen to it it's about faith and how God doesn't really answer our
prayers in the way we expect him to,'' Mattea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes God can see the picture in a way you can't. And many
times in my life things I thought were disasters turned out to be
blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   Her family's crisis is an example.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, her father's goal for the day was to get out of
bed and crawl to a chair to watch television so he would not be
bed-ridden. After operations and chemotherapy, his cancer is in
remission. He's approaching 80, playing golf several times a week
and lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother struggled with a number of health problems that now
are under control.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Mattea and her songwriter husband of 12
years, Jon Vezner, began writing together _ the title track and
``Callin' My Name.'' More are in the works, and they're trying to
have a baby.
</P>
<P>
   She also stopped worrying about things that used to bother her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a sense that life is a real finite thing and how
precious it is. I didn't want to waste time and energy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mattea considers the title track the album's centerpiece. It
works on many levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a metaphor for society and where we're headed and
the sense that people can't grow up as innocently as they did once
_ and the things we've lost along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   She also took a bigger role as co-producer, which allowed bolder
strokes for her artistic vision.
</P>
<P>
   Mattea ranks the album among her best, a high point on a road
she began traveling when she started singing in church in her
hometown of Cross Lanes, W.Va. She moved to Nashville in 1978 as
part of a bluegrass band and worked a number of jobs, including a
stint as a tour guide at the Country Music Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Her job as a demo singer for songwriters eventually landed her a
contract with Mercury, and Mattea moved into the fast lane. Part of
the journey included a performance on the South Lawn of the White
House for President Clinton, a gig she landed with the help of one
of her fans _ Vice President Al Gore, who used to catch her act
when he was a senator from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Mattea is planning to hit the road soon in support of ``The
Innocent Years,'' on tour with Asleep at the Wheel; there's also a
European tour, a Christmas tour and the beginnings of her next
album.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, though, she'll remember the lessons of her
parents _ and especially her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad struggled to live because he loves us, but his life is
simple. He has a garden, putters in the yard, plays golf,'' Mattea
said. ``We forget that the essence of life is really in the simple
things but we can get caught up in so much other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay grounded and live like a real human being.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Goodspeed can be reached by e-mail at
jgoodspeed(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
