<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-TEXAS-FISHING-HNS &LR;      05-19 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FISHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CATFISH PARADISE FOUND AT TEXAS RESERVOIR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RALPH WININGHAM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THREE RIVERS, Texas _ Weaving in and out of gnarled, weathered
tree limbs that poke through the surface of Choke Canyon Reservoir
sometimes makes a person wonder how such a bleak-looking site could
be so popular.
</P>
<P>
   Although the above-the-surface appearance is less than eye
appealing, what lurks below is something fishing dreams are made
of, particularly for the summer and early fall months. This is as
close to a catfish paradise as anyone can imagine, and with just a
little luck and the right equipment, the result can be a big fish
fry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no telling how many blues and channel cats are in
here,'' guide Charles Brown said during a recent early morning
outing at Choke Canyon, 50 miles south of San Antonio. ``I'd like
to have someone with an underwater camera film under here just to
see how many catfish are in this lake. I think it would be scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's method of catching enough catfish for a monster fish fry
is simple and similar to most of the guides and other fishermen who
work over the lake each summer.
</P>
<P>
   He uses a single hook _ the Daiichi Bleeding Bait Circle Wide
hooks work particularly well _ on a 6-inch piece of leader line
topped by a small slip sinker. The hook is dipped into a bucket of
smelly cheese bait and gently lowered into the water. After the
bait hits bottom, the line is cranked up about 1 or 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Brown wraps his hooks with a small piece of polyester batting,
like that used to stuff pillows, in order to keep the cheese bait
on the hook. He also makes his own bait, like several other guides
at Choke, although the main ingredient in any of the concoctions
seems to be stink.
</P>
<P>
   This type of fishing is not brain surgery. When something tries
to take the bait, you set the hook and crank the fish into the
boat. If the catfish is 12 inches or longer, it goes into the fish
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one gets to make the trip home,'' Brown said time after
time during our fishing foray.
</P>
<P>
   Each fisherman is allowed to keep 25 fish, most of which will
range from a little more than a pound up to 2 or 3 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger fish move into the shallows, but not in the numbers
that you will find in water that is 10 to 15 feet deep,'' Brown
said. ``It's not unusual to limit out on the little ones like
these, but an average catch of bigger fish in shallow water is
about 10 or 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Although our trip began at 7 a.m. and we were back in the dock
at 2:30 p.m. with 60 keepers, Brown said catfish can be fickle and
bite at any time of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said his favorite fishing holes are ``the ones near the
dead tree stumps.'' Like most of the guides, he has his spots that
seem to hold fish and he can easily find them in areas of the lake
that all look the same to anyone who has not spent years on the
water.
</P>
<P>
   He added that with the lake level about 21 feet low, boaters
have to be cautious when running around looking for fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of fishing is really good for kids and people who
just want to put a lot of fish in the boat,'' he said. ``It's easy
and fun. Fishing shouldn't be work.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting moments during our trip was watching
a swarm of honeybees sweep across the sky just a few feet above our
heads. The bees were spread out across an area of about 30 feet and
flew by for at least a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen swarms out here before, but they are normally more
compact,'' Brown said as we all stopped to watch the buzzing show
and tried not to draw attention to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Having a swarm of bees try to land on the boat, even if they
weren't the Africanized ``killer'' variety, would not have been a
fun thing.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to our fishing, we found that whenever the catfish
being hauled in were mostly undersized, Brown would crank up the
motor and head for another favorite spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year, you will normally catch a little larger
fish by using a float that lets the bait dangle about 3 feet below
the surface,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added that blue catfish are more numerous than channel
cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't catch the big blues like this,'' he said. ``You have
to use a trot line or jug line to catch the 50 or 60 pounders.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with many fishermen looking for fine table fare rather
than a rough and tumble struggle between man and fish, the smaller
cats are the best eating size, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information about fishing Choke Canyon, call guide Charles
Brown at 830-780-2162.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
