<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-TOURISM (Undated) _ Many American travelers are taking
advantage of the remarkable surge in the value of the dollar
against most of the currencies in the world.That is especially so
in the 11 European nations that have adopted a common currency, the
euro, in 1999. While the dollar is not quite as mighty as it was in
1985, it is the strongest it has been since, when measured
historically against the currencies the euro is replacing. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GERMANY-MARKETS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Cracks begin to
appear in the agreement to merge Europe's two largest stock
markets, the London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Borse. Several
German officials have suggested that a merger will dilute
Frankfurt's power, while some in London complain that the deal was
driven by big American investment banks. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-VIRUS (Undated) _ Anti-virus software companies say that a
new version of the ``I Love You'' virus is spreading via
Microsoft's Outlook e-mail program, hiding again as a deadly
attachment to an apparently forwarded message. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ Nissan Motor reports a $6.3 billion
loss for its fiscal year _ the biggest annual loss by a Japanese
automaker _ as the company tallies the charges for an overhaul that
it expects will bring a return to profit this business year. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MARKET (Seoul, South Korea) _ Members of Korea's
securities industry union are angry over the the Korea Stock
Exchange's stock exchange plan to abolish the lunch hour break in
trading, saying that it will destroy a Korean tradition. The
30,000-member union threatens to strike on Monday, when the new
hours take effect. By Samuel Len.
</P>
