<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GAY-AIR-FORCE-HNS &LR;      05-19 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-AIR-FORCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOMOSEXUAL DOCTOR SUES AIR FORCE OVER DISCHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They didn't ask, but John Hensala decided to
tell anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco resident believed that to serve in the Air
Force as a psychiatrist, he had to be honest about his
homosexuality, a decision that led to an honorable discharge in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years later, Hensala claims the military is
going against its own regulations, trying to recoup more than
$71,000 in scholarship funds from him even though he was more than
willing to stay in the service. Hensala sued the Air Force in
federal court on Thursday, seeking a judge's order that says he
doesn't have to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala, 35, may face some invasive questioning from Air Force
lawyers during depositions and a possible trial, but he said he
will never regret his decision to reveal that he is homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was very important from a psychological standpoint
to be open about my personal life to co-workers,'' Hensala said.
``I didn't want to be in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Chet Curtis, an Air Force spokesman, said he had not seen
the lawsuit and declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala's lawyer, Steve Collier, said his client has faced a
financial ``witch hunt'' since he left the military, and claims
that Hensala did nothing to violate his contract with the armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Collier said that under the law, the Air Force could have
demanded the funds back only if his client had committed
misconduct; refused to serve; engaged in homosexual acts; or made
the statement in an effort to escape service.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks a court order restraining the Air Force from
collecting the scholarship funds, plus legal fees and costs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Hensala entered into a ``health
professions scholarship contract'' with the military in 1986. It
meant the government provided money for school in exchange for
service in the Air Force Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala, who earned his undergraduate degree at Stanford
University, had his tuition and expenses paid by the Air Force when
he attended medical school at Northwestern University until 1990.
He also had a residency at Yale and a fellowship at the University
of California at San Francisco that the Air Force didn't subsidize.
</P>
<P>
   After attending summer training programs and two six-week
clerkships with the Air Force, Hensala was sent in 1995 to begin
active service as a psychiatrist at Scott Air Force Base near St.
Louis, an assignment that Hensala said he was willing to take.
</P>
<P>
   When he told his superiors about his sexuality, there was a
formal inquiry, including interviews with Hensala and several
witnesses. He received notice in February 1997 that he would be
honorably discharged.
</P>
<P>
   Hensala turned down an option for a hearing before an
administrative discharge board, the lawsuit states, deciding that
it would be futile.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that the Air Force ordered Hensala to pay
back the scholarship funds on Nov. 19, 1997, the day he was
formally discharged. Hensala petitioned to have the order
rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   But in an Air Force administrative review, officials stated that
Hensala ``failed to prove by a preponderance of the evidence that
he was not a person who engaged in, attempted to engage in . . . or
intended to engage in homosexual actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials also suggested that he revealed his
homosexuality to get out of duty ``that he had agreed to perform in
return for the advanced educational assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force Board for Corrections of Military Records panel
agreed with the findings, and Hensala said he had no other remedy
except a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Collier said the lawsuit probably will not lead to any challenge
of the military's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, but both the
lawyer and Hensala said it highlights its flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that people make a stand against a very
discriminatory policy,'' Hensala said. ``A lot of people were
looking forward to a change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
