<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Country clubs have traditionally been places where
affluent, white (mostly Protestant) Americans could get together to
play golf, drink, eat mediocre food and casually discuss business.
Talking politics was never polite but, come election time, the
members would line up behind Republican candidates, including that
consummate club member, George Bush, Sr. But George W. Bush would
be wise not to take his father's group for granted. He may have
solid country-club credentials and even a decent golf swing, but
