<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, May 21, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-PARTIES (New York) _ With Sotheby's, Christie's and now
Phillips battling for supremacy in the auction world, the grueling
round of brunches, cocktails parties and dinners given over the
past two weeks to promote the firms' crucial multimillion dollar
May sales of Impressionist, modern and contemporary artworks in New
York has left many art lovers reeling from social exhaustion. For
seasoned warriors in the cutthroat art world, attendance at such
events is often less a matter of making whoopee than determinedly
pursuing contacts, deals and artworks that are likely to slip out
of reach in one's absence. By Christopher Mason.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-HANDBAGS-FASHION (New York) _ Designers have pounced on a
new trend. Tod's, Lambertson Truex and Burberry are among a number
of companies that have recently introduced or plan to introduce
matched sets of handbags, meant for the woman who must have two.
``Women tend to use a larger bag for practicality, a smaller one
for fashion and social reasons,'' noted Richard Lambertson of
Lambertson Truex. ``We believe in merging the pair.'' By Ruth
LaFerla.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCANDINAVIAN-CHIC (New York) _ For some time now we've been in
the midst of some sort of Nordic intermezzo, stylewise. The
appetite for mid-century modern American furniture led, inevitably,
to a taste for the clean-lined Scandinavian designs of the same
era. Manhattan is full of 25-year-olds who burble passionately
about the Finnish master Alvar Aalto and his Danish contemporary
Hans Wegner, and there are entire stores and magazines devoted to
this new/old esthetic. It seems there's now an appetite for the
entire Scandinavian lifestyle. By Penelope Green.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-CELEBS (Undated) _ Just as Asian culture has penetrated
the worlds of cuisine, decorating and fashion in the past few years
(prayer-bead bracelet, anyone?), Asian-American women have emerged
as formidable, stylish figures. By Jennifer Tung.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-BOURDAIN (New York) _ Anthony Bourdain, who for eight
years has been the executive chef at Les Halles, has emerged as a
literary chef, as appreciated for quips as steak frites, a kind of
Clifford Odets with a mandoline. By Ginia Bellafante.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Plant vigor, Anne Raver says, depends
upon the functioning of mycorrhizae _ Latin word that translates to
``fungus-roots'' _ ad refers to the symbiotic associations between
fungi that colonize inside and outside of feeder roots. It's that
old you-scratch-my-back-and-I'll-scratch-yours.
</P>
