<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BAY-TO-BREAKERS-HNS &LR;      05-19 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-TO-BREAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR SOME RUNNERS, BAY RACE MEANS FULL EXPOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in the ``l'' and ``s'' categories)  
 &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., Idaho)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is the only time you can strut buck naked for
miles across San Francisco and not find yourself wearing jailhouse
orange at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Examiner Bay to Breakers run, which will be held
Sunday, is famous for the goofy costumes its participants wear. But
each year a growing number of the race's 80,000-plus runners shed
their costumes and hit the road wearing nothing more than running
shoes, socks and, maybe, a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Nude runners come from as far away as Australia and Algeria or
as close as Berkeley and Burlingame to participate in the race that
stretches 7.5 miles from one side of San Francisco to the other.
Some runners have said that the Bay to Breakers provided their
first nude, public experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running nude and unpunished across 8 miles through the streets
of a major city was something I had to try,'' said Mike Marinaci in
a posting on a Web site devoted to nude running.
</P>
<P>
   For 364 days of the year, public nudity in San Francisco is
against the law. But on race day the police tend to look the other
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public nudity is against the law. . . . But when you're
keeping track of 80,000 runners and another 50,000 people watching
them, we have other things to worry about first,'' said police
spokesman Sherman Ackerson. ``Our top goal is to make sure that
everyone there gets home safely. After that we trust our officers
to use their discretion in handling the situation appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   About 25 years ago, people began showing up in the race in the
barest of essentials, often in jock straps or thongs. But in the
mid-1980s an increasing number of men and women began jogging bare
or even painting decorations on their naked bodies. Some guys have
gone naked except for a rubber mask over their faces. The masks of
presidents have been popular, especially Nixon, Reagan and Clinton.
But Elvis is still king.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of running the Bay to Breakers in the buff has become
so popular that there is a Web site devoted to the
``Bare-2-Breakers'' race. The group responsible for the Web site
for years has given hats to nude runners, and on Sunday also will
give T-shirts to all naked finishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us something to wear home,'' wrote one participant in
an Internet posting that did not include a real name.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates put the number of nude runners in recent years from
100 to 300. (Shoes, socks and fanny packs don't count as clothing
on Bay to Breakers day).
</P>
<P>
   Most clothed runners take the show of skin in stride. Few
complaints have been received by city officials or race organizers.
</P>
<P>
   But one nasty letter last year got Mayor Willie Brown's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter was shocked, when, as the race got under way, a
big percentage of the participants had NO CLOTHES ON,'' Cleo
Clancey of Garden Valley, Idaho, wrote. ``She said one-third of the
runners were in this state of nakedness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancey did not attend the race, but her daughter shared plenty
of tales with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter and a few other participants yelled to those NUDE
runners to `get some clothes on' and the nude people yelled back,
`get some clothes off,''' Clancey wrote in the May 28, 1999,
letter.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor wrote back that ``less than 100'' of the estimated
80,000 runners were unclad.
</P>
<P>
   ``For generations a small number of participants have run the
course unclothed,'' Brown wrote in his Aug. 4 letter to Clancey.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a police standpoint actual arrests present
complications,'' Brown wrote. ``First, they must have a complaint
from someone offended by public nudity.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, he added, it is difficult to line up an unclothed
runner, a complainant and police officer amid thousands of race
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he wrote, any attempt to enforce the city's public
nudity laws during the race would detract from the Police
Department's traffic management duties.
</P>
<P>
   The only recorded police hassle was in 1997 and did not result
in an arrest. It happened when a naked runner separated from his
pack to use a Port-a-Potty. The police singled him out, telling him
public nudity was illegal. The police didn't arrest him, but the
runner wasn't allowed to finish the race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medically, there are few recorded problems from running without
clothing or support.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just need to exercise common sense,'' said Dr. Steve
Bretz, an attending physician at San Francisco General Hospital's
emergency room. ``If it's sunny, you should liberally apply
sunscreen to those areas that are normally unexposed.''
</P>
<P>
   For women, the doctor offers this advice: exercise without a bra
before embarking on the 7-mile jaunt.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Bare-2-Breakers assure men that their anatomy
will survive undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how floppy you are, nature takes care of male
genitals during exercise by tightening the scrotum,'' the Web site
advises. ``The ancient Greeks and Native Americans engaged in
competitive sport without clothing or injury.''
</P>
<P>
   But the naked runners face injuring their vanity.
</P>
<P>
   The last couple of years, people began chanting ``Viagra!
Viagra!'' at the sight of naked men. Another year, a group of women
raised numbered signs rating the naked guys as they passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are always really fat and ugly,'' said Crisicq Loya,
of Daly City, who has run or walked in five of the past eight Bay
to Breakers races. ``I have never seen an attractive man running
naked here before. . . . The good-looking ones are more modest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
