<HEADER>
A9984 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-KODAK-CUSTOMIZED-CD-N     05-19 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KODAK-CUSTOMIZED-CD-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL TOUCH  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MAY 22, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By BARRY FOX  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new type of CD or DVD that is part prerecorded and part blank,
ready for recording, will soon be hitting the shops. Devised by
Kodak, the discs will let you add your own snippets to commercially
recorded audio, video or games discs, and will allow short runs of
customized CDs to be made more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak likens the discs to a programmable read-only memory (PROM)
chip, and is calling them CD-PROMs or DVD-PROMs.
</P>
<P>
   At present, it is very expensive to make small numbers of
customized CDs or DVDs, as the whole of each disc has to be
individually recorded onto a blank. Making a stamper to press short
runs is even pricier.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's new discs could change all that. The stampers used to
press them transfer whatever sound, video or computer data is
common to all the discs. At the same time it presses a plain spiral
groove into the remaining blank part of the disc, which is then
coated with a light-sensitive cyanine dye.
</P>
<P>
   Customized sections can then be recorded relatively quickly onto
the blank spiral groove, to produce a disc sporting a mix of
pressed and recorded data that plays like an all-pressed disc.
Alternatively, the dyed area can be left blank for home recording
on a personal computer or CD recorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will let people update the content of an optical disc
without cluttering the hard disc on their PC. The update then
travels with the removable disc,'' comments Emil Dudeck, director
of optical disc technology at Technicolor. ``It's a nice idea if
the cost can be kept down.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1511EDT &QL; 
