<P>
   HAPPINESS-INDEXES (Undted) _ Social scientists as well as
communities from Jacksonville to Honolulu are beginning to say,
``It's not just the economy, stupid.'' They are looking beyond
purely economic numbers _ at health and crime statistics, clear-air
days and commuting time _ to gain a fuller measure of our elusive
sense of collective well-being, and discovering some surprising
results in the process. By Alexander Stille. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-EXPERTS (Undated) _ Intellectuals and others who
make up the American ``strategic class'' are suddenly focusing
their attention on China. Yet unlike traditional sinologists, who
have made a broad study of China's complex history and culture,
this new crop of experts are preoccupied with a much narrower
question: will China be our next enemy? Within the circumscribed
world of strategists, this sharpened approach is stirring bitter
debates over how to interpret China, while in the larger political
arena it is having an impact on pressing policy debates in
Washington, including next week's congressional vote on China's
trade status. By Kurt M. Campbell. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move with an ``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MUNDANE-BEHAVIOR (Undated) _ If deviants can have a slew of
journals devoted to their weird obsessions, why not humdrum normal
types? The online Journal of Mundane Behavior seeks to fill the
gap. By Emily Eakin. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
