<HEADER>
A9997 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BEARS-DNA-HNS &LR;      05-19 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARS-DNA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DNA USED TO COUNT GRIZZLY BEARS IN GLACIER PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLACIER NATIONAL PARK, Mont. _ Clever scientists have come up
with a new grizzly bear census in Glacier National Park by using
DNA in bear hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the new technique, the bear counters estimate that
there are 332 grizzlies in the park, located in northwestern
Montana. By comparison, a 1970 census based on bear sightings came
up with an estimate of 200 bears in the park.
</P>
<P>
   A team led by Katherine Kendall, an ecologist and bear
researcher with the U.S. Geological Survey, designed hair traps
that lured the elusive grizzlies with sweet-smelling liquid
concoctions of rotten fish and cattle blood that had been brewed
for weeks in warm 55-gallon barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists then poured some of the gunk on piles of rotting
logs and surrounded each site with strands of barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the source of that irresistible aroma, the bears had
to cross the barbed wire that snagged small pieces of their fur.
Kendall and her colleagues then recovered the fur snippets and
produced a who's who of grizzlies, based on the fur's DNA and the
DNA in scat _ bear feces _ found at the 331 traps in the
1.2-million-acre park. Dr. Lisette Waits performed the analyses of
the genetic material in the nucleus of the bear cells at the
University of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall noted that conducting a grizzly census by DNA was
cheaper and less disruptive to the bear population than previous
ways of counting bears through live capture and the use of radio
collars and aerial tracking.
</P>
<P>
   Grizzlies once roamed most of the North American continent, but
habitat destruction and conflicts with humans have reduced their
range by 99 percent in the lower 48 states. Researchers estimate
there now are fewer than 1,000 grizzly bears south of the U.S.
Canadian border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
