<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     05-19 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SIDES TO `WONDERLAND' PROTESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The broadcast networks introduced next season's prime-time
lineups this week amid the usual pronouncements about how network
TV is in better shape today than those of us media folk who analyze
it for a living would have you believe. Looking at the preliminary
schedules, and having an idea of which shows are being considered
to replace those that are certain to fail, it's clear that a lack
of invention and fear of risk continue to play large roles in
network TV decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's heartbreaking when ambitious series like Peter
Berg's ``Wonderland'' aren't even allowed a full gallop out of the
starting gate. We knew ``Wonderland'' would not show up on ABC's
schedule since the network axed the drama, set in a mental ward of
a big city hospital, after two episodes earlier this year. No
growth potential was the reason.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote, and rather harshly, that the network was weak-kneed and
pathetic in its decision to discard the series, and that a ratings
excuse wasn't good enough for a show that so clearly needed time to
take root.
</P>
<P>
   Criticisms from mental health organizations that ``Wonderland''
unfairly portrayed the mentally ill as violent is what doomed the
series, especially when advertisers began to bail.
</P>
<P>
   I watched four episodes of the series and noticed a balance that
would give viewers a much better insight into the world of not only
the mentally ill but also the people who work with them. Based on
that, I refuse to back down from that point.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has long been the network that took risks in picking up
pilots others would not, such as ``Nothing Sacred,'' about a
liberal Roman Catholic priest, and ``Cracker,'' about a
psychologist who helped the police solve crimes. And it's also been
the network that caves in to pressure from protest groups. Some
Catholics figured a priest who sees the gray areas of any kind in
religious doctrine ought not be a priest, and psychology
associations complained that the lead in ``Cracker'' drank too
much, gambled too much and was an adulterer.
</P>
<P>
   But an e-mail came in recently from Katherine Garivay that
should be shared. Under the subject of ``Wonderland _ Been There?''
Katherine said I didn't have the whole picture, and she proceeded
to paint it for me.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that if it were not for protests, there would
still be segregation, society would have made no accommodations for
physical disabilities, and women who are victims of spousal abuse
would have no safe place to go.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote back in agreement on that point.
</P>
<P>
   She went on:
</P>
<P>
   ``True, the public needs educating, clarification, and
understanding when it comes to persons who are sick with mental
illness,'' she wrote. ``And, yes, there are those who jump at every
mention of a negative portrayal of any affliction. Usually, you
would find that those consumers are the caregivers, family members,
or friends or someone who has a similar misfortune. When someone
reacts from the heart, they can be impulsive and not completely
objective when there poses a threat, real or implied.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the advocacy of the mentally ill is a real and difficult
battle. There is much misinformation in the real world. There is a
real need for those who speak up and make noise because there are
children who suffer from the same illnesses. Children, not just
adults. Children are the minority of the mentally ill. Would you
care to see a child, in the interest of a pet project, portrayed in
such a manner? These children grow up and become adults. They will
be the future.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to urge me and other critics to be careful of
endorsing projects that not only offend but also disseminate
information that, down the line, could be harmful, if that
information is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As for mental health in particular, she wrote: ``I am presuming
that you have been blessed by not having a serious mental illness
plaguing someone you care about. I think you would certainly be
more objective and not so harsh in your criticism. You have to live
it to believe it. I have.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
