<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     05-19 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INOCULATE YOUR COMPUTER AGAINST VIRUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: After reading about the ``Love Bug'' virus,
I've been afraid to open any e-mail attachments. Is there some way
to tell which ones are safe?
</P>
<P>
   _ Loveless
</P>
<P>
   DEAR LOVELESS: You know what ticks me off? That a bunch of
little four-eyed cockroaches without social lives can intimidate
anyone into even asking that question.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet used to thrive on cooperation and trust, and
because of that, it was a special, idyllic place. Turns out it's
just like the rest of the world, though, susceptible to the lowest
urges that motivate our pathetic little species. Some pinhead with
no conscience wants to validate his existence, so he finds a way to
mess with everybody's e-mail and wreak computer chaos for a week,
all so he can brag about it to the rest of the zeros he hangs out
with. We're all so impressed. Gee, can we be like you?
</P>
<P>
   Virulent as it was, the sad part about the ``Love Bug'' outbreak
is that it appears to have been written by a real bonehead _ or
group of boneheads _ with no sense of style or even the
intelligence to cover his _ or their _ tracks. The virus code was a
Windows script, a list of tasks for a computer to complete, in a
language close enough to regular English that even nonprogrammers
could get a clue what it was meant to do. Oh, and cleverly included
in the script were things like nicknames, e-mail addresses and lots
of other smoking guns, all pointing to the dweebs who thought this
little stunt was so funny.
</P>
<P>
   If you know what you're doing, the code is easy to extract
without infecting your computer. Any decent e-mail program will
display the name of an attachment without actually extracting it.
Because Windows depends on a filename extension to know what to do
with the file, you can tell which kinds of files to dump.
</P>
<P>
   If the file has a .VBS or .JS extension, delete it. It's a
script, you don't know what it does and you don't want to find out.
It executes when you open it.
</P>
<P>
   If you see an .EXE or .COM or .BAT, be very wary. These are all
extensions that Windows will attempt to execute. The file could be
harmless, but unless you know for sure, dump it.
</P>
<P>
   You also need to be suspicious about documents created by any
application program that has a script language, and that includes
all the stuff in Microsoft Office. A virus writer can create an
Excel or Word file that launches a destructive script when it's
opened. The newest versions of the programs warn users that a
script is about to execute, but that doesn't always stop them from
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, please buy a good anti-virus program like McAfee or
Norton, and keep it up-to-date. These guys release virus signature
updates at least monthly, and they burn the midnight oil to come up
with overnight fixes for new viruses like the Love Bug. You might
also download a free copy of ZoneAlarm (www.zonealarm.com), a
personal firewall program that now includes a defense against
script viruses.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: When are you going to put together a book of
your weekly columns? Your advice is the most competent available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deranged
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DE: Whoops! Somehow I got Heloise's mail.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay would gladly compile a book of his
accumulated wisdom, but there appears to be no market for a
page-and-a-half tome. Write him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
(snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: (817) 390-7257. In the nonvirtual world, he is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-E-COMMERCE-FRAUD20-CO     05-19 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-FRAUD20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SALE OF FAKE IDENTIFICATION BURGEONING ON THE INTERNET
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From teenagers trying to buy beer to sophisticated
criminals trying to defraud banks, thousands of Americans are
turning to the Internet to obtain fake driver's licenses, birth
certificates and other identification documents.
</P>
<P>
   According to experts at a Senate hearing Friday, computer-savvy
con artists are getting better by the day at churning out
authentic-looking IDs from Internet sites with names such as
fakeid.net and fakeids.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sites offer phony documents of shockingly high
quality,'' said K. Lee Blalack II, staff director of the Senate
permanent subcommittee on investigations. ``The distribution of
these counterfeit materials is growing because of the expanding
technology of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Blalack led a five-month investigation to find out how to get ID
documents that could be used for criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers passed out copies of phony documents that put the face
of Sen. Susan Collins, the Maine Republican who chairs the Senate
subcommittee, on a U.S. Army Reserve identification card, a
Connecticut driver's license and a Boston University student ID
card. The selection of fake IDs, created in the basement of the
Russell Senate Office Building, cost about $50 to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, for a fee, the operator of a Web site allows Internet
users to download programs or buy software that will print driver's
licenses, birth certificates, immigration cards, job certificates
and school transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   One site, for example, promised that its Fake ID Kit version 2.0
would provide ``college diplomas, new birth certificates, green
cards, Social Security cards, updated drivers licenses, plus
more!'' And all for just $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   While selling fake legal documents is against the law, the sites
often dodge
</P>
<P>
   that issue by labeling the documents ``novelties'' or
``souvenirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fake IDs are nothing new, especially to college students with a
thirst, but the Internet offers counterfeiters a high-speed,
low-cost way to entice customers.
</P>
<P>
   Though the subcommittee could not determine precisely how many
counterfeit documents are being used to commit crimes, David C.
Myers, identification fraud coordinator for Florida's Division of
Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco, said that about 30 percent of the
phony IDs he sees now come from Web sites, up from 1 percent two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that some false-ID sites have received more than
10,000 inquiries on a single day, and that a single ID seller can
generate more than $1 million a year in income.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said more police training on how to spot fake IDs would
help. But stopping fake documents will be difficult because sellers
can operate from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one exhibit showed a Web page containing this
announcement: ``We have moved our Web site to the UK but continue
to process orders for our clients from around the world. ... In the
next few months, we expect to be shut down again but we will bound
back as always from another part of the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins suggested that lawmakers may need to create tougher
penalties for making and using fraudulent documents, which now
range from three to 25 years in prison, depending on the crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Stafford, director of the U.S. Secret Service, said he
doubted new laws could keep ahead of the Net-based vendors. A
better approach, he said, would be to spend more money on the
research needed to improve ways to identify people based on
immutable physical characteristics, such as fingerprints and
patterns in the eye's irises.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
www.senate.gov/(tilde)gov(underscore)affairs/psi.htm
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
