r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-19 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY, RUDY, ROSIE, BOBBY AND GEORGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON: It's official. Hillary Rodham Clinton is the
New York Democratic Party's choice to run for the U.S. Senate
against ... against whom?
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's long-presumed opponent, New York Mayor Rudy
Giuliani, dropped out of the race to deal with his recently
revealed prostate cancer and marital problems. Which leaves Hillary
in a quandary, seeing as how she spent months gearing up for a
no-holds-barred battle with Giuliani and now will have to take on
someone entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just hope that whoever runs against her is up to the task.
America wants _ needs _ a break from the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   RUDY GIULIANI: I was hoping _ lots of Americans were hoping _
that he would run. He might have been the Republicans' only hope to
keep Clinton out of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you can certainly understand Giuliani's
decision. His personal problems are daunting enough without taking
on a long, tiring and sure-to-be unspeakably nasty political
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: The president was on the scene Tuesday night,
basking in reflected glory as his wife accepted the Senate
nomination in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted that the president is here,'' Hillary said. ``I
am so grateful for his support. I would not be standing here
tonight were it not for Bill and were it not for all he has done
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a happy couple. Seeing them together sort of makes you warm
all over, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ROSIE O'DONNELL: If you were offended by O'Donnell's rude
treatment of Tom Selleck on her TV talk show and/or repulsed by her
hopelessly unfunny stint as host of the Grammy awards, then you had
to be horrified by her shrill and obnoxious performance as
ringmaster for the Million Mom March.
</P>
<P>
   But there's good news for Joan Rivers: She is hereby relieved of
her long-held designation as the most annoying woman in show
business. Rosie makes Joan look like Miss Congeniality.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN GONZALEZ: Now the anti-Castro zealots in Miami are
throwing a fit because the 6-year-old Cuban kid was photographed
wearing a blue scarf around his neck _ supposedly proving that he
is being brainwashed by Fidel Castro's operatives while awaiting
the outcome of a court case that could clear the way for him to
return to Cuba with his father. Cuban officials said that the scarf
is part of the school uniform worn by Cuban kids and has nothing to
do with brainwashing.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said that Eli n's wardrobe is none of America's
business.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: The Republican presidential nominee-to-be is
moving up in the polls, burning up the TV interview circuit and
coming up with some new policy initiative every few days or so. Is
the Texas governor on a roll or what?
</P>
<P>
   It's a long time from May to November, yet Bush seems to be
gaining momentum at a rate that could carry him right through
Election Day. But Bush backers should beware: The further ahead he
gets, the meaner his opponent will get.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: I used to like this guy. Even before Bill Clinton
tabbed Gore as the Democrats' vice presidential candidate back in
1992, I wrote a column urging Slick Willie to choose the
then-senator from Tennessee as his running mate. It may have been
the last time I agreed with Clinton on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's close association with Clinton, however, seems to have
turned the vice president into an unprincipled worm who will say
and do anything to get ahead. Maybe this will work with some
voters, but I'm guessing that after nearly eight years of
Clintonism, most Americans have had it up to here with that brand
of politics.
</P>
<P>
   BOBBY KNIGHT: The Indiana basketball coach is a jerk, no doubt
about it. But don't some of these big-time college athletes need
somebody to grab them by the throat once in a while?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
