   Though the subcommittee could not determine precisely how many
counterfeit documents are being used to commit crimes, David C.
Myers, identification fraud coordinator for Florida's Division of
Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco, said that about 30 percent of the
phony IDs he sees now come from Web sites, up from 1 percent two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that some false-ID sites have received more than
10,000 inquiries on a single day, and that a single ID seller can
generate more than $1 million a year in income.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said more police training on how to spot fake IDs would
help. But stopping fake documents will be difficult because sellers
can operate from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one exhibit showed a Web page containing this
announcement: ``We have moved our Web site to the UK but continue
to process orders for our clients from around the world. ... In the
next few months, we expect to be shut down again but we will bound
back as always from another part of the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins suggested that lawmakers may need to create tougher
penalties for making and using fraudulent documents, which now
range from three to 25 years in prison, depending on the crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Stafford, director of the U.S. Secret Service, said he
doubted new laws could keep ahead of the Net-based vendors. A
better approach, he said, would be to spend more money on the
research needed to improve ways to identify people based on
immutable physical characteristics, such as fingerprints and
patterns in the eye's irises.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
www.senate.gov/(tilde)gov(underscore)affairs/psi.htm
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
