<HEADER>
A0075 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-     05-19 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INTERNET SOIL EXPERT EXPLAINS THE OTHER WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
 By ANNE RAVER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I ordered 13 heirloom roses last fall, I vowed that I would
prepare the rose beds before winter, working in plenty of compost
and some aged manure to give those shrubs and climbers a good
start.
</P>
<P>
   Did I accomplish this noble goal? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   My roses arrived two weeks ago, 13 slender little plants with
fragile leaves, sticking out of long tubular plastic pots. So I
stuck them in the vegetable garden, which has a nice, crumbly feel
after 15 years of compost and plenty of earthworms.
</P>
<P>
   Then I decided to study what is really going on beneath the
surface. If I could picture all those transactions between bacteria
and fungi, protozoa, nematodes, micro-arthropods _ the interactions
called the soil food web _ I might work more on feeding my soil. A
friend told me about a good Web site, www.soilfoodweb.com, which
explains the basic biology in articles and links to other sites
while providing images of the key players in this process.
</P>
<P>
   Plant vigor, I'm learning, depends upon mycorrhizae (a Latin
word meaning fungus roots) and refers to the symbiotic associations
between fungi that colonize inside and outside of feeder roots.
</P>
<P>
   It's that old you-scratch-my-back-and-I'll-scratch-yours. In
healthy soil, a naturally occurring fungi called
vesicular-arbuscular mycorrhizae (VAM, for short), colonize the
cells of a plant's feeder roots. In exchange for carbohydrates made
by the plant during photosynthesis, these fungi bring phosphorus,
other minerals and water from the soil to the root. They also
protect the roots from root-rot fungi and parasitic nematodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plant is like the feudal warlord,'' said Dr. Elaine
Ingham, a soil scientist at Oregon State University in Corvallis.
``It puts out the protein and carbohydrates to feed all the
warriors to protect it against all those bad guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria, as well as fungi, swarm around those plant roots,
slurping up the sugars. The bacteria, which are high in protein,
are a feast for protozoa and beneficial nematodes. They convert the
protein into nitrogen, which can then be used by plants.
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria and fungi also break down woody tissues, stems, leaves
and the dead roots of plants, turning them into nutrients for
somebody in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why good gardening comes down to compost, compost,
compost.
</P>
<P>
   Ingham runs a company called Soil Foodweb Inc., which analyzes
soil and diseases for growers and helps them develop organic
systems. Like many microbiologists, she uses the expression food
web, rather than food chain, because the biochemical interactions
are not one continuous chain. A fine-tuned food web doesn't need
fertilizer, or even lime. Acidic soil usually occurs when the soil
is compacted and anaerobic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add fertilizer to the soil, the plant will take up a
tiny bit of it, but if you don't have a lot of bacteria and fungi
to take up the rest, it will leach right out of the soil,'' Ingham
said. And who needs it, if you have a food web making everything
from soup to nuts.
</P>
<P>
   And another thing, she said. Don't rototill if you want good
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Good, crumbly soil is made out of aggregates of sand, silt and
clay particles held together by the gums and gels formed by
bacteria. Fungi, root hairs and roots bind these aggregates, and
the arthropods, insects and earthworms build the tiny rooms that
let air and water trickle through.
</P>
<P>
   Ingham paints a picture of what the grasslands in the central
valleys of California were like before the Europeans first came
with their plows in the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soil was so rich, they could put seeds in and walk away,''
said Ingham, who has pored over the journals of those early
farmers. ``There were no insects, no diseases.'' Manure or compost
was unnecessary, because the symbiosis taking place in the soil
gave the plants everything they needed.
</P>
<P>
   The glory days lasted for more than a decade, before destructive
fungal disease and insect infestations became a problem. ``By
plowing and not adding residues back in, they were destroying the
food web, which wasn't holding on to nutrients or maintaining
disease suppression,'' Ingham said.
</P>
<P>
   By the post-World War II years, verticillium wilt a fungal
disease that attacks everything from strawberries to string beans,
was threatening crop productivity. And though farmers used stronger
and stronger chemicals, the fungi just developed stronger
resistance. And now, methyl bromide, ``which basically sterilizes
everything,'' Ingham said, is used before every planting of
strawberries and other crops in commercial fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's every bit as toxic as arsenic,'' said Ingham, who has
been working with strawberry growers in San Luis Obispo, north of
Los Angeles, to switch to more organic methods. ``But methyl
bromide doesn't kill the root-feeding nematodes that can go down
eight feet.'' It doesn't kill pathogens, either, she said, which
can go dormant and germinate later from spores.
</P>
<P>
   And since there are no beneficial organisms left in this soil,
it's essentially dead. Chemical fertilizers must be added for those
strawberries to grow, and there is nothing to keep the nitrates
from leaching into the water table.
</P>
<P>
   These soils have ``less than a half a percent of organic
matter,'' Ingham said. A hundred years ago, they had 8 percent to
14 percent. What do we have left? Sand, that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Ingham basically uses compost to rebuild these degraded soils.
To help growers envision what to aim for, she measured life teeming
in soil taken from a protected area in the Santa Maria Valley, near
San Luis Obispo. In a single teaspoon of soil she found 600 million
bacteria; ``a couple of miles of fungal hyfea,'' she said,
referring to their microscopic threads; 10,000 protozoa; 30
beneficial nematodes; and too many other organisms to recount here.
</P>
<P>
   So don't throw that banana peel in the trash. Put it in your
compost pile. Your roses, and everything else, will thank you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
