<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0076 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HNS &LR;      05-19 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEARS OF SADNESS FOR A WINNING JOCKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM DENT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ One of the great sensory experiences of racing is
turning for home in the Kentucky Derby with the wind in your face
and the wall of sound rolling like thunder from the throats of
150,000 fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux lives for the moment when the sound washes over
him.
</P>
<P>
   It often wakes him in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Others have compared this tidal wave to a religious experience.
It charges the body with electrical waves, triggering a long rush
of adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys such as Desormeaux have been so overcome by the
sensation that they cry like babies when they reach the wire at
Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   When Fusaichi Pegasus roared to victory two weeks ago with
Desormeaux in the pilot's seat, tiny rivers formed on the jockey's
face.
</P>
<P>
   But these were not tears of joy. These were tears for a
14-month-old son who only weeks earlier had been diagnosed as being
totally deaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated when I heard the news,'' Desormeaux said. ``I
mean, what can you say about the depression that me and my wife
feel? My son will not be able to hear so many things, and it kills
me that he couldn't hear the cheering at Churchill.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux paused and studied the tops of his shoes. ``Hopefully
he will be able to feel the roar of the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   From the day that Jake Desormeaux was born five weeks premature,
Sonia and Kent Desormeaux suspected that his hearing was impaired.
He wouldn't respond to voices _ only to the stomping of a foot on
the kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   But they clung to threads of hope until an examination was
conducted the Monday following Desormeaux's overwhelming victory
aboard Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood Memorial, the colt's final
tune-up for the Triple Crown series.
</P>
<P>
   The couple started to sob at the doctor's office. That is when
9-year-old Josh Desormeaux tapped his mother on the leg and said,
``It's OK, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux, like most jockeys, is accustomed to heartbreak and
pain. He plays the only sport in which the participants are
followed by an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   It is a game that will walk on you when you're down.
</P>
<P>
   One day you are winning the Kentucky Derby, and the next you
watch as trainers turn and walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at Pimlico, Desormeaux will take a second leap toward
greatness aboard that fire-breathing monster known as Fusaichi
Pegasus _ the winged horse of the Greek lore.
</P>
<P>
   People in Baltimore have already conceded the Preakness to this
fabulous 3-year-old, and if this happens, the racing community will
hold its collective breath until the June 6 Belmont Stakes, when
the final jewel in the crown is run.
</P>
<P>
   The Triple Crown has become the ghost of thoroughbred racing.
Twenty-two years without a Kentucky-Preakness-Belmont parlay is the
second longest gap in racing history _ the longest drought coming
between Citation in 1948 and Secretariat in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   To know there were no Triple Crown winners in the '50s, '60s,
'80s and '90s is to understand the quiet desperation within this
industry.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the inner turmoil of Kent Desormeaux is to weigh
the pressure that has been dropped like barbells on his tiny
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five elite riders in United States, his life has been
anything but calm.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the bush tracks of South Louisiana, Cajun Country,
Desormeaux took off to Baltimore and in 1987 he led all jockeys
with 450 victories. Determined to test the deep water of the
Southern California circuit, he won several riding titles and he
set a national record in 1989 with 598 winners.
</P>
<P>
   But with the victories there was always the attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Dismounting, Desormeaux would scold trainers for not doing a
better job of preparing the horse. He was accused of not riding out
horses to the wire when he had no obvious chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his success, trainers became tired of the nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Desormeaux gladly accepted the mount on trainer
Bob Baffert's Real Quiet, and proceeded to win the first two legs
of the Triple Crown before losing by a nose at the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Baffert has turned his back on both the jockey and
his agent, citing Desormeaux's demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Baffert's cold shoulder was a hidden blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of riding Baffert's Captain Steve, he pilots the horse
America now embraces. And he embraces a new perspective on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothin' in life is good all of the time,'' Desormeaux said.
``In this business, the good times roll, and the bad times roll,
too. You just got to roll with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Desormeaux will carry the weight of the industry on
his back, and the sadness for a child in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   That is surely enough to inspire maturity within a man.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Dent can be reached by e-mail at jdent(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
