<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0077 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-ASIAN-CELEBS-$ADV21-N     05-19 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-CELEBS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAY SO LONG, DRAGON LADY AND CHINA DOLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
 By JENNIFER TUNG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Old Navy commercials shown during the Academy Awards in
March, a new spokeswoman was promoting the cheap, cheerful clothing
line: Lisa Ling, the 26-year-old co-host of ``The View'' on ABC.
Ling, wearing red capris and white T-shirt, said cheekily, ``A good
pair of shorts is hard to find, unless you know where to look.''
Behind her, a group of hunky young men sprinted by in cargo shorts.
</P>
<P>
   I was amazed. Not at the sexual innuendo but at the sight of a
young Chinese-American woman representing an enormous clothing
company, on national television, on Oscar night _ the ultimate
convergence of celebrity, glamour, and fashion. Suddenly Ling, with
her crisp looks and newscaster-like delivery, was a style icon.
</P>
<P>
   That might not sound like a big deal today, but I remember
seeing a very different Ling on television as a kid in the 1970s.
My sisters and I were in our family room watching a re-run of the
1967 James Bond movie, ``You Only Live Twice.'' One of the first
scenes takes place in Hong Kong, or more precisely, in a bed in
Hong Kong, where Agent 007 kisses a long-haired Chinese woman with
blunt bangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that Chinese girls taste different from all other
girls?'' he asks her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think Chinese girls bet-tuh, huh?'' she replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not better, just different _ the way Peking duck is different
from Russian caviar, but I love them both,'' Bond says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dah-ling, I give you very best duck,'' Ling says.
</P>
<P>
   Then she jumps out of bed right before two men with machine guns
burst in and riddle Bond with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's Ling was the amalgam of almost every Chinese female
stereotype: a submissive sex nymph speaking in breathy, broken
English, and a calculating dragon lady. (If she'd leapt out of bed
and into a lab coat and thick glasses, the cliche would have been
complete.) She is also the only representation of Asian women in
film or television that I remember from my childhood _ aside from
the ``ancient Chinese secret'' laundry lady in the Calgon
commercials. At the time, I didn't know enough to be angry or
offended. I was just embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   But lately there has been an Asian population explosion in the
pop culture landscape. In Hollywood, there's a new kind of A-list
that includes Asian It Girls like Ming-Wa, Bai Ling, Michelle Yeoh
and Lucy Liu. Beaming from a billboard in Times Square is CoCo Lee,
the Hong Kong-born, San Francisco-bred singer whose first United
States album, ``Just No Other Way'' was released two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been an Asian style invasion: Vera Wang, the
fashion designer, on the cover of Town &AMP; Country this winter, Ahn
Duong, the artist, on the cover of Banana Republic's new catalog
just last week. Fashion models like Devon Aoki and Ling are
fixtures on the runways. Asian faces are even infiltrating society
pages. The actress China Chow and the Visionaire editor Cecilia
Dean are downtown scenesters who appear regularly in Vogue's party
pictures. W magazine's May issue alone features a profile of Wendy
Deng discussing the Asia Society and marriage to Rupert Murdoch, a
story about Hong Kong-born Grace Leo Andrieu, owner of the
celebrity-studded Hotel Lancaster in London, as well as a 12-page
swimsuit portfolio starring Aoki.
</P>
<P>
   But if Asian women are busting out of the China doll
stereotypes, their new image does tend to borrow some of the old
cliches. They may no longer be mousy math whizzes but they're still
brainy. Clawed dragon ladies might be out but style queens with
sharp tongues and sharp wardrobes are very in. ``We're never
portrayed as bimbos,'' said the Malaysian-born designer Yeohlee.
``It's because of our flat chests.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean they aren't physical. On screen, Asian women
often combine sexiness and action heroism with unusual ease, like
Michelle Yeoh, the actress whose long glossy hair flies as she
leaps tall buildings in the Jackie Chan movies. Lucy Liu, the
acerbic Ling Woo on ``Ally McBeal,'' will be a kickboxing cop in
the film version of ``Charlie's Angels'' in November alongside Drew
Barrymore and Cameron Diaz. (It's somehow harder to imagine the
neurotic Calista Flockhart chasing down bad guys with a gun.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite such new cool roles, the effort to create a hip identity
that can include Asian-ness rather than try to hide it is still
pretty new and often self conscious. When I met Lisa Ling at an
event for Nutrisse home hair-coloring products two months ago, she
said: ``What I try to convey to other Asians with my sense of style
is that we can defy the stereotypes that we are submissive and not
gregarious. We don't have to conform. I can be obnoxious and
blunt.'' As if to prove her point, Ling added, ``So many Asians are
label whores. Have you noticed that?''
</P>
<P>
   But even Ling's bravado only set in a few years ago. ``I hated
being Chinese as a kid!'' recalled Ling, who was born in
California. ``I was teased mercilessly. I went to public school,
and the kids called me `Risa Ring.' Kids would come over to my
house, and it would smell like Chinese food, and that was
embarrassing. Or if I had friends over, my dad would say, `Tell
them to go home' in Chinese, right in front of them.''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded vigorously in agreement, remembering the time a
classmate of my younger sister's came over after school, smelled
rice cooking and asked if we had pet gerbils. My sister explained
the odor by saying that our heating system was broken.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always clear growing up in Albuquerque, how to bridge
the divide between my Chinese heritage and my desire to fit in with
the tall, tanned set at the tennis club. My parents, a scientist
and a classical pianist, spoke Cantonese to each other, and to us,
when we were small. In our house, high style was my grandmother
wearing a cheongsam and singing Chinese opera as we kids padded
around the house in our embroidered Chinese pajamas with frog
buttons.
</P>
<P>
   But away from home, being Asian could be nerve-racking. My white
and Hispanic classmates flattened their noses with their fingers to
mock my wide features. When we had to line up by height I was
always shortest and last. My beauty ideals were the blond models in
Seventeen and in the ads for Ocean Pacific, the Southern California
clothing company. When Madonna hit the charts, I wore crucifixes,
black lace gloves and rubber bracelets up to my elbows. My New Wave
phase followed: head shaved on the sides, dyed orange hair forced
skyward with gel and diluted glue.
</P>
<P>
   If only I had had a role model like Margaret Yang, the quirky
high-school girl in last year's film, ``Rushmore,'' who played rock
guitar, acted in avant-garde school plays and got the boy in the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden embrace of Asian women and culture?
</P>
<P>
   The designer Vivienne Tam, who was raised in Hong Kong (and
whose style guide ``China Chic'' will be published in September by
ReganBooks), links it to the new global economy and the opening up
of Asia. ``When Hong Kong went back to China in 1997, I think there
was more awareness around the world of Asian culture,'' she said on
the phone from her Seventh Avenue office. ``And then Prada and Miu
Miu started the whole chinoiserie trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoebe Eng, the author of ``Warrior Lessons: An Asian American
Woman's Journey into Power'' (Pocket Books), said its not the rest
of the world but Asian women themselves who have changed. ``We are
the crop of daughters who finally had choices,'' Eng, 37, said.
``We didn't have the same sense of duty and boundness of our
mothers, so we took our own paths and went into acting, comedy and
entertainment. The number of Asian women entering FIT and Parsons
is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eng also pointed out that Asians are not only fashion forward
but their ethnicity is integral to their style. ``You see lots of
15-year-olds wearing Hello Kitty and chinoiserie,'' she said. ``And
older Asian women have an androgynous look, and that is what makes
the look sensuous. We used to think of Asian models as chiseled and
Eurasian-looking, now some have very small eyes, and others have
square jaws. Anything goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
