<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DINOSAUR-ANIMATION-TE     05-19 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-ANIMATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DINOSAUR' HATCHES EXPRESSIVE, REALISTIC CHARACTERS `ON LOCATION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not every day that you see an animated movie conclude with
a ``filmed on location'' credit, much less one that lists more than
a dozen locations on three continents. Yet that's the type of
realism that the makers of the new movie ``Dinosaur'' were after.
Location filming was done in Australia, the United States and South
America, then computer-generated models were placed seamlessly into
the live settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an animation standpoint, there are a few issues with
(doing this),'' says Michael Belzer, one of the supervising
animators on the film, which opened Friday in wide release. ``But
the primary one is that you as an audience see live action. (And
when) you put a computer-animated character within that, all of a
sudden you raise the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur'' has indeed raised the bar. Although you can quibble
about the lack of originality in the film's story _ an orphan
dinosaur's life journey, including an Exodus-like trek with other
dinos to find an elusive paradise _ it's hard not to be amazed by
the movie's animation, which not only incorporates live-action
backgrounds but also presents what may be the most expressive
characters in animation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us first became aware of the movie when its stunning,
wordless five-minute preview _ a short film in itself _ screened
before showings of ``Toy Story 2'' last fall. But the movie has
been in the works, in one form or another, for a dozen years.
Director Paul Verhoeven and effects whiz Phil Tippett were among
the first people connected to the project, back in 1988. When they
couldn't bring it to fruition, it made its way to Disney, where
work began about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Belzer, who was the supervising animator on a character named
Baylene, was one of the late-comers to the project _ he spent 2 1/2
years on it. Baylene is the largest character in the film, a
dignified, aged brachiosaur voiced by Joan Plowright. Although
Baylene is a computer creation, Belzer refers to her weight (70
tons) and height (70 feet) as if she were a real, living creature.
To him, she is _ and he made her so.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to dinosaurs, of course, size matters. So an
important part of the animators' efforts involved matching the
movements of their virtual creations with the actual size and
weight of the dinosaurs that once roamed the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started by going to paleontologists, finding out about the
bone structure (of dinosaurs), how these creatures really moved and
existed,'' Belzer says. ``And on top of that we would say, `OK, we
got the basic material, let's put in the artistic license, have
some fun with it and put the character in with all of that.'''
</P>
<P>
   The research also involved visiting zoos and having animals
brought to the set. The movie's animators learned about dinosaur
movements from ostriches, hippopotamuses and Komodo dragons (which
influenced another Belzer-supervised character, a puppylike
ankylosaur named Url). Belzer's own crew studied elephants to learn
about brachiosaur movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It taught us a lot, not just in terms of motion, but really
what the skin was doing,'' Belzer says. ``The body structure of an
elephant is very similar to that of a brachiosaur. So we were able
to look at the pillarlike shape of the legs, and as the foot came
down, realize that inertia doesn't so much go north and south, but
it's more of a rotational inertia. We tried to incorporate a lot of
these principles into the muscles and skin of the brachiosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those principles come into play in one of the movie's
most dramatic scenes (warning: mild spoiler ahead). The dinosaur
herd, moving across a vast desert in search of their paradisical
``nesting grounds,'' cross a ridge only to discover more desert.
Their intractable leader sends strong dinos in search of water,
leaving behind Baylene and other misfits befriended by Aladar, the
movie's hero. Aladar discovers, however, that water is not far
below the surface of the desert, and with the help of Baylene's
tremendous foot pressing down on the sand, he dredges up enough
water to quench the thirst of the herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty tough scene, because it had to do with a lot
of different elements,'' Belzer says. ``Basically, they constructed
a set here in Burbank on a stage (and had) sand (brought in). They
had a (tank) of water set underneath the hole that Baylene's foot
presses down into.''
</P>
<P>
   The water was then pumped in to where Baylene's foot was
supposed to be. But, because the character's foot was a
computer-graphic model, adjustments had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``So a hard-cast, half-size sculpture was made of Baylene's foot
that was rigged to actually push down into the sand,'' Belzer says.
``It wouldn't move; it was just a hard, static piece. But that
allowed the water to actually come up onto the shape of a foot. So
we used that as a template or reference for our animation to go on
top of.''
</P>
<P>
   Belzer, who worked on the Tim Burton-produced stop-motion
features ``The Nightmare Before Christmas'' and ``James and the
Giant Peach,'' wasn't just a late-comer to ``Dinosaur'' _ he was a
late-comer to computer animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was resistant to the computer for a long time,'' he says,
adding that the tide turned when he took a job at Pixar Animation
Studios, the brains behind ``Toy Story'' and ``A Bug's Life.'' ``It
gave me my first taste of the computer. I really embraced it with
the help of Pixar. I think they really helped me appreciate that
it's nothing to be scared of, it's just opening up a new venue.''
</P>
<P>
   Belzer believes that computer-animation is the right medium for
``Dinosaur,'' which originally was planned as a
puppetry/stop-motion film. The computer allows the freedom to
accurately depict the huge creatures, which have inspired
filmmakers _ especially animators _ almost since the beginning of
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's just animators (who are fascinated by
dinosaurs),'' Belzer says. ``It's the public in general. I think
there's a genuine fascination with these giant things that used to
roam the earth. That's what draws the question of, `How would these
things move?' When I stood under a skeleton of a brachiosaur, I
realized at that time, `This is the character I'm working on? My
God, it's huge!' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
