<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM4KIDS-NYT &LR;      05-19 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE YEAR 3000, TRAVOLTA IS THE ONLY ONE WHO LAUGHS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATTLEFIELD EARTH
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta, Barry Pepper, Forest Whitaker, Sabine Karsenti
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Roger Christian
</P>
<P>
   PG-13, 117 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Remember Y2K? Now another millennium has flown by, and what's
left of mankind scampers around icy mountain crags, wearing scraps
of fur and hide and eating rats raw. In the year 3000 humans are
enslaved by 9-foot-tall aliens called Psychlos, after their planet,
who came and conquered all the Earth's peoples. It took them nine
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Humans are so traumatized they communicate in grunts while
slowly relearning all the old cliches. ``A good woman is hard to
find,'' someone says. Actually any woman is hard to find, save the
lithe and smoldering Chrissie (Karsenti), who is around to be
paired with the bounding hero of the piece, Jonnie Goodboy Tyler
(Pepper).
</P>
<P>
   Jonnie would defy the oppressors. They want the earth's gold,
these Psychlos, who are none too natty themselves in outfits that
put one in mind of Bert Lahr's Cowardly Lion in ``The Wizard of
Oz.'' Their chief of security, Terl, runs the show. Despite the
simian hairdo and ludicrous nose apparatus, Terl occasionally
reminds one of Travolta. Anyway, the movie frequently is so murky
that it is hard to tell who is who or what is what.
</P>
<P>
   The gist seems to be that if Jonnie can race over here to do
this and then rush over there to do that, the Psychlos will be sent
packing. At that Terl just throws back his maned head and emits
phony roars of laughter (not Travolta's strongest vocal suit).
</P>
<P>
   Then the humans hop into some thousand-year-old jet fighters as
if they were in ``Independence Day.'' A huge glass dome cracks and
shatters, which is bad for the Psychlos. Terl ends up in a cage.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Psychlos bat Earthlings around and subsequent warfare
results in moderately graphic injuries and death.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Some musings, but no sex to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: A small amount.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE: This is an amazingly bad movie adapted from a novel by
L. Ron Hubbard, the founder of the Church of Scientology. Since
Travolta is dedicated to that belief, it has been conjectured that
the film is intended to push moviegoers in that direction, perhaps
with subliminal messages. Considering its overall ineptitude, that
is hard to imagine. Is it a trick?
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 9: Much too loud and violent for the little ones.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12: Absurd twaddle that few would take seriously, and no
great harm will be done.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP: It's their money.
</P>
<P>
   GLADIATOR
</P>
<P>
   Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie Nielsen, Oliver Reed,
Richard Harris
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ridley Scott
</P>
<P>
   R, 150 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The Romans always could lay on a battle, and we begin with
legions led by the general Maximus (Crowe) performing their
catapult-and-pike routine on a mob of howling tribesmen in the
forests of Germania. Arriving late as usual by plushly appointed
carriage, the emperor's son, Commodus (Phoenix), and his scheming
sister, Lucilla (Nielsen), pay their respects to their father,
Marcus Aurelius (Harris), and give a wary nod to the general.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly there is unease in the command tent. With his son an
unbalanced weakling, the elderly emperor plans to pass power to
Maximus, who would really prefer to go home and tend his fields and
be with his wife and young son. But the frail and dying Aurelius
needs him to effect a major shift of authority from the throne to
the Senate. Rome is to become a republic again.
</P>
<P>
   Commodus is not comfortable with that idea. In short order his
father has gone to his end even more quickly than his condition
indicated. Maximus is taken off to be executed but escapes. Not so
lucky, his wife and son are crucified and burned alive by
Praetorians dispatched by Commodus. When next we encounter the
grief-stricken general, he has been sold to a gladiator merchant
(Reed) and sent to a training camp in North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Invincible on the battlefield, Maximus butchers all comers in
the ring and is soon ready for the big time in Rome. After
decimating half an army in the Colosseum, he becomes a hero of the
people. But how does he stand with Commodus?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Those who are about to die salute you, and that's just
about everybody. Decapitations, mutilations _ even a tiger gets his
in the ring, stabbed in the belly.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None, though gladiators could be excused a
four-letter outburst or two.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 12: Forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-13: An individual parental decision. Until the end, when
the melodrama and digital enhancement go over the top, the film is
an entertaining experience. But then there is the violence.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: Undoubtedly most of them (boys anyway) have
already seen the film. On balance, a thumb's up.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER STAGE
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Schull, Zoe Saldana, Susan May Pratt, Peter Gallagher,
Ethan Stiefel, Donna Murphy, Sascha Radetsky, Eion Bailey, Ilia
Kulik
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nicholas Hytner
</P>
<P>
   PG-13, 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Culled from stiff auditions, the teen-age dancers come to New
York to train at the American Ballet Academy and vie for a chance
to join the American Ballet Co. This crop includes Jody (Schull)
with a lovely face but a weak turn-out, bad feet and the wrong kind
of body; Maureen (Pratt), supremely talented but bulimic and
miserable; and Eva (Saldana), also gifted, but with a possibly
ruinous attitude problem. Sergei (Kulik) is from Russia and in
clubs tells girls he is Mafia, not a ballet dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan (Gallagher), the duly arrogant academy director, drives
them hard. Three boys and three girls will be chosen for the
company, with the decision to be announced after a workshop
performance before a packed house at Lincoln Center. Pressure? It's
enough to make Maureen buckle and run off to her calm, funny,
Columbia pre-med boyfriend (Bailey). After a lot of abuse, Jody
thinks she might be a better Broadway dancer.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal note she weighs the attentions of Cooper
(Stiefel), an established company star, and a classmate (Radetsky).
Eventually the three resolve the matter before an audience of
thousands in a number choreographed for the workshop by the
flamboyant Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   In a film that doesn't devote much effort to inventing original
characters and situations, careers and relationships take shape _
or don't _ strictly according to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: None.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: The dancing gets risque and Jody and Cooper go to bed,
though the act goes unrecorded.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Some.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-7: Too young.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 8-10: Parents should make a cautious judgment, but most
children will enjoy the film.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP: The film's formulaic approach may annoy some
viewers. Otherwise they should have fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
