<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-BOURGAIN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TELLTALE CHEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Screaming orders (``Calamari followed by filet
poivre! Am I waiting for a frisee?'') to his coterie of beloved
line cooks at Les Halles as he neared the end of his 13-hour day at
9 p.m. on Thursday, Anthony Bourdain was interrupted from his work
by diners darting in to shake his calloused hand.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Bourdain has emerged as a literary chef, as
appreciated for quips as steak frites, a kind of Clifford Odets
with a mandoline. Last year, after nearly three decades of
monitoring 30-quart stockpots, searing meat and, too often, his own
fingers, Anthony Bourdain decided that the world might want to know
how grizzly things can get around a Garland stove.
</P>
<P>
   Bourdain, who for eight years has been the executive chef at Les
Halles on Park Avenue South, sent an unsolicited article about
restaurant deceptions to The New Yorker, and to his surprise, the
magazine's editor, David Remnick, called Bourdain at work to let
him know it had been accepted. When the article ran, it caught the
attention of a book editor at Bloomsbury USA, who persuaded the
chef to spin his blustery culinary decrees (``Margarine? That's not
food. I can't believe it's not butter? I can.'') into a book.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Kitchen Confidential,'' a 307-page memoir, which
has been optioned by David Fincher, who directed the movie ``Fight
Club,'' elevating Bourdain to a celebrity status chefs usually
achieve after marketing their sauce lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great meal,'' said one man who seemed to stand at about half
of Bourdain's lanky height. ``My wife had the scallops. My sister
had the tuna. My other sister had the tuna.'' Bourdain thanked the
diner, though compliments on fish dishes might not flatter a man
who presides over a restaurant known for its in-house butcher, and
who flushes with animation at the mention of tete du veau, the
arcane veal dish he describes as ``mashed up face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is heaven tonight,'' Bourdain said of the restaurant's
large but not overwhelming crowd. He was turning out a mere 180
dinners, 70 fewer than the average.
</P>
<P>
   Even truer heaven for Bourdain might be an evening when no one
asks him to violate one of his creations. An order for onion soup
came in with a request to ``torch and nuke it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask us to do some pretty ugly things to the food,'' he
said. ``But I don't throw plates anymore. I don't try to make
people cry anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10, Bourdain left the remainder of the night's duties to his
charges. Removing his chef's coat and topping his black acid-wash
Levis with a T-shirt and jacket, he walked to Chicama, a Peruvian
restaurant about 10 blocks away, where he convenes with other chefs
after hours to eat marinated fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want is the kind of food I've been cooking
all day,'' he said, somewhere between rants about his hatred of
vegetarians (``Vegetarians are the enemy of everything good and
decent in the human spirit,'' he writes in his book), the chef
Emeril Lagasse and the unseemly concept of brunch.
</P>
<P>
   At Chicama, Bourdain received no special treatment. Though no
other chefs could join him this evening, he sat down to ceviche
negro, sea urchin and mojitos.
</P>
<P>
   Bourdain has a contract to write two more nonfiction books, one
on Typhoid Mary and the other about a round-the world odyssey on
which he will consume demi-glace-free fare like monkey brains. As
much as he relishes the writing life before him, he said, smoking a
cigarette at the end of supper, it makes him insecure as turning
out cassoulet every day does not. ``Now I'm wondering, will people
like me?'' he said. ``Why hasn't my agent called?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
