<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0520-COX     05-19 1858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Guiliani out of the race
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani ended his campaign for the Senate in New York
today, leaving Hillary Clinton temporarily without an opponent. The
decision, announced at a televised news conference, ended weeks of
speculation about his political future that was sparked by recent
disclosures of prostate cancer and a marital separation. The New
York mayor has said medical treatment might interfere with his
political campaign. With Giuliani out, it is thought that Rick
Lazio, a congressman from Long Island, will step in to run. Lazio
had been preparing for a Senate campaign until Gov. George Pataki
backed Giuliani in August.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREES CAN KEEP BUSY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush proposed incentives today to encourage older
Americans to volunteer, saying the nation should make better use of
``the healthiest, most energetic, best-educated generation of
seniors in history.'' Speaking at the McCracken County Senior
Center in Kentucky, Bush proposed a ``silver scholarship'' program
in which senior citizens would serve as tutors in after-school
programs in exchange for $1,000 educational scholarships. The money
could be used by the seniors' children, grandchildren or other
young people in need. Bush also said that if elected he would seek
an increase in funding for the Senior Service Corps from $183
million to $250 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   GORES SLIP AWAY TO MARK 30TH
</P>
<P>
   Al and Tipper Gore slipped out of town by Marine helicopter
today to celebrate their 30th wedding anniversary at the Delaware
shore. Aides said the couple _ with a Secret Service detail, a
military aide and press aide in tow _ were borrowing the beach home
of campaign chairman Tony Coelho and would return to Washington on
Sunday. Gore recently promised campaign reporters, apparently
without consulting the missus, that they could accompany him on
vacation travels in a small press pool. White House aides notified
reporters of the trip just this afternoon _ after the Gores were on
their way.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE NEEDED IN VERMONT FOR MCCAIN TO MAKE A NOISE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will be in Montpelier, Vt., Saturday to try to
salvage his ability to influence the party platform at the
convention. The Vermont Republican State Convention meets Saturday
to elect 12 delegates and 12 alternates. McCain won Vermont's
winner-take-all primary in March,
</P>
<P>
   65-35 percent, but it now appears that party regulars _
supporters of George W. Bush _ will win the majority of delegate
seats. Under party rules, someone can raise matters on the
convention floor only if the majorities of six state delegations
support the move. Vermont was one of seven states won by McCain.
After Bush forces seized the Michigan delegation, McCain controls
only five. He can't let Vermont slip away.
</P>
<P>
   CASTING A WIDE NET FOR A NO. 2
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush sent letters to 450 Republicans seeking advice on
a running mate. He also suggested in an interview that he would
accept someone who favors abortion rights _ within limits. ``I
assure you that your views and any advice you render will be kept
confidential,'' Bush wrote to senators, representatives, governors,
state GOP committee members, state party chairmen and
Bush-for-president committees. Separately, Bush was asked by Fox
News TV if he would consider teaming up with someone who, unlike
him, favors abortion rights. Bush said he'd consider Pennsylvania
Gov. Tom Ridge, who supports his state's strict legislation on
abortion and favors a ban on late-term, ``partial-birth''
abortions. By contrast, New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman vetoed a
bill that would have banned the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   STICKING A WEDGE BETWEEN THE BROTHERS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign is trying to pit brother against brother in
the debate with George W. Bush over Social Security. It circulated
a column in which Florida Gov. Jeb Bush warns against letting all
of the state's pension funds ride on the stock market. Bush wrote
in the April 18 Tallahassee Democrat of his concern that state
workers' retirement money was at risk because stock market losses
had caused the Florida Retirement Fund to lose about $8 billion in
a week _ $4 billion in one day. Jeb Bush argued it would be prudent
to put part of the $12 billion pension surplus ``and place it in a
reserve that is not affected by changes in the market'' in order to
``cushion future volatility'' and assure long-term stability.
</P>
<P>
   OUTSIDER ANGLING INSIDE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush likes to emphasize that he's a political outsider
from Texas, not a Washington insider. Increasingly, however, he's
making his opinions known on Capitol Hill, arguing that policy made
now could affect his presidency later. Joining with Republican
leaders and the Clinton administration this week, he urged Congress
to vote in favor of normal trade relations with China. He said he'd
make phone calls seeking support if House Majority Whip Tom DeLay
asked him. And through back channels, Bush also complained when
Congress was voting on setting a deadline for pulling U.S. troops
out of Kosovo. Bush and his foreign policy adviser, Condoleeza
Rice, warned lawmakers that such a deadline could limit his
flexibility if he wins in November.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT FOLLOWS `FELLOW TRAVELER', `PINKO'?
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party hopeful Pat Buchanan criticized George W. Bush for
supporting permanent normal trade relations with China, calling him
``a Clintonite fellow traveler.'' Buchanan, in a prepared
statement: ``Mr. Bush endorsed a Clinton trade policy that has
given Beijing $300 billion in trade surpluses since 1993, money
Beijing has used for the military buildup that now threatens Taiwan
and the U.S. 7th Fleet,'' Buchanan also condemned Bush for opposing
a bipartisan effort to set a date for withdrawal of U.S. troops
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   MOVING UPTOWN TO BIGGER DIGS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's national campaign headquarters is moving again _ to
Nashville's MetroCenter on June 10. It will give the campaign staff
about three times the space it now has as it gears up for the fall
campaign against George W. Bush. The operation has been
headquartered in tight quarters in a bargain-priced location since
the vice president uprooted it from Washington in October. ``We had
to really cut the budget, but the facility has been great for the
transition. It brought people together,'' said campaign chairman
Tony Coelho. Gore credits the move to Nashville for jump-starting a
primary campaign that was being bruised by a stronger than expected
challenge from Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL STEPS MISSING THE FOOTHOLD
</P>
<P>
   It was Al Gore's crowd in Orlando, Fla.: thousands of senior
citizens at the AARP convention. But among the crowd were people
such as Janet Mayhew, 69, who seemed to crystallize a concern
enveloping the Gore campaign: ``To me, Gore hasn't got a platform.
He has not said what he would do.'' Such reaction chills the Gore
campaign, which has spent more than a year distributing position
papers on nearly every imaginable topic. Clearly, Gore does have a
platform, but it is perceived by many voters as a status-quo,
preserve-the-prosperity campaign _ and the vice president is
finding that it may not be enough to win. His strategy has been to
put forward what he believes is a realistic, if less audacious,
agenda, while vowing not to take ``risky'' steps that could upset
the prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL POLLS PROVIDE THE CLUES
</P>
<P>
   Never mind those national polls that show George W. Bush
slightly ahead of Al Gore. The electoral system designed by the
founding fathers makes it almost impossible to predict November's
outcome by national polls alone since the battle is fought by
separate elections in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
The presidency is decided by who can put together 270 electoral
votes. Each state has a share of votes based on population, and
whoever wins a state claims all of its votes. But analysts say
national polls serve an important purpose by providing insight on
how candidates are doing with certain groups like women or
independents, on people's feelings about their personal qualities
and positions on issues, and by measuring broad movement.
</P>
<P>
   SO SIMILAR, YET SO DIFFERENT
</P>
<P>
   Here's one difference between Tipper Gore and Hillary Clinton.
At last weekend's Million Mom March for gun control, Clinton,
wearing a light spring pantsuit and straw hat, was so busy working
the crowds, she created rally gridlock. Fellow blonde baby boomer
Gore, with a white T-shirt tucked into blue jeans, marched arm in
arm with other women, without an entourage and relatively
unheralded. The two women's different styles at the march provided
a vivid contrast between their current approaches to their public
roles. The New York Times quoted one person who knows them both:
``Hillary went as a candidate; Tipper went as a mom.''
</P>
<P>
   A MAN CAUGHT IN THE MIDDLE
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan lost much of his social conservative base when he
bolted the GOP, and now has alienated many supporters of his
adopted Reform Party _ including some state leaders who prefer the
party run nobody and forfeit the $12.6 million in federal funding.
With Buchanan registering just 4 percent in the polls on the eve of
his self-imposed deadline to break into double digits, the Reform
Party seems headed for its worst presidential showing yet. Old
Buchanan supporters are leery of his embracing a party that shares
few of his views on abortion, homosexuality and other social
issues. And supporters of Reform Party founder Ross Perot are
concerned that he wants to take over and reshape their
organization.
</P>
<P>
   SOUND-ALIKE NAME GAME OVER
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Gebhardt, whose sound-alike primary challenge to
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri had Democrats in a
frustrated frenzy, dropped his candidacy. Gebhardt filed paperwork
withdrawing from the 3rd District primary and will not appear
alongside the veteran congressman on the Aug. 8 primary ballot. The
state GOP denied being behind the challenge, but GOP activists said
Gebhardt often attended Republican meetings in St. Charles County.
Gebhardt-with-a-B, 65, said his decision was ``doctor's orders.''
</P>
<P>
   UPHILL BATTLE IN FLAT STATE
</P>
<P>
   With a Presbyterian church as his backdrop, David Johnson, a
Democrat who serves as a policy adviser to Indiana Gov. Frank
O'Bannon, cast himself as a champion of Hoosier values in beginning
his campaign to unseat Sen. Richard Lugar, a Republican seeking a
fifth term. Johnson declared it was ``time we have a new senator
who will put these values into action,'' as he stood outside the
Indianapolis church where his father was once pastor. It will be an
uphill battle for Johnson, who has raised $412,000 in
contributions. Lugar has amassed $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
