<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0090 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SCANDINAVIAN-CHIC-ART     05-19 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANDINAVIAN-CHIC-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEERS FOR ALL THINGS SWEDISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was so much good will blowing through the
Altman Building on West 18th Street the other day _ generated, in
part, by bottles of warm Carlsberg beer _ it hardly seemed like a
fashion show. ``Fashion Strikes Down From the North!'' the
invitation promised, in charming, Ikea-esque ``English is my second
language'' prose, beckoning you to a three-day exhibition of
fashion, food and design conceived by a magazine called Stockholm
New. ``Frontline Nordic Gastronomy! Blondes with Braids!''
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30 on the night of May 10, the building was filled with
hundreds of men and women with terrific skin smoking cigarettes.
``All Swedish people know each other, and I believe they're all in
this room,'' said Johan Svensson, the art director of Jane
magazine, explaining the absence of Americans. ( Svensson is not
Swedish, although his wife, Maria Virgin, is. Virgin is the fashion
editor of Stockholm New, an English-language magazine of Swedish
fashion and design with a circulation of 53,000.)
</P>
<P>
   A forest of fake fir trees lurked just inside the door, guarding
a phalanx of five-inch-high Dalecarlian horses, the red-painted
wooden horses that are the Swedish mascot. Other Swedish symbols
were represented, too: a silver Volvo Cross Country; a display from
the cheap-chic retailer H&AMP;M featuring young Swedes in low-priced
leather; and beautiful furniture in pale wood and wool made by
contemporary Swedish designers, including a chair that looked like
a fat comma designed by Bjorn Dahlstrom for a company called Cbi.
</P>
<P>
   Short films played as a backdrop to the catwalk show: there were
clips of flames, of feathers floating in a river and, I think, of
tick larvae. The models drifted by in clothes by five designers.
Swedish furniture is smooth; Swedish fashion is rather furry.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, you could take plates of smoked salmon to tables
covered with a vintage Marimekko design (Melooni, in orange, blue
and black) that looked so right and so contemporary after all these
years, you felt you had to have it. Marimekko is a Finnish company,
but no matter; Nordic countries like to stick together.
</P>
<P>
   It was all very attractive and so familiar, because for some
time now we've been in the midst of some sort of Nordic intermezzo,
stylewise. The appetite for midcentury modern American furniture
led, inevitably, to a taste for the clean-lined Scandinavian
designs of the same era. Manhattan is full of 25-year-olds who
burble passionately about the Finnish master Alvar Aalto and his
Danish contemporary Hans Wegner, and there are entire stores, like
Totem on Franklin Street, and magazines (hello, Wallpaper), devoted
to this new/old aesthetic. It seems there's now an appetite for the
entire Scandinavian lifestyle, lock, stock and herring.
</P>
<P>
   May 22, the American Craft Museum will be the host of a seminar
on Swedish furniture design.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be talking about the fact that Scandinavian design has
become a global phenomenon,'' David McFadden, chief curator at the
museum, said. ``Why? Because there's something so human about it.
Something spare and lean and wonderfully hopeful. It's that feeling
I like very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Brule, 31, and the editorial director of the
Nordic-worshiping Wallpaper, said, ``You could look at this whole
thing as part of a broader Nordic moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How did it start?'' he asked. ``You remember going to your
Auntie's house and she had all these weird Danish pieces, and then
it started to look really odd. In the 90's you wouldn't touch it,
but now it looks right. It's not made out of a gel, and it doesn't
have those scary spindly legs. It looks clean and maybe a little
bit honest. That's why people are still switched on to this
midcentury moment and by default great Scandinavian products. Look
at cell phones. Those countries are way ahead of us in terms of
cell phone penetration.''
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned to Brule the Marimekko tablecloths, how beautiful
they looked and how weird it is that something you once dismissed
as hopelessly retrograde could seem so fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a girl in our office who dresses in head-to-toe
Marimekko, and she looks fantastic,'' said Brule, who will be
spending the summer in his new '60s modern house outside of
Stockholm. ``You see the store in Stockholm, and it's so
progressive. And it makes Miu Miu look not particularly
progressive. If you go on to look at Swedish fashion design, you'll
see that it's not particularly tricky. I think a lot of fashion,
that's fashion with a capital `F,' has become very tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   At his store Moss, on Greene Street in SoHo, Murray Moss sells
the work of Pia Wallen, a contemporary designer, whose felt
slippers and wool blankets with a Swiss cross have become like
chocolates to people who can pronounce Arne Jacobsen properly.
(It's arn YAK-ob-sen, and Moss also sells his vintage stainless
steel flatware, which appeared in the movie ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes from a lack in the diet,'' Moss said, using a
nutritional metaphor to explain the taste for all things
Scandinavian. ``You've had the gleaming stainless steel and
aluminum and techno fibers in fashion and techno music and all of a
sudden, the way you say, `Too much salt!' you say: `Where is the
humanity in all this? Where is something tactile? Where is
something fragile for God sakes!'''
</P>
<P>
   Moss says the essence of current Scandinavian style resides with
Droog Design, a Dutch collective with an intellectual bent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Scandinavian thing is a ripple effect,'' he said. ``Here's
Droog: you get the designer Hella Jongerius, and she shows a
carbon-fiber chair with this very raw felt that looks like a pelt
out of `King Lear' or something. It's from this company Not Tom,
Dick or Harry _ get it? _ and the woman whose company it is raises
sheep, she shears them herself and weaves the wool herself and
sells it to Hella, who incorporates this raw wool into her chair,
and the result is the hot-cold product. It's Baked Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if anything is a trend, that's an example of it,'' Moss
added triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   There were all kinds of hot-cold things at the Milan Furniture
Fair last month, like a steel cube chair by a Dutch partnership, Do
Create, which you warm up yourself by whacking with a sledgehammer
(included with the chair).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a cartoonish example of what we're talking about,''
Moss said. ``It's a not-subtle manifestation of the idea that now
we need to sense human interaction in design.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
