<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0091 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SMALL-HANDBAGS-FASHIO     05-19 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-HANDBAGS-FASHION-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDBAGS GO ON DOUBLE DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Pratique, always pratique.'' Announcing her credo
in a Gallic drone, Carlyne Cerf de Dudzeele, a freelance fashion
editor, was about to put it to the test. She reached into the
depths of her Hermes Birkin bag _ a high-capacity satchel that
could, in a pinch, hold her Yorkie _ and pulled out a minuscule
shoulder bag spattered with tawny LVs.
</P>
<P>
   Trim and flat as a postcard, it would see her through lunch. De
Dudzeele's second sack holds little more than a lipstick, a credit
card and a set of keys _just right for this professional vagabond,
whose day might take her from an office to a boutique in the Nolita
neighborhood of lower Manhattan to Seventh Avenue and back, ending
in a late-night dinner with friends. A woman who lives the maxim
``You can't be too streamlined or too thin,'' she reaches
reflexively for her Louis Vuitton Pochette whenever she heads for a
restaurant, leaving her tote at the office or the coat check.
</P>
<P>
   De Dudzeele, who has spent the better part of her career
obsessing over details of self-packaging, is at home with the
notion that a big bag packs power, while its smaller companion
carries a different sort of clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bag may be so small it barely holds a lipstick, but it's
definitely the status bag,'' said Laird Borrelli the co-author,
with Valerie Steele, of ``The Handbag: A Lexicon of Style''
(Rizzoli). The tote, by contrast, is usually more humble, Borrelli
pointed out. ``I think of the canvas L.L. Bean version carried by
Conde Nast editors,'' she said. ``Both together function as a
survival kit for the glamour puss.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Spade, the handbag designer, who personally subscribes to
the two-bag system, said: ``For a while, I think it was just people
in fashion who carried two bags. But now a lot of people have
picked up on the idea. It's a trend, absolutely. The small bag is
so prevalent now that you have to carry another bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers have pounced on the trend. Tod's, Lambertson Truex and
Burberry are among a number of companies that have recently
introduced or plan to introduce matched sets of handbags, meant for
the woman who must have two. ``Women tend to use a larger bag for
practicality, a smaller one for fashion and social reasons,'' noted
Richard Lambertson of Lambertson Truex. ``We believe in merging the
pair.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrelli said that the trimmer, daintier bag is the one with the
fancier provenance. ``It was associated way back with the
chatelaine of the castle,'' she said. ``Her servants did the
marketing. She was required to carry no more than embroidery tools,
a handkerchief and smelling salts.'' Placed on a lunch or dinner
table, the contemporary model becomes ``a bibelot,'' she added,
``part of a milieu and also part of the conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Many women feel as she does that the compact style denotes
class. Marian Rivman, a New York public relations consultant,
stashes a small shoulder bag inside her satchel to pull out at
receptions and meetings. ``The Queen of England, you always see her
with a handkerchief and little purse, and she's not carrying a
dime,'' Rivman rationalized. ``A small bag means refinement. It
means you have your stuff together.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, it's sexy. ``Do you really want, in a room full
of men, to go fishing into your tote for a business card?'' Rivman
asked pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Beatty Adler, an art dealer and the vice president of
Richard Feigen &AMP; Co., finds her small bag liberating. She walks to
work each day with a shiny brown leather tote from Tod's. ``If
you're busy and have a lot of things on your plate, you carry it
around in the hope you might be able to get them done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But its weight and the burden of chores left undone sometimes
leaves her winded. ``I often feel like a donkey,'' she said. That's
where her second bag comes in. A medium-size fake Kelly, it makes
her feel like a sprite. ``Sometimes I feel it's my right not to be
burdened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As style watchers see it, the small bag is a badge of hip. ``It
reflects a woman who is definitely streamlining herself,'' said
Daniel Harris, who wrote ``The Content of Women's Purses,'' an
essay published in 1995 in Salmagundi, a literary magazine. ``You
can actually take it out on the dance floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In contrast, the larger bag represents a stodgy matron with a
big dowdy purse that impedes her mobility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As distasteful as such an image may be, it hasn't induced most
two-bag women to part with their thunderous totes. The reason,
Harris suggested, is that the large bag is an emblem of ``a woman's
migration from private life into public life,'' as a consequence of
which the bag functions as ``a surrogate home'' replete with items
more commonly found on desk tops and dressing tables, and even in
the kitchen sink (like a can opener).
</P>
<P>
   Adler, for one, views her large bag as a traveling survival kit.
It houses art magazines, auction catalogs, paperbacks for reading
in a cab, part of the contents of her lunch and her children's
hockey and lacrosse schedules. ``You never know,'' she said, ``when
you're going to get stuck in an elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   Marta Ibarrondo, a freelance advertising art director, said:
``Personally, I feel like I'm always traveling. I work in New York,
but on most days I carry as many things as when I'm in an airport _
cookies and sunflower seeds, nail polish, face cream _ you name
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are those who swim against the current. It takes a
leap of courage, but from time to time Irene Albright forsakes her
tote for something trimmer. The owner of Imelda's Closet, a fashion
rental business that caters to stylists, Albright believes in
rigorous editing. She has, accordingly, reduced the contents of her
purse to a small Filofax, a wallet, a compact and keys.
</P>
<P>
   Though she struggles to make less do more, she asks herself from
time to time if she's being realistic. ``Can I keep this up?'' she
asked. `` Who knows? One lives in hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
