<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     05-19 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF INFORMATION OVERLOAD AND THE `EFFICIENT' MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX BERENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 2000, volatility has turned into a four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming steadily more variable over the last five years,
stock prices have reached new levels of instability this year. The
Nasdaq composite index now routinely rises or falls 3 percent in a
session. That used to be rare: Between 1971, when the Nasdaq was
created, and the end of 1997, there were only 40 days with moves of
3 percent or more. In 1998 and 1999, there were a total of 35. In
the 4{ months since Jan. 1, there have been 34.
</P>
<P>
   Many professional traders and money managers view the increased
volatility as an ominous sign, directly connected to the rise in
day trading. With trading costs falling, chat rooms spreading
rumors and securities markets fragmenting into competing electronic
networks, it is no wonder prices swing wildly, they say. And that
should worry even people who are not CNBC habitues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When intraday volatility is high, people lose confidence in
the meaning of price,'' said Robert Schwartz, professor of finance
at Baruch College.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a more benign explanation for the rise in
volatility, said Greg Duffee, a professor at the business school of
the University of California at Berkeley and a former researcher
for the Federal Reserve. Understanding it requires a short primer
on efficient market theory, which luckily is not as dry as it
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   In its most rigorous (and absurd) form, efficient market theory
says investors can never beat the market except through luck,
because stocks are always properly valued based on the information
available to investors. So stocks should rise and fall only in
response to new data. Company X reports earnings that are lower
than expected; Company X's stock falls. Company Y announces a new
biotechnology breakthrough; Company Y's shares rise.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the real world, efficient market theory has lots
of holes. An investor who researched Company X thoroughly might
anticipate those ``lower than expected'' earnings. A biotechnology
expert might see Company Y's breakthrough coming before other
investors do. But efficient market theorists regard those cases as
rare. And few serious investors disagree with the theory's
practical implication that it is very hard to beat the market over
long periods.
</P>
<P>
   So never mind the day traders, and forget fragmentation.
Volatility may be rising simply because investors must digest more
information every day. With product cycles shortening, with
breakthroughs every week in technology and biotechnology, no one
should be surprised that share prices are bouncing all over, Duffee
said.
</P>
<P>
   If the day-trader theory were right, he said, there would be
telltale statistical evidence. ``Imagine it's just more trading
that's causing more price changes, and not more information,'' he
said. ``Then people are just pushing prices, and you're going to
see a lot of negative serial correlation'' _ what went up Monday
comes down Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Duffee conceded that in the last six months the Nasdaq has
taken just that kind of round trip, from 3,500 to 5,000 and back,
he said thorough analysis over longer periods finds no such
oscillating trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your eyes can't determine statistical significance,'' Duffee
said. ``I'm not saying markets are efficient. I'm saying, if they
were inefficient in this way, it would be really easy to make a
boatload of money.'' And whenever that's true on Wall Street,
someone steps in to make it _ and the inefficiency disappears.
</P>
<P>
   For the clincher, Duffee said, look back at past occasions when
trading volume rose sharply. The best example came in 1975, when
brokers were forced to compete on commissions for the first time.
``Trading just exploded,'' he said. ``Volatility didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
