<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0102 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      05-19 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT DO YOU KNOW THIS ABOUT THAT?
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   A gender gap study shows that men
know more about things like who's running Russia and women know
more about allergy shots.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center, which does studies on people and the
press, regularly analyzes the information gender gap by giving pop
current event quizzes. In the latest one, which matched others in
the past, men answered more accurately than women questions like,
``Does the Dow Jones company own a news organization?'' and ``Which
country was accused of spying and stealing nuclear technology from
the U.S.?''
</P>
<P>
   Any kind of gender study is bound to offend someone, but this
one doesn't seem that incendiary once you get past the initial
implications that men are deep and women are lightweights.
</P>
<P>
   Men, according to the study, are inclined to know more about
business and government, which some of you might remember from
Trivial Pursuit days.
</P>
<P>
   But women come in higher on health, education and cultural
subjects. More women than men answered correctly about the Supreme
Court ruling on parental notification about abortion. More women
know who Ellen DeGeneres is.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers concluded that what we know best reflects what
we're interested in. In other words, cholesterol and abortion
speaks to women more than the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   That could be true. Many a woman is probably content to leave
wastewater politics to someone else while she studies the latest
finding on chromosomes and disease.
</P>
<P>
   (Warning here: I'm generalizing and so are the researchers. Of
course there are exceptions and some women can't get enough of
political dealings _ ask me about ``West Wing''_ and some men can
talk all night about school test scores.)
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that one gender knows more about really important
matters than the other? I think not. First of all, the majority of
this pop quiz had to do with business takeovers, the U.S.
government and foreign military conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   But, are these the only things we need to know about? No one
asked anything about genomes or the high cost of housing. If we all
knew about the same thing we'd have pretty dull parties.
</P>
<P>
   More men can tell you the president's annual salary, the study
showed, but more women could remember what President Clinton
declared his top priority for his second term. Surprise. It was
education.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime newspaper readers may remember when the newspaper was
divided by gender. There was a separate women's section. That left
the rest of the paper _ war, money, sports, politics and business _
for men. Back then, if women didn't start reading until they hit
the fudge recipes they had a excuse not to know about matters of
state.
</P>
<P>
   For a time there was a notion that men liked hard news, which
often comes with a lot of numbers in it and a government source.
And women were drawn to soft news, which is not always tied to a
current event and has a lot of people in it. Hard news was about
power and influence. Soft news was about people like your neighbor.
Hard news was about money and products. Soft news was about
families.
</P>
<P>
   Hard news and soft news got together a while back and we don't
divide up the paper by gender, so I worried that this pop quiz
study was an attempt to drag us back to our old boxes.
</P>
<P>
   No judgments, they say. Women follow disaster stories, reactions
to court rulings and controversies over health procedures like
mammograms and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Men are more likely to follow stories about military action,
international politics, business and finance and sports. Someone
pointed out that you can see how politics play to men by using
sports analogies.
</P>
<P>
   I guess we'll know they're trying to appeal to women when they
start referring to the highly-placed as ``smooth dancers'' as well
as ``team players.''
</P>
<P>
   I believe that women do read about the latest corporate takeover
and that fighting has broken out again in Sierra Leone. Maybe we
just don't feel the need to retain it.
</P>
<P>
   When we need to know, we find out. Two years ago, women didn't
do as well as men on identifying Bill Gates. Now he's our new best
friend, or maybe we don't like him this week, but we know the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we don't have as many file drawers in our brain reserved
for statistics, because we need space for the pediatrician's
number, high school counselor's name and the in-laws' anniversary
date. Besides, if we want to know who's in charge of Russia we can
check out the Kremlin's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The category where men and women have equal knowledge is crime,
scandal and personality. During the height of the Clinton scandal,
an equal number of men and women could identify the name Kathleen
Willey. Equal numbers could also name four characters on
``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ellen DeGeneres, here's the deal: I'll keep track of
Ellen if he'll take Putin.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
