<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-$ADV21-COX     05-19 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPULIST FORMER COKE EXECUTIVE CLOSING IN ON MEXICO'S RULING
PARTY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In an obscure slum plagued by open sewage and
rotting unclaimed garbage, Mexican presidential candidate Vicente
Fox found something to smile about.
</P>
<P>
   His arms stretched high and wide into a victory sign, the
towering, cowboy-booted politician looked out on an adoring crowd
of factory workers and housewives chanting his slogan _ ``Enough!
Enough! Enough!''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six-and-a-half-feet tall, Fox had to double over to kiss
an Indian woman who defected from Mexico's 71-year-old ruling party
so she could back the charismatic opposition leader. ``Kiss!
Kiss!'' the crowd shouted, breaking into wolf whistles fit for a
movie star.
</P>
<P>
   With six weeks to go before the most competitive presidential
election this country has ever seen, Fox is a phenomenon who could
unleash a revolution in Mexico if he wins on July 2. Judging from
most opinion polls, the rancher, and former Coca-Cola executive and
governor is the first opposition candidate who has a chance at
finally defeating the party that has controlled Mexico's presidency
since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Most opinion polls are showing Fox a few points behind or even
with Francisco Labastida, the candidate of Mexico's Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI (pronounced, ``pree''). Fox's own polls
_ and at least one independent one _ show he has even pulled
several points ahead of Labastida. It's a claim that has
electrified this race and given Fox extra ammunition in his war to
lure voters of all political stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to extend an invitation to all the PRI supporters in
the country. They shouldn't feel left out. They're all invited to
join this great popular movement,'' Fox told residents of this poor
section of Mexico City's Alvaro Obregon borough.
</P>
<P>
   He paused and grinned. ``The only ones that will be left out are
the corrupt!''
</P>
<P>
   True to a broad-based campaign strategy he launched several
years ago, Fox is also trying to drain votes away from Mexico's
leftist opposition even though he is a conservative proponent of
free-market economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   He is promising Mexicans what the PRI can't offer after decades
in power _ a total change in government _ while extending an olive
branch and pledging to build a plural, corruption-free government
with experts and ideological input from all parties.
</P>
<P>
   Because he can be blunt and theatrical _ he is a rancher who
relaxes by racing around on his favorite horse _ Fox has sometimes
been compared to former U.S. President Ronald Reagan. But the
57-year-old, who was president of Coca-Cola's Latin America Group
from 1975 to 1979, is a crafty marketing expert whose election
strategy is more like President Bill Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Clinton moved from the left to the middle of the
American political spectrum, Fox has moved to the right to position
himself as a moderate. He is urging Mexicans to make history _
comparing his possible victory to tearing down the Berlin Wall _
and trying to convince them that he's the best option for ending a
political monopoly and installing a ``transitional'' democratic
government.
</P>
<P>
   Fox belongs to Mexico's National Action Party, the PAN, which
governs six states and is generally considered the most socially
and fiscally conservative of Mexico's political parties.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox has cultivated his image as a Jesuit-educated
compassionate conservative. He left his job as governor of
Guanajuato last year on a high note after attracting record amounts
of foreign investment for industries there. A gritty rancher whose
love of the outdoors is genuine, he is fairly popular among the
poor _ although his record is ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   While he was governor, his state started charging residents for
some basic medical services. But Fox also made grants and
low-interest loans available to women who wanted to start small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He is running for president under the banner of the Alliance for
Change, a coalition that includes the PAN and Mexico's smaller,
environmentalist Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   As the final weeks of the campaign approach _ a televised debate
is scheduled for Tuesday _ the PRI is pummeling its chief foe with
accusations that he is too conservative and contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has indeed, for example, sent mixed messages in the past
about whether he believes Mexico's state-run oil industry should be
privatized. He has suggested that the industry is not benefiting
Mexicans because it is rife with corruption and mismanagement. But
he now says that privatization probably wouldn't be acceptable in a
transitional government.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the PRI have even questioned whether Fox is ``Mexican
enough'' to be president because his mother was born in Spain and
one of his grandfathers _ hence the Fox surname _ was an American.
In a paid pro-Labastida newspaper insert in Tabasco, a state
politician suggested Fox doesn't have the ethnic make-up to care
about Mexico's oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong feelings toward country, history, tradition, culture
and nationalism are learned at home,'' the ad said. ``But they can
also be a genetic matter . . . Vicente Fox doesn't have one drop of
Mexican blood.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week with Cox Newspapers at one of his
campaign offices here, Fox said he expected an onslaught of
attacks. Despite the PRI's proclamation that it's a new party, he
said, it is also preparing its legendary political machine to make
sure that PRI governors and federal bureaucrats get out the vote
for Labastida on election day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida's strategy changed after he dropped to second in
polls,'' Fox said. ``He called in the dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   After a televised debate in April, much of the news media here
proclaimed Fox the winner of the event. Afterward, Labastida's
campaign took into its fold some infamous PRI politicians
derisively known as ``dinosaurs'' because they have been accused in
the past of old-fashioned vote buying and electoral fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're trying to trying to put Fox in a niche or put a
label on him branding him a reactionary, a right-winger, an
anti-feminist, `` Fox said. ``We expected that. It's the campaign
of a loser. There is desperation in the ranks of the PRI. It's
never been a loser before. But they're going to have to get used to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, it looked like the PRI's toughest opponent
for the presidency would be Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a former PRI
member who broke from the party in the 1980s and formed the leftist
Democratic Revolution Party, the PRD. Despite Cardenas' noble image
as protector of the poor, he has slipped to a distant third in most
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas has refused overtures from Fox to retreat and join his
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has attracted some of Cardenas' former political advisors
who say their priority is defeating the PRI. And just days before
the Tuesday debate, Fox won the endorsement of the former personal
secretary of Luis Donaldo Colosio, a 1994 PRI presidential
candidate who was assassinated by gunman in Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Fox says his own polling shows Labastida enjoys a 20-point
advantage in Mexico's countryside, where 30 percent of the
electorate lives. He says his campaign plans a blitz to get to
those voters in the final two weeks before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's success stems in large part from Mexicans' general disgust
with PRI corruption and cycles of economic crisis. His rise also
coincides with a freer press and new campaign rules that are more
egalitarian. And he has kept his message simple, said University of
Guanajuato political expert Luis Miguel Rionda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy he uses is the same as Coca-Cola's,'' Rionda
said. ``Saturation, repetition and simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's multi-faceted personality hasn't hurt him either.
</P>
<P>
   He is a good-looking man with a Harvard business degree who in
the 1980s became a leading voice against electoral fraud after a
tainted governor's election in his state. He speaks excellent
English and has taken to traveling to the United States to meet
with Mexican immigrants there who can influence their families at
home.
</P>
<P>
   And he easily amuses working-class Mexicans by trashing the PRI
and lacing his campaign speeches with ripe language.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit to Mexico City's Alvaro Obregon neighborhood,
Fox modified a Mexican folk song for comic effect. ``Mexico
beautiful and dear,'' he recited into a microphone, ``if I die far
from thee, tell them I was screwed because of those in the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Anita Islas Trejo, a 44-year-old housewife who attended the
rally, said she's for Fox precisely because he is so plain-spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't come down here and make promises that he would give
us more houses or drainage systems,'' she said. ``He was just
willing to come down here and see those of us who live in dirty
corners like this. I look at him as a person who is like me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.fox2000.org.mx
</P>
<P>
   www.labastida2000.org.mx
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
