<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0114 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-JESSEJAMES-TEXAS-TEX     05-19 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSEJAMES-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE BELIEVERS SAY BODY IN GRANBURY CEMETERY IS THAT OF JESSE
JAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ All those true believers who insist that the
legendary train robber Jesse James is buried in a Granbury cemetery
might finally get their answer soon.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-delayed quest to exhume the body of a man known as J.
Frank Dalton _ but whose gravestone says Jesse Woodson James _ has
been scheduled for May 30 in Granbury, the Hood County seat, 40
miles southwest of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   This time, an Oklahoma used-car dealer-turned-amateur historian
who has championed the effort isn't saying who will carry out the
forensic testing, other than that the person is from outside Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell anyone,'' said Bud Hardcastle of
Purcell, Okla., who has the power of attorney for three of James'
purported grandsons. ``I'm not going to have them besieged by phone
calls and have them back out again.''
</P>
<P>
   In February when he received a court order from Hood County
Judge Linda Steen, Hardcastle said Harrell Gill-King, director of
the University of North Texas' Forensic Anthropology Laboratory in
Denton, would conduct the tests.
</P>
<P>
   But Gill-King said he had dropped out of the project two years
before.
</P>
<P>
   David Glassman, a forensic anthropologist at Southwest Texas
State University, will also participate in the exhumation,
Hardcastle said. Glassman was out of the country and couldn't be
reached to comment. In an interview last month, Glassman said that
he would probably participate in the project, but that he couldn't
conduct all tests in his own laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Most historical accounts maintain that Bob Ford shot James on
April 3, 1882, and that James is buried in Kearney, Mo. But
nonmainstream historians and some people asserting kinship have
long questioned that version.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, George Washington University professor James
Starrs said at a forensic science convention that findings from the
DNA in a tooth led his team to conclude that the body buried in
Kearney is James'.
</P>
<P>
   Like other revisionists, Hardcastle contends that James faked
his death and made his way to Texas, using the alias of Dalton.
Moreover, the tooth tested for DNA came not from the Kearney grave
but from a Missouri museum, Hardcastle said.
</P>
<P>
   When Dalton died in 1951, a casual ``autopsy'' by the Hood
County sheriff listed at least 16 bullet wounds, rope burns on a 17
1/2-inch neck, scarred and burned feet, and the tip of the left
index finger ``sawed off.'' If Dalton was James, he would have been
104 when he died.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton went to Granbury shortly after World War II and told
people that he was Jesse James. Some longtime residents recall
being charged admission to see him in his last days.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hite of Godley, who says he is distantly related to
James, said, ``It would satisfy my curiosity if it turns out to be
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if it turns out not to be him, I won't accept the fact
that he's buried in Missouri until they test the body of a man in
Falls County,'' in Central Texas, said Hite, 65. ``I think he might
be down there too.''
</P>
<P>
   Hite will host about a dozen people at his Godley cafe, the
Chisholm Restaurant, the day before the exhumation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get together and discuss what we know,'' Hite
said. ``I've got plenty of room. I expect Mr. Hardcastle and a
couple of the relatives from Arkansas as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The three purported grandsons, who live in Arkansas, Oklahoma
and Iowa, are expected to attend if their health permits,
Hardcastle said. He also expects at least one representative of
those who believe that James is buried in Missouri to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this should finally settle the question, providing
everybody stays hooked in place,'' Hardcastle said. ``They've told
me this will take about eight weeks to find out, but I'll believe
that when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
