<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-PERSONAL-FINANCE-DISA     05-19 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-FINANCE-DISASTERS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING YOUR FINANCIAL LIFE FROM DESTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before a wildfire burned their house _ and more than 200
other Los Alamos, N.M., homes _ to the ground last week, Dick and
Judy Opsahl were told they had a last chance to rescue what they
could. Opsahl said they first grabbed ``a few treasures'' and a bit
of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next part,'' he added, ``was to be sure we got the hard
drives.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of their financial lives, from tax records to rental
payments, were on their computers, which were soon up and running
again in their temporary home at the Cities of Gold Casino Hotel in
nearby Pojoaque.
</P>
<P>
   Laina Katcher, in her rush to leave Los Alamos, did not think to
bring the family computer, but she did pack her bills for the
current month. ``Isn't that stupid?'' she said, looking back. ``Why
would I want those?''
</P>
<P>
   Even during a catastrophe, people seem concerned about their
financial responsibilities, though usually after paying heed to
things with more sentimental value. Now that residences are often
home offices or home-based businesses, too, many have more data to
lose. People also now tend to carry more debt, which makes dealing
with creditors and worrying about cash flow part of the daily
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more going on in the household than ever before,''
said Brent A. Neiser, director of collaborative programs at the
National Endowment for Financial Education, a nonprofit group in
Englewood, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate databases can reconstruct most financial documents,
though the bureaucracy can be overwhelming. ``We're all financially
networked with large institutions, not just community banks and
credit unions where you can go down the street and ask, ``What's
going on?''' Neiser said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the devastation of Hurricane Andrew in 1992, Neiser's
group began working on a way to provide financial guidance to
disaster victims.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the Red Cross, it interviewed victims of previous
floods, fires and earthquakes and found that many experienced the
same financial obstacles. Some were as basic as not having change
on hand for pay phones when residential lines were down. Others
involved an added cause of misery, like unscrupulous contractors
who show up immediately after a calamity to take advantage of
homeowners still in shock.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines were developed, and later revised in tandem with the
Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Some seeming nightmares have a way of working out. Almost as
soon as the Los Alamos post office closed for a few days, for
example, the Postal Service began unloading mail at a Red Cross
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving, say, a Visa bill was important to the evacuees, said
Jo Anne Jones, a Red Cross spokeswoman in Los Alamos. ``When
they're in the shelter all day, they do worry about those things,
simply because there is not much else they can do,'' she said.
After the post office reopened, temporary post-office boxes were
set up for those who no longer had much of an address.
</P>
<P>
   Most large insurance companies send claims adjusters to disaster
sites, where they can write checks on the spot for people with
immediate needs. These representatives often also wind up fielding
general financial questions from their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just basically telling them not to worry,'' said Gloria
Brown, a Los Alamos claims adjuster for State Farm, who lost her
own home of 26 years in the fire. The only document she brought
with her in the evacuation was a birth certificate, but the last
thing on her mind was getting a copy of her mutual-fund statement,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is start all over again,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, coping with a communitywide disaster is easier
than going it alone. ``The Rotary Clubs in Japan sent thousands of
dollars to this area,'' said Richard Hardman, whose home and
business were damaged in Northridge, Calif., earthquakes in 1994.
``Because it was so visible throughout the world, people kind of
rallied around.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether the catastrophe involves one home or 200, there are
many steps people can take to keep things from getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Prompt phone calls, for example. Utility companies will usually
stop billing a residence and switch the service to another
location, waiving initial connection charges.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-card companies usually monitor disaster situations and
mark ZIP codes where homes have been destroyed, but a call from a
card holder can help. Steve Boyden, a spokesman for the big card
issuer MBNA America Bank, said his company offered things like
payment holidays and increased credit lines for emergency
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Filing insurance claims, and collecting the benefits, can be a
daunting task. Some victims of previous disasters have said they
took years to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Neiser recommends submitting claim forms quickly and alerting
the insurer to the fact that the list of damages might be
incomplete. If property records are destroyed, catalogs or
classified ads can help establish a fair value for damaged or
destroyed items. A real estate agent can provide escrow papers for
the value of a home, the county assessor can provide property-tax
records, and contractors can determine the value of home
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Administration offers loans to homeowners and
renters in declared disaster areas as well as to small businesses.
FEMA offers grants; local governments may help, too.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS will provide copies of prior tax returns and will allow
certain deductions for casualty losses. The costs of documenting
losses may also be deductible. Disaster victims may want to amend
their previous year's tax returns to report current losses, to get
a refund more quickly. Filing deadlines may be extended.
</P>
<P>
   Though getting fresh copies of documents is usually possible,
extracting information from a melted computer is not. Evacuating
with a computer or backup disks that have been kept current, or
having backup copies stored in remote locations, can be vital.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies also offer ways to replicate a desktop
environment through the Internet; these services _ sometimes free _
are essentially a means of storing back-up files on a server.
Experts warn, however, that there still are privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, the items that are most worth saving are
not Quicken files or Social Security cards. For Brown, the State
Farm adjuster, they were her jewelry, her Lladro porcelain
figurines and photographs of her nine children and 18
grandchildren. ``We have a lot of photographs,'' she said, and no
regrets at hauling them all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
