<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MCCARTNEY-REVIEW-N     05-19 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MCCARTNEY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAINT 
</HEADLINE>
 
`THE LINDA McCARTNEY STORY': THE MYTHOLOGY OF A 20TH CENTURY(Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First we hated her for marrying Paul. She wasn't beautiful
enough; she wasn't famous; she was American, for heaven's sake.
Later we hated her for breaking up the Beatles (with Yoko's help),
then joining her husband's new band when it was clear she couldn't
sing, and wasn't she just a little too self-righteous about those
vegetarian cookbooks and her work in animal rights? Then, two years
ago last month, she died of breast cancer at the age of 56 and we
made her a saint.
</P>
<P>
   Now Linda McCartney is the heroine of the baby boomers' new
favorite love story. She and Paul McCartney were destined to be
together and incredibly happy every moment of their 29-year
marriage, you know. He couldn't have cheated because they never
spent a night apart (except for his six days in a Japanese jail in
1980 for marijuana possession). Proving that true love really does
exist and that even the wildest, cutest, most happily promiscuous
young rock star really just wants a farm in Scotland and four
children and a good woman by his side. That kind of mythology is
the use we make of famous people's lives, and then we make
television movies about them.
</P>
<P>
   The one the former Linda Eastman has gotten, ``The Linda
McCartney Story,'' which has its premiere Sunday night at 9 on CBS,
is a typical celebrity biography. It's far less than a saint
deserves, but at least Elizabeth Mitchell plays her with
intelligence and charm.
</P>
<P>
   As the film tells it, the story begins when Linda's photography
career does. She's a pretty, blond 24-year-old divorcee with a
4-year-old daughter, Heather, living in New York and working in a
very low-level job at City and Village magazine (in real life, Town
and Country, as you might guess). One day she and an equally young,
hip co-worker grab a press party invitation for a get-together with
the Rolling Stones on a yacht. Linda takes her camera, catches Mick
Jagger's eye and gets some nice pictures.
</P>
<P>
   She soon has a book contract and uses her advance to travel,
among other places, to London, where she catches the eye of Paul
McCartney (Gary Bakewell) at a club. (In between, she has also
caught Jim Morrison's eye at an American club. Linda's legend is
that this was always happening to her.)
</P>
<P>
   While in London, she's invited to a press lunch for the ``Sgt.
Pepper'' album at Brian Epstein's house and simultaneously snaps
pictures of Paul and charms the socks off him. This is not
Christine Berardo's script's finest hour. Linda asks about the new
album's title. Paul explains: ``Well, you know those little packets
you get on airplanes. Someone said to me, `Would you pass me the
salt and pepper?' I thought, `Salt and pepper _ Sergeant Pepper.
It's a bit of a pun, that's all. Playing with words.'' Linda can
only reply, ``What a mind!'' The dialogue is better at times. Later
a friend _ Danny Fields (David Lewis), on whose biography the film
is based _ reminds Linda that Paul has been living with the British
actress Jane Asher for five years. ``He'll never marry her,'' Linda
says confidently. Danny replies, ``Has he asked you?'' She smiles
again and says, ``He doesn't have my number.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily she soon finds herself at a Beatles press conference and
passes Paul a piece of paper with her telephone number on it. The
next thing you know, her answering service is reporting that Paul
McCartney of London called: ``He's on his way to Los Angeles. He'd
like you to meet him there at the Beverly Hills Hotel.'' She goes,
arrives at his bungalow and the two are undressing each other
before he has even asked if she had a nice flight.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to know that late-20th-century saints are allowed to
have slept around. Mick Jagger (Matthew Harrison) almost manages to
utter our culture's most feared four-letter word on network
television in his proposition to Linda in the yacht scene, and
although we don't see their sexual liaison she acknowledges later
that it took place. She is also seen in bed with Morrison (Aaron
Grain).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe film producers should give up the idea of look-alike
casting. At times, Bakewell, who has played McCartney before, in
the 1994 film ``Backbeat,'' looks more like Donny Osmond _ although
that improves as the character ages. On the other hand, Tim Piper
is thrilling as a dead ringer for John Lennon, but he has a lot
fewer scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Beatles fans should not expect even re-creations of the group's
music. All they'll hear is a snippet of ``I Want to Hold Your
Hand,'' played over film of the group's famous Shea Stadium
concert. ``Along Comes Mary,'' by the Association, is the theme
music for Paul and Linda's picturesque New York wanderings, and
``Never, My Love'' plays over the scenes of Paul's final,
successful marriage proposal and the couple's 1969 London wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Once Linda and Paul are married, and it's established that his
fans despise her, ``The Linda McCartney Story'' makes the
inevitable transition into disease film. The situation has already
been set up with one reverse flashback to her diagnosis, and Paul
has told her earlier that his mother died of breast cancer when he
was 14. The film now jumps back and forth in time, juxtaposing
hospital scenes with accounts of Paul's depression after the
Beatles' breakup, Linda's reluctance to be a part of Wings (``You
don't need a total amateur onstage with you''), the couple's
surprise Christmas visit to the Lennons in New York and the
horrifying news of John's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell elevates her own scenes of illness, deterioration and
death with an admirable dignity. Throughout the film, George Segal
is also good (with less than brilliant material) as Linda's father,
Lee Eastman, who becomes the lawyer for the Beatles' troubled
company Apple. In the end, though, the film is just another
tear-jerker. Any fan who really wants to pay tribute to Linda and
Paul McCartney's life together might do better to get out the
``McCartney'' album and play ``Maybe I'm Amazed'' once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE LINDA McCARTNEY STORY'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on CBS (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Patricia, Barnet Bain and Stephen Simon, executive
producers; Jacobus Rose, producer; Armand Mastroianni, director;
teleplay by Christine Berardo, based on the book ``Linda McCartney:
A Portrait,'' by Danny Fields. Produced by Mandalay Television in
association with Lions Gate Television and Metafilmics and
distributed by Columbia TriStar Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Elizabeth Mitchell (Linda McCartney), Gary Bakewell (Paul
McCartney), George Segal (Lee Eastman), David Lewis (Danny Fields),
Matthew Harrison (Mick Jagger), Aaron Grain (Jim Morrison) and Tim
Piper (John Lennon).
</P>
</TEXT>
