<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRI CANDIDATE TRIES TO SHORE UP SUPPORT IN NORTHERN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 21)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTERREY, Mexico _ For Mexico's ruling party, this northern
industrial Mecca surrounded by jagged mountains is enemy territory.
</P>
<P>
   But Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the presidential candidate of the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, is here to
shake the hands of the elite business class and hopefully win some
influential votes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the opposition National Action Party (PAN), has
ruled the border state of Nuevo Leon, a manufacturing and banking
hub.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida knows he is stumping on the turf of his closest rival,
the PAN's tough-talking Vicente Fox Quesada, a northerner himself.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that Fox is catching up to, if not overtaking,
Labastida. In one recent survey, the respected Mexico City daily
Reforma showed Labastida leading Fox 42 percent to 40 percent _ a
statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dive from the 10-point lead Labastida had consistently
held earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I want to win with a bigger margin. I'm working to
win with a lead of 10 points difference,'' Labastida said Thursday
while on a campaign bus taking him to meet with members of a
teachers' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most competitive election in Mexico's history,''
Labastida added. ``Now, why am I confident that we will win with
more than 10 percentage points? Because Fox's proposals don't have
consistency and people are perceiving it.''
</P>
<P>
   A calm economist who has worked in public service most of his
adult life, Labastida, 57, is unruffled six weeks before the July 2
general election, rattling off numbers with the ease of someone at
home with statistics.
</P>
<P>
   On a balmy Thursday, Labastida is in good spirits prior to a
lunch with former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to talk to him (Kissinger) about many subjects, the
perspectives of the relationship of our two countries,'' Labastida
told a panel of radio hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has had 37 years in public service, from governing his
native Sinaloa state, to heading the Agriculture, Energy and
Interior secretariats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his experience, some in the PRI are worried at the
closeness of the race. The party has governed Mexico for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   As the election nears, the Labastida campaign called in all its
old political war horses to blunt the growing appeal of Fox and get
out the PRI vote.
</P>
<P>
   This has caused consternation in the Fox camp, which fears the
PRI may resort to fraud to win the election, as some believe
happened in the 1988 presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a rancher who governed northern Guanajuato state, has said
he would challenge the results if PRI wins by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
   Giving a thumbs-up to motorists who spot him through the bus
window, Labastida doesn't apologize for recruiting some of his
party's aging troops, called dinosaurs by critics.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the former governor of Puebla state, Manuel
Bartlett, who many Mexicans believe played a role in what they
allege was computer fraud that swung the 1988 race to the PRI
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always said I would have an inclusive government,''
Labastida said. ``They are participating in more than in my
campaign. They are coordinating campaigns for senate and
congressional candidates. ... Manuel is participating in our
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about the new PRI, you have to say what the new
PRI is. It is a more democratic PRI, a party that fights for
diversity. You can't say that from now on everyone in the PRI must
leave ... that only 20-year-olds can join. ... The possibility of
fraud is zero.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI may have lost the statehouse of Nuevo Leon, but at a
luncheon for 1,300 at the exclusive Mexico-Palestinian-Lebanese
Club of Monterrey, Labastida attracted the big industrial guns.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is the first time the PAN has governed Nuevo Leon,
many top industrialists are divided between support for the PRI and
PAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the richest people in Mexico,'' said Alfonso Guzman,
a city councilman in Monterrey's exclusive San Pedro district.
``And they got rich thanks to the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others at the luncheon, Guzman thinks Labastida will win
Nuevo Leon, with the help of the heavyweight businessmen of
Monterrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida will rise in the next month,'' Guzman predicted.
``We were asleep because Labastida was strong, but now we think
not. It's `wake up, wake up, baby!'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Susana Hayward can be reached by e-mail at
shayward(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
