A0147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KOREA-MARKET-480&AMP;ADD-     05-19 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-MARKET-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREA'S STOCK-EXCHANGE WORKERS MAY STRIKE OVER LUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Workers in South Korea are known for their
not-infrequent strikes over issues like pay and job security. But a
coming showdown with the Korea Stock Exchange will be the first
time they have threatened to strike over the right to have a
relaxing lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-thousand members of South Korea's securities industry
union are planning to strike during their lunch hour beginning
Monday, when the stock exchange plans to continue trading during
what has historically been a midday break. The change, approved by
the South Korean government, makes this country the first in Asia
to keep its stock exchange open during the lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   Government and exchange officials are hoping the extended hours
will draw more investors to the exchange, where share prices have
fallen 29 percent in value so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   But dealers at domestic brokerage firms have expressed
skepticism that the move will make a difference in this or any
other Asian market, where, for decades, trading has been halted for
an hour at midday. Dealers expressed disgust and dismay at the
prospect of having to eat fast food in front of their computers
instead of going out to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans can function fine eating just hamburgers,'' said
Jung Yong-geon, president of the Korea Securities Trade Union.
``But we come from a culture of eating hot bowls of hearty
bean-paste stew and rice. Taking away our one-hour lunch breaks is
like shoving Western practices down our throats and taking away a
tradition that has been passed down for thousands of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others agreed with Jung, saying the negatives of working
through lunch outweigh any possible benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamburger meals just don't go well with Korean workers,'' said
Choi Won-yang, a dealer at Shinhan Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   Park Jae-han, a dealer at Hanvit Securities Co., said, ``It's
going to take much more than just an added hour of trading to turn
the bearish market around, so why can't they just let us eat in
peace?''
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons that trading through lunch may not work,
securities industry workers said.
</P>
<P>
   One is that more than 70 percent of all investors in the South
Korean bourse are individuals, and many have personal relationships
with their dealers. Under the new trading hours, dealers said, they
would have no time to eat, as they would be effectively chained to
their desks and phones, advising clients throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, investors won't trade unless it is through a trusted
broker,'' Choi at Shinhan Securities said, explaining why deploying
dealers in shifts to cover the lunch hour was not a feasible
option.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Korea exchange have rejected such arguments.
They say it is high time that the securities industry in South
Korea, where hard work is an ingrained part of the culture, apply
that to buying and selling shares.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Dealers can eat Korean food delivered to their offices,'' said
Kim Yu-kyung, head of securities research at the Korea Stock
Exchange. ``It won't be a big problem once people get used to the
new system.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that complications arising from working through lunch
should be settled between the management and workers at individual
brokerage firms, instead of creating difficulties for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea will be a test case for other Asian nations to
observe,'' said Yon Kang-keum, professor of finance at Yonsei
University. ``We can no longer wait and see until other nations set
precedents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
