A0148 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TRADE-DEFICIT-CHINA-H     05-19 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-DEFICIT-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHINA TRADE OPPONENTS CLAIM TRADE DEFICIT WOULD WORSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Democratic congressmen charged Friday that
granting permanent normal trade relations to China would worsen the
U.S.-China trade deficit that reached $5.1 billion in March.
</P>
<P>
   They also argued that the agreement would encourage American
businesses to take advantage of cheap labor overseas and result in
the loss of American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio, said a Commerce Department report
Friday shows that China is selling more technology to the United
States than in previous years, and that the U.S.-China trade deal
the House is expected to vote on next week would continue that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote would confer permanent normal trade status on
China and is tied to a U.S.-China pact that calls for China to
lower its tariffs. In turn, the United States would end its annual
review of the U.S.-China trade status. That review has provided a
forum for critics of China's policies on human rights, the
environment and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. is poised to have massive losses in high technology _
our jobs for the future,'' Kucinich told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He said U.S. imports of Chinese-made camcorders, laser printers
and cellular telephones have already cut into U.S. manufacturing
industries.
</P>
<P>
   The overall U.S. trade deficit with China jumped from $7 billion
in 1988 to $70 billion last year. The U.S.-China trade deficit last
March was $4.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., the No. 2 ranked Democrat leader in
the House, said ``the China trade deal won't help us export
American products, only American jobs. After all, how many cell
phones and how many SUVs and how many microwave ovens can you sell
to a Chinese factory worker who is making and earning 13 cents an
hour?''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the agreement said that since the deal would bring
more jobs to China and would lower import tariffs, the Chinese
people would be able to purchase more U.S. goods with their greater
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the medium-to-long term the deficit will definitely be
reduced,'' Daniel Cruise, a White House spokesman on trade, said in
an interview. ``There will be more and more middle income folks who
can buy more and more American products.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Crist, spokesman for the House Ways and Means Committee,
said he expected that U.S. exports to China would eventually
outpace imports. In an interview, he said the trade agreement would
cut in half the average Chinese tariff for American farm products
and would require China to end its quotas on imports, creating
opportunities for American producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're best at exporting is high technology and products
that need qualified American labor,'' Cruise said.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade agreement passes the House, it is expected to be
approved by the Senate and President Clinton, who has lobbied
strongly for it as one of his final major policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
