<HEADER>
A0156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CONSUMER-FILES0520-CO     05-19 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-FILES0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frugal. Thrifty. Cheap. Epithets? Maybe. Maybe not. Who hasn't
been a penny pincher?
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ever make washers by slicing up a garden hose?
Clip a coupon? Cut an old rubber glove into sections to make rubber
bands? Swipe the toilet paper from a hotel room?
</P>
<P>
   (While I am at it, did you buy this newspaper or pick it up off
a coffee shop table?) Then you might just be a thrifty person.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, some hide behind the guise of recycling while others
claim that that a-penny-saved-is-a-penny-earned thing is a vital
part of their financial strategy. Common-sense saving is normal;
miserliness is not. Truth is some people are, well, cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Saving a buck could be as easy as using those free CDs in the
mail for coasters. Why merely cut paper towels in half when you can
wash and reuse them? Why not wash sheets on a clothesline (if you
have one) and water the lawn at the same time like Aunt Elsie?
</P>
<P>
   Tales of separating toilet paper sheets to conserve or removing
makeup with petroleum jelly are fairly common and harmless. I am
concerned about those who wash and reuse Q-Tips, shave their legs
with hair conditioner or anchor a golf tee with another tee and
string.
</P>
<P>
   Do you figure a waiter's tip to the penny? Fine. Steal the tip
off another table? Not so fine. Never go to a restaurant because
you have a panic attack over tipping? Therapy time.
</P>
<P>
   But where does that tendency toward thrift come from? Is it ever
harmful? Want to know more about stretching a dollar? This edition
of the Greig Files answers these queries and peeks into the world
of the cost conscious.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S TO BLAME: THE PULPIT OR THE PURITANS?
</P>
<P>
   For the national attitude toward thrift? Both.
</P>
<P>
   Freed of the restraints of class barriers and royalty, the
colonists worked like the dickens, revering production and
disdaining consumption. Through discipline and hard work (and of
course unlimited land and opportunity) the pioneers were confident
of success. When you are settling a prairie, long-term
gratification comes naturally, as does resourcefulness and
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Many religions praise a pared-down lifestyle and refraining from
material desires. In Hinduism one reaches a higher state of life
through renouncing worldly possessions, for example. Then there is
Calvinism, which offered the possibility of salvation through being
diligent with resources.
</P>
<P>
   And the New Testament is chock-full of sobering reminders of the
merits of husbandry such as in Matthew: ``And again I say unto you,
It is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle, than
for a rich man to enter into the kingdom of God.''
</P>
<P>
   EVER HEARD OF THE SUMPTUARY LAWS?
</P>
<P>
   These days, they are called sin taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Originally intended to define classes by regulating diet and
dress in England, the Puritans were no strangers to the concept of
better living though frugality. Ostentation was shunned; propriety,
prized.
</P>
<P>
   If you were living in 17th-century Massachusetts, legislation
forbid ``the wearing of gold or silver lace, or buttons, or points
at their knees, (walking) in great boots; or women of the same rank
to wear(ing) tiffany hoods or scarves . . .'' Many of the New World
colonists were subject to import taxes on luxury items, including
sugar, spice, wine and tobacco, reports the Acton Institute for the
Study of Religion and Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Overindulgence was a moral and legal no-no.
</P>
<P>
   WHO IS THE TIGHTEST PERSON YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   Whoever he is, there is no way he could be cheaper than the
French millionaire Samuel Tapan, who committed suicide in a fit of
depression after losing $50,000. Mind you, Tapan still had $1.5
million in cash along with castles and vineyards galore. Relatively
speaking, the loss was negligible. He was a bargain-hunter to the
end _ literally _ as Tapan reportedly haggled over the price of the
rope he used to hang himself.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the waste-not-want-not, wildly wealthy Howard Hughes?
This gazillionaire lived on cans of chicken soup for weeks and
reheated the same portion several times so as not to waste a drop.
</P>
<P>
   Who could be more frugal than the reputed witch of Wall Street,
whaling ship heiress Henrietta Howland Green, who wore newspapers
for petticoats and heated her lunch (oatmeal _ yum, yum) on an
office radiator to save fuel?
</P>
<P>
   Know anyone more tightfisted than oilman Haroldson LaFayette
Hunt, who always carried his own lunch to work in a brown paper
bag, a bag he reused until it disintegrated?
</P>
<P>
   For more about the lives and stewardly ways of the wealthy,
check out Karl Shaw's ``Mammoth Book of Oddballs and Eccentrics.''
</P>
<P>
   YOU THINK YOUR PARENTS ARE CHEAP?
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   No one in my research into the world of spendthrifts matches
this gentleman. (The story can be told only because I agreed not to
use names.)
</P>
<P>
   When Mr. X's son married, the traditional rehearsal dinner was
held. Does this financially comfortable father of the groom rent a
hall? A restaurant? A hotel's private dining room? No, this bon
vivant took the entire wedding party (20-plus folks) to that
bastion of prenuptial indulgence _ Long John Silver's. (No, I did
not make this up.)
</P>
<P>
   Not only were the wedding eve festivities held at this fast food
restaurant, but the guests were instructed to sit at tables for
four since the coupons (yes, the coupons) the father of the groom
was using were only good for groups of four. Separate checks,
please. (Imagine George and Nina Banks' chagrin.)
</P>
<P>
   The good news? The fried fish send-off did not deter marital
bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU SURROUNDED BY JACK BENNY WANNABES?
</P>
<P>
   D.G. is. She takes ribbing regularly for the frugal family in
which she lives.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband tapes holes in plastic bags so they can be reused
indefinitely. Not so wacky, but he also saves the microwave popcorn
duds (unpopped kernels) until he has enough to pop a ``free''
serving. ``What do you expect from an engineer?'' she moaned to me
in her missive.
</P>
<P>
   D.G.'s father-in-law saves napkins and condiments from fast-food
restaurants and airlines (which, by the way, have a six-month shelf
life) and her grandmother used scraps for quilts or braided them
into rag rugs or pot-holders.
</P>
<P>
   And a gift that keeps on giving? D.G.'s church friend sends
greeting cards (complete with envelope) in oversized envelopes with
a signature on a Post-it note inside so the card may be reused.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN IS THRIFTINESS NEXT TO ZANINESS?
</P>
<P>
   ``When it has a significant negative impact on your quality of
life and your functioning,'' notes psychologist Dianne Lindewall.
If your family does not mind that you never leave a tip, it is not
a problem; but if such behavior causes stress in the family _ look
out.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of such interruption include the inability to do routine
tasks. Can't work because you are unable to let a moment go by
without checking stock prices? Unable to walk through the living
room because it is filled with unread magazines? Then you may have
a problem and need professional help.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT HOARDING?
</P>
<P>
   That is often a sign of a past institutionalization, says
Lindewall. Once the concept of private property has been
compromised, it is difficult for anyone to trust in it again.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many American families are still reacting to
the impact of the Great Depression as well as the home front
sacrifices necessary in World War II. So the Oreos under the bed,
the dissatisfaction with what appears to be substantial savings, a
distrust of banks and financial institutions or the need to
stockpile anything is normal behavior for some.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of
inquiries, Jane cannot respond to every request.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
