<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HENLEY0520-COX     05-19 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENLEY0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henley says he shares concerns with listeners
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Say you're a rock star making the kind of money
that small countries do. OK, medium-sized countries. You're
reuniting with your old bandmates who, it turns out, can stand each
other's company in this particular fiscal period. You've met the
girl of your dreams and want to start a family. Everything is going
great.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as quick and blindsiding as earthquakes can be, your beach
home in Malibu slides into the ocean and you've got no place to
hang your platinum albums.
</P>
<P>
   That's how 1994 went for Don Henley. That same year, not
surprisingly, the famed Eagles singer and native Texan decided to
move back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I commute to Los Angeles,'' said Henley, 52, who grew up
in Linden, Texas and today lives in Dallas with his wife, model
Sharon Summerall, and their three children.
</P>
<P>
   The relocation, the earthquake, the reunion with the Eagles and
especially the new family explain why Henley is just now getting
back into solo-career mode, 11 years after his last new album came
out. His latest CD, ``Inside Job,'' hits stores Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone last weekend in Los Angeles, where he was
rehearsing with his band, Henley said he doesn't regret leaving
L.A. for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it a little difficult for me on the business end
because I have to be away a lot more. But it's working fine on the
family front. My wife's family is near us, and of course my mother
still just lives up the road a piece. It was important to us that
our kids grow up around their grandparents, aunts and uncles and
cousins.''
</P>
<P>
   Family plays a big part on ``Inside Job,'' too. Half the songs
are based around Henley's new lifestyle, including ``Taking You
Home'' and ``My Thanksgiving.'' In the opening line of ``Everything
Is Different Now,'' the singer comes right out and says it: ``I
hate to tell you this, but I'm very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley said he has been surprised by reactions thus far to those
new songs, as many believe he has turned a new leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm definitely happier than I've ever been before, but
people say that as if I weren't happy before,'' he said. ``I've
always been a happy kind of guy, I just had a few axes to grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like these songs had some universal sentiments to
express. I think people of my generation, and other generations
too, who have families, can relate to these songs.''
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the record, to use his own words, features the
old ax-grinding Don Henley. In songs like ``Nobody Else in the
World'' and ``Workin' It,'' he takes on burgeoning corporate
America with lines like, ``We've got a whole new class of
opiates.'' Meanwhile, ``Goodbye To a River'' shows Henley's
unflinching commitment to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Henley said moving back to Texas has made him even more
concerned about the issues of his native state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas' frontier mentality and the notion that there is still
plenty of everything is of a bygone era,'' he said. ``But our fine
Texas Legislature is, as always, pandering to business interests,
while kids in Texas are developing asthma and respiratory diseases
in epidemic numbers. We still have coal-fired factories in East
Texas spewing out toxins by the ton. . . . And then there's our
governor. There were others before him who cared even less, but the
notion that the air or the environment under Governor Bush has
improved is a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley's environmental commitments hogged much of his time in
the spotlight throughout the '90s, particularly surrounding his
support for the Henry David Thoreau-inspired Walden Woods Project,
about to celebrate its 10th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the reunion with Eagles _ two of whom, Glenn Frey and
Don Felder, perform on ``Inside Job,'' as does Jimmie Vaughan _ Don
Henley music was scarce in the '90s. In the midst of a contract
battle with Geffen Records, the label released ``Actual Miles,'' a
collection of his solo hits, including ``Dirty Laundry'' and Grammy
winners ``The Boys of Summer'' and ``The End of the Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley said he probably would have taken a break from his music
even if things hadn't gone the way they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `The End of the Innocence,' I was tired of touring,
tired of being in the limelight, tired of the business,'' he said.
``Then grunge came in in the early '90s, and I didn't particularly
see a place where I fit. I'm one of those people who believe you
don't have to dance every dance. Sometimes it's good to sit one
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the recent comeback success of Santana and, to a lesser
extent, Steely Dan, Henley believes the timing is right for his
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wheel has taken another turn,'' he said. ``I think
there are 78 million baby boomers who really don't have a lot to
listen to, who don't have any music that speaks to their lives and
concerns. I've grown up and gone through a lot, like the rest of
them, and here's what I have to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
