<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CHINA-TRADE-SPLIT-HNS     05-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SPLIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MICHIGAN HOUSE MEMBERS ILLUSTRATE SPLIT OVER CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the China trade bill nears a pivotal House vote
next week, Reps. Dave Camp and James A. Barcia, both of Michigan,
are firmly set in their opposite positions, reflecting Congress'
contentious split on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Camp, a Midland Republican, is strongly for the measure. Barcia,
a Bay City Democrat, is staunchly against it.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the landmark legislation to grant China permanent
trade ties with the United States say it appears headed for
passage, but scores of House members are still undecided and the
outcome is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Camp, a fifth-term conservative who serves on the trade
subcommittee of the House Ways and Means panel, is a self-described
free-trader who favors a permanent commercial relationship with
China because he thinks it would help farmers in the state's 4th
congressional district, which he represents.
</P>
<P>
   Barcia, a fourth-term Democrat who reliably backs organized
labor and votes against international trade agreements, opposes the
China deal because, he said, other countries, especially China,
renege on such pacts. He argued that the China pact would hurt
farmers in his area, the 5th congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Camp has voted every year after he was elected in 1990 to renew
China's trade privileges, a two-decade-old annual rite that would
end if the country's trading ties are extended permanently. Camp
also supported the 1993 North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)
that opened U.S. trade channels with Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Camp said in an interview that his district's farmers who grow
sugar beets, potatoes, mint and fruit have watched crop prices fall
and are anxious to find new markets for their produce in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is a huge potential market for us,'' Camp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not have enough arable land to support their people,''
he said. ``They may as well import from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Elected in 1992, Barcia, who serves on the House Science
Committee and the Transportation Committee, voted in 1993, 1994 and
1996 to renew China's trade ties with the United States but says he
opposed renewal in 1995 and 1997 through last year because of the
escalating trade deficit with China. He also voted against NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   Barcia's position pits him against President Clinton, who has
made the legislation a top foreign policy priority. But that's
nothing new for the conservative lawmaker. Barcia has voted only
slightly more than half the time with Clinton and the majority of
his House colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Barcia said in an interview that farmers in his district,
especially sugar beet growers, are upset over what they see as
violations of the NAFTA pact by Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great suspicion and universal disappointment over
NAFTA from our agricultural producers,'' Barcia said. ``It seems
all of our trade agreements are negotiated from a weak
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Barcia said the United States has been more interested in
importing goods than exporting them. ``We have consistently taken
it on the chin on trade agreements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barcia accused China of failing to stop knockoffs of
American-made VCR tapes. ``I am for engaging with China,'' he said.
``I am for honest trade, but based on China's track record, that
doesn't look like the direction we're going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Barcia added that correspondence from his congressional
district, which has many retired and active auto workers, has been
``overwhelmingly against'' permanent trade ties with China. He said
organized labor had lobbied him heavily to vote against the China
trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he felt ``great pain'' in opposing Midland-based
Dow Chemical Co., which would benefit from the China bill because
it would have a new market for its fertilizer and pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he feels that overall China's farmers would hurt
America's with added food exports.
</P>
<P>
   Like other opponents of the China trade pact, Barcia cited the
country's poor record on human rights and said if the annual review
of Beijing's trade status ends, the United States will lose its
leverage in opposing China's human rights abuses, including forced
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Barcia, who is co-chairman of the House Pro-Life Caucus, said he
finds China's one-child limit ``repugnant'' because it forces women
to have abortions. ``The government has no right to interfere in
such a personal decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Camp, on the other hand, said both sides ``agree that China
mistreats its people.'' But he added, ``I believe the best way to
change that is to expose them to our way of life. Ignoring them is
not the way to bring about change.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp said if more American companies do business in China, they
will pay higher wages and help create a middle class in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   Camp says he has been lobbied hard by members of organized labor
who have warned him they will do anything they can to defeat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a particularly helpful tactic,'' Camp said.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
