<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI-SENATE _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
decided to drop out of the U.S. Senate race against first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Republicans close to the mayor said today.
Several who the mayor called said he told them he wasn't running
because of concerns over his health. Mrs. Clinton, in Brooklyn for
a campaign appearance, said, ``I have no control or say over what
happens on the other side.'' she said. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-FRAUD _ WASHINGTON _ From young college students
trying to enter over-21 bars to sophisticated criminals trying to
defraud banks, thousands of Americans are turning to the Internet
to easily obtain fake identification documents. At a Senate hearing
Friday, witnesses described how dozens, perhaps hundreds, of
companies are churning out fake drivers' licenses, birth
certificates and other documents to help people commit a wide array
of crimes. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AARP _ ORLANDO _ A 50-something woman walked up to the
microphone in a cavernous hall hidden within the Orange County
Convention Center. The woman, one of thousands of AARP members who
descended on the city
</P>
<P>
   last week for the organization's national convention, had
something to say to noted sex therapist Dr. Ruth Westheimer. ``Dr.
Ruth,'' the woman began, ``I ordered one of those things you
endorse.'' ``Oh, the vibrator!'' Westheimer responded, adding that
the Euroscillator
</P>
<P>
   is the only product carrying her seal of approval. ``Yes,'' the
woman said. ``And I just want to say, 'Sister, girlfriend, thank
you, thank you, thank you.''' (Lambert, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   NRA-MEETING _ CHARLOTTE - Covering news on opening day of the
National Rifle Association's annual meeting and exhibit. It
features speeches by NRA President Charlton Heston and executive
vice president Wayne LaPierre, countered by a peace march, prayer
vigil and a mock funeral remembering Charlotte's victims of gun
violence. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
