<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another unseasonably cool day will prevail across parts of
eastern New England and the northern middle Atlantic seaboard, as
chilly ocean winds work in tandem with clouds. Patches of drizzle
and light rain will add to the raw feel of the day in several
coastal locations.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms, some with heavy rains, will erupt along
a cold front extending from the Middle Atlantic States to the
western Gulf states. The lack of a potent upper-air disturbance,
however, will limit severe weather to just a few spots.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated potent thunderstorms will develop in West Texas as
humid air from the Gulf of Mexico is lifted by a weak upper-air
disturbance. Thunderstorms are possible in Florida, but very warm
air several thousand feet aloft will keep storms isolated.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HAIL STREAKS
</P>
<P>
   Hailstones as big as baseballs strafed the Chicago suburb of
Niles on Thursday. Hail falls from severe thunderstorms in streaks,
much like white stripes painted on a newly resurfaced highway by
large machines. The diameter of a severe-thunderstorm machine spans
tens of miles, but the hail streak painted on the landscape by such
a storm has average dimensions of about one mile wide and a few
miles long. Because of their small size and infrequency, hail
streaks with large hailstones are not often observed in urban
areas, just as tornadoes do not frequent cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
