<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SOUTH-WATERFALLS0520-     05-19 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-WATERFALLS0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wonder of waterfalls
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTAHOOCHEE NATIONAL FOREST, Ga. _ Eyes up, arms outstretched,
Mark Morrison takes in the glimmering cascade. It tumbles over a
sheer rock face, crashes into a bed of broken stones below and
courses past dense thickets of rhododendron and towering hemlock
trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this beautiful?'' Morrison exclaims, grinning. He should
know. The 47-year-old railroad engineer is one of the Southeast's
most ardent admirers of waterfalls. In a little more than a decade,
he's visited more than 400 in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Amicalola or Anna Ruby, are heavy-traffic falls. But
many, like this sequestered splasher on Little Ridge Creek south of
Neels Gap, are virtual secrets, represented only by anonymous blue
ticks on topographical maps.
</P>
<P>
   They may not be anonymous for long. A former surveyor and
skilled photographer, Morrison has published four books on
Southeastern falls, including ``Waterfall Walks and Drives in
Georgia, Alabama and Tennessee'' in 1996 and ``Waterfall Walks and
Drives in the Great Smoky Mountains and the Western Carolinas''
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The homemade guides _ typeset on an Adobe Pagemaker computer
program at Morrison's home and transcribed, packed and shipped by
wife Deeanna _ are full of common-sense advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pretend to be a writer,'' he says modestly. ``The
books are basically directions.''
</P>
<P>
   When is the best time to visit a waterfall? ``Go when they
flow!'' Morrison tells readers. ``Many of these spectacular falls
will be disappointing in the dry months of summer and fall.''
Morrison recommends visiting in the winter or spring, or after a
good rain.
</P>
<P>
   But what directions. Armed with his surveyor's acumen and a
measuring wheel (as well as permission from various land management
officials), Morrison has plotted explicit paths to more than 250
waterfalls. Hikers accustomed to the vagueness of many park maps
will flip over their walking sticks when they read Morrison's route
to Little Ridge Falls:
</P>
<P>
   ``An old logging road . . . ascends moderately through a tunnel
of rhododendron and crosses three branches, each of which are .1 of
a mile apart. After crossing the third branch (just over .3 of a
mile into the hike), pace off 300'. There, look carefully for a
slim path leading 45 degrees to the right . . . (There may be a
coffee table-sized boulder in the road for further verification.)
This leads approximately 100' to the creek bank. . . .
</P>
<P>
   On the creek's east side, hike uphill to intersect a logging
road which parallels Little Ridge Creek upstream. In .1 of a mile
reach a point where the pathway steepens. The lower falls may be
seen from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison's obsessive approach is paying off _ he has sold more
than 40,000 books through chain stores such as Borders and Barnes &AMP;
Noble, as well as the online retailer Amazon.com and his own Web
site, www.waterfallwalks.com.
</P>
<P>
   The methodical measuring sprang from an interest in nature
photography. Morrison's been an avid shutterbug since 1985, when he
bought his first 35mm camera. ``I was baffled by the thing at
first, and used all the automatic settings,'' he remembers. He
quickly grew more assured _ his books and Web site feature gorgeous
color shots taken mostly with a Nikon FM2. (His beloved Nikon N90S
ended up in a creek on one of his hikes.)
</P>
<P>
   But Morrison found that ferreting out waterfalls to shoot could
sometimes be frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked up a lot of free info about locations,'' he says.
``And many times I would end up lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
