<HEADER>
A0179 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COL     05-19 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
 
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers) SOUTHERNERS STRUGGLE WITH CHINA TRADE VOTE  
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ It is the biggest
vote of the short congressional career of South Carolina Rep. Jim
Demint and the freshman Republican is feeling the heat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservative groups are running ads in his district, assailing
the lack of human rights in China. He faces pressure from local
textile executives worried about more competition from Asia.
Colleagues opposed to normalized trade with China are warning that
it will be the political mistake of his life should he approve the
trade pact.
</P>
<P>
   Yet DeMint, after a listening tour of his Upstate district, is
leaning toward supporting permanent normal trade relations with
China, figuring the agreement will provide new openings for
American firms that already have to contend with competition from
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't see how this is going to hurt,'' said a DeMint
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   DeMint's struggle is typical of the plight of congressional
Southerners who remain undecided on the issue. They are torn
between human rights and free enterprise, business and labor,
textiles and high-tech, their own communities and the overall state
and national economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very complex issue,'' Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., wrote
recently. ``There can be benefits for America, but are their
benefits for Eastern North Carolina?''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Democratic Rep. Bill Jefferson agreed the subject is
complicated but that he finally decided the bottom-line answer is
simple: ``Our market is virtually open to Chinese goods and it's
imperative that our exports receive reciprocal treatment,'' said
Jefferson. ``This is the only way we can maintain U.S. jobs in this
dynamic global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   SWEET DREAMS
</P>
<P>
   Foes of the federal sugar program believe the Agriculture
Department's recent announcement that it will have to spend $60
million to buy surplus sweetener gives them new ammunition to fight
the politically protected price supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am outraged that a corporate welfare program which already
costs consumers $2.2 billion per year in hidden costs will now cost
taxpayers $60 million up-front,'' said Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla.,
referring to some estimates of the impact the price supports have
on food manufactured with sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Agriculture Chairman Richard Lugar, R-Ind., promised to
introduce legislation blocking the purchase and Miller is also
looking for ways to get the issue before the House.
</P>
<P>
   But the sugar program, while it has been modified in recent
years, has so far proven impervious to challenge and may be able to
survive this new assault.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING IN ACTION
</P>
<P>
   Following the Million Mom March in Washington, Democrats on
Capitol Hill are renewing their call for new gun-control measures _
but there's no Southern accent in this latest rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Democrats have been noticeably absent from the debate
on gun control, consistent with their long history of generally
opposing any measures that could infringe on Second Amendment
rights. While some Southern Democrats have indeed supported
measures such as instant background checks, they rarely step
forward on the issue, and this year is no different even as many of
their party brethren push for stricter controls on sales at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Still, President Clinton and Democratic leaders prefer to ignore
the dissension within their own ranks, directing their partisan
barbs at Republicans who control Congress. Democrats are pressing
GOP leaders to adopt a gun-control package that has been stalled in
Congress for 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT CARD
</P>
<P>
   Southern schools are still failing to make the grade when it
comes to educating their students.
</P>
<P>
   A new report by the Southern Regional Education Board in Atlanta
found that several Southern states reached or exceeded the national
averages for at least one barometer of student achievement, ``but
none has reached that goal for most measures of student
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, most fourth and eighth-graders in Alabama, Florida,
Louisiana, and South Carolina all fell below the national
proficient standard for reading and writing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, however, exceeded that standard for its
eighth-grade students. Still, for all states there remains a
significant achievement gap between white students and minorities,
with black and Hispanic students lagging.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs of progress. The report found that since 1988,
Southern states have led the nation in increasing the number of
students who take Advanced Placement examinations while in high
school, along with the number of public schools that participate in
the program.
</P>
<P>
   The report calls for ``strong accountability systems'' within
schools to encourage ``high expectations'' for students, teachers
and school leaders.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
