u f BC-NEW-VIRUS-BOS &LR;      05-19 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-VIRUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST COMPUTER VIRUS OUTBITES `LOVE BUG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A computer virus discovered Thursday afternoon could have made
the recent international ``Love Bug'' attack seem like child's
play. But the new virus, which destroys all the data stored on a
computer, failed to infect millions of machines around the world,
as the previous virus did.
</P>
<P>
   For this, the Love Bug itself gets part of the credit, because
it prompted many e-mail users to take precautions.
</P>
<P>
   That virus forced the shutdown of electronic mail systems at
government agencies and major corporations two weeks ago. But virus
experts say the Love Bug also spurred companies and individuals to
adopt new security precautions that screened out the new, deadlier
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being on the tail end of (the Love Bug) love letter,
people were very conscious of this kind of thing,'' said Ben
Venzke, manager of intelligence production at iDefense, a Virginia
computer security firm.
</P>
<P>
   The new virus, called ``NewLove,'' spreads the same way as the
Love Bug did _ by automatically sending copies of itself to every
e-mail address in a victim's electronic address book. In theory, it
could have swept the globe in a day, just as the Love Bug did.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NewLove disguises itself. Instead of sending itself
as an e-mail message with the subject heading ``I Love You,'' the
new virus gives itself the name of a file it found on a previously
infected machine. As a result, the name of the virus message
changes constantly.
</P>
<P>
   But NewLove contains another trick that seriously undermines its
effectiveness. NewLove automatically ``mutates'' so that each
version of the virus looks different to virus-checking programs.
The mutation, though, adds extra lines of meaningless code to the
virus each time it's spread to a different machine.
</P>
<P>
   This changes the appearance of the virus, but it also makes it
much bigger. Graham Cluley, spokesman for Sophos Anti-Virus Inc. in
Oxford, England, said that after making its way through just three
computers, NewLove grows to about 800 kilobytes in size. A file
that big takes several minutes to download using a standard modem.
Many e-mail systems won't accept messages that large, and users who
get one would be immediately on the alert for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   So the very feature that was supposed to sneak NewLove past
virus scanners has made it too inefficient to spread rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think this thing got so fat and heavy, it just fell
over its own feet,'' Cluley said. His firm received only one report
of a user infected by the bug, from an American company.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a survey released Friday found that the Love Bug may
have had less impact than earlier thought. The Pew Internet and
American Life project found that only about 15 percent of American
e-mail users received messages containing the Love Bug.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, frequent e-mail users, which would include
many office workers, were much more likely to be affected. The
survey found that a quarter of all frequent e-mail users got Love
Bug messages.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses such as NewLove and Love Bug can be rendered ineffective
if users of Microsoft Corp.'s Windows operating systems alter their
software settings to prevent certain kinds of ``script'' programs
from running automatically. For instructions, go to
www.datafellows.com/virus-info/u-vbs/.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
