<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNDY IN A CIVIC IS A BLAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you were wondering whether the sad sack, schlumpy
public persona of New York Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy was a true
indicator that he's not what you would call a major conspicuous
consumer, the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   You may have heard about the bizzare incident at Westchester
County Airport when the Knicks' charter plane landed at 3 a.m.
following their frustrating loss Wednesday night in Miami. During
the taxi to the ramp, the pilot observed a large quantity of gravel
on the runway. Fearing the gravel might be sucked into the right
engine, he shut it down. In order to make a turn, he then boosted
power to the left engine. The thrust exhaust blew in the direction
of several nearby parked cars. Van Gundy's car was blown into the
air, landing on automobiles belonging to Allan Houston (1997
Mercedes), assistant coach Brendan Malone (1999 Lincoln), and media
relations director Lori Hamamoto (make and model unrecorded). Van
Gundy's vehicle was totaled.
</P>
<P>
   And what kind of car was a coach making well over a million
dollars a year driving? A 1995 Honda Civic. No offense, Civic
owners, but how many of you would be driving one if you were
pulling down seven figures?
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that Van Gundy wasn't concerned about his car.
``That's what insurance is for,'' he said. Anyway, the mode of his
personal transportation is of little concern to the single-minded
mentor. ``I couldn't give a (mildly naughty word) at that point,''
he said. ``I only cared about the win. That was my first thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Celtic fans with long memories may recall a similar incident
involving a plane that had a bearing on the 1969 playoff run. Jim
``Bad News'' Barnes was knocked down in Phoenix late in the season
by an ill-timed engine thrust. He sustained an injury to his neck.
Player-coach Bill Russell later decided Barnes was not getting
himself ready to play quickly enough, so he essentially banished
his only legitimate pivot backup to non-playing status for the
playoffs. On the few occasions coach Russell decided player Russell
was in need of a blow (foul trouble hardly ever being a Russell
concern), he stuck the 6-foot-6-inch Satch Sanders in the pivot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York being New York, and the New York newspapers being the
New York newspapers, the Knicks lose one game (OK, three games) and
suddenly everyone takes turns being Chicken Little.
``BICKERBOCKERS'' screamed a headline in the New York Post, which
has never seen a trivial issue it couldn't turn into the Cuban
Missile Crisis. Even the stately New York Times used the word
``Unravelled'' in a headline. So what happened? Well, Patrick Ewing
and Chris Childs exchanged words in the second period of Game 5
when Childs ignored Ewing's signal for the ball. And Van Gundy
spoke bluntly about his team's rebounding deficiencies. All hardly
major stuff, but this is New York.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that there weren't some real issues for the Knicks. The
team was poised to issue an APB for Marcus Camby. The 1999 playoff
darling has pitched a no-show performance in this series, capped by
Wednesday's effort in which he had as many fouls (six) as points
and rebounds combined in 27 dismal minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Another target is Houston, who only took two shots in the second
half of Game 5. Making matters worse for him was that Dan Majerle
picked this cruical game to add 16 points (including two late
threes and a killer 3-point transition layup plus foul) to his
usual aggressive defense. When Majerle wins the matchup outright,
the Knicks are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley on the playoffs: ``I walk into the locker room and
I've got a hole in my gut. You can't say that in the regular
season.'' . . . There was a significant New York crowd presence in
Miami. There was not going to be a reciprocal Miami presence in
Madison Square Garden Friday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
