<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CANNES-FILMS-2TAKES-N     05-19 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNES-FILMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANNES AND ASIA: IT'S LOVE AT FIRST SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France _ The evidence after a week and a half of the
Cannes Film Festival is that the usual excess, the hype, the
anxiety, the strenuous star-studdedness of this annual event can
coexist rather comfortably with what the French would call a
serious cinematic sensibility. Serious is a serious word in this
country, a word that suggests a willingness to do the hard job, to
take pains, to be not just flashy but also good. So far it's been a
serious festival, a festival where, contrary to custom, no
big-budget Hollywood film was included in the official competition,
even though the festival directors are said to have tried
unsuccessfully to open this year's event with the ``Mission
Impossible'' sequel starring Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every television network in Europe is here, so Tom Cruise
going up the red carpet would have been great from their point of
view,'' said the critic Roger Ebert, who has been coming to Cannes
for 25 years. ``The biggest moments this festival has ever had were
when Jimmy Stewart, Clint Eastwood and Madonna were here. I
remember Eastwood especially, with everybody in their French
accents shouting `Cleent! Cleent!'''
</P>
<P>
   So the festival has produced little in the way of surprise or
shock or disgust or rebellion. But if it has not been the year of
Tom Cruise, it is being proclaimed the year of Asia. And with films
in the competition from Iran, China, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Korea and
Japan, it is indeed the year of Asia. This is serious, for it
represents the real possibility of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling that the festival still recognizes the
value of auteur cinema,'' said Edward Yang, an American-educated
director from Taiwan whose film ``Yi Yi'' is one of the Asian
entries in the official competition. Yang is not the only grateful
person here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a real breakthrough for Korean films,'' said
Hong-Joon Kim, a member of the Korean Film Commission. Kim was
referring to the appearance in the competition of ``Chunhyang,'' Im
Kwon Taek's postcard-pretty story of official malfeasance, based on
an 18th-century Korean legend. It is the first film from Korea ever
to make it to such an exalted status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best effect will be in Korea itself,'' Im said. ``Even in
Korea, Korean films are not taken seriously. This will serve notice
to our own people that Korean films may be a little bit better than
they think.''
</P>
<P>
   All this doesn't mean that there hasn't been plenty of glitter.
Cannes at this time of year has more chartered yachts, more
Mercedes convertibles, more cell phones than are usually found in
any one city on the planet. But the political overtones that
characterize this festival have been more interesting than the
garden-variety narcissistic parades.
</P>
<P>
   One political question has to do with the relative scarcity of
American films. Even though there are six of them in the
competition, that number is relatively low compared to those of
other years, which raises the issue of whether this represents an
expression of French cultural protectionism. The French have made
no secret of their fear that European culture, which they deem to
be ``serious,'' is being crushed by Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   On another political front, reports have circulated that the
festival's organizers rejected a formal request by the Chinese
government that the Chinese entry be withdrawn, giving the festival
a touch of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Did the festival's directors, who decide in secret which films
will be invited to compete, discriminate against American films
this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but it's more complicated than that,'' said one studio
executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The studios don't
make available the films the festival wants; the festival doesn't
want the films that the studios make available. The French have
mixed feelings about the Americans, who bring glamour but can be
too dominant. But the studios are afraid to have their films in
competition, knowing that they might not win.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, after a week of viewing the Asian entries, one
might be inclined to agree with Yang that the festival is doing its
job, recognizing work with a strong individual character. The Asian
films have been a rich and varied cinematic panorama of the sort
that could be created only at a festival, never in the commercial
arena. Among the other strong entries so far was ``Gohatto,'' or
``Taboo,'' a drama about homosexuality among samurai in late
Tokugawa Japan by the Japanese master Nagisa Oshima. The film
concentrates on one Sozaburo Kano, played by Ryuhei Matsuda, a
boyish, coquettish recruit in a local militia who attracts the
sexual attentions of several members of the force. The members of
the militia and its leaders do not take an intolerant attitude
toward homosexuality; indeed, they accept it as a normal tendency.
Still, tragedy ensues when Kano's presence stirs up murderous
jealousies and rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese entry, directed by the 37-year-old Jiang Wen, was a
densely affecting, emotionally violent story called ``Devils on the
Doorstep,'' set during the Japanese occupation of China. The
Iranian film, ``Takhte Siah,'' directed by Samira Makhmalbaf, takes
place in Iranian Kurdistan and depicts a group of teachers made
homeless by a bombing and wandering from city to city in search of
students.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most cerebral of the Asian entries was Yang's ``Yi
Yi,'' which is about three generations of modern-day Taiwanese.
Yang's film suggests a kind of precariousness to ordinary life, a
sense that barbarism is never far away.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Im's ``Chunhyang,'' lushly scenic, full of spacious vistas and
decorous ceremony, is a cinematic version of a popular Korean
ballad commonly told in a musical form called Pansori, a one-man
opera accompanied by a single drum. It is the story of a nobleman's
son, Mongryong, who falls in love with a beautiful and cultivated
girl, Chunhyang, the illegitimate daughter of a high-class
courtesan and a deceased provincial governor. When she refuses the
demands of a newly arrived provincial governor that she serve him
as a courtesan, he tortures her and orders her to be executed
during his birthday celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's ``Devils on the Doorstep'' begins when a Chinese
guerrilla fighter bursts in on a villager named Ma Dasan and orders
him to watch over two Japanese prisoners until he can come back to
take them away. The villagers are afraid not to follow his order,
but they are also terrified of a nearby Japanese detachment that
will exact terrible retribution if they discover the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's work, filmed in black and white, has a grainy intensity
to it and is steeped in the idioms and accents of peasant life in
northern China. It captures the shrewd simplicity of people who
hate the foreign occupier before whom they ingratiate themselves,
since the immediate cause is not to fight a patriotic war but to
survive as best they can. Perhaps it is the absence of overt
patriotism that led the Chinese authorities to ban it in China and
to ask that it be withdrawn at Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have not officially stated their reasons. But for
Jiang, the politics of his film are both confusing and
paradoxically bothersome. He referred to an article in a French
newspaper that raised a cynical possibility. The banning of the
film was announced, the newspaper suggested, as a promotional
gesture, the idea being that for a Chinese film to be seen as
worthy of attention internationally, it has to arouse the ire of
the Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about this, not because I'm afraid of
what might happen to me but because it seems that Chinese films all
need this sort of packaging.'' Jiang said. ``To be banned makes it
important. But whether a film is banned or not has nothing to do
with its importance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't understand.'' Jiang continued. ``Because even
if you go through all of the approvals, you might still not be
allowed to show your film. You might submit a script idea based on
a novel only to be informed that the novel, though approved for
publication, can't be made into a movie. Sometimes a novel can be
made into a television program but not a movie. I don't know why.
Even after your script has been approved, when you shoot it, the
Film Bureau comes to see if you've made any changes. And even if
you pass this stage, your film might still not be distributed, and
it might not be approved for festivals. I myself really don't
understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
