<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED MOVE DEPRESSES NASDAQ INDEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq stock index fell more than 4 percent Friday, in a
third day of fallout from the Federal Reserve Board's vote this
week to intensify its campaign to raise interest rates and engineer
a soft landing for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq Composite index slid 148.31 to
3390.40, and dragged the Dow Jones industrial average down with it
on a light trading day when there were few buyers to shore up stock
prices. The Dow lost 150.43, or 1.4 percent, closing at 10,626.85.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was unusual in that no dramatic event could be pinpointed
for driving the market down. The Nasdaq is now a third below its
March 10 high of 5048.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a general gloom has settled over investors, who
are beginning to absorb the implications of Tuesday's half-point
hike in the federal funds rate, to 6.5 percent. Since then, the
still-high Nasdaq has fallen every day, with each day worse than
the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the gloom, the US Department of Commerce
reported Friday that the US trade deficit hit yet another record,
growing to $30.2 billion in March, as prices for imported oil rose
to Gulf War levels.
</P>
<P>
   For investors the report meant one thing: Consumers are still in
a buying frenzy and may give the the Fed reason to raise rates for
a seventh time at its June meeting, said Kathleen Camilli, a market
analyst in New York for Tucker Anthony Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While inflation has been edging up slowly, the Fed is
increasingly concerned about the relentless pace of growth in the
economy, which shows few signs of slowing down. Claims for
unemployment benefits fell again last week, another indication of a
small and growing pool of labor.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, when an economic boom matures, ``consumption
snowballs and that draws trade in,'' Camilli explained. ``The
market should care'' about a growing trade deficit because it is
``another sign of stronger-than-expected economic growth, added to
all the pieces we've gotten since January, further giving reason
for the Fed to continue on the path of tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Dow fell Friday, analysts said the
technology-dominated Nasdaq is more vulnerable. The Dow held up
amid Nasdaq's slide on Thursday, but gave way Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line companies are, in theory, more sensitive to interest
rates than are technology companies. The Nasdaq is vulnerable,
though, analysts said, because it is still high and because
technology company stocks suffer if their ``old economy'' clients
trim capital spending in response to rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have been justifying paying extraordinary prices for
tech stocks because of the expectation for continued revenue
growth,'' said Charles Crane, market strategist at Spears, Benzak,
Salomon &AMP; Farrell Inc., which manages $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech companies themselves aren't heavy borrowers, but their
customers are going to be hurt by higher interest rates'' and
reduce their spending on technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Intel Corp., the world's biggest chip maker,
reported that it would reduce its first-quarter profits by a penny,
to 77 cents a share, after some sales were reversed. Intel plunged
$6.0625 a share, to $117.875.
</P>
<P>
   Another technology leader, Cisco Systems Inc., which rose 50
percent in the first three months of the year, has almost wiped out
all of that gain. The number one computer networking company
dropped $1.9375 Friday, to $53.4375 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold the last of my Cisco Friday,'' said Johan Vystavel, a
fund manager at HWB Capital Management, in Surrey, England. ``It's
a good company, but at 100 times earnings it's just too
expensive.'' The shares trade for 110 times profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
