<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SKIP-CARAY2NDTAKE21-C     05-19 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIP-CARAY2NDTAKE21-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: more money than a lot of players.
</P>
<P>
   Partying hard after divorce
</P>
<P>
   After announcing minor-league baseball in Oklahoma and Georgia _
he was the voice of the old Atlanta Crackers in '64 and '65 _ Caray
arrived in Atlanta for good in 1969, to do Hawks basketball. He was
30, married and had two children. But the marriage broke up (``I
was too young''), the kids moved back to St. Louis with their
mother, and Caray followed in his father's hard-living footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got divorced just when birth control came into being, and
before AIDS became a problem _ every night was New Year's Eve,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Most nights were spent at the now-defunct Brave Falcon Lounge,
near the Tara movie theater off Cheshire Bridge Road. It attracted
that era's men on the make _ sportsmen, lawyers, salesmen _ and
plenty of women wanting to make it with them. For a while, Caray
had his mail delivered there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Dewar's and water and let's see what happens,'' he
says. ``God, I loved that place. For the most part I was with good
friends. The laughs _ the laughs were so much better than the
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he adds, ``A lot of the happiness was superficial. A little
booze and a young lady and you sorta forget about missing your
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray eventually met his second wife there. Paula Prather owned
the hairstyling salon Caray went to next door, and she'd stop by
the Brave Falcon after work. She turned down a bunch of Caray's
advances; born in Georgia, she didn't know anything about baseball
or Harry Caray. ``I just sorta stumbled into it,'' she remembers.
</P>
<P>
   They married in 1976. Caray adopted Paula's young daughter, and
a few years later they had Josh. When he wasn't on the road, Caray
became a homebody.
</P>
<P>
   Says oldest son Chip, now a Cubs announcer, ``That's where
there's a difference with my grandfather (Harry): My dad had a
greater appreciation for the importance of family at a younger age.
While he loves his job, he doesn't live for his job like my
grandfather did.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather loved meeting and talking with people all the
time _ that was his personality. My dad can't do that. Nobody's
like Harry Caray. And nobody can be.''
</P>
<P>
   He earned his way
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine now, with the Braves' decade-long success,
the degree of utter lousiness Caray described for fans of those
early Hawks and Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bad with the Hawks that Kasten, then the team's
assistant general manager, challenged Caray nightly by finding an
obscure word for him to work into the broadcast: syzygy, homunculus
_ like that.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Bob Costas recalls in the middle of one Hawks blowout
Caray giving viewers permission to turn off their sets, as long as
they patronized the station's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the greatest thing I heard an announcer
say,'' Costas says. ``It breaks that wall, where the announcer is
telling the fan, `I'm thinking what you're thinking.' It was, like,
subversive.''
</P>
<P>
   Caray kept it up when he joined the Braves. ``Ted (Turner) told
me, `I don't know anything about this (stuff). Say whatever you
want.'''
</P>
<P>
   He did: He'd page through a TV Guide during a game to see what
else was on; give scathing reviews of the sci-fi B-movies that then
filled TBS' schedule; instituted a ``punch line of the day,'' with
viewers sending in dirty jokes that couldn't be told on the air, to
which Caray would read only the punch line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Skip's humor really came in. His imagination would
run amok,'' says broadcasting partner Pete Van Wieren, who joined
the Braves the same year as Caray. ``We were out of some races so
early that there were no boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Those lean years are what carved Caray's unhyped,
it's-just-a-game style that, because of TBS' cable reach, became
familiar around the country. ESPN anchor Eisen remembers imitating
Caray while growing up in New York, and now regularly imitates him
during ``Sports Center.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People love the voice. They come up to me in airports and ask
me to do it,'' Eisen says. ``I'm a New Yorker, and I never thought
I'd be known for doing an imitation of a guy who does baseball in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Skip, you get a kind of good-natured world weariness,''
adds Costas. ``I'm sure he's too low-key for some people, in the
same way Harry could be too over the top. But those of us who have
an interest in broadcasting and baseball have an appreciation for
what he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry was broad enough that everybody got him. Only the
intelligentsia get this.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't be pushed
</P>
<P>
   An hour before another game. Caray is hunched over a live mike
inside a cramped WSB radio hut in Turner Field's centerfield
pavilion _ ``Skip-in-a-box,'' some at WSB call the setup _ hosting
the pregame show. He's fielded a half-dozen calls so far and been
nice as pie.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone's enamored of the new, mellow Skip. For some, his
doesn't-suffer-fools-gladly approach was a cult find. Chipper Jones
compares him to ``not Rush Limbaugh, exactly ... He's the Neal
Boortz of play-by-play.'' Boortz says he should have a forum on
``60 Minutes'': ``He'd make Andy Rooney look like a priest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate baseball but I never turn off the pregame show,'' says
Marcia Killingsworth, Georgia native and public relations manager
at Georgia Public TV. ``The people who call are so passionate about
the Braves, and the tone Skip uses when he responds to some of
their minutiae _ it's so dry, honestly, I almost drive off the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People either love him or ... dislike him,'' adds Braves
pitcher John Smoltz. ``I've grown to really like him. The first
time I listened to the pregame show, I couldn't stop laughing.
People say he's a rude son-of-a-gun, but I know how many calls he
has to deal with, and it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz grins. ``I'm thinking of getting somebody to call him up
and ask a really stupid question. Just to see how he responds.''
</P>
<P>
   Could that person be Rob in Stone Mountain?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where and how,'' begins a caller identified on a computer
screen inside the WSB hut only as Rob in Stone Mountain, ``should I
consolidate my student loans?''
</P>
<P>
   Caray's confused. He asks Rob to repeat the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' says Rob. ``Where and how should I consolidate my
student loans?''
</P>
<P>
   Caray is trying to decide if this is the kind of call he'd so
famously boot in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a job and then pay 'em off ...'' Caray begins.
</P>
<P>
   Rob interrupts. ``Is Clark Howard around?''
</P>
<P>
   Rob's got the wrong show. Caray tells him to try back another
time and breaks for a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to make me mad,'' he says off the air. ``A
simple'' _ he uses an expletive phrase _ ``would have been an
appropriate answer. But I'm going to be this way all year. Until I
lose it. If I lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Caray smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Smiles!
</P>
<P>
   THE SKIP CARAY FILE
</P>
<P>
   Harry Christopher ``Skip'' Caray Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Occupation: In his 25th season as Atlanta Braves announcer, on
TBS, Turner South and WSB radio.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Married to Paula for 24 years. Four children: Harry
``Chip'' Caray III, 35; Cindy Hines, 33 (both from a previous
marriage); Shayelyn Woodbery, 31 (from Paula's previous marriage);
Josh Caray, 18.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Journalism degree with honors, University of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On calling a baseball game: ``I'm always thinking of the guy
driving a tractor-trailer rig, driving across the South, busting
his (rear end). He wants to stop, but he can't, he has to keep
going. I try to keep him awake and entertain him as he's driving
from Birmingham to Montgomery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On imitating Caray calling a baseball game: ESPN's Rich Eisen,
who often imitates Caray on ``Sports Center,'' says, ``I channel
Dudley Do-Right, a little Charles Kuralt and some Marvin the
Martian, of Bugs Bunny fame _ you know, the little guy in the funny
helmet who goes, `Where's the ka-boom? There was an
earth-shattering ka-boom!'''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
