<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0195 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WATERFALLS-SIDE20-COX     05-19 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERFALLS-SIDE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going with the flow: Here are some of the best
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 20
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A waterfall is the surprise at the end of a hike,'' says Mark
Morrison. And each is startling in its own way. We asked the
47-year-old Douglasville resident, author of four guidebooks on
Southeastern waterfalls, to describe, in his words, the most
distinctive cascades in Georgia . . . and slightly beyond.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most scenic: Falls on Big Creek, Chattahoochee National
Forest, east of Clayton. ``The falls tumble in three small leaps
through about a 4- to 5-foot channel in the rock. The rock to the
right is especially pretty _ it's multicolored with moss and
lichens. The falls end in a beautiful, deep, blue-green pool. Then
you have the surrounding hemlocks and white pines, which give the
area almost an alpine look.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most peaceful: Crow Creek Falls, Chattahoochee National
Forest, near Lake Rabun. ``The falls aren't hard to get to _ you
can drive to within 300 feet of them _ but hardly anybody goes
there. They are on the back side of Lake Rabun, and it seems that
people don't venture to that side very often. The waterfall spills
over four small ledges and flows into a shallow, shady-bottomed
pool surrounded by dense rhododendron. A steep mountain slope with
hemlock trees and chestnut stumps flanks the left side.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most unusual. Virgin Falls, Cumberland Plateau, Tennessee.
``The falls are located on a creek that flows out of a cave, then
drops 110 feet into a sinkhole. The water disappears into the earth
_ it does not run on from there. I think it eventually ends up in
the Caney Fork River.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgia's best-kept secret. The Falls on Horse Branch,
Chattahoochee National Forest, west of Clayton. ``Nobody knows
about this one. I haven't found it represented on maps _ I heard
about it from a fellow in Rabun County. An old logging road
descends to Horse Branch Creek. You have to hike up the creek
three-tenths of a mile, through a jungle of rhododendron. The
waterfall runs over stratified rock. It's unlike the granites that
you normally see _ there are hundreds of layers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most difficult to reach (included in book): Lee Falls, Sumter
National Forest, South Carolina. ``The last time I was up there,
about a year ago, they had a lot of storm damage. You have to hike
the last half-mile to the falls wading through Tamassee Creek, and
I had to go over and under a lot of fallen trees. But it's
beautiful there _ the whole rock wall is green with mosses and
water plants. It's about the greenest place I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most difficult to reach (not included in book): Flat Creek
Falls, east of Clermont. ``I didn't even publish directions to this
one because I felt it was too difficult. The trail is virtually
straight up the side of a mountain. Once you get to the waterfall,
it's all barren rock, like Stone Mountain. There's nothing to stand
on or hold on to. I hiked up through rhododendron as thick as it
could be. It's very pretty but very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
