<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      05-19 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAZIO TO CHALLENGE CLINTON IN N.Y. SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Little-known Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., jumped into
the race against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton for a Senate
seat from New York on Friday, quickly filling a political vacuum
created by the withdrawal of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from
the showcase contest.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a conservative four-term congressman from Long Island who
once had close ties to former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.,
declared his candidacy minutes after Giuliani's withdrawal from the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I am the strongest Republican candidate, and the
Republican who is best able to unite our party and defeat Hillary
Clinton in November,'' Lazio declared.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is expected to get the backing of New York Gov. George
Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers to capture the
Republican nomination for the Senate at the party's convention in
Buffalo, N.Y., on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, diagnosed with a treatable form of prostate cancer in
late April, told a New York City Hall news conference that he was
withdrawing ``to put my health first.'' The announcement came days
after Giuliani announced that he is seeking a legal separation from
his wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover, to spend time with Judith
Nathan, a ``very good friend'' who lives in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani promised to support any Republican nominated by the
state GOP to battle Clinton for the Senate seat held by retiring
five-term Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is a lesser known politician than Giuliani, a combative
former federal prosecutor and Justice Department official who has
applied tough remedies to many of New York City's ills.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who held a narrow 44 percent to 43 percent edge over
Giuliani in the latest statewide survey, swamped Lazio 50 percent
to 31 percent in the same Quinnipiac College Poll completed on May
15.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a lawyer and a former member of the Suffolk County
Legislature on Long Island, faces the immediate task of introducing
himself to the state's 10.7 million registered voters, particularly
voters outside his district in the New York metropolitan area and
upstate New York who have barely heard of him.
</P>
<P>
   Three out of four voters questioned in a statewide CBS News-New
York Times survey completed April 5 said they had not heard enough
about Lazio to even form an opinion about the 42-year-old
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who held a news conference in New York City moments
after Giuliani's withdrawal, declined to assess the political
impact of her rival's withdrawal or Lazio's entrance into the race,
saying she would ``just wait and see what develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had steadily gained on Giuliani to overtake his edge in
statewide surveys since she launched the first Senate campaign by a
first lady in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were quick to offer Lazio public support. Giuliani
said Lazio ``can count on my help and my support'' if he wins the
GOP Senate nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee that is working to expand the GOP's 10-seat
edge over Democrats in the Senate, all but anointed Lazio as the
GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is ``a top notch campaigner and fundraiser'' with a
``running start'' in the race, McConnell said, adding: ``Lazio is
probably in the best position to make a seamless transition as a
vigorous candidate with the single goal of representing New York's
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the prospective GOP presidential
nominee, said he was ``confident that the New York Republican Party
will nominate a New Yorker who will be able to win'' in the race
against Clinton, a dig at Clinton who is fighting to overcome
``carpetbagger'' criticism because she only recently moved into the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who had explored challenging Giuliani for the GOP Senate
nomination last fall, first won his seat in 1992 by upsetting a
better-financed Democratic 18-year incumbent, Rep. Thomas Downey.
Lazio has built a reputation in Congress as a moderate Republican
who is well-liked by conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last month, Lazio described himself as someone
who ``can unify the party, who can draw soft Democrats and
independents, (and) who can bring the Conservative Party on
board.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's small-but-influential Conservative Party often is a
make-or-break force among Republican candidates, adding 300,000
votes or more to any GOP candidate who earns the party endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has a pro-abortion rights voting record but opposes
federal spending on abortions through federal programs such as
Medicaid. He favors banning certain forms of late-term abortions.
He has bucked Republican leaders by supporting the five-day waiting
period for handgun purchases and the ban on certain kinds of
semi-automatic assault weapons. The Sierra Club and the League of
Conservation Voters endorsed him in his House races because of his
pro-environment position.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio voted to impeach President Clinton in the wake of the
Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio made his mark in Congress by shepherding compromise
legislation on public housing in 1998 that overhauled the federally
supported system that shelters 1.3 million families and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In mounting his Senate campaign, Lazio may be able to look to
Giuliani for assistance. The two-term mayor of New York City raised
$19.3 million for his Senate campaign from 200,000 donors
nationwide and still had $9.2 million on hand as of March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Snyder, spokeswoman for the Federal Election Commission,
said Giuliani faces a number of options for dealing with his Senate
campaign war chest. He could:
</P>
<P>
   _ save the money for a subsequent campaign, such as seeking the
New York governorship . His second four-year term ends Dec. 31,
2001, and he cannot seek a third term under state law.
</P>
<P>
   _ return the donations to his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   _ make two $1,000 campaign donations to Lazio's Senate bid, one
donation for the primary contest and one for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   _ donate his Senate campaign treasury to the New York state GOP
or the Republican National Committee ``without limitation'' to
finance party efforts on behalf of Lazio or any other Republican.
</P>
<P>
   _ transform his Senate campaign committee into a political
action committee that could support selected candidates, including
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Were Giuliani to return individual campaign donations to
supporters with a letter suggesting that they donate the money to
Lazio, the FEC might regard the mailing as an in-kind campaign
contribution by Giuliani. The Lazio campaign might finance such a
mailing, however, to avoid any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of variations,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had long coveted the Republican Senate nomination and has
contrasted his record of legislative compromise with Giuliani's
combative style and role in defending New York police in a series
of controversial shooting incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had courted New York's Conservative Party, winning
encouragement from party leader Michael Long, who has a long
history of hostile relations with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Long made no commitment to support Lazio in a telephone
interview on Friday. ``If he announces, then in fact I'll cross
that bridge when I get to it,'' Long said. ``I don't want to get
involved in making a quick judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Joe Joseph J. DioGuardi, who has already announced
his quest for the Conservative party's Senate nomination, ``has a
head start on the others,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan &LR; hearstdc.com. Stewart M. Powell can be reached at
202-298-6920 or at the e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
