<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0205 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-ABOUT-CARS-LOWRIDERS-     05-19 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-LOWRIDERS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
TAMPA, Fla.: of Guadalupe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The featured event of lowrider gatherings is the car-hopping
contest, where hydraulic-equipped cars compete to see how high they
can bounce their wheels off the ground. The contestants stand
beside the vehicles, operating the hydraulics with a switch box
connected to the car through a cable. Jorge Guzman's 1987 Toyota
pickup truck set a world record in the truck hop, with a wheelie 62
inches high, before the truck's gas tank ruptured and the vehicle
burst into flame, sending judges and contestants scampering for the
fire extinguishers.
</P>
<P>
   Without exception, each of the cars suffer heavy damage in the
course of the competition. Because the hydraulics overheat, fire is
a common occurrence. Wheels fall off, hubs shatter and suspensions
collapse. As each car disassembles itself in noise and fire, the
crowd gets to its feet and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reinforce them a lot,'' says Armando Nunez, the leader of
the hopping team sponsored by Hilow Hydraulics. ``But they don't
last too long.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, a freak accident: During the truck dance competition,
a tire explodes, firing a portion of the fractured wheel rim like
an artillery shell. It hits the truck's owner, Glen Strickland of
Jacksonville, Fla., in the face, dropping him to the concrete
floor. His jaw is shattered and he loses some teeth. It takes 15
minutes to summon an ambulance to the arena floor. The festive mood
sobers quickly and further competition is canceled.
</P>
<P>
   An R-rated rap concert ends the show. But the kids themselves
don't seem to notice the performers. Many are interested instead in
the lowrider bikes and trikes, Schwinns and Huffys given the full
lowrider treatment, including custom frames, elaborate gold-plated
scrollwork, even hydraulics, TVs, stereos and Playstations. In
time, the kids who own these bikes will trade them in for something
faster, and lower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-290     05-19 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL INCREASES PEACEKEEPING FORCE IN SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council on Friday increased the
number of troops allowed in the U.N. peacekeeping force in Sierra
Leone by 2,000 and is likely to expand the force by several
thousand more in the next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Leone mission, originally limited to 11,000 troops by
the council, is already the largest U.N. peacekeeping operation
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's increase was required after reinforcements from
Bangladesh, Jordan and India arrived this week. Those troops were
expected to push the force above the limit set in February, just
before the United Nations took over peacekeeping in Sierra Leone
from a regional contingent led by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But another increase to as many as 16,500 troops, which
Secretary- General Kofi Annan is expected to recommend to the
council in the next few days, will represent a substantial
commitment to bringing peace to Sierra Leone, even while rebels
there are still holding more than 300 peacekeepers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Some hostages have been freed, but with alarming delays, U.N.
officials said. Releases have been promised, then have not taken
place, causing the United Nations to increase the number of troops
listed as missing. More than 500 soldiers and monitors, most of
them African, were seized by rebels at the beginning of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Any increases in the size of the peacekeeping force in Sierra
Leone pose a problem for U.S. diplomats here because they are
expected to give Congress, where there is considerable opposition
to these operations, 15 days' notice of any new or augmented
mission. The administration can waive this notification, as it
apparently did for Friday's vote, but the procedure could seriously
delay the next move in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials are concerned about how a weak elected
government in the capital, Freetown, will deal with Foday Sankoh,
the leader of the Revolutionary United Front, whose forces took the
hostages. Sankoh is now in custody after nine days in hiding. But
the fact that the government has not decided what to do with Sankoh
appears to be emboldening some of his followers to demand that he
be freed if the war is to be settled.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Friday that it was investigating Sankoh's
case. His troops have been responsible for savage brutality in a
civil war that has lasted nearly nine years. In 1997, Sankoh was
sentenced to death for treason. In an agreement signed in Lome,
Togo, last July, Sankoh was nevertheless given amnesty _ not
recognized by the United Nations _ in return for a promise to
disarm. But when his soldiers began turning in weapons to
peacekeepers, rebels in the group responded by taking the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's representative at the
United Nations, who introduced the resolution to enlarge the
peacekeeping force, said that Sankoh had violated the Lome
agreement, implying that all promises made to him in the peace
accord were off. Sankoh had also been promised a role in a
power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   Greenstock also warned that there could be no negotiating for
the release of hostages or attempts to link the fate of the U.N.
soldiers to any other issue.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has about 800 troops in Sierra Leone who were sent to
evacuate foreigners. But now those troops are playing a major role
in keeping Freetown reasonably calm, said U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
   With an increase in U.N. troop strength for Sierra Leone,
Nigerian troops are likely to return to the country, along with
other West African peacekeepers representing a regional
organization, the Economic Community of West African States and its
cease-fire monitoring group, known as Ecomog. It is still not clear
whether they will be under direct U.N. command or deployed in some
other way.
</P>
<P>
   In Monrovia, Liberia, on Friday, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, a
special envoy sent to the region by President Clinton to work for
the release of the hostages, said that there was no room for
negotiation. ``Peacekeepers cannot be target practice for the
RUF,'' he said. Liberia's president, Charles Taylor, another former
rebel leader with ties to Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front, has
been credited with a role in the freeing of about 150 hostages
before the releases stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told reporters in Monrovia that during an earlier stop
in Lagos, he had urged Nigeria to send more troops to Sierra Leone
to help settle the political crisis. ``They have the power to
remove the RUF as a military consideration in negotiations,'' he
said at a news conference at Monrovia's airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
