<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NASCAR-CHAPLAINS-NYTR     05-19 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-CHAPLAINS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C., N.H.)  
 CHAPLAINS HELP FAMILY, FANS COPE WITH PETTY DEATH
</HEADLINE>
  By BETHANY BRADSHER   
 Spartanburg (S.C.) Herald-Journal   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday, May 12th, started out as a routine day for the staff of
Motor Racing Outreach. Some chaplains were at various racetracks
throughout the nation, watching practice runs or talking to crew
members. Others were in the ministry's Charlotte, N.C., office.
</P>
<P>
   And then a crash killed Adam Petty, 19, the rising star in
NASCAR's most famous family. Five chaplains quickly mobilized in
five different directions. They dropped everything to comfort the
grieving members of the Petty family and the extended stock-car
community.
</P>
<P>
   Busch Series chaplain Eddie Robison was on hand as cars
practiced that day for last Saturday's Busch 200 at the New
Hampshire International Speedway. When he heard about the crash, he
reported to the track's medical center, where he usually stays with
the injured driver as he is treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine times out of 100, it's nothing serious,'' Robison
said. ``I'll just be around, just like your pastor would visit the
hospital when you're sick.''
</P>
<P>
   But medical personnel were on the track with Adam Petty's car
for an unusually long time. It took 20 minutes, Robison said, to
cut Petty out of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Robison learned that Petty was in critical condition, and
he put in a call to the Charlotte office at Lowe's Motor Speedway.
As Robison headed to the hospital to be with Adam Petty and his
crew, Motor Racing Outreach founder and Winston Cup chaplain Max
Helton was calling Kyle Petty in London, where he was vacationing
with his daughter, to tell him the news.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gary Rutherford, the chaplain for the Petty
Enterprises racing shop, was en route to the Petty shop in
Thomasville, N.C. He gave word of the crash to Richard Petty, who
was in the shop that day, and the other employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Beaver, another Winston Cup chaplain, had already left for
Kyle Petty's home to tell Kyle's wife, Patti.
</P>
<P>
   This network even reached overseas. After Helton finished his
phone conversation with Kyle Petty, he contacted Phil Aiken, a
London resident who leads chapel services for some Formula One
teams in England. Aiken went to visit Petty and to help him make
arrangements to fly back home.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR embraces Motor Racing Outreach's ministry because of
times like these, Robison said. The chaplains spend years leading
Bible studies and chapel services, praying with drivers and crew,
and when tragedy strikes they are spiritual comforters as well as
friends to those left behind.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Aiken in London, all of the chaplains knew
the Petty family. When they came to the front door to bring the
news every mother dreads, when they walked into the office with the
news that would eventually leave a gaping hole in the life of a
grandfather, they stepped in on a carpet of trust.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more group that will need a wise and listening ear
during the aftermath of Adam Petty's death, the largest branch in
this fiercely loyal family. They are the fans, the tens of
thousands who travel to tracks each weekend and camp in tents for
the chance to watch the exhilaration of controlled speed and,
occasionally, the heartbreak of collision.
</P>
<P>
   The fans have chaplains, too _ Dennis McGowan and his staff at
Racing Fans Outreach, which is part of Motor Racing Outreach.
McGowan will be in the camping areas around the Charlotte speedway
this weekend for The Winston. He said he expects to have
significant conversations with those who never knew Adam Petty, but
are devastated by the loss just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see fans seeing the need for spiritual growth through
deaths like this,'' McGowan said. ``There's a real sense of
mortality that strikes them once they see their hero, and he's
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal in Spartanburg, S.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
