<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0208 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-$ADV2     05-19 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-$ADV21-800(4TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLYING ROUND THE NEW CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 21) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the House of Representatives this week tackles the issue of
liberalizing trade ties with China, the voice of American business
will be heard loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Newt Gingrich tried unsuccessfully in 1995 and 1996 to
make liability laws more favorable to corporations have so many
types of American companies banded together to lobby for a single
issue, according to Bruce Josten, executive vice president of the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce. From agricultural processors to Internet
businesses, and from automakers to movie studios, corporate America
sees profits in China.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobbying effort, the bigger fish are leaning hard on the
smaller ones. Companies that sell everything from cleaning supplies
to titanium to Boeing _ even hot dogs to its employees _ may not
seem like exporters. But with Boeing increasingly reliant on
overseas aircraft sales, and convinced that China will become the
world's fastest-growing aircraft market, the company has enlisted
its parts makers to badger members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The effort could be potent, for there is a supplier in nearly
every pot. Boeing's 10,000 suppliers are spread across 420 of the
nation's 435 congressional districts _ a distribution that rivals
that of even the most politically durable military program _ and
Boeing has contacted them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those suppliers is an exporter and should
understand the importance of China, and we think they do,'' said
Philip Condit, Boeing's chairman and chief executive, who has made
10 trips to Washington from his Seattle office this year. ``You're
just running an all-out campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to counter the corporate effort, unions and environmental
and other advocacy groups have organized demonstrations, started
letter-writing campaigns and sent supporters to Washington by the
busload. But American business has responded with its own
mobilization, using connections to lawmakers forged over years of
nickel-and-dime lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   The pact has wide corporate support because it would require
China to lower tariffs, end restrictive business rules and
dismantle many other trade barriers. The United States, in turn,
would halt its annual congressional reviews of China's access to
the American market. Those reviews have often focused on human
rights and have made some American companies leery of long-term
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and equipment makers want lower tariffs on American
grain. Insurers, banks and brokerage houses want to eliminate
licensing requirements that turn any hope of entry into China into
a multiyear marathon of wining and dining government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers want an end to China's requirement that 80 percent of
the parts in any car built there be made in China. Retailers are
eager to import far more low-priced clothing from China. Hollywood,
drug makers and high-technology businesses want improved
protections against the illegal copying of movies, medicines and
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of government regulation and intervention, we'd like
it to be the minimum necessary,'' said Robert Kimmitt, vice
chairman and president of Commerce One in Pleasanton, Calif., which
has already set up business-to-business Internet exchanges in the
United States and is trying to do so in China, too.
</P>
<P>
   The normalization of trade would bring all this and more as
China seeks to integrate its economy more closely with the global
market by joining the World Trade Organization. Membership in the
WTO would require Beijing to comply with extraordinarily detailed
free-trade rules, which extend far beyond tariffs and duties to
cover most everything from intellectual property rights to the
freedom granted to companies to set up their own distribution
networks. Proponents say full entry into the world market will make
China more prosperous, more open and less prone to abusing human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to favor free trade and we also think that if we
really do want to progress in human rights within China, one of the
ways to do that is to actually open up trade,'' said Jacques
Nasser, the chief executive of the Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   American labor leaders and their allies reject the executives'
reasoning. The United States, they say, would lose its ability to
influence human rights in China, particularly because the bill
would eliminate the annual votes in Congress on trade ties _ votes
that have sometimes prompted China to ease policies.
</P>
<P>
   Still fuming over the North American Free Trade Agreement, which
they blame for a loss of jobs to Mexico, union presidents are even
more fearful of free trade with the world's largest low-wage
country. Stephen Yokich, president of the United Automobile
Workers, said congressional approval would ``give American
corporations an incentive again to ship jobs, this time to China,
which is even cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   But while unions worry about losing jobs, American companies
fret about losing markets. ``We have the potential of a 100-fold
increase in travel per person in a country of 1.2 billion people,
and that's a huge market,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deal, he contended, poses a question from China to
America: ``Is the U.S. a reliable trade partner and can we buy
airplanes from Boeing, or is it not a reliable trade partner and do
we look to Europe?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Following are closer looks by reporters for The New York Times
at how various industries would be affected by a new China trade
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Autos: Huge Investments, And Seeking More
</P>
<P>
   When the Transportation Department won approval from Beijing
four years ago for the first nonstop air route between the United
States and China, the American city chosen was not Los Angeles, San
Francisco or Seattle, but Detroit. The selection reflected the
enormous role that automakers have played in American investment in
China.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors is building Buicks at a $1.5 billion factory in
Shanghai and is about to assemble Chevrolet S-10 pickups and Blazer
sport utility vehicles in Shenyang. Ford makes delivery vans, car
seats and radiators in China, while DaimlerChrysler assembles Jeep
Cherokees and Mercedes sedans. Delphi Automotive Systems, the
world's largest auto parts company, produces most everything from
batteries to door latches there.
</P>
<P>
   Normalized trade ties would transform the way automakers do
business in China, said Theodor Cunningham, executive vice
president for global sales and marketing at DaimlerChrysler.
China's requirement of 80 percent local content would disappear,
allowing DaimlerChrysler to ship higher-quality parts from
elsewhere. Chinese restrictions on private networks of car
dealerships would end, as would requirements that extensive
research and development be done in China, allowing DaimlerChrysler
to design cars in Michigan for Chinese production. Perhaps most
important, the country could no longer demand that the company hand
over the blueprints for its minivans before allowing them to be
built in China. For years, that rule has kept the company from
starting production there, for fear that knockoffs would be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire package is very meaningful to us,'' Cunningham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders dismiss the Chinese concessions, questioning
whether they will be honored. ``Who's going to enforce it? We can't
even enforce deals with Japan,'' said Yokich of the UAW.
</P>
<P>
   The union also expressed concern that permanent trade ties with
China would make companies more comfortable about establishing
factories there that might otherwise be built in the United States.
Auto parts companies have already moved considerable production _
and jobs _ to Mexico, Yokich said.
</P>
<P>
   But J.T. Battenberg 3rd, Delphi's chairman and chief executive,
said that concerns about American job losses were unwarranted and
that most auto parts production in China would be for cars sold
there. ``The point they miss,'' he said of critics, ``is that the
logistics costs of moving parts around the world are expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KEITH BRADSHER
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceuticals: Approving Factories, But Not the Drugs
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer will sell billions of dollars worth of Lipitor, its
popular cholesterol-fighting drug, this year, but none of those
sales will be in China.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist government agreed last year that Pfizer would have
the exclusive right to sell Lipitor in China. But days later, the
government said a generic-drug company, which may have obtained the
drug's patented formula on the black market, could also sell the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer still hopes to sell Lipitor in China, but it could lose
many sales to the generic-drug company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a level playing field,'' said C. Louis Clemente, a
Pfizer executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer owns a large factory in Dalian, in northern China, and
sold $60 million of other drugs in China last year. It says it
could sell much more if China would do more to protect intellectual
property rights and to lower other barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has such high hurdles for foreign
companies that several have built factories in China, only to find
that they could not obtain government approval for some drugs they
had planned to make there.
</P>
<P>
   In its trade deal with Washington last November, China agreed to
change many practices that hurt American companies. Most important
for American drug companies, it agreed to strengthen its protection
of patents and other intellectual property rights. It has also
agreed to lower tariffs on drugs, end pricing practices that favor
Chinese companies and allow foreign companies to distribute their
own products.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, the
industry's trade group, estimates that American drug companies,
which already sell about $700 million worth of drugs to China,
could increase sales by more than $100 million in the first year if
China, as promised, cut tariffs by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is explosive,'' said Mark Grayson, a spokesman
for the trade group. ``As people become middle class, they want
Western medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   _MELODY PETERSEN
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment: Hollywood Wants A Bigger Box Office
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment industry _ especially Hollywood _ has been
enthusiastic about easing trade barriers with China and has been
pushing hard for the trade bill. There are two reasons: China is a
huge potential market, even if few American movies are now released
there. And studios worry that rejection of the bill would prompt
Beijing to spitefully cancel the fledgling trade agreements already
in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our trade with China is minuscule,'' said Jack Valenti,
president of the Motion Picture Association of America, which
represents studios. ``The reason we are passionately in favor of
the trade bill has far more to do with the long-range future.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last summer, China limited United States companies to
exporting 10 movies a year there, with the studios keeping half the
revenue and China the remainder. On the other hand, there was no
limit to how many films the studios could simply sell to Chinese
distributors. In recent years, 40 to 50 films made outside China,
mostly small independent ones, have been sold for flat fees there.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood studios, however, are not interested in flat fees.
They want a continuous share of the loot.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, President Clinton's trade negotiators reached a new
deal that doubled, to 20, the number of American movies that could
be imported, with promises of further increases in future years.
That is still small potatoes by Hollywood standards, but a step in
what the studios consider the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   The studios now do about $25 million of business a year in
China. That is a tiny fraction of what would start flowing in if
most movies were given a Chinese release and if lower trade
barriers continued to expand a Chinese middle class hungry for such
diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Some entertainment conglomerates have negotiated separate
commercial deals with China. Disney is planning a new theme park in
Hong Kong, and Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. has an extensive
telecommunications agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is theaters. Most in China are in sad shape. The
nation has been eager to attract foreign investment in new cinemas,
but foreigners are limited to a minority share of any operation.
</P>
<P>
   Again, not good enough for Hollywood. ``We're not going to buy
any theaters until we own them,'' Valenti said. ``And we're not
going to put more money into theaters if they're not letting in
more American pictures.'' Under a new agreement, foreigners could
own a controlling interest in new Chinese multiplexes within three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Video piracy is also a source of irritation. Even Hollywood
films not released in China are often quickly available through
bootleg sources. Then, of course, not a penny of revenue flows back
to the studios.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, American trade officials say, the Chinese have
clamped down more vigorously on bootleggers. Bringing more
Hollywood movies into China, along with more multiplexes, would
give the Chinese authorities reason to crack down harder,
entertainment executives contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress votes no, my judgment is that all the agreements
we have made will be null and void,'' Valenti said. ``I mean, would
you keep an agreement with someone who just exiled you and kicked
you on the backside?''
</P>
<P>
   - RICK LYMAN
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Textiles: Cheaper Clothing, But at What Price?
</P>
<P>
   Americans love to get fashion on the cheap. Even with the
economy booming, they are snapping up more $4.99 cotton T-shirts
and Indian print sundresses than ever.
</P>
<P>
   And shoppers are not being tricked into getting less. They have
actually been winning the war on costs. Over all, apparel prices
have fallen about 1 percent a year throughout most of the 1990s.
Last year, prices fell even more.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason that Americans pay so little for products from
blue jeans to sneakers is that manufacturing jobs have been shipped
wholesale to countries with cheap labor _ countries like China.
Long before the trade agreement was negotiated, employment in the
American apparel and textile industries was already plunging.
Together, the two industries employed 1.2 million people in this
country as of January of this year, according to the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees. That is down from
2.5 million in 1973, the peak employment year for apparel workers.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the trend toward exporting sewing
jobs has been helped by earlier trade agreements that lowered
tariffs and quotas. Union data shows that in the 36 months before
Nafta took effect, the United States lost 2,000 apparel jobs.
During the following 36 months, the loss was 134,000.
</P>
<P>
   But because so many jobs have already disappeared, the effect on
manufacturing still based in the United States may not be as severe
in the future _ even the union predicts a loss of 15,000 jobs a
year at most. The real impact of the China agreement _ which allows
it to participate in the phasing out of nation-by-nation quotas on
clothing imports to the United States by 2005 _ is likely to fall
mostly on other Asian countries that will not be able to compete
with China's even lower-cost labor.
</P>
<P>
   When judging China's importance, consider that Wal-Mart Stores,
the nation's largest importer, already gets 53 percent of its
clothing imports from China, according to a study of U.S. Customs
Department documents by the Citizens Trade Campaign, which is
critical of the company and opposed to the China trade agreement.
Wal-Mart refuses to give specifics on its imports, but a spokesman,
Jay Allen, acknowledged that the company contracts directly with
``several thousand factories.''
</P>
<P>
   Once China joins the World Trade Organization, the retail
industry says, there will be gains at home to offset the job losses
abroad. Most important, executives argue, are the tariff cuts will
allow them to sell more to China. ``We see a great market
opportunity,'' said Candyce Cummings, general counsel of the VF
Corp., maker of Lee and Wrangler clothing.
</P>
<P>
   -LESLIE KAUFMAN
</P>
<P>
   Financial Services: Investment Capital And Car Loans, Too?
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to find legislation that has been embraced so
unconditionally by America's financial institutions as the China
trade bill. Whether they think they have more to gain from its
passage or to lose from its failure, they have been lobbying hard.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with commercial banking operations, like Citigroup,
salivate over the prospect of providing auto loans and other
services. Investment banks are more concerned that rejection could
chill relations with Chinese officials who have begun to tap
foreign capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   New York companies have played leading roles in raising capital
for several state-run enterprises, including the initial public
offering this month for PetroChina.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from political skirmishes over that underwriting, Henry
Paulson, chairman of Goldman Sachs, said rejection of the bill
could hurt his firm's chances of advising on future privatizations.
But he is more worried that client companies would not play as big
a part in China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need any changes in the rules to work on
privatizations and other assignments,'' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs advises the Chinese government and sells foreign
securities in China. But the firm does not have an investment bank
there, as it does in Japan, because the American company would be
limited to a minority stake.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks are much more eager to expand their physical
operations in China. Citibank has only four branches there and
cannot do business in local currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There essentially is no consumer banking system in China,''
said Lionel Johnson, Citigroup's director of international
government relations. ``People have very limited relationships with
banks, limited opportunities to invest their savings.''
</P>
<P>
   While China is expected to remain wary of anything that
threatens the stability of its state-run banks, all that is
supposed to start changing within five years under the trade pact,
potentially giving Citibank and other foreign banks an even chance
to compete with domestic banks for tens of millions of consumers.
The banks see an opportunity to lend money to Chinese customers for
big-ticket purchases, especially cars. They also anticipate being
able to decide where to put branches, instead of having the
government assign the sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time,'' Johnson said, ``market forces will make
those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   _PATRICK McGEEHAN
</P>
<P>
   Insurance: A Foot in the Door To Selling Policies
</P>
<P>
   For American insurance companies, China is a virtually untapped
market. Most Chinese do not have coverage, and though they lack
great wealth, they save a larger share of their earnings than
Americans do. American insurers hope to sell them life insurance
with savings features, as well as health insurance and pension
plans.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, nearly a dozen insurers from the United
States and about 90 others from Japan, Europe and elsewhere have
been romancing the Chinese _ meeting with government officials and
potential business partners, offering free classes in underwriting
and making gifts to universities.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, a few insurers have been invited to apply for
licenses. Then, after a couple of years of stepping through
government hurdles, they have been allowed to open.
</P>
<P>
   Nine foreign insurers, mostly life insurers, now sell policies
in China, including two from the United States _ the American
International Group and Aetna. Passage of the trade bill would mean
that any company could apply for a license. But American insurers
do not expect China to suddenly issue licenses to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to wake up and all of a sudden find the flood
gates open,'' one American executive said. ``They are very
cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, perhaps a half-dozen foreign insurers would be
allowed in each year, and all would operate on a short tether.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the exception of AIG _ which was founded in Shanghai
in 1919 and, in 1980, was the first American financial services
company to open an office in modern China _ they are restricted to
Shanghai. Under the pact, they would be allowed to expand gradually
to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   American insurers say they would prefer fewer restrictions, but
like other foreign businesses, they are overwhelmed by China's
potential. ``Things don't have to be perfect,'' said Brad Smith of
the American Council on Life Insurance. ``This is a good first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   -JOSEPH B. TREASTER
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   High Technology: Intellectual Property And Other Issues
</P>
<P>
   To the high-technology industry, China is a vast emerging market
that is virtually out of reach. Analysts estimate that China will
soon be one of the three largest markets for computers, software
and Internet products. While companies like Motorola, Advanced
Micro Devices and Intel have some operations there, they say
Chinese regulations and lax intellectual property protections
significantly interfere with their ability to do business.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade bill does not pass, the industry says, China will
become a World Trade Organization member but will not be treated as
such by the United States and thus will not have to follow the
group's rules when dealing with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we negotiated will go to our non-American competitors,''
said James Whittaker, chairman of the U.S. High Tech Coalition on
China, a lobbying group based in Washington. ``We will be at a
severe disadvantage in one of the most important markets in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including labor organizations, are concerned that
high-technology companies will exploit China's large pool of
skilled engineers and weak labor protections and move jobs
overseas. Chuck Mulloy, an Intel spokesman, noted, however, that
while 60 percent of Intel's revenues came from abroad, 70 percent
of its work force was in the United States. ``Success in China,''
he said, ``can help create jobs in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications is also seen as a potential bonanza for
American companies. Arthur Kobler, president of the China operation
for AT&AMP;T, expects China's roughly $50 billion communications market
to double by 2004, fueled largely by an explosion in wireless
telephone use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime this year or next year, China will become the
second-largest wireless market, behind the United States but ahead
of Japan,'' Kobler said. ``China is a market that you cannot not be
in.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, China's extensive restrictions on foreign
business operations severely limit American high-technology and
telecommunications companies. Foreign-made products are subject to
high tariffs. Yet foreign companies that want to produce in China
face restrictions on what parts they can buy from abroad and are
permitted to distribute their products within China only through
local distributors. State-owned enterprises control a significant
share of the trade in electronics goods, and American companies
complain that they give preference to higher-cost Chinese
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   That could change soon. In the bilateral pact reached in
November, China agreed to phase out tariffs and other restrictions
and to immediately become subject to the WTO's patent and copyright
rules. That provides tremendous opportunities not only to the
United States but also to China, said David Levine, a professor at
the Walter A. Haas School of Business at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``High tech,'' he said, ``is one instance of the general theory
that if you want to learn from the rest of the world, you trade
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Communications services are likely to be an important part of
that trade. Moreover, the opportunity to sell services to Chinese
businesses and consumers may well be surpassed by the chance to win
over big foreign corporations that want to link their Chinese
operations with their other units. _SARA ROBINSON and SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture: Poised to Become A Big Winner
</P>
<P>
   American agriculture could be one of the biggest beneficiaries
of the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering through nearly three years of depressed
commodity prices, American farmers hope that improved trade
relations will let them sell millions of bushels of surplus corn,
soybeans and other crops to China over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the United States had more than $50 billion in
agricultural exports; only about $1 billion of that went to China.
Agriculture officials say that if relations are normalized, exports
could double in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Farm equipment makers like Caterpillar, Deere and CNH project
strong exports of farm tractors and combines. Cargill and Archer
Daniels Midland expect to sell more processed goods, like soybean
meal and vegetable oil. And the prices that farmers get for beef,
poultry and pork could also get a lift.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all agriculture officials see a win-win situation that
could only increase exports and raise commodity prices. ``Everybody
except for a few splinter groups wants this to happen,'' said Bob
Callanan, a spokesman at the American Soybean Association. ``China
needs so much. Their people want to eat better.''
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans are the leading American farm export to China. Although
little corn reaches the country, China has already made concessions
that would including importing 4.5 million metric tons of corn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be easy to get China to implement this
agreement,'' said Susan Keith, an official at the National Corn
Growers Association in St. Louis. ``But if they're denied access,
they will do nothing to accommodate the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   China has already said that if it receives trading privileges,
it would lower its tariffs on most American agricultural goods.
Most everything from apples to wine would have a better chance of
getting in. Tariffs could fall from 31 percent today, on average,
to 14 percent in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   If China, as promised, also cuts subsidies to its own farmers,
American corn growers could have a better chance of selling their
crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is the largest consumer market in the world,'' said
Tamara White, director of commodities at the Illinois Farm Bureau.
``To get in on the ground level would be great. You want American
beef and American corn there, so you can get your flavor on their
taste buds.''
</P>
<P>
   -DAVID BARBOZA
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
