<HEADER>
A0226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-A     05-19 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK MAY CANCEL U.S. TRIP BECAUSE OF FIGHTING IN WEST BANK, GAZA,
LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT3 and 4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A week that began in violence ended violently here,
with bloody clashes in the West Bank and Gaza and intensified
fighting in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On the one-year anniversary of his election by a sweeping
majority, Prime Minister Ehud Barak was trying to put out fires on
many fronts at once.
</P>
<P>
   Because of trouble in the north, the south and within his
political coalition, he was weighing a cancellation of his
scheduled departure this weekend to the United States to confer
with President Clinton and meet with American Jewish leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence, back-channel peace talks continued in
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli, Palestinian and U.S. officials have characterized them
as a serious and constructive dialogue on the process itself and on
the final status issues.
</P>
<P>
   News accounts here say that Israel is offering as much as 90
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians, although it is
difficult to assess what is really happening by the bargaining
moves that are leaked.
</P>
<P>
   Near a heavily fortified Jewish settlement in the Gaza Strip, an
Israeli soldier and a Palestinian policeman were wounded as
Palestinian protests for the release of 1,650 prisoners degenerated
into confrontations. Israeli military officials said they were
investigating the source of fire that wounded the soldier, but that
there was no gun battle between troops like the one that took place
Monday near Ramallah in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister views the events severely and has ordered
the Israeli Defense Forces to act accordingly to restore calm,''
Barak's office said in a statement Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's protests, which began as prayer services ended, were
organized before Monday's demonstrations erupted into severe
rioting that ended with three Palestinians dead. Palestinian
authorities said they were trying to keep tensions low, although in
Ramallah their effort did not appear to be of sustained high
intensity. Many officers stepped to the side as a march, organized
by the militant Islamic group Hamas, headed toward confrontation
with the Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Qalqilya, in contrast, Palestinian police officers held back
demonstrators with nightsticks. At least 20 Palestinians were
injured by rubber-coated bullets. Another ``day of rage'' was
scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the violence would delay the transfer of
Abu Dis and two other villages near Jerusalem to the Palestinian
Authority. Barak's advisers said he would turn over the towns
within days, provided that Palestinian officials calmed the streets
and cooperated with their investigation of how things got out of
hand on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, Israeli warplanes attacked suspected guerrilla
positions in southern Lebanon on Friday. This followed fighting
Thursday, the heaviest in two weeks, in which 14 people were
wounded, including four 4 Lebanese civilians and a U.N.
peacekeeper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-REALITY-TV-FEATURE-LA     05-19 2312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALITY-TV-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOYEURISM COMES HOME TO ROOST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe we've lost our sense of shame. ``Every day on `Jerry
Springer,' secrets are confessed to that, in the past, people would
have gone to their graves with without telling a single soul,''
observes Robert Thompson, founding director of the Center for the
Study of Popular Television and a professor at Syracuse University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're revealing these dark secrets to the general public
through most sophisticated mass-communications system in history.
That's a major, major cultural shift _ one of the biggest stories
of the last quarter century.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also spawned the phenomenon known as ``Reality TV.'' When
television promises you ``reality,'' what it means of course is
heightened reality, the spectacular emotional terrain that most of
us travel only occasionally (tragedy, ecstasy, fury, intense
romance) and not the humdrum facts of day-to-day living (doing the
dishes, paying the bills, walking the dog). The ``reality'' part
occurs because viewers are seeing not actors spouting lines and
emoting grandiosely, but non-professionals honestly agonizing.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has been ratcheting up in recent years to today's
white-hot level. ``MTV's The Real World'' threw together dissimilar
young, attractive people in trendy environs and let them grope and
gripe with one another; afternoon talk shows like ``Springer''
upped the ante with frequent virulent clashes between guests. ``The
Blair Witch Project'' was a huge hit last summer because moviegoers
felt they were watching real people undergoing psychological
torture. And ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' is an unprecedented
TV phenomenon, in no small part because the show accentuates the
contestant's squirming in ``The Hot Seat'' to melodramatic music.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, CBS brings to America a couple of European imports
that are massive sensations overseas. In ``Survivor,'' debuting May
31, 16 contestants are plopped on an exotic island and must
scramble to attain food and shelter. Early clips show participants
bickering over who wasn't contributing to the group effort;
contestants hold regular sessions in which they vote members off
the island and, obviously, off the show. The final ``Survivor''
wins $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' coming in July, is even more claustrophobic: 10
contestants are locked into a two-bedroom, one-bathroom house
equipped with dozens of cameras and microphones and not allowed to
leave the grounds for 100 days. A combination of participant and
viewer votes ousts cast members; the last remaining houseguest wins
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``A show like this would have been unthinkable 10 years ago,''
suggests ``Big Brother'' executive producer Paul Romer, who created
the series in the Netherlands. ``It's kind of the next step. We
have a different attitude to our personal privacy. We're used to
webcams, to surveillance cameras in the streets and shopping malls.
Real soap operas are boring: This is a marriage between real life
and a soap opera. It's about human interaction _ relationships.
There are no scripted lines and no actors, and that's why it's very
appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer also cites the films ``ED-tv'' and ``The Truman Show'' as
proof of the audience's interest in the subject, neglecting to
mention that by the end of those films, the characters have grown
to hate those intrusive cameras.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it was argued that merely placing a camera at a
location altered the reality, but now, with the ubiquity of
camcorders, that may no longer be true. Larry Fleece, executive
producer of the syndicated series ``Real TV,'' which compiles
footage of unstaged feats and traumas, notes, ``If you put camera
in someone's face, it changes things. But if you build a blind for
a nature show, the animal becomes used to its presence after days,
weeks and months. The camera's presence becomes second nature.
After the novelty wears off, the camera becomes part of the family
and people become desensitized to it, and not so self-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The miracle is that this didn't happen long ago _ that TV and
voyeurism, two of America's favorite pastimes, became bedfellows,''
says Thompson. ``They were made for each other. Humans have had
voyeuristic tendencies since the moment we crawled out of the
primordial ooze. TV allows incredible opportunities for peeping-tom
experiences _ and you don't have to find a window. The window comes
to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social mores have relaxed significantly over the past
generations,'' Thompson continues. ``There used to be rules about
what you show and don't show on TV. But with the increased
competition from cable and the Internet, all bets are off. Networks
say, 'We've got to bring people into our tent.'''
</P>
<P>
   David Wild, TV critic for Rolling Stone and author of ``The
Showrunners,'' a book examining a tumultuous year in network
television, jokes, ``The only thing more painful than reality is
reality TV.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues, ``The bankruptcy of fiction TV is a large part of
the reason for reality TV's success.'' He confesses to being a
closet fan of ``Blind Date,'' a relationship game show, and ``The
Real World:'' ``I like seeing people even stupider than myself as
much as the next guy. But I don't know what it says about the
future of TV as a medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popularity of genres in television is cyclical _ this is
cyclical, but it's also sick. Darva (Conger) and Rick (Rockwell)
are part of our lives (thanks to the intense coverage of ``Who
Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'') but I don't know what any of
us gain from it,'' Wild says. ``It's not like 'Network' (the 1976
film anticipating and excoriating cheap TV publicity stunts) _ it
!ital!is 'Network.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those whose livelihood depends on creating fictional TV see
reality TV's explosion as a threat. Peter Mehlman, whose sitcom
``It's like, you know'' was canceled for ``Millionaire,'' recently
told Wild, ``Being canceled for ``Millionaire'' is like having a
girlfriend leave you for a rapist _ and she knows it. The networks
aren't catering to the lowest common denominator _ they !ital!are
the lowest common denominator.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Wild applauds the networks for trying new things.
``There's a sense that they're going down, but they're going down
guerilla style,'' he says. ``Say what you will about these shows,
but they're very spunky, and little else is working. So why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson agrees: ``The bottom line is, if done correctly, these
shows could be absolutely huge. I think 'Big Brother' will be
bigger only because of the illusions to similarity to our real
life. It's 'The Real World' and just as contrived, but still
earthbound. There's a sense that we can relate to the arguments
they'll be having. With 'Survivor' and the island, there's a sense
of costume drama about the whole thing _ it's 'The Blue Lagoon'
plugged in. These shows will live and die on how well they're
executed, which means, how much the contestants don't get along.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer admits that each time ``Big Brother'' debuted _ in the
Netherlands, Germany and Spain _ ``there was a lot of passion in
the media response. ... I really understand (the complaints), but
they were making judgments without enough information. People do
not go unprepared into the house _ we'd prepare them extensively
and tell them of all the potential pitfalls ahead of time. We were
responsible and ethical. If you prepare them well, you do no
harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, here are a few examples that suggest not all makers
of reality TV have the best interest of their participants in mind.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Jesse Emmons of West Hills says he was approached by the
producers of the game show ``Crush'' _ in which a person confesses
to having a crush on someone else, and if the object of those
affections reciprocates, they win a trip together _ and, seduced by
the idea of a free $6,000 cruise, he contacted a female friend he
knew liked him, helped the show wrangle a couple of ringers to
appear alongside him and went to the taping.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made me lie about things, they made me say I was a
Playgirl model,'' Emmons says. ``Crush'' executive producer Barry
Poznick says that the woman offered that information in a story she
told about seeing revealing photos at his home.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the show, Emmons says, the show's producers
convinced her to reject him. ``She told them, 'Yeah, I want to go
with Jesse,' and they were all, 'Well, no. You can still have the
trip, but we want you to say you don't want to go with him.' And
she put up a fight ... And they said, 'No, no, no, it's OK, we do
this all the time. For TV purposes, it'll be better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So she comes out and holds up the card reading, 'Just be
friends.' And I'm like, 'What?' I can't believe it. The host pats
me on the shoulder, like a concerned guy, and says, 'Maybe it's
better this way.' And I said, 'Dude, (expletive) you!' I knew it
was utter bulls---. She comes up to me afterwards: 'Jesse, they
made me say that.' The main producer was my best friend all day,
and the second the show was done, she knew I was pissed; she
split.''
</P>
<P>
   Poznick allows, ``We do tell everyone, don't make a rash
decision just because it's on TV. She specifically said, 'I don't
know if I want to become lovers.' We said, 'If your answer is not
yes, don't say yes.' He insists, however, that the show was not
manipulated in any way.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Robert Young Pelton, who travels to war zones, films the
people living there and places the stories in their political
context _ his work was shown on the Travel Channel on ``The World's
Most Dangerous Places'' _ once pitched his show to the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had footage from Liberia of a street fight where a guy
actually takes a machete and cuts this guy's head off,'' Pelton
recalls. ``It's very disgusting, and there was footage of people
playing football with heads. I played this stuff for him. Most
people's reactions are, 'I can't watch this stuff'; you can see
their face tighten. His was, 'That's nice, that's nice, you go
places, but what I need is this.' The thing I felt disgusted about
was we were discussing the merchandising of death, and he was
telling me what he wanted. He wanted tourist snuff movies.''
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!The Associated Press reported that in a Swedish version of
``Survivor'' three years ago, a contestant voted off the island
committed suicide a month after returning home. Series executives
denied any responsibility, but the man's widow claimed that after
getting ousted from the island, her husband returned home ``deeply
depressed and agonized.''
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Of course, the most famous instance of reality chicanery
was Fox's lambasted ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' A
thorough background check of Rick Rockwell was done _ not by Fox,
but by an Internet site that discovered Rockwell had had a
restraining order filed against him. The marriage was annulled
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Even prim and proper PBS juiced the ball, reality-wise,
with its series ``Antiques Roadshow,'' when it admitted that some
of the alleged ``attic discoveries'' worth small fortunes were, in
fact, staged.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Thompson points out, ``This sleazy genre, this ultimate
fall of the medium _ began with PBS in the 1970s with `An American
Family' (a documentary assiduously following the life of one family
through trials and triumphs). It was salacious and voyeuristic, but
we got the sense that it was a classy sociological experience. It
was less bogus than 'Real World' and 'Big Brother' and these other
things, which are just chemistry experiments. Soon, we're gonna
look back at 'Real World' as the classy, early period.''
</P>
<P>
   PBS has another reality series coming in June, ``The 1900
House,'' in which a family agrees to live using only
turn-of-the-century amenities. It became difficult at times, but in
surprising ways _ Joyce Bowler, the mother and wife of the family,
was upset that the soaps of the era ruined her hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little different from those other shows _ this is
'The Real World' meets real history,'' Hoppe says. ``What you get
is new understanding of technology, how far we've come. This series
debunks the myth of a simpler life. People have come to believe
that before technology made us speed around everywhere, life was
simpler. What happens is, the Bowlers realize it was simpler, but
it was dirty, and it was unbelievably hard work, especially for
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoppe says that the Bowler family was chosen in part due to
their reticence to be on TV, but with most of these shows, the fame
that comes with television is the overriding motivation, regardless
of how difficult the experience may become.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real sense that you aren't fully manifest until you
have been turned into 575 lines of dots sent throughout the
universe,'' Thompson observes. ``Our culture is obsessed with
celebrity. For most of these people, being on TV, in and of itself,
is reward enough, even if no residual rewards or fame come from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson points out that despite intense media attention,
``it's a small percentage of the population who are willing to do
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it is catering to a base part of the human spirit,
this is not even in the top-500 things threatening America today,''
Thompson concludes. ``We watch 'Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire' because we enjoying the pleasure of watching our
jaw drop further than it has before. It's a freak show, there's a
surrealistic bizarreness about it, but we had fun with it. It's
harmless in its current manifestation. People know better than to
take this stuff seriously. The people most threatened by this are
those who go on these things. Them, and the networks that are sued
when the morning-after story of the day comes out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
