<HEADLINE>
DR. ALEXANDER S. NADAS, PIONEER IN PEDIATRIC CARDIOLOGY; AT 86 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Alexander S. Nadas, a ``founding father of pediatric
cardiology,'' died in his sleep Tuesday in his home in Needham,
Mass. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nadas was the author of ``Pediatric Cardiology,'' which was
the first text on the subject when it was published in 1957. He was
chairman of the department of cardiology at Children's Hospital in
Boston from 1949 until his retirement in 1982 and trained hundreds
of doctors as a professor of pediatrics at Harvard Medical School
from 1969 to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, when a professorship was named in his honor at
Children's Hospital and Harvard Medical School, he was described in
the Children's Hospital newsletter as a man who ``created a legacy
of patient care, research and teaching that established him as a
founding father and innovative practitioner of pediatric
cardiology.''
</P>
<P>
   David S. Weiner, the president of Children's Hospital, described
him as a man who ``combined intellect, clinical skill and humor to
benefit the entire hospital family and the hundreds of children in
his care.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nadas was born in Budapest and graduated from the University
of Budapest. In 1938, at age 25, with World War II approaching, he
immigrated to the United States and completed his training at
Children's Hospital and Wayne State University Medical School in
Detroit. After four years in private practice in Greenfield, Mass.,
he joined the staff at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A former president of the American Pediatric Society, he was a
Guggenheim Fellow and a member of the editorial boards of the
American Journal of Cardiology and The Yearbook of Cardiology.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two daughters, Trudy Murch of Phoenix and Betsy
Seamans of Pittsburgh; a son, John of Wellesley, Mass.; and three
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
