<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MULTITASKING-FALLACY-     05-19 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULTITASKING-FALLACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUGGLING TOO MUCH MEANS DROPPING THE BALL, SCIENTISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desperate to squeeze a 25th hour out of each day, busy Americans
clamor for new ways to save time. In a society where talking on the
cell phone while driving is so common, can minivans with washers
and driers in the backseat be far behind? How about dinner
placemats that display e-mail messages?
</P>
<P>
   As slaves to tyrannical to-do lists, people juggle many things
at once in the hope that they'll do them all fast and do them all
equally well. But scientists who study the brain increasingly they
can't.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, studies show that trying to do two or more mentally
demanding tasks, such as carrying on two conversations at once, may
actually be self-defeating, burning up more total brain power than
if they did them one at a time. And studies show people are
becoming less happy and more error-prone in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, say neuroscientists, ``Chill out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are absolute limits to what we can do simultaneously,''
said Marcel Just, co-director of the Center for Cognitive Brain
Imaging at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, Pa. ``It's a
question of sheer biological resources.''
</P>
<P>
   From university centers to federal aviation labs, recent studies
show that people can juggle a fair number of tasks _ and even get
better at this by picking what balls they toss in the air. But
often, dividing their attention makes them exhausted, stressed and
more forgetful.
</P>
<P>
   For example, pilots who juggle excessive amounts of information
have faster heart rates, higher blood pressure and slower reaction
times to new events, according to research at the Air Force and
Federal Aviation Administration labs.
</P>
<P>
   There's no magic number on how many tasks humans can juggle.
Scientists say it varies widely depending on the intensity of the
tasks, how experienced people are at doing them, age (the brain's
juggling ability peaks around 30) and whether they are particularly
gifted at handling many things at once.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many researchers say tackling two difficult tasks at
once, such as balancing the checkbook while taking part in a work
conference call, can put many people into cerebral overload.
</P>
<P>
   Juggling becomes even more difficult if one of the tasks is new
or complex, like driving in a rental car in a foreign land. Brain
scans show that certain parts of the brain require more blood when
tackling a hard task or two jobs at once. No wonder it's all so
exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brain gets fried,'' said Ann Fitzgerald, 37, a mother and
part-time medical accountant who juggles working at home, watching
a baby, doing laundry and starting dinner. ``I'm frazzled. I don't
know which end is up.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to keep track of different tasks _ often referred to as
multi-tasking, a term that began when computers did more than one
thing at a time _ also affects the ability to remember in the
long-run what we've just read or said, according to Harvard
psychology professor Daniel Schacter.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some people can read a book while keeping track of
a TV program. But there's a good chance what's read will be deleted
from long-term memory, which means people may forget it a few days
later, or even the next day. Reading the book only once actually
makes for more sticking power.
</P>
<P>
   There are no reports of task-jugglers blowing neurological
fuses, but there is such a thing as using up so much mental
resources, it affects the ability to react to a surprise, such as
noticing a toddler opening the medicine cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can push yourself to the limit and get away with it,''
said Glenn Wilson, a US Air Force senior research psychologist.
``But the problem comes when you introduce something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are using special magnetic resonance imaging to
locate what brain cells light up when humans split their attention
between two tasks. The lit-up areas appear to focus in the
prefrontal cortex, the area directly behind the forehead and the
part responsible for high intellectual thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Within the prefrontal cortex, scientists have fine-tuned the
neurological map even more. They can point to the areas that are
responsible for keeping track of competing tasks rather than simply
prioritizing them. This detailed map will help researchers better
understand the effects of brain damage and aging. It may even help
in creating novel treatments for attention-deficit disorder, a
condition in which the victim has difficulty focusing on any one
task, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   A recent federal study found that people use very different
parts of their brain when switching between simple tasks, such as
deleting a series of e-mails while placing stamps on envelopes,
compared to demanding tasks, such as talking on the telephone while
also following a recipe to bake a cake.
</P>
<P>
   The more intense kind of juggling act forces people to use their
``working memory,'' a sort of mental bin in their prefrontal cortex
that enables people to keep track of where they left off while
attending to something else. This ``working memory'' is a more
energy-intensive use of the brain, making it more draining than
juggling simple chores, said Jordan Grafman, chief of the cognitive
neuroscience section at the National Institute of Neurological
Disorders and Stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Research also shows that it may be easier to juggle tasks that
are very different from each other, rather than similar ones that
draw on brain power from the same region. For instance, reading
while walking on a treadmill is less demanding than reading while
talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University researchers, Silvia A. Bunge and John
Gabrieli, found that when people juggled two verbal skills (one was
a set of true-false questions, the other was a word memory game),
their prefrontal cortex worked just as hard, if not harder, than
the combined effort of doing each task separately.
</P>
<P>
   This ``dual-tasking,'' as researchers call it, also caused them
to recall their learned information more slowly, and sometimes less
accurately, suggesting an overtaxing in one region of the brain,
according to this study in the March issue of the National Academy
of Sciences publication.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, University of Oklahoma researcher Mark Edward found
that people got more confused trying to remember a shopping list if
they were interrupted with questions about the list. If the
interruption was unrelated, however _ such as asking the person to
repeat some numbers _ people went back to their memorized list with
little problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When interrupted with something similar, it killed their
concentration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One way to help people handle more information is to appeal to
more of their senses. Federal Aviation Administration officials
said cockpit warning signals, for instance, don't have to be
strictly visual. Researchers are constantly experimenting with new
methods, such as warning bells (perhaps one that even relays in
digitized voice what the problem is) or vibrations on a stick-shift
device.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
