u s BC-CAR-INDY-FISHER-BOS &LR;      05-19 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-FISHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARA FISHER HAS A DRIVING AMBITION, AT 19 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Sarah Fisher is a self-reliant woman.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus, Ohio, native lives in her own apartment here with
her dog, Alby, and pays her own rent, bills, and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   She loves to work out, watch ``Friends'' and hockey games on TV,
listen to country and rock music, and drive her Mitsubishi Eclipse.
She lists her mother's fettuccini alfredo and Froot Loops as her
favorite foods.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher insists she is just like any other red-blooded,
19-year-old, American girl.
</P>
<P>
   But when you ask her what she does for a living, you realize she
isn't. After all, how many girls strap themselves into the cockpit
of an open-wheel Indy car and mix it up with male competitors twice
their age?
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, a rookie driver in the Indy Racing League, elicits
skeptical reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reaction? Well, a lot of people are surprised and they
laugh,'' said Fisher, a 1999 honors graduate of Teays High in
Commercial Point, Ohio, who plans to study mechanical engineering
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know if they believe me at first because when
they look at me, they see two things _ I look like I just got my
driver's license and I'm a girl. So, it's a bit of laughter, but I
think once people get to know me and once they read about me, they
know that I'm taking this seriously, and it's definitely not just a
media stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher will no doubt grab a few headlines _ and turn a few heads
_ if she qualifies for the 84th running of the Indianapolis 500
when time trials are held this weekend at the Brickyard. If she
makes the 33-car field, Fisher would become the youngest woman _
and third-youngest driver, male or female _ to compete in the
Greatest Spectacle in Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sarah has a lot of potential,'' said car owner Derrick
Walker, who is fielding cars for Fisher in the IRL series and
Japanese rookie driver Shinji Nakano on the CART circuit. ``She's
at the right age and she's got a good opportunity in being in the
IRL to learn her craft. She'd made a good step into open-wheel
racing in the IRL series, so there's a perfect opportunity to get
into the series and grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge, in part, is hers and ours because no race
driver is a race driver by themselves,'' he added. ``They have to
have the right mechanism around them to be able to do what they
need to do, and when you've got somebody Sarah's age, then there's
a lot of experience that they need to experience to actually build
their confidence and knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lyn St. James, 53, makes the race, then the oldest and
youngest drivers in this field will be women, marking yet another
Indy 500 first.
</P>
<P>
   St. James and Janet Guthrie paved the way for women to compete
at Indy. ``Well, as far as Lyn goes, I think, yes, she helped kick
the door open, but I want to blow it open,'' Fisher said. ``I want
to win and I think that's maybe a little bit different attitude
going about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win the Indy 500. That's my goal and, like I said, I
don't know if I can do it this year, but I'm certainly going to try
my hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is the daughter of kart racer Dave Fisher, who competed
against IRL drivers Scott Goodyear and Mark Dismore. He brought his
daughter and his wife, Reba, to many of his races. Sarah just
happened to be a byproduct of her parents' love of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my childhood goes . . . I've always been in an
open-wheel car and I just thought it demanded a lot of respect out
of the drivers,'' said Fisher, who started her career in
quarter-midget cars at age 5. ``You can't just take them in there
and knock someone out of the way, or you're going to go flipping
down the front stretch, and we don't do that here. I've always
admired that amount of respect in open-wheel racing.''
</P>
<P>
   While she won respect and admiration on the karting circuit,
where she was a three-time World Karting Association champion
(1991-92, '94), and on the sprint car circuit, where she came to
idolize World of Outlaws champion Steve Kinser, Fisher hasn't been
as warmly received on the IRL circuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the last IRL race at Las Vegas, Fisher was running second
when she spun out and hit the wall, collecting Eliseo Salazar's
car. He harshly criticized Fisher afterward, saying, ``She's way in
over her head, and she should go back to racing against little
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Salazar's comments landed only a glancing blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take criticism real well,'' she said. ``You know, they just
brought him out of the infield care center and he was a little
upset. He just crashed his car and I certainly didn't mean to spin
out in front of him, because it was going to tear up my equipment
as well. I was running second at the time and we were doing a
really good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it in a little deep (in the corner); I had cold tires
and I was in the marbles passing cars, so it all pointed to a spin
and it was a rookie mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, the other drivers that I've talked to are accepting of
what I'm doing here. They seem to be really happy that I'm here and
I'm happy that they think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of the inherent risks? The day before Fisher took the
track for the first time at Indianapolis Motor Speedway, Adam
Petty, her 19-year-old contemporary, was killed while practicing
for a Busch Series race at New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of accidents that have happened this year,''
said Fisher. ``I think (Geoffrey) Bodine in the truck looked 10
times worse than that. I just think that when it's time for you to
go, it's time for you to go and, as a race driver, you can't think
about that. It is certainly sad that happened to him at such a
young age because I think, like myself, he had a lot of potential,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year-old, Fisher said she dreamed of racing at Indy.
Now, all that stands between her and that goal is a four-lap,
10-mile sprint around the 2.5-mile oval. She knows it will take all
the guile, savvy, and resourcefulness she can muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been given a very unique opportunity, especially for my
age,'' Fisher said. ``It's something that you really can't put into
words, the opportunity that someone gives you to run the
Indianapolis 500. It's very unique and it's very rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is something that I've always wanted to
accomplish in my life and I'm finally here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
