<HEADLINE>
LUKAS BETTING ON ANOTHER ALSO-RAN IN THE PREAKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Last year, trainer D. Wayne Lukas came to Pimlico
with the Kentucky Derby winner. He had revived Charismatic _ who
twice ran for a $62,500 claiming tag _ and the bighearted horse won
the Preakness, before breaking down in the Belmont Stakes during
his attempt to win the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Lukas, who has won the Preakness five times, has just
another Derby also-ran for the 125th running of the second leg of
the Famed Triad. High Yield, who had won the Blue Grass at
Keeneland, finished 15th in the Run for the Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has been remarkably candid in discussing his charge's
surprising Derby flop. He doesn't usually admit failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought High Yield was good right before the Derby,'' said
Lukas. ``I don't have the answer. I wish I could tell you he had a
foot bruise, or a head cold. Anything. But I can't. I hate to beat
on the track surface; we beat that to death. He trained so well
over it. It serves no purpose for me to be a cheerleader for him.
He's working well here, but he was working well at Churchill, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say that I'm confident he'll run his race, but he
fooled me so badly in Kentucky. He had no tenderness at all after
the race, and we scoped him and found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield's energy is good, and he's sound and clean, Lukas
said. ``If you don't want to bet on the other horse (prohibitive
favorite Fusaichi Pegasus), you could do worse than to bet on mine.
If you watch him go around the barn, he's an absolute standout. No
horse in this race will look nearly as good, that I'm positive
of.''
</P>
<P>
   In defense of High Yield, who is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis
(who also owned Charismatic), Lukas said horses who run poorly at
Churchill Downs often reverse form at Pimlico. Three of the five
Preakness winners from 25 starters saddled by Lukas did not run
especially well in the Derby. Tank's Prospect, the 1985 Preakness
winner, was seventh in the Derby; Tabasco Cat, the 1994 winner, was
sixth; and Timber Country, who scored in 1995, ran third. Lukas's
first Preakness winner, Codex in 1980, did not run in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take solace from the way my own horses ran,'' said Lukas.
``Three of them had less than sterling credentials to win this
thing, but they came through. Pat (Day, who rides High Yield) took
a hold of him when he wasn't competitive in the Derby. He knew we
were going to the Preakness. He dropped six or seven spots in the
finish to save me some horse. Pat and Willie Shoemaker are the best
ever at giving a trainer something back.''
</P>
<P>
   The last three Derby winners, which include Silver Charm in 1997
and Real Quiet in '98, have also won the Preakness. Surprisingly,
none was favored at Pimlico. Silver Charm was 3-1, while Captain
Bodget (finished third) was 2-1; Real Quiet was 5-2, while Victory
Gallop (second) was 2-1; and Charismatic was 8-1, while Menifee
(second) was 2-1. That won't happen Saturday, as Fusaichi Pegasus,
touted as the next superhorse, is odds-on in the morning line, at
3-5, for the eight-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more than one horse in this race,'' said Lukas. ``I
respect Captain Steve and Red Bullet. And, I'm wondering a little
about Impeachment _ he may be just coming around. You don't beat
that one horse and be successful; you have to beat all seven of
them. If you try to beat that one horse, you'll beat yourself, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, the Derby winner enjoyed the perfect scenario. He
was a target at Churchill, too, because you guys made him such a
favorite. They had him trapped on the fence, then they let him off.
If they keep him in there, (trainer Bobby) Frankel's horse
(Aptitude, who finished second) might have won. I know Frankel was
ranting and raving about it after the race.''
</P>
<P>
   High Yield was beaten by 24 lengths in the Derby, and when asked
if three tough races in a row (High Yield won the Fountain of
Youth, then ran second to Hal's Hope in the Florida Derby, both at
Gulfstream, prior to the Blue Grass) might have knocked High Yield
out for the Derby, Lukas jumped at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be,'' he said with a laugh. ``I'll take all the excuses
I can, and that's as good as any.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
