<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-PARTIES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINE ART OF GIVING PARTIES TO SELL ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MASON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On half a dozen nights in the last two weeks,
tuxedoed men have whispered discreetly into telephones, and gavels
have rapped down in brightly lighted rooms where the earnest
business of the big spring art auctions was taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was wildly different, however, on Monday evening at
Christie's. Foam spewed from bubble machines suspended above the
building's canopy at Rockefeller Plaza, as 900 guests arrived for a
party called the Bubble Bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not a reference to any bubbles bursting on Wall
Street,'' said Jill Spalding, as she sidestepped a volley of
descending bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, to the astonishment of many longtime auctiongoers,
lights were dimmed and disco music was booming. Tom Finn, the DJ,
described his playlist as ``sexy, modern, with a combo of R&AMP;B,
ambient groove and acid jazz.'' In the crepuscular light, it was
virtually impossible to see the high-priced artworks, which were to
be sold the following evening, including the inspiration for the
bubble theme, ``Woman in a Tub,'' a 1988 sculpture by Jeff Koons.
(It went for $1.71 million.)
</P>
<P>
   In a second room, the only discernible source of light was the
spectral glow emanating from another Koons sculpture, consisting of
two vacuum cleaners mounted in a plexiglass box, garishly
illuminated by white fluorescent bulbs. While many seemed amused by
the nightclub atmosphere, others were aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horror,'' said Holly Solomon, the art dealer. ``It's so
dark, you can't even get picked up.''
</P>
<P>
   With Christie's, Sotheby's and now Phillips battling for
supremacy in the auction world, the crucial May sales of
Impressionist, modern and contemporary art produced weeks of record
prices. At Sotheby's, new highs were recorded for Mark Rothko,
Clyfford Still and Bruce Nauman, and at Christie's records were set
for 15 contemporary artists. Phillips, whose new owner, Bernard
Arnault, spent lavishly to get into the big-time-auctions game, was
embarrassed by the house's lackluster Impressionist and modern
sale, but it saved face with a successful contemporary sale,
including a record $552,500 for the cows-in-formaldehyde school of
Damien Hirst.
</P>
<P>
   The competition was not only in the sales rooms. It was equally
frenzied during the grueling round of brunches, cocktail parties
and dinners given by all three houses to promote the sales, which
this season left many art lovers reeling from social exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's alone held 16 promotional events between May 4 and May
16, including a populist Sunday brunch and an intimate boardroom
dinner to cultivate major donors to the Dia Center for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time when it's just crazy,'' Solomon said. Her
Monday night peregrinations included, besides the Bubble Bash, a
cocktail reception at Phillips' temporary headquarters in the
American Crafts Museum and a dinner for 250 guests afterward at
Asia de Cuba, where stalks of green bamboo sprouted roofward from a
buffet table, and waiters urged cosmopolitans upon arriving guests.
</P>
<P>
   The lavish socializing may seem a sideshow, but it is actually
crucial to how auction houses market themselves, by providing an
overlay of glamour and social standing to what is essentially a
highfalutin swap meet. Especially in New York, the
multimillion-dollar auction world dominated by Sotheby's and
Christie's has long offered the chance to join in the social swim
at a rarefied level. This is not serendipitous, but part of their
business missions. New-money buyers get to rub shoulders with
old-money sellers. The slightly tawdry business of liquidating
estates after death and divorce is given the cultural and social
gloss of the museum or art-gallery world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Client entertaining is a huge, important focus of our
business,'' said Andree Corroon, a spokeswoman for Christie's.
She's not fooling. Christie's has held approximately 450 social
events during the past year, Carroon said. During the same period,
Sotheby's held 528 parties at its newly expanded York Avenue
headquarters, including breakfasts, dinners, boardroom lunches and
teas, according to Mallory Andrews, senior vice president for event
marketing at Sotheby's. Neither house would reveal the cost of such
prodigious entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, long an also-ran behind the two other houses, declared
its desire to compete this season by paying handsomely for major
works to sell and by renovating the craft museum at a cost of $1.3
million. But no less did the once fusty British firm venture into
the world of heavyweight party-giving.
</P>
<P>
   To promote its Impressionist and modern sale, Phillips gave a
dinner for 120 on May 7 in association with the Society of Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, the charity committee with perhaps
the swellest social standing in town. In the two-story Magic Room
of the LVMH Tower, Sloan-Kettering supporters such as Pat Buckley,
Nan Kempner, Carroll Petrie and Julia and David Koch were served
roast lamb and plentiful Moet Chandon in a room decorated with 20
mandarin and oleander trees, to evoke ``Environs de Gardanne,'' a
Cezanne painting that brought $5.62 million in Phillips'
Impressionist sale.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Thompson, the chairman of Phillips, had lured his
dinner committee out of their townhouses and triplexes by donating
$200,000 to the cancer center.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rule, I never leave this place on weekends, and certainly
not on a Sunday night,'' Buckley said, referring to her Connecticut
house. ``But for $200,000? Certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' dinner at Asia de Cuba eight nights later to promote
its contemporary sale was an entirely different affair. The guest
list was a downtown, haute bohemian crowd, including Marlon
Richards, a son of Keith Richards; the models Karen Elson and
Michelle Behennah; the Schnabel sisters, Jacqueline and Stella; and
the artist Damian Loeb.
</P>
<P>
   The host for the evening was Jade Jagger, the formidably
beautiful 28-year-old daughter of Bianca and Mick. Phillips had
taken the remarkable step of flying Jagger and her boyfriend, Dan
Macmillan, a grandson of former Prime Minister Harold Macmillan,
from London on the Concorde for the evening. It also treated Jagger
to the sleeveless Christian Dior gown she wore, another of the
luxury brands in the portfolio of Arnault's LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   A demicelebrity in England, where she designs jewelry and is an
occasional fashion model, Jagger's connection to the high stakes
world of contemporary art auctions was somewhat tenuous. Among the
youthful revelers at her party, potential bidders for serious art
seemed few and far between. An exception was the fashion designer
Narciso Rodriguez, who bid successfully on Friday for a black and
white painting by Udomsak Krisanamis.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the parties, hardly anyone mentioned the ongoing
Justice Department investigation of price-fixing at Christie's and
Sotheby's. The scandal may have led to the resignation of Sotheby's
chairman and its chief executive, but you would never have known so
from the banter of party-goers. In fact, the taint now muddying
both houses' images may have added new impetus to their
party-giving departments to pour on the revelry. While the events
at Christie's _ traditionally the more conservative firm _ are
fewer in number than those of its chief rival, there are
considerably more than are held at the London-based company's King
Street headquarters.When Ed Dolman, the company's chief executive,
arrived from England a few years ago, he expressed bewilderment at
the number of parties at Christie's in New York, recalled one
Christie's executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what people expect, so we can't cut back, exactly,'' the
executive said, noting that officials at Christie's are keenly
aware of the gangbusters entertaining going on at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, if you're Bergdorf's, you always want to know what
Barney's is doing,'' said Andrews, who held event planning jobs at
both stores before bringing her skills to the terrain of auction
house entertaining. ``There's always a sense of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing that Christie's and Phillips had both hired DJs to
enliven their Monday night parties, several eyebrows were raised at
Sotheby's. ``We are not a discotheque,'' said Tobias Meyer,
Sotheby's worldwide head of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we know how to dance,'' added Lisa Paulson, his deputy in
the contemporary department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's froth,'' Tobias continued, rolling his eyes, ``and we try
to be serious. At the end of the day, art is a serious business.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
