</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-PARTIES-$ADV21-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: serious business.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With an eye to serious future business, Sotheby's was giving a
dinner that evening for 130 young guests invited by Serena Boardman
and Jane Lauder at its vast new museum-like 10th floor galleries,
where artworks including a Mark Rothko painting (later sold for
$14.3 million) were on display. Boardman and Lauder, young women
from socially powerful New York families, had compiled a guest list
that comprised a veritable Who's Who of young, affluent New York,
including a royal flush of Miller sisters, de Kwiatkowski siblings,
Eliza Reed, Rena Sindi and the ubiquitous contemporary art
consultant Kim Heirston.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the substantial heft of the combined bank accounts of
those in the room, however, few seemed likely candidates for major
bids at Sotheby's auction the following night, when Meyer brought
down the hammer on $46.1 million of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Ross, a senior vice president at Sotheby's for museum
services who also is chairman of the Young Collectors Council _ a
group of 12 socially active employees at the firm whose mission is
to cultivate future Sotheby's clients _ said that immediate sales
gratification was not a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Sotheby's expected its young guests to be major
bidders at the auction house's Wednesday night and Thursday morning
sales, Ross shook her head. ``It's about long-term cultivation,''
she said. ``We don't expect to see the results immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sotheby's, she noted, ``I don't have to prove purchasing
activity after every event. It's really about the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
