<SLUG> BC-DAWSON'S-PEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 PEEPING TOM IS ORDERED NOT TO WATCH `DAWSON'S CREEK' 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY E. TURNBULL   
 Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ As part of his punishment for peeping on
``Dawson's Creek'' actress Katie Holmes, a Charlotte man has been
ordered not to watch the popular television show or anything else
starring the actress.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Drury Medearis, 36, was reported to police by one of
Holmes' neighbors, who in February saw him standing outside her
Wilmington apartment, watching the actress through binoculars.
Holmes plays the role of Joey Potter on ``Dawson's Creek,'' a WB
network show filmed in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Medearis, who works for a Charlotte printing company, was
released on $2,000 bond on charges of secret peeping and
misdemeanor stalking. The stalking charge arose from a series of
letters Medearis sent to Holmes in which he detailed his daily
activities. The letters were not threatening, but more like
diaries, said Assistant District Attorney Mike DeSilva.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the court, psychologist and sex therapist John
Wheeler of Charlotte, who treated Medearis twice, wrote, ``It is my
impression that the incident in question was not motivated on his
part by a desire to do any physical harm or any harm at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The stalking charge was dropped. Medearis appeared Thursday in
New Hanover County District Court and pleaded guilty to peeping.
</P>
<P>
   Chief District Court Judge John Smith suspended a 45-day
sentence for Medearis, put him on supervised probation for two
years, assigned him 24 hours of community service and ordered him
to stay away from the actress no matter where she is.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also ordered that Medearis ``not attend or watch any
films/programs or movies'' featuring Holmes, unless his
psychologist determines that prohibition would be detrimental. The
judge's order also requires Medearis to continue receiving
psychological treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, the daughter of an Ohio lawyer, was not present for the
plea. A call to her publicist went unreturned.
</P>
<P>
   (Amy E. Turnbull writes for the Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
