<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-ASSESS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMBOLISM HOLDS BACK PEACE EFFORTS IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Just as a breakthrough in the long deadlock over
guerrilla disarmament is at hand, the Northern Ireland peace
process is falling back into the grip of politically charged
symbols, which have often been as divisive as firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionist leader, David Trimble, has postponed a
crucial meeting Saturday of his ruling council for a week. That is
to give him time to persuade the party to endorse an Irish
Republican Army offer to permit international inspections of its
secret arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Northern Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson, told the
BBC Friday that the importance of the vote could not be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice that the Ulster Unionists are going to make next
Saturday is going to determine the course of Northern Ireland
politics, its political stability and also its economic prosperity
for a generation to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fight for the heart and soul of the Ulster Unionists,
but the debate is now turning as much on issues like what flag
flies atop government buildings, what name the new police force
bears and what symbols end up on the officers' uniforms as much as
it is on weapons and secret armies.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble spent the past week trying to exact clarifications and
concessions on these points before announcing Thursday night that
he was postponing the ruling council vote. Prime Minister Tony
Blair's spokesman, Alastair Campbell, said: ``We have come to the
end of that process this week. We have set out the position in
terms of flags. We have, we believe, gone some way to meeting
concerns in terms of policing and names.''
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of IRA offer would speed the return of the
power-sharing home rule government in Belfast that was suspended in
February when the IRA failed to make expected moves on arms. But on
May 5, the IRA said it would permit the inspections of its arsenals
of weapons by international figures, would re-engage with an
international commission on disarmament and would ``completely and
verifiably put IRA arms beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days to come, Trimble will be lobbying his own party to
treat the IRA pledge as the long-sought promise of disarmament, and
to support him in his desire to return to government with the
party's Catholic rival, Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Refusal would deliver the two-year-old peace accord its most
serious setback and would likely end the leadership of Trimble, a
Nobel Peace Prize winner who is viewed as the only Protestant
politician able to turn the party from its rejectionist past.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are reforms dropping the name Royal Ulster Constabulary
for the province's police force and calling it instead the Police
Service of Northern Ireland, abandoning national insignias from the
caps and badges of officers and permitting officials of the
power-sharing administration to decide whether to fly the British
flag, the Irish flag or no flag at all above government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of emblems are freighted in Ulster where Protestant
communities mark their boundaries with red-white-and-blue painted
curbstones and Union Jacks, and Catholic neighborhoods hoist the
Irish tricolor and promote the wearing of the green.
</P>
<P>
   The most contested declarations of differences are the summer
parades of members of the militant Protestant Orange Order, who
march through resentful Catholic neighborhoods, sporting their
black bowler hats, white gloves and bright orange regalia. Seen as
acts of triumphalist defiance by Catholics, the marches commemorate
battles three centuries ago in which the Protestant King William
defeated the Catholic King James.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists, who are generally Protestant, are so called because
they believe in keeping Northern Ireland part of the United
Kingdom. Republicans, almost all of whom are Roman Catholics, want
to see Northern Ireland become closer to and eventually part of the
Irish republic to the south.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The conflict between the two ``traditions'' has grown over the
past three decades, causing more than 3,600 deaths and prompting
periodic and ultimately failed efforts at a settlement apportioning
power more fairly among the Protestant majority and Catholic
minority. The current accord, struck in April 1998, has raised the
greatest hope of a real resolution but putting it into effect has
encountered continual setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has long faced opposition from a significant hard-line
minority in his party who, in a stance known as ``no guns, no
government,'' insist on IRA disarmament as a condition for sharing
government with Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the IRA announcement, Trimble's persuasive
deputy, John Taylor, predicted the party would overwhelmingly
accept it. But last week he said the British government's
insistence on going through with the police name and badge changes
and its position on flags had cast the matter into doubt.
Unhappiness over the changes in symbols has for the moment turned
that minority into a majority, causing Trimble to delay the
reckoning. It is not known now whether Taylor himself will back his
leader next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble received support Friday from an unlikely source, Gerry
Adams, the Sinn Fein president. In unusually conciliatory language
Adams said, ``I fully understand why the unionist people are
suspicious and distrustful of republicans,'' and he added that he
would ``vehemently oppose any political arrangement that
discriminated against the unionist people.'' He appealed to ``the
rank and file of the UUP.'' to would work together with republicans
``as equals'' to achieve a better future for Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The comment prompted Ian Paisley, the firebrand preacher who is
the peace agreement's most vocal opponent, to say that Trimble had
now become ``the chief salesman of the IRA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
