<HEADER>
A0274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-EUROPE-25     05-19 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-EUROPE-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE AND EUROPEANS AGREE ON TERMS FOR BEIJING'S ENTRY TO WTO 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Chinese and European trade negotiators agreed
Friday on the terms of China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's trade commissioner, Pascal Lamy, toasted
China's foreign trade minister, Shi Guangsheng, over the deal at
the ministry's imposing headquarters in Beijing just hours after
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji had stepped in to help conclude the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Shi told reporters that the deal embodied ``the principle of
equality, friendship and mutual benefit'' between China and the
European Union. It clears the way for China's entry to the global
organization this year.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides scrambled to reach the agreement before the vote in
Washington next week on whether the United States will grant China
permanent normal trading status, abolishing what Beijing considers
a humiliating annual review of its worthiness as a trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   China's agreement with the Europeans is the last major step
before it can join the global body, which regulates trade between
most countries. Many people think that the deal will add momentum
to the Clinton administration's last-ditch effort to get the trade
legislation passed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States vowed to make China's trade status permanent
as part of its deal last year on the terms of China's entry into
the World Trade Organization. If Congress votes against the
permanent status, China is still expected to join but can then
exclude the United States from benefits it extends other countries
in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with the European Union over China's membership
terms had broken down three times this year as the Europeans sought
to push the Chinese beyond the concessions they had granted the
United States in a deal signed last year.
</P>
<P>
   WTO candidates must complete separate agreements with any member
country that asks, outlining the market-opening measures they will
make to join.
</P>
<P>
   After five fruitless days, the talks between China and the
Europeans seemed to be in danger of failing again as the Europeans
held out for control of some telecommunications networks. The union
had been seeking 51 percent ownership of cellular networks, while
China, under its deal with the United States, had agreed to allow
49 percent foreign investment in most telecommunication services
and 50 percent foreign ownership of value-added services, including
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Lamy and Shi continued late Thursday evening, and
the two men met again Friday morning before Zhu summoned Lamy to
China's walled leadership compound. In the end, the Europeans
abandoned their demands and accepted some expansion in the kinds of
telecommunications services covered by the agreement and some
acceleration in carrying out the new ownership rules, although
details were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Terms agreed to with any one trade organization member must be
extended to all members, and Chinese negotiators were under
pressure not to go beyond the wide-ranging concessions granted to
the United States at the end of two years of difficult negotiations
last year. Those concessions are already vilified by many Chinese
government officials, who say they will put China's struggling
industries at too great a disadvantage to powerful multinationals
eager to expand business here.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhu and other Chinese reformers want the trade organization
rules as a tool to force change in areas protected by domestic
political interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European Union believes that WTO can provide a boost for
the reform process, hence the extra special importance of this
successful conclusion of our agreement,'' Lamy said at the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-member European Union had been the largest of six
remaining trade organization members that had not yet concluded the
separate market-access agreements necessary for Beijing's
membership. Agreements with the remaining countries is expected to
be a formality, though Switzerland or Mexico could yet slow the
process with additional demands, diplomats warned.
</P>
<P>
   China has been trying to join the WTO or its predecessor, the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, since July 1986. And
despite Friday's agreement, it will take months more for China to
actually join the group. A trade organization working party must
first consolidate the agreements Beijing has signed with various
countries into a single document outlining the terms of its
membership, for instance. And China must provide the organization
with a clear accounting of its current trade rules together with a
schedule of when specific rules will change to comply with the
terms of membership.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the trade organization at its headquarters in
Geneva said it would probably take until October before the process
was completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
