<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PROFILE-BARSKY-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: NEIL BARSKY AND SCOTT SIPPRELLE OF MRG NUCLEUS
FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 21) 
 By ALEX BERENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would have been easy for Neil Barsky and Scott
Sipprelle to just join the crowd three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two men run a $120 million hedge fund, the MRG Nucleus fund,
from a modest office suite in Midtown Manhattan. They opened MRG
Nucleus in July 1998, a few months after striking out from Morgan
Stanley, where Barsky was a well-regarded casino industry analyst
and Sipprelle a top investment banker. By February, 19 months into
the fund's life, they found themselves stuck in the middle of the
pack in the hotly competitive hedge fund business.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds try to produce above-average investment returns
using tactics ranging from traditional stock-picking to complex
derivative and arbitrage plays. High minimum investments,
redemption restrictions and aggressive strategies make them
suitable mainly for more sophisticated and well-heeled investors.
</P>
<P>
   MRG concentrates on overlooked and undervalued newly public
companies, chosen eclectically without a particular sector bias. By
ordinary standards, its returns have been solid _ 63.5 percent from
inception through February, a 19-month stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But over the same period, the Nasdaq composite index rose 151
percent. And many hedge funds posted even stronger returns with the
help of aggressive leverage and heavy bets on technology _
techniques that Barsky and Sipprelle avoided. MRG fell further
behind the index in February, when the Nasdaq rose a scorching 19.2
percent, triple MRG's gain.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, with a return of 42 percent in 1999, MRG was not
exactly facing a wave of redemptions from investors angry at
missing the technology runup. Still, ``it's always difficult in the
investment business to underperform,'' Sipprelle said.
</P>
<P>
   So when the two managers sat down to draft their monthly letter
to investors after the February results came in, they felt
compelled to explain: ``We are not Luddites. We are huge believers
in the power of technology to accelerate the efficiency of
commerce, the productivity of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   What they did not believe in, they warned, was the market for
technology stocks, which they concluded had gone seriously haywire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not drunk from the Kool-Aid that has mesmerized the
market into thinking that `growth at any price' is a sound
investment strategy,'' they wrote. ``We are underweight technology
today, and expect to remain so as long as valuations stay at
current levels. We think the stock market is in the midst of a
dangerous game of `chicken' with tech stocks. We suspect it will
end badly; we don't know when.''
</P>
<P>
   They also spelled out a series of specific concerns, including
accelerating price declines in software and hardware, and the
explosion in initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one verity of the IPO market that has proved
itself over the years,'' they wrote, ``it is that when capital
becomes too available, a hot sector ends up gorging itself,
overinvesting, and ultimately lowering returns for the entire
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven weeks later, they look smart. The Nasdaq has fallen
almost a third from its early March high, but MRG is up 15 percent
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Barsky and Sipprelle say they try not to gloat, but they
acknowledge feeling pretty good. ``If you're building a long-term
business, you have to weigh the easy money against the
responsibility you have not to take outsize risk,'' Barsky said.
</P>
<P>
   What is MRG bullish on now? The fund is still staying away from
high-growth technology stocks, which mostly remain expensive by
traditional valuation measures even after their tumble over the
last two months. Instead, the managers prefer small-capitalization
companies that offer relatively strong growth on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Argosy Gaming, which runs midsize riverboat casinos and
hotels across the Midwest and South. Drawing on his years as an
analyst, Barsky keeps a close eye on the casino industry, which
fell into a painful slump from 1996 to late 1998 before turning
around last year. He expects the gains to continue, at least for
smaller operators like Argosy.
</P>
<P>
   Several macroeconomic trends are combining to invigorate the
industry, Barsky said. The long economic boom has given adults more
disposable income for gambling. It has also put local government
finances into surplus, making states where gambling remains illegal
less inclined to legalize it. With capacity constrained and demand
rising, companies that do have licenses are seeing profits rise.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many states where Argosy has boats have recently
relaxed regulations on their operation, allowing the company to cut
costs and increase profits. Illinois, for example, dropped a rule
that boats must actually cruise the rivers on which they float,
rather than remain permanently docked.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring out a one-time charge related to a debt financing,
Argosy's net income soared from $5.7 million, or 23 cents a share,
in 1998 to $41.7 million, or $1.44 a share, in 1999. Revenues grew
from $507 million to $595 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect continued growth this year and are forecasting
earnings of $1.73 a share, an estimate that has risen recently. Yet
Argosy closed on Friday at $16.50, less than 10 times expected 2000
earnings and barely five times the company's cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Argosy ``is so cheap it's not even funny,'' said Barsky, who
called the multiples ``inexplicably low.''
</P>
<P>
   At these prices, Argosy could be takeover bait for larger casino
operators like MGM Grand or the Mandalay Resort Group, which now
focus mainly on the Las Vegas Strip. The spread of Native
American-owned casinos in California threatens companies with big
investments in Las Vegas, making them ``feel some need to
diversify,'' Barsky said.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks Argosy, which has accumulated a large database of
gambler-customers and is among the strongest of the midsize
riverboat operators, makes an inviting target.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
