<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: COURT AND CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's conservative critics often condemn as undemocratic the
Supreme Court's power to hold legislative actions unconstitutional.
Former Judge Robert Bork has gone so far as to propose, in the name
of democracy, that all Supreme Court decisions be subject to
reversal by majority votes in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   This week's Supreme Court decision striking down part of the
Violence Against Women Act as beyond Congress' power over
interstate commerce puts those critics in something of an ironic
bind. Most of them probably disliked the act. But the court's 5-4
majority overrode a signal example of the democratic process: Years
of hearings and mountains of evidence showing that violence against
women is so pervasive in this country that it affects interstate
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   I think it was a close case. The provision struck down by the
court, allowing abused women to bring civil damage suits in federal
courts, was indeed at the edge of congressional power. On the other
hand, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist's opinion for the majority
was troubling in the way it substituted its appraisal for Congress'
careful effort to show the effect on national commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The really troubling part of the decision is the larger context.
In a series of cases in recent years the five-member majority of
this court has undertaken to cut back the power of Congress
vis-a-vis the states.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in half a century the majority has
second-guessed Congress' exercise of its commerce power. The same
majority, in its most extreme decisions, has held that Congress
cannot authorize damage suits against state institutions to enforce
federal wage-hour and other laws.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases the majority seemed to believe that it was
returning to a historic role of the Supreme Court in protecting the
states from federal power. But a masterly recent article in the
Columbia Law Review, by professor Larry D. Kramer of the New York
University Law School, shows that view of history to be a myth.
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, Kramer points out, the Supreme Court
repeatedly upheld such expansive federal legislation as the
establishment of the Bank of the United States. It took a broad
view of the federal power over commerce. Before the Civil War, the
court stepped in only once to protect state sovereignty. That was
in the ill-fated Dred Scott case.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as Kramer says, ``States do most of the governing in
this country.'' Their law covers most contracts, property, torts,
domestic relations, crime and so on. So despite the vast growth of
federal law, the states have held their own. They have done that,
mostly, not because of protection by the Supreme Court, but because
our political traditions and institutions work in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system may not be perfect,'' Kramer concludes, ``but its
costs are probably less than those likely to follow from aggressive
judicial intervention in politics. ... More than two centuries of
successful federalism without the aid of an aggressive judiciary
suggests that no such intercession is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical difficulties of trying to draw judicial lines on
what is ``interstate commerce'' are also great. The Supreme Court
tried that early in the 20th century, for example deciding that
mining was not ``commerce.'' That effort collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   If the violence against women case and other recent decisions
are part of a judicial effort to define categories of activity that
are beyond federal power, my guess is that it will not work. Our
economy and society are too dynamic to be confined in such abstract
terms.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not seem to me unwise to have the Supreme Court as
an ultimate protector of federalism. Politics, for example, has not
proved to be effective in keeping federal criminal law out of
traditional state areas. Paranoia about drugs and crime has led to
much unwise federalization of criminal law.
</P>
<P>
   For such reasons, professor Gerald Gunther of the Stanford Law
School took a benign view of the violence against women decision.
The court should have paid more heed, he said, to the record made
by Congress. But ``it was not a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   What would be a catastrophe is a headstrong majority pressing a
dubious historic vision to a serious clash with Congress, and with
reality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
