<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TREES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING THE FOREST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 21, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Englanders who want better protection of federal forest
lands should raise their voices at two rounds of public hearings on
the minimal improvements offered by the US Forest Service. It may
be the only chance to stiffen regulations that would leave up to 60
million acres vulnerable to logging and other activities, robbing
these natural assets of their unique character while adding little
to the overall supply of timber and forest products.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the Forest Service draft plan seems to provide
protection, but the realities of modern logging techniques rob it
of much of its force. The Forest Service proposes to ban roads in
60 million acres, about a third of the 190 million acres under its
control. But determined loggers can economically drag timber as
much as three miles on skids that need no roads.
</P>
<P>
   The remedy is to supplement the road ban with other restrictions
on logging itself and on the use of off-road vehicles, mining, and
other activities that threaten unique forested areas. In New
England much forest land is in private hands, but the 800,000 acres
of the White Mountain National Forest in New Hampshire and Maine
contain some of the most impressive old forest growth in the
Northeast, which is in need of additional protection.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service proposal is also flawed for failing to
include the Tongass Forest in southern Alaska, the last major
northern rain forest in the world and home to magnificent stands of
trees so far untouched by loggers but in danger of destructive
harvesting. While the Forest Service leaves open the possibility of
action in 2004, much damage can take place in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Interested parties can register their opinions at hearings to be
held May 23 in Concord, N.H., and the next day in Shelburne, N.H.
The limited Forest Service proposals have already spawned
objections from logging and other interests who argue they are too
repressive. The possibility that Forest Service leadership could
change following the November elections argues for firm action now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
