<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-KODAK-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KODAK IN TRANSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may be the quintessential company in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, Eastman Kodak has jettisoned the
legacies of failed diversification efforts, cut $1.2 billion in
overhead and embarked on a series of digital photography
initiatives intended to catapult the company into the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts laud Kodak's efforts to reshape itself. The
company, they say, has little choice but to wean itself off its
reliance on the silver halide print photography business, with its
high margins but flat long-term growth prospects, and embrace the
less profitable, though potentially larger, digital-imaging market.
</P>
<P>
   But given the lackluster results shareholders have endured, many
wonder if Kodak is really on the verge of such a transformation.
``They're doing a lot of things right,'' said B. Alex Henderson, an
analyst with Prudential Securities. ``But the company's digital
growth prospects are hardly spectacular, relative to other
companies'' engaged in other areas of the digital universe.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Kodak will not resemble a highflying dot-com anytime
soon. At $57.0625 a share, the stock trades at around 10 times the
$5.64 a share that analysts expect Kodak to earn this year. By
contrast, the multiple for the Internet hardware maker Cisco
Systems is about 100.
</P>
<P>
   The modest valuation suggests that investors still associate
Kodak stock with old-economy torpor. The shares are about where
they were in December 1997, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index has climbed nearly 50 percent since then. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, some tepid bulls say Kodak deserves some credit for the
substantial progress it has made. ``Kodak's problem has not been
execution,'' said Jonathan Rosenzweig, an analyst with Salomon
Smith Barney. The company, he said, has met or exceeded Wall
Street's earnings expectations for the last five quarters. He
expects the shares to reach $87.50 over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Rosenzweig said, ``the domestic film business won't
deteriorate as fast as most expect,'' and demand in emerging
markets, which accounts for about 25 percent of the company's film
sales, is expanding. Still, he acknowledged, ``Long term, the
overall film business looks flat.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Kodak's digital businesses to drive top-line growth,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Jack L. Kelly of Goldman, Sachs, thinks that the company's
investment is about to pay off. Though Kodak has not yet earned a
nickel on the $2.8 billion digital portfolio, which accounts for
about 20 percent of its $14.1 billion in 1999 revenue, digital
losses shrank to 24 cents a share in 1999, from 53 cents a year
earlier, and the business should turn a modest profit this year,
Kelly said. His 12-month price target is $80-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most analysts say Kodak must move beyond low-margin,
nonproprietary offerings like digital cameras and digitization
services to earn real money in this arena.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson of Prudential thinks the company's commercial ventures
_ particularly its online repository of scenes used as backdrops
for films and videos _ are promising. ``Kodak is uniquely qualified
to provide this kind of database engineering,'' he said. Despite
his bearish long-term outlook, he rates the stock ``accumulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also liked Kodak's recently announced plans to purge $1
billion from its $6 billion procurement budget by 2002, in part by
eliminating vendors who cannot achieve double-digit productivity
gains that can be passed along the supply chain and in part by
using the Internet as the primary procurement channel.
</P>
<P>
   Management is likely to expound on its digital strategy at a
June 14 meeting with analysts in New York. Most expect the new
chief executive, Daniel A. Carp, who replaced George M.C. Fischer
in January, to be more aggressive in raising the market's awareness
of the breadth of the company's e-commerce initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton M. Christensen, the Harvard Business School professor
who coined the term ``disruptive technology,'' for emerging
technology that threatens the status quo, said it applied to the
digital imaging arena. As for Kodak's understanding of the stakes,
he said, ``I think management gets it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
