<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SAFE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHDOGS FOR CHILD SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Memorial Day last year, organizers of a safety campaign
enlisted thousands of police agencies to spot people who were not
wearing seat belts or had not buckled up small children. This year,
the campaign is enlisting millions of drivers, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Bag and Seat Belt Safety Campaign has established a
toll-free line (1-800-764-5755) that people can call from May 22 to
May 29 if they see a child who is not properly buckled. If the
caller can give the license plate number and describe the vehicle,
the campaign will send a letter to the vehicle owner that says, in
part: ``There are laws in all 50 states that require children to be
buckled up. While the laws vary from state to state by what age and
size child they cover, the laws of physics are the same everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to remind you that it is extremely dangerous for
children to ride unbuckled in motor vehicles. You could have been
stopped by authorities and ticketed, resulting in a fine or points
on your license. If a crash had occurred, the child could have been
seriously injured or killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has access to the motor vehicle registration
records in 40 states, including Connecticut and New Jersey. (Laws
in New York and nine other states do not allow access.) The program
is to be announced Monday by the Transportation Department, but
letters later sent to motorists will specify that they are not from
a government agency, and that no government agency will be
notified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect a certain segment of the population that will not
like this,'' said Janet Goss, a spokeswoman for the campaign. But
many people will be eager to call: The campaign has surveyed adults
on their attitudes toward unbuckled babies and small children, and
``four-fifths of them think it's tantamount to child
endangerment.''
</P>
<P>
   People who complain about others who do not follow the law are
not butting in, she said. ``I can say, `I mind very much if you
smoke,''' Goss said. ``I should be able to say, `I mind very much
if you drive with kids unbuckled.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
