<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SHAHEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP FROM SHAHEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 21, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen surprised no one when she
revealed last week she will run for a third term. The question mark
is whether she will renew the pledge she made four years ago to
oppose any broad-based state taxes. That pledge has limited her
response to the biggest challenge her state has faced _ the 1997
state Supreme Court decision declaring unconstitutional its system
of financing schools through local property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after her announcement, there was another watershed
event in the state's politics: The Senate joined the House in
voting to repeal the state's death penalty. Shaheen, a supporter of
capital punishment, vetoed the bill Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, one initiated by the court and the other by the
Legislature, Shaheen has missed opportunities to step out front and
help move public opinion toward new approaches. Her reluctance to
break her tax pledge is understandable, but the promise _ first
made before the court ruling _ deserves rethinking. She should at
least make clear whether she will support a broad-based tax if an
analysis of tax alternatives by a blue-ribbon commission she
assembled points in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   When Shaheen was first elected in 1996, she seemed a good match
for a changing state and won the endorsement of this page. A
pragmatic Democrat, her winning issues were bread and butter ones _
reducing electricity rates and increasing the number of towns
offering kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, however, the court decision on school financing
changed the dynamics of New Hampshire politics. In a state that has
never had a sales or income tax, the ruling cried out for
leadership from the governor to devise a way to meet the schools'
needs. A fair, broad-based tax should at least be considered.
</P>
<P>
   But no such banner was raised by Shaheen, who stuck by her
antitax pledge and repeated it when she ran for reelection two
years ago. The state jury-rigged a statewide property tax that duns
rich towns for poor ones but still doesn't raise enough money.
Shaheen has chosen not to let her state be a leader on death
penalty repeal, but it is not too late for her to lead on the tax
issue. Dropping the pledge would be a start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
