<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHAT'S LOVE GOT TO DO WITH IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many moralists can dance on the head of a pin? The more the
merrier.
</P>
<P>
   On its way to Friday's touching climax, in which New York's
mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, was reborn as Jimmy Stewart's George
Bailey in ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' the Rudy-Judi-Donna-Cristyne
soap opera has offered many memorable sideshows: an aggrieved
wife's press conference outside a cardinal's wake, a rollicking new
Abe Hirschfeld campaign for senator, an eBay auction of a mayoral
galpal's high school yearbook. But none topped the spirited
tap-dancing of Clinton-bashers as they labored to draw fine
distinctions between White House and Gracie Mansion infidelities.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least his affair is the traditional Other Woman kind, as
would suit a conservative,'' wrote Danielle Crittenden in Slate.
According to Andrea Peyser of The New York Post, ``He didn't lie,
he didn't fudge, he didn't equivocate. . . . He spoke the truth, no
more, no less.'' According to a reader's message on lucianne.com,
``A separation shows dignity in light of a mistake. Hillary looks
like a whore for not leaving Bill.'' Peggy Noonan told National
Review Online that ``Rudy is normal compared to Clinton,'' and
praised the mayor in The Wall Street Journal for being ``ragged and
human'' and refraining from ``finger wagging.'' For Ann Coulter,
there's the Talmudic difference ``between a dirtbag, and a dirtbag
and a felon.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Hillary Trap,'' her new entry into the crowded
anti-Hillary book sweepstakes, Laura Ingraham faults the Clintons
for holding ``the modern view that moral values are relative.'' But
her tome had the misfortune to be published just as the Giuliani
marital meltdown confirmed that moral relativity is in the eye of
the beholder and is becoming an epidemic among conservatives, who
only last month put aside family-values absolutes to oppose the
reunion of Elian Gonzalez with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did many of the scolds who bemoaned the dreadful example
set by Monicagate for the American people's children make no
mention whatsoever of children in Judigate _ neither the American
people's nor the Giulianis' own. Those who accused Bill Clinton of
sliming the discarded women in his life gleefully trashed Donna
Hanover, either for her taste in off-Broadway stage roles or for
defying her husband. (``New Yorkers never really liked Donna
Hanover to begin with,'' opined Dick Morris, accusing her of
exploiting her marriage to advance her career.) Those who berated
Clinton for allegedly using Arkansas state troopers to further his
extracurricular sex life were mum about the NYPD honor guard at the
Rudy-Judi trysts in the Hamptons. Those who decried Vernon Jordan's
thwarted effort to secure Monica Lewinsky an entry-level job at
Revlon ignored the mayor's successful installation of Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas in a $150,000 taxpayer-subsidized job at the
city's tourism bureau.
</P>
<P>
   And some of those who ridiculed Mrs. Clinton for her theory that
a ``vast right-wing conspiracy'' had targeted her husband dropped
hints that a left-wing conspiracy set up Giuliani. Both Morris and
Robert Novak have gone on TV to float the notion that, as Novak
ominously intoned, Giuliani's marital problems ``may not'' be ``all
of his own doing,'' since ``bad things happen'' to ``people who go
up against the Clintons.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few conservatives resisted this moral-relativism
epidemic. Hours before the mayor's withdrawal, William Bennett
called him ``loutish'' and urged him not to run. Earlier and
gutsier was Maggie Gallagher in The New York Post, who took on the
``repulsive'' spin doctors in her own political camp: ``Suddenly,
adultery is nothing, and telling the truth about adultery makes you
a stand-up guy.'' Gallagher went so far as to say that Giuliani
``made Bill Clinton look good as a husband and father.''
</P>
<P>
   But I don't buy the argument that Giuliani is a total hypocrite.
Yes, his serial infidelities (according to Hanover's allegation)
would seem to contradict his endorsement of public-school displays
of the Ten Commandments, his zero tolerance of sex shops and his
policing of museums for salacious art. But is he really being
inconsistent when he humiliates his wife and his two school-age
children by informing them of his divorce plans by press conference
or by parading down Second Avenue with his ``very good friend'' for
the paparazzi? He has treated his own family with the exact same
compassion and sensitivity that he lavished upon the family of
Patrick Dorismond _ no hypocrisy there!
</P>
<P>
   I'd also posit that this whole soap opera is in some ways a
public service, for Giuliani, intentionally or not, helped uncloset
one of the most common traumas of modern America _ divorce. For it
is divorce, not adultery, that made this ``scandal'' novel. We have
become inured to infidelities in officialdom, especially among
Gingrich Republicans, but this is the first time most of us have
watched a political leader's adultery morph before our eyes into a
high-profile divorce, complete with male midlife crisis and
hovering lawyers, that played out in full view on television in
real time. For those of us who've been through divorce, there is
cathartic value in seeing that the high, mighty and normally
self-possessed can behave as childishly and be hurt as badly as the
rest of us at that tragic moment when a marriage dies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0316 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-N     05-19 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: marriage dies.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The good political news for Giuliani, should he run for governor
in '02, is the burgeoning size of this constituency. According to a
Rutgers study last year, divorce rates have risen 30 percent since
1970, the marriage rate has fallen faster, and only some 38 percent
of Americans who are married pronounce themselves very happy in
that state. (The figure was 53 percent 25 years ago.) Nearly 50
percent of all American marriages end in divorce. Yet divorce and
unhappy marriages are underrepresented as a phenomenon in
mainstream mass culture; it's easier to find homosexuality on
prime-time TV than it is to find divorce. This may be one reason
national audiences proved far more hungry than Hollywood expected
for a movie like ``American Beauty'' and a TV series like ``Once
and Again,'' a rare network drama centered on divorce. The
phenomenon of ``The Sopranos'' may be less fueled by its Mafioso
operatics than by its realistic presentation of the chilled
marriage of Tony and Carmela Soprano and its fallout on their
children. Not for nothing has the mayor declared it a personal
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But political punditry, especially on TV and in Washington,
seems completely clueless about the state of American marriage.
``New York is France,'' quipped George Stephanopoulos of ABC,
explaining why 81 percent of New Yorkers told pollsters that the
Giulianis' separation wasn't going to change their votes. But in
fact New York has the lowest divorce rate in the United States,
whereas in the Bible Belt divorce rates are so high that Oklahoma
has some counties where divorces outnumber marriages.
Stephanopoulos was one of many commentators who, in the immediate
aftermath of the Giulianis' dueling press conferences, fell victim
to the Sam Donaldson syndrome _ instantly asserting that domestic
mayhem effectively ``ended'' Giuliani's campaign, much as Donaldson
pronounced Clinton's presidency ``numbered in days'' after
Monicagate broke. These prognosticators, so fast to assume
widespread public condemnation of marital sinners, don't seem to
realize that, sadly, it's happy marriages, not broken ones, that
are increasingly the aberration where their viewers live.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, as Giuliani indicated Friday, it was solely the battle
against cancer, not that against his wife, that knocked him out of
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Of course some anti-Clinton moralists are now holding the
president accountable for the resiliency of Giuliani's post-Judi
poll numbers; under this theory, Monicagate lowered acceptable
standards for politicians' behavior. But the record shows that when
the mayor was reported by Vanity Fair to be involved with Lategano
in the summer of '97 _ a year before Monicagate _ the same polls
showed that 85 percent of voters didn't care then either.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the public has been corrupted, or is latently
Gallic, but that it has too often experienced marital heartbreak
firsthand. Anyone who has done so knows that only fools can presume
to judge what goes on in someone else's marriage. And they know as
well that it is difficult but possible to perform in a job, whether
in the public or private sector, even as a family breaks apart. For
millions of Americans, that's not a scandal _ it's just another
normal day at the office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
