<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DROPS OUT OF SENATORIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ citing concerns about
treatment for his prostate cancer and beleaguered by personal
scandal _ dropped out of the US Senate race Friday, ending what was
shaping up as the year's most dramatic political battle.
</P>
<P>
   His departure leaves the Democratic candidate, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, in an uncertain position. She looked tense, if not gloomy,
when she appeared at a union headquarters shortly after the mayor's
announcement, to wish him well.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Giuliani was the feistiest, best-known, and
most media-savvy opponent she could have faced. On the other hand,
he was, in many quarters, the most fiercely disliked.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton now will have to re-tool her campaign strategy, which
had placed great premium on attacking Giuliani for his abrasive
personality and an un-senatorial inability to get along with other
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll have to sell herself on who she is, not on who she
isn't,'' Democratic consultant George Arzt said. ``So far, she
hasn't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's Republican leaders are scurrying to come up with a
new candidate in time for their party convention on May 30. The
most likely choice seems to be Rick Lazio, a four-term congressman
from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a boyish 43, had threatened to run against Giuliani in a
primary last summer _ and raised $3.5 million for the contest _
until Governor George Pataki urged him to move out of Giuliani's
way.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has also been mentioned as a possible replacement, and
would likely be the strongest candidate; he is the only Republican
who leads Clinton in the polls. However, he has insisted the past
few weeks that he has no interest in leaving his job for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show Clinton with a wide lead over Lazio, but pollster
John Zogby said Friday, ``By next week, I think it will be tied. A
lot of Rudy's support was in fact more anti-Hillary than
pro-Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani leaves the race with a gracefulness that was
surprising, given the unpleasant circumstances of his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, he stunned the city by announcing that he had
prostate cancer. A few days later, he stunned everyone again by
confirming reports that he has been seeing a woman not his wife _
and, a few days after that, turned the shock-knob higher by
announcing he would seek a separation from his wife of 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after that declaration, his wife, actress and TV
anchorwoman Donna Hanover, fought back, appearing outside Gracie
Mansion and blaming the decline of their marriage on an affair that
she said the mayor had three years ago with yet another woman, his
former press secretary, Cristyne Lategano _ a charge that she and
the mayor have denied.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's newspapers reported that Hanover has retained one of
the city's most high-powered law firms to represent her in drawing
up a separation agreement from Giuliani. Many observers took this
as a clear signal that Hanover may have more shocks to deliver in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   However, Giuliani said Friday that his decision to leave the
race was based entirely on concerns about his health, not about the
other aspects of his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that what I should do is put my health first,'' he
told a packed room of reporters, aides, and political supporters in
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the right time for me to run for office,'' he went
on.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had been saying for weeks that he would decide what
kind of treatment to undergo _ surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation
pellets _ and then determine, from that, whether he would have the
stamina to go ahead with a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, he said he still had not decided on the treatment, but
had concluded he could not run an effective campaign, no matter
what his choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ran, I don't think that I'd concentrate the way I
should,'' he said. He also realized he could not predict how he
would feel in August or September, when the political race would
heat up. ``Nobody can tell you on a percentage-basis what the
side-effects are going to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani seemed shakened when he started to make his
announcement, but grew more comfortable, even buoyant, as the
half-hour news conference went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is not as important as I thought it was,'' the
once-singlemindedly political mayor declared. ``I've made a lot of
decisions the last 10 years around politics. From now on, I'm going
to make them around other things.''
</P>
<P>
   He even called the decision to withdraw ``probably the most
useful thing that happened to me, to get me reoriented to what's
important in life _ I think something good's going to come out of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he started talking in a way that nobody has heard, at least
publicly, for years.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that leaving the Senate race gives him an additional 18
months to be mayor _ his term runs out at the end of 2001 _ and
that he realizes certain people feel they have been left out of the
city's good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to devote the extra time I've been given,'' he said,
``to overcome some of the barriers that maybe I've placed.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark was clearly a reference to the deep distrust and
alienation that many black and Hispanic New Yorkers feel toward the
mayor, especially since the police shootings of black immigrants
Amadou Diallo and Patrick Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a rare thing for Giuliani to admit that he might be
responsible for the divide.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had expressed nearly identical sentiments in his
victory-night speech when he was reelected to a second term in
November 1997. However, Friday, he explicitly recalled that speech,
and said he regretted that he had not followed through.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be changes I have to make,'' he said. ``I want my
time as mayor to count for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, in a nationally televised town-hall meeting,
Giuliani had made similar overtures. For the first time ever, he
said he had ``made a mistake'' when he publicly attacked Dorismond,
a private security guard who was killed by police in a botched drug
sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have also conveyed the human feeling that I had _ of
compassion and loss for a mother,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This led newscaster Andrea Mitchell _ who interviewed him at the
meeting _ to speculate that there might be a ``new Giuliani''
emerging from his confrontation with his death. He laughed off the
phrase, and Friday called it ``silly,'' but he seemed to explore
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's something when you confront your limits, your
mortality,'' he said at the City Hall news conference. ``You
realize you're not Superman, you're just a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he had been leaning against running on Thursday,
but then leaned the other way during that night's wildly
well-received televised town-hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Gee, I don't know how I can walk away from this _
this is so exhilarating,' '' he recalled. ``Then I got home,
thought about it some more, talked with people some more, couldn't
get to sleep till the early hours of the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he woke up, he said, ``I thought, `There are more
important things in life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He made his final decision around noon, just after his weekly
radio call-in show, then called Gov. Pataki, Rep. Lazio, and other
Republicans and friends to notify them.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani leaves the race with $9 million remaining in his
campaign warchest. Federal laws prohibit him from turning it over
to another candidate, but he could give it to the party, which
could then distribute it. He said Friday he had not decided what to
do with the money, but he said he would do all he can to help his
replacement in the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
