<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIZZLY-RELOCATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WANTS TO IMPORT GRIZZLIES FROM CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Beginning next year, grizzly bears from
British Columbia could be following in the paw prints of wolves and
lynx as the latest Canadian import aimed at restoring predator
populations in the American West.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service wants to restore the
solitary, ferocious ursus horribilis to the vast Selway-Bitterroot
Wilderness Area of Idaho and Montana, where Lewis and Clark shot
grizzlies on their epic journey nearly 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadian conservationists are divided over whether it is
wise to remove grizzlies from the Kootenay region of southeast
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne McCrory, a grizzly bear biologist who serves on a
scientific advisory panel to the British Columbia government, likes
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, any grizzlies going to the United States would
have a lot more value put on their lives than bears do in British
Columbia right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCrory points out that Canada does not have an endangered
species act and cites widespread shooting of bears that have
allegedly menaced humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we blow away 90 to 100 `problem' bears a year, I have no
problem with sending 13 of them to the Bitterroots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Scott, director of Canadian programs for Defenders of
Wildlife, said it would be a bad idea. Scott noted that bear
populations in the Kootenays are already under pressure from
road-building, clearcut logging, mining, pipelines and powerlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extent of habitat loss in that area is extreme. We are
talking about some of the most endangered bears in all of North
America,'' Scott said. ``It's critical that we first have a
population count, a direct head count.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to release five grizzlies annually into remoter
parts of the Selway-Bitterroot country between next year and 2006.
An initial ``seeding'' stock of 25 bears _ half taken from British
Columbia, half from elsewhere in the United States _ should grow to
maximum of 280 grizzlies. The slow-breeding species could take a
half-century or more to reach this population level.
</P>
<P>
   The transplanting of species from Canada to the United States
has racked up at least one spectacular success.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 70 years after hunters and trappers exterminated canis
lupus from Yellowstone National Park, 14 wolves from Alberta were
released in 1995 by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and National
Park Service. An additional 17 wolves were let loose the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, they have multiplied to an estimated 160 wolves _
including one pack frequently seen by visitors to the Lamar Valley
in the northeast corner of the park.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 30 Canadian lynx from northern British Columbia and
the Yukon were set loose in the Colorado Rockies, another effort to
bring back a species that has become endangered in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious conservation activists in both the United States and
Canada have dreamed of going much further. They want to create an
unbroken wildlife corridor stretching 1,700 miles from the Yukon to
Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Y-to-Y'' corridor would require limiting such human
incursions as oil and gas exploration, and closing hundreds of
miles of logging roads.
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries ago, grizzly bears needed no corridors. An
estimated 50,000 grizzlies roamed the American West from the Great
Plains to the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, however, only about 1,000 survive in the United
States, outside of Alaska. Most are found in two pockets, one
centered on Yellowstone National Park and adjoining wilderness
areas, the other Montana's Glacier National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Selway-Bitterroot wilderness, stretching over more than 2
million acres in north-central Idaho and crossing the Continental
Divide into Montana, is historic grizzly habitat, but the last of
its grizzlies was shot by a hunter in the mid-1940s. Uninhabited by
people, with no major highways, it has been proclaimed by bear
biologists as ideal habitat for an animal that ranges over 30 to 50
square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Some Idaho politicians and ranchers in surrounding counties
aren't happy about the prospect of reintroducing grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   Custer County, Idaho, commissioners have passed a resolution
``authorizing'' the shooting of any grizzlies restored to the
region. The bears, however, are protected by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   One voice of opposition comes from a politician who has long
campaigned to save critical wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Former Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus has pointed out that the
grizzlies will need a food supply. Historically, the bears ate
salmon from tributary streams of the Snake River. Since
construction of four downstream dams, however, salmon have
virtually disappeared from even the wildest tributaries.
</P>
<P>
   With no more salmon, Andrus fears, grizzles will chase away
other predators like cougars and black bears, and then come out of
the wilderness to take cattle and sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans bent on restoration of species will be making a mistake
if they act with the same heavy hand as the exterminators did early
in this century,'' Andrus, who served as Interior Secretary in the
Carter administration, wrote in his 1998 memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   That view is disputed by Bruce McLellan, a bear biologist with
the British Columbia ministry of forests in Revelstoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Selway-Bitterroot isn't unique,'' McLellan said. ``Where I
live on the Columbia River, we used to have salmon. We have no more
salmon but we have many grizzly bears.''
</P>
<P>
   (The construction of Grand Coulee Dam in the 1930s shut off more
than 1,100 miles of salmon spawning habitat in the upper reaches of
the Columbia river system.)
</P>
<P>
   A Fish and Wildlife Service plan estimates that a fully
recovered bear population would kill about six cattle and 25 sheep
each year. Under the plan, ranchers in areas near the wilderness
could obtain a special permit to kill grizzlies that have attacked
their livestock.
</P>
<P>
   Even with hostile ranchers nearbly, grizzlies transplanted to
the Selway-Bitterroot likely would find a better chance of survival
than in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters shoot 25 to 35 grizzlies a year in southeast British
Columbia, far fewer than in the rest of the province.
Guide-outfitters have longstanding permits and quotas on the number
of bears their clients can shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect bears taken to the U.S. would be taken off that
kill,'' said McLellan. ``There would be some kind of a deal with
the hunting guides.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bergenske of the East Kootenay Environmental Society
confesses to ``a lot of reticence'' about removing grizzlies from
the mountains flanking his home in Skookumchuck.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however: ``It is preferable to have an exchange like
that than have them shot.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials worked out a deal to compensate trappers in the
Yukon when lynx were relocated to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are worries north of the border. By official
estimates, Canada has about 22,000 grizzlies, with 10,000 of the
bears living in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   But the official estimates are mainly just guesses. ``There's
been no direct population count,'' said Scott, of Defenders of
Wildlife. ``It's all anecdotal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears are becoming an economic asset, not just for guides who
hunt them. Visitors armed with cameras flock to the Khutzeymateen
River north of Price Rupert, British Columbia's first grizzly
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Habitat Adventures, which takes people to view wildlife
around the world, recently began bear watching trips in the Dean
Channel near Bella Coola. ``It has really taken off. It is
unbelievable how many grizzlies there are in this area,'' said Ben
Bressler, the company's director.
</P>
<P>
   But British Columbia has done little to protect its bears.
Between 300 and 400 grizzlies are shot legally each year throughout
the province, by hunters and by wildlife agents dispatching
``problem'' bears. According to McCrory, studies have shown that at
least an equal number of bears are killed illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Under such circumstances, McCrory is quite willing to see a few
grizzlies taken to the Selway-Bitterroot. ``You'll take care of
them down there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
