<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0327 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BRAZIL-SUGAR-ART-2TAK     05-19 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SUGAR-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE AND PAIN CLASH IN BRAZIL'S SUGAR INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 21)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SIMON ROMERO    
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SERTAOZINHO, Brazil _ If there is any place that captures the
quiet desperation of Brazil's sugar industry, it is probably the
Bar do Gaucho, an open-air drinking establishment in this gritty
town surrounded by seemingly endless fields of green sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Antonio Carlos Castilho, the owner, serves up
shots of cachaca, the potent yet dirt-cheap rum derived from sugar;
the drink is favored by the cane cutters who wander in to idle away
the day or shoot billiards on a raggedy table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar cane teaches you to love anything else that is not sugar
cane,'' Castilho, 43, himself a former cane cutter, mused one
afternoon. ``Run from cutting cane any way you can, because it is
the surest way of being a slave without even knowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a century since Brazil, the world's
largest sugar producer, prohibited slavery, although sugar has
played an important role in Brazil's economy for nearly five
centuries, since shortly after the Portuguese established a
foothold in the New World. The harvest can still be brutal,
depending to considerable measure on a sinewy arm swinging a big
knife at the base of a cane stalk.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, the sugar industry has witnessed unprecedented
change during the last few years. Indeed, the country's
modernization _ the shift in power from an entrenched provincial
oligarchy to a sophisticated urban elite, the swap of
low-technology economic practices for high-technology tools and the
discarding of isolationism for greater integration with a global
economy _ has been played out with fervor in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar workers like Miguel de Oliveira, who is 59 but has the
leathery skin of a man a decade older, know this well. ``It has
been good fortune to have lived this long doing such work,''
Oliveira said outside his home near the Bar do Gaucho as he showed
visitors his facao, the arm-sized knife used to harvest sugar cane.
``The smell of burning cane that makes your body sweat before the
heat reaches you, that is the smell of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is likely that Oliveira's grandchildren will never know
what cutting sugar cane is like. In the sugar plantations
surrounding Sertaozinho in this fertile region of southeastern
Brazil, harvesting machines are fast replacing people.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, as the share of the crop harvested
mechanically rose to more than 50 percent on many sugar cane
plantations, the number of people working in Brazil's sugar
industry has declined to 700,000, from 1.2 million, according to
the National Confederation of Agricultural Workers in Brasilia.
</P>
<P>
   The trend shows few signs of letting up as mechanization moves
forward. Understandably, growing joblessness in the sugar industry
is heightening social tension in Brazil's countryside and in the
small cities that serve as hubs for the agricultural industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what these people will do, if they are desperate and
out of work?,'' asked Ceres Oliveira Bueno Abe, a retired
schoolteacher who lives in Piracicaba, a city surrounded by sugar
cane plantations in the interior of the state of Sao Paulo. ``Who
can blame them if they resort to crime to feed their families?''
</P>
<P>
   While many out-of-work cane cutters are expected to migrate to
the gritty peripheries of large cities like Sao Paulo or Recife, in
the country's northeast, just as other hard-pressed farmhands and
their families have done during the last several decades, others do
not see that as a viable choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My existence is here and I'm doing everything I can to make
sure I am not dependent on sugar cane,'' said Julio Faria, 24, a
regular at the Bar do Gaucho who has secured work as a painter at a
nearby metals factory to supplement his income as a part-time cane
cutter.
</P>
<P>
   These grim long-term prospects stand in contrast to the
improvement in the lot of large numbers of cane cutters and
millions of other low-skilled laborers in Brazil in recent years.
Indeed, some argue that rural workers' economic gains have fueled
the drive to mechanize agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   According to union statistics, the base salary for sugar workers
in the southern region of the country has risen in recent years,
above the monthly minimum wage of $85, to about $122 a month, while
in the poorer northeast the base salary is about $100 a month. Much
of the advance resulted from the growing clout of rural unions.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of sugar workers are hired under labor
legislation giving them benefits like limited unemployment
insurance and the chance to retire with a small government pension.
The number is up from less than 50 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Working conditions have also improved. In Sao Paulo state, for
example, authorities moved to prohibit the burning of sugar cane.
Although burning makes it easier to harvest cane by hand, because
much of the stalk is removed, it is also dangerous because of
potential harm to the lungs of cane cutters and the chance that
winds could cause field fires to go out of control, burning cutters
to death. ``It is inhuman and absurd to think that a modern
democracy could permit such a practice,'' said Alceu Arruda Veiga
Filho, the director of Sao Paulo's Institute of Agricultural
Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Such victories for the sugar workers have inspired other
low-income workers, like maids and other agricultural laborers, who
have sued to get their employers to grant them some benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In the sugar workers' case, though, the advances are deceptive,
because the growing expense of hiring laborers has led many growers
to replace people with machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the dilemma of Brazil,'' said Guilherme Pedro Neto, a
director of the National Confederation of Agricultural Workers.
``The poor win concessions but are no better off than before, and
probably worse. It is like we're winning battle after battle, but
losing the war.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
