<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-STORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA PLANS SHOOTING-SPORTS STORE IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Even for New Yorkers, it's an in-your-face
move: the National Rifle Association has chosen Times Square, the
center of a city with one of the nation's strictest gun-control
laws, as the site of a new gun sports store, complete with a
virtual shooting range.
</P>
<P>
   The megastore, to be called the NRASports Blast, will offer
``family'' entertainment in the form of simulated target shooting,
along with the sale of sport-shooting paraphernalia, NRA executive
vice president Wayne LaPierre announced at the opening ceremonies
of the groups' national convention Friday. Guns will not be sold at
the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want NRASports to be a world-class shooting sports venue,
right in the Big Apple,'' LaPierre said. ``Sport shooting is an
Olympic sport. What better place (than New York) to enable more
people to get involved in shooting?''
</P>
<P>
   The gesture demonstrates that in the wake of the Million Mom
March, Smith &AMP; Wesson's recent agreement to push for safer guns,
and the Clinton administration's aggressive campaign for tighter
gun laws, the NRA isn't retreating.
</P>
<P>
   The group's membership is increasing, with LaPierre estimating
it will reach 4 million by election day. And the NRA also is trying
to expand its appeal to women and youngsters _ a target audience of
the sport-shooting store planned for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates were dumbstruck by the plan. Although the
crime and murder rates have declined sharply in recent years, New
York City still had 667 murders last year, and the city severely
restricts gun ownership and carrying privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, we thought it was a joke,'' Kim Mariani, spokeswoman
for Washington, D.C.-based Handgun Control Inc., said the NRA
store. ``The last thing that the people of New York want is the
glorification of the gun culture, after they worked so hard to cut
crime through strict gun laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Josh Sugarman, executive director of the Violence Policy
Center: ``What will their sign say, `Over a Million Killed?' It
will quickly become a protest Mecca in the wake of the high-profile
shootings that now define our nation, each of which will be laid at
the NRA's doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also chagrined by the announcement. ``It's a
strange message to be sending in a city that's done its best to get
violent crime and gun crime under control,'' said White House
spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA store, modeled after the ESPN Sports Zone in Times
Square, will not offer live-ammunition target shooting, instead
featuring ``virtual'' sport shooting games, said NRA spokesman Bill
Powers. The designs of the store and the games are still being
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The store will be operated by a new division called NRA Sports,
and may involve ``co-branding'' of products with manufacturers of
sports shooting materials, LaPierre said. Neither he nor Powers
would put a price tag on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The group is ``still in negotiations'' over a lease for the
store, LaPierre said. Assuming the theme shop is successful, the
NRA intends to open similar stores in cities around the country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA also released a video spot promoting the new store, in
which LaPierre is seen standing on a busy Manhattan street
extolling the pleasures of shooting. ``It's fun for the whole
family,'' the NRA chief says in the video.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, famous for targeting political candidates unfriendly to
its pro-gun rights agenda, has itself become the target of a heavy
gun control campaign by the White House and other supporters of gun
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In travels across the country, President Clinton has pounded the
NRA for its refusal to accept limits on gun ownership, and demands
for mandatory safety latches on weapons. More than 200,000 people
participated in last Sunday's Million Mom March for stronger gun
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development last month
wrought an agreement from Springfield, Mass.-based Smith &AMP; Wesson
company, which said it would put safety latches on all new guns it
produced, and develop ``smart gun'' technology to ensure only
authorized people can fire a particular gun.
</P>
<P>
   Under threat of a potentially costly lawsuit, the company also
agreed not to sell guns at gun shows unless a backgroud check is
done on the would-be purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   But Powers insisted the decision to promote the NRA as a sports
organization was not part of an image-burnishing strategy. ``We are
mainstream,'' he said. ``And I think they're mainstream in New York
City more than elected politicians would like to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Chosing New York City was a marketing decision, not a political
move, LaPierre said. ``If you look at Times Square, it realy is the
mega-marketing center of the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NRA members wandering among the booths at the first day of the
groups' three-day convention greeted the idea with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we'd go there,'' said New Jersey State Trooper Nelson
Prus, Jr., 37, after he finished playing a video duck-shooting
game, complete with animated blood splatters to mark a downed duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people in New York, and the more people we
get our message out to, the better,'' he said. Prus said he shoots
targets and hunts, and is teaching his 4-year-old and 6-year-old
sons to shoot targets in their backyard. All are life members of
the NRA, he said.
</P>
<P>
   New York ``is the best place to have it,'' added Michael
Shrewsbury, 38, as he, his wife and two children browsed among the
guns displayed at the massive Charlotte Convention Center hall.
``The ones who are most strongly against it are the ones who need
to learn more about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sport shooting draws 30 million enthusiasts annually, LaPierre
said, making it among the most popular sports. The
Connecticut-based National Shooting Sports Foundation estimates
that 15 million to 21 million Americans hunt every year. Hunting
and sport shooting spark $30 billion in economic activity every
year, according to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Sport shooting ``is probably about the safest activity Americans
can participate in as a hobby,'' LaPierre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
