<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0329 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BRAZIL-SUGAR-ART-$ADV     05-19 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SUGAR-ART-$ADV21-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SERTAOZINHO, Brazil: the war.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, sharp inequalities have defined Brazil and its sugar
industry for 500 years. In the 16th century Brazil became the
world's leading sugar producer, with much of the colonial
slave-owning society built around the workings of the sugar
plantations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, historians say sugar's dominant role helps explain why
slavery in Brazil was said to be more harsh than in many other New
World colonies, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar was a killing activity,'' said Stuart Schwartz, a
professor at Yale University who has written about the history of
Brazil's sugar industry. ``The mortality rate in sugar was higher
than in any other agricultural activity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-17th century, when the Caribbean colonies of European
powers began emerging as leading sugar producers, sugar began to
decline in importance in Brazil. Only in the 20th century did the
country re-emerge as the world's leading sugar producer.
</P>
<P>
   A program designed by the country's military dictatorship in the
1970s to drive development was responsible for an immense increase
in sugar output. Wary of high petroleum prices, the generals asked,
why not use sugar, so abundant in Brazil, to produce alcohol for
use as an automobile fuel?
</P>
<P>
   The program was a huge lift for the sugar industry. As recently
as a decade ago, 90 percent of Brazil's automobiles were powered by
fuel made from alcohol, when generous subsidies buoyed its
production. Sugar developed into an advanced industry, with
cultivation and processing integrated at various sites.
</P>
<P>
   At nearby Santa Elisa, for instance, a sugar plantation that
employs many residents of Sertaozinho, there are processing and
production facilities that resemble a futuristic petrochemical
complex. A stone's throw away are vast fields where sugar cane is
harvested by machines and by hand.
</P>
<P>
   But just as sugar grew in importance after the military
government encouraged alcohol production, the crop fell out of
favor when democratically elected leaders in the 1990s went about
dismantling the privileges enjoyed by the ``usineiros,'' as
Brazil's sugar barons are called.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and subtly, the government of President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, drawn from urban bankers, academics and foreign-educated
economists, went about slashing the subsidies enjoyed by the sugar
industry. In stages, elaborate financing programs and price support
systems were phased out, and producers were forced to cope with
free-market forces.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only 1 percent of Brazil's cars run on sugar-based fuel _
a change welcomed by many motorists. Alcohol was cheaper and said
to be cleaner-burning than regular gasoline, but it could be a
problem during the moderately cool winters in southern Brazil:
Alcohol-fueled cars often took a long time to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, most cars now run on gasoline, much of it from domestic
sources, a result of efforts to bolster production, mainly at
offshore drilling platforms. The country now produces nearly
three-fourths of its petroleum needs, up from less than half a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government has moved to liberalize parts of the
oil industry through the sale of concessions to foreign companies
seeking to drill at offshore sites. As market forces come to
dominate the country's fuel sector, the usineiros' prestige has
declined.
</P>
<P>
   To many Brazilians, the wealthy usineiros, who sent their
children to be educated at finishing schools in Europe while
migrants from the countryside swelled the slums surrounding the
large cities, have long been a symbol of the nation's social
inequality.
</P>
<P>
   In Pernambuco, a state in Brazil's northeast, a literary
movement originated by the novelist Jose Lins do Rego used the
contrast between the usineiros' wealth and the poverty of their
workers as a platform to discuss Brazil's ills.
</P>
<P>
   Today, leaders of the Landless Workers Movement contend that
stubbornness of the usineiros is a main reason that Brazil, unlike
other large Latin American countries such as Mexico, did not have
an effective land reform program until the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sugar industry was really despised for many years because
of the favoritism it enjoyed on the part of the state,'' said Tamas
Smrecsanyi, a professor at the University of Campinas. ``So it's
really no big deal for society to see them suffering a little in
having to adapt to new times.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that many usineiros are unhappy with the
changes of recent years. Maurilio Biagi Filho, the owner of Santa
Elisa, one of the country's largest sugar plantations, is among the
most vociferous critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the most fantastic soil in the world, the best
climate, everything really, and yet we're suffering,'' Biagi said
as he barreled over a dirt road on his plantation at 80 miles an
hour in his alcohol-powered Volkwagen sedan, one hand on the wheel,
the other motioning in the air. ``What do they want us to do, flood
the world market with sugar?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that is exactly what is happening. As the usineiros
wade their way through the free market, many of the 120
sugar-producing countries around the world that cannot effectively
subsidize or shield their sugar industries from foreign shocks are
increasingly concerned about the changes in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In what analysts have called the ``alcohol bomb,'' Brazil has
transferred sugar to export markets that was previously used to
produce alcohol. The price of raw sugar has plunged by 40 percent
during the last year, to about 6.3 cents a pound from 10 cents, as
international markets have struggled to absorb Brazil's rising
exports.
</P>
<P>
   During the last few years, the country's annual sugar production
has risen to 20 million tons, from 13 million, as wider use of
mechanization has both increased efficiency and cut costs. By
contrast, Cuba, another country with a large sugar industry,
produces 4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   The devaluation last year of the Brazilian currency, the real,
made the price of the country's sugar more competitive in foreign
markets. But the downward pressure on prices continues to mount,
with dampened demand in countries like Indonesia and Russia. so
Brazil's producers are enticed to export even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like watching a Greek tragedy unfold, witnessing today's
situation,'' said Tony Hannah, an analyst at the London-based
International Sugar Organization and co-author of ``The
International Sugar Trade.'' ``The bomb just keeps on exploding.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws here that still require small amounts of alcohol to be
added to gasoline have eased the situation a bit. But it is
difficult to discern whether the legal protections that produced
the alcohol industry will survive much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to fire my cutters,'' Biagi, the usineiro, said.
But he added that such layoffs are a growing trend ``and the
government needs to be prepared to help them find other jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a thinly veiled warning to the authorities, he said that
if growers were to use all of their cane to make sugar, they could
produce 40 million, doubling Brazil's production, an increase that
would have dire consequences for the world market. The government
must come to realize that possibility, Biagi said. ``I don't think
it does.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
