<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NRA-MEETING0520-COX     05-19 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-MEETING0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NRA plans to merchandise products
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ As it seeks to blunt rising outrage over guns
and youth violence, the National Rifle Association said Friday it
intends to appeal to the American mainstream by selling
NRA-emblazoned merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The showcase for NRASports, a firearms-themed brand of clothing,
camping gear and electronic shooting games, will be a store and
theme restaurant in New York City's Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA hopes the store, to be called NRASportsBlast, will draw
as big a following as such popular New York City outlets as the
World Wrestling Federation store or the ESPNZone.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came on the opening day of the NRA's annual
convention in Charlotte, where gun-control organizations rallied to
counter the NRA's patriotic show defending Americans'
constitutional right to own firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns can turn children and emotionally disturbed people into
criminals,'' said Lisa Price, executive director of North
Carolinians Against Gun Violence Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Sugarmann, executive director of the Washington, D.C.
-based Violence Policy Center, said the NRA's merchandising plans
``will go down in history as the worst marketing decision since New
Coke. What will their sign say: 'Over a Million Killed'?'' The
store, he said, would become a protest mecca.
</P>
<P>
   But the NRA, boasting of surging contributions and a record 3.6
million members, is spending this weekend mobilizing supporters for
the Nov. 7 presidential, congressional and local elections.
</P>
<P>
   NRA President Charlton Heston called this weekend's meeting the
most important in the organization's 129-year history because of
the crucial fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our gun rights of the 2nd Amendment are truly in peril,''
Heston said in a video message to Friday's opening session.
</P>
<P>
   The 75-year-old actor plans to arrive for today's session as he
seeks a third terms as NRA president.
</P>
<P>
   NRA officials presided over a grassroots organizing session
Friday during which members applauded one another's political
victories and booed whenever the names of ''anti-gunner''
congressmen were mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a need for God-fearing Americans to stand up, those
who believe in their constitutional freedoms . . . to be involved
directly with the political process,'' said Richard Jordan,
president of Christian Sportsmen's Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 45, pointed to the recent largest police manhunt in
Georgia's history as a practical reason he owns a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   ''It gave me a level of confidence, a level of comfort, that my
family would be out of harm's way,'' said Jordan, a father of seven
children.
</P>
<P>
   NRA Second Vice President Sandra Froman, who chairs the group's
grassroots committee, said women are especially effective at
lobbying politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figure that a woman is good for about three men'' when
visiting legislators, said Froman, applauding the dozen or so women
in the audience of several hundred attending the grassroots
workshop.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's efforts to align itself with more women and encourage
them to become politically active face hurdles demonstrated by
national polling. Research shows women favor gun regulation more
than men do, a finding experts attribute to youth violence such as
last year's massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get out and do your job, we will win,'' said Froman,
urging NRA members to recruit their friends and neighbors to ''keep
America on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
