<HEADER>
A0335 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-RATES-ART-$ADV21-     05-19 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-RATES-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YIELD, THE BYPRODUCT OF THE FEDERAL RESERVE'S INTEREST INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tempting, tempting . . .
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since the prospect of putting cash in
the bank held any attraction for most people. Interest rates were
paltry, and the eager money forsook income investments to chase
capital gains in the stock market. That drove prices so high that
the average dividend paid by companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
is now barely 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the Federal Reserve's drive to head off any surge in
inflation is returning the luster to the word ``yield'' _ on bonds,
of course, but also on such prosaic and convenient products as
certificates of deposit and money market funds, especially for
consumers willing to shop a little.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, a bit of negotiating _ even a ploy as simple as
inquiring whether your bank might be willing to improve on the rate
posted in the window _ can also pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got more than $50,000 or so, you can always get 25
to 50 basis points more, often by just asking,'' said Warren
Heller, research director at Veribanc, which analyzes banking
trends. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, banks do not advertise or even acknowledge
that this goes on, but some customers of major banks have found
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the most succulent rates, the place to look is the
Internet _ both the electronic offshoots of traditional banks and
the stand-alone cyberbanks like Wingspan bank.com, ETrade Group's
Telebank, X.Com and USAccess Internet Bank.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of online banking published last Wednesday by Consumer
Action, an advocacy group in California, found ``much better
interest rates, not only on savings accounts but on checking and
money market accounts and certificates of deposit,'' than were
found elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Their examination of 19 virtual banks, all federally insured,
and 10 traditional ones showed, for example, that online operations
paid about a half-point more interest on six-month CDs, and that 4
of the 19 required smaller minimum deposits than any of the
ordinary banks.
</P>
<P>
   As promotion-minded as many a dot-com, Wingspanbank is
temporarily offering an eye-popping 10 percent interest rate on
checking accounts that Kevin Watters, its senior vice president for
marketing, called ``probably the highest in the country.'' The rate
applies to amounts from $100 to $10,000 and runs until Sept. 1;
after that. the accounts will pay 3.10 percent for deposits of at
least $2,500 and 4.50 percent for $10,000 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can pay such high rates because we don't have the physical
infrastructure that brick-and-mortar banks have,'' Watters said,
adding that Wingspanbank's computer system, built from scratch,
avoided the technical incompatibility problems that traditional
competitors face after numerous mergers.
</P>
<P>
   In 12-month certificates of deposit, Wingspanbank immediately
echoed last week's half-point increase by the Federal Reserve for
overnight money, bringing its rate to 7 percent. The average bank
in the country offered 5.47 percent on 12-month CDs after the Fed
move, up from 5.42 percent from the previous week, according to
Bank Rate Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Wingspanbank, owned by Bank One, is based in Wilmington, Del.,
but you may not have to look beyond your hometown institutions for
newly enticing deposit rates.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank in New York, for example, has a cyberspace facility
that it calls Citi f/i (for financial interactive). A visit to
citifi.com, its Web site, found its insured money market account
paying a 5.50 percent rate, for an annual yield of 5.65 percent,
with a $1,000 minimum. As is common with Internet banks, Citi f/i
reimburses any ATM fees charged to its depositors by other
institutions for withdrawals from its accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Citi's online rates are well above the 4.59 percent rate (4.70
percent annual yield) offered at Citibank branches on ``preferred''
money market accounts, which require deposits or loans totaling at
least $50,000 in a customer's accounts. Customers with $25,000 to
$49,999 in their accounts get a 3 percent rate, yielding 3.05
percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   The difference reflects ``lower infrastructure costs,'' said
Maria Mendler, a Citibank spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Textbook economics, however, holds that prices are made by
supply and demand, not costs, leading analysts to suggest that
Internet banks' rates are high because they are little known and
because consumers hesitate over the idea of a bank they cannot
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something goes wrong with a transaction, it's not like just
driving down to the branch and taking it up with the manager,''
said Heller of Veribanc, noting that credit unions often combine
very close proximity with high rates.
</P>
<P>
   Local banks sometimes bid so aggressively for money that there
is no need to send it away to get a higher rate, he said.
``Sometimes there's a pleasant surprise.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
