<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-CHEN-BOS &LR;      05-19 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PRESIDENT SYMBOLIZES GAP BETWEEN TAIWAN, CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ It is fashionable and politically correct here to
speak of the inexorable reunion of the tragically divided ``Chinese
motherland'' _ with the conviction that it will culminate
gloriously in the not-too-distant future with the return to the
fold of the renegade province of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   It is a view widely shared among mainland Chinese of all ages,
levels of education, and income. But for most people in Taiwan's
capital Taipei, that scenario for now couldn't be scarier.
</P>
<P>
   As Taiwan inaugurates Chen Shui-bian as its president, a man who
long advocated independence from China, there is a yawning gap
between two peoples who share a common language and long history
but remain divided by 100 miles of sea and 50 years of contrasting
political and economic systems.
</P>
<P>
   Both peoples have made stunning economic advances in the last
two decades, but while Taiwan's government has transformed itself
in just 13 years from an oppressive military regime to a vibrant,
free-for-all democracy, China has remained frozen under one-party
communist rule that tolerates little dissent.
</P>
<P>
   People in China and Taiwan agree that reunification _ whether
done peacefully or forceably _ seems increasingly inevitable. But
like the two Koreas or the former East and West Germanys, many
people in China and Taiwan regard their governments and each other
suspicion, contempt, and misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the Chinese government or state-controlled press
threatens war if Taiwan doesn't fall into line _ a sabre that has
been rattled almost daily since February _ most Taiwanese feel ever
more alienated from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not brothers _ we're more like enemies,'' Eric Lin, 25,
a Taiwanese graduate student, said recently outside a Taipei mall.
``There's no big brother who would beat up his younger brother
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   For many mainlanders, the very idea of Taiwan as an independent
state is at best laughable, at worst a poisonous notion that must
be stamped out by force. Chinese media published a survey Friday
asserting that 95 percent of mainlanders support going to war if
Chen declares independence.
</P>
<P>
   That hard-line attitude is not commonly heard in informal
interviews here, however, a discrepancy that may reflect a legacy
of decades of authoritarian rule; the habit here is to toe the
party line when questioned by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   China has demonized Taiwan's incoming vice president,
Harvard-educated lawyer Annette Lu, ever since she referred to the
two sides last month as ``distant cousins and close neighbors,'' a
not-uncommon attitude among Taiwanese.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last week by a Taiwanese public relations firm found 70
percent of Taipei residents say the island should be independent,
and 57 percent said they could not accept the ``one country, two
systems'' model that now governs Hong Kong and Macao _ and which
Beijing has offered Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But like Chan Yeini, 38, a software consultant, many Taiwanese
businessmen admire China for its rapid economic reforms and they
say political change will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will ask for more rights,'' he said. ``Taiwan took 20
years to get where we are, and they'll take maybe 10 years,'' he
said. Even so, ``it is impossible to reunite. . . . It is like when
a kid grows up and leaves the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most striking disconnect between the two sides is at
heart not so much political as a question of identity _ how they
perceive themselves, and each other. While most Chinese genuinely
believe that Taiwanese are for better or worse their ``brothers,''
it is hard to find a Taiwanese, especially of the younger
generation, who will echo that view.
</P>
<P>
   A survey published by the government three months ago found that
45 percent of Taiwan's people identify themselves as ``Taiwanese,''
far more than the 14 percent who consider themselves ``Chinese'' or
the 39 percent who say they are both.
</P>
<P>
   Although people-to-people contact has become possible since 1987
with growing commercial links and tourism _ Taiwan is the number
two investor on the mainland, and 60,000 Taiwanese companies do
business there _ distrust on both sides persists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been there and I wouldn't want to go,'' Claire
Yang, 25, a Taiwanese website designer, said emphatically. ``Since
childhood, I was educated that it's a bad place and that they are
bad people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lin Huei-mei, 58, a teacher in Taipei, visited the mainland, and
didn't like it. ``I didn't like the way people related to each
other. They don't respect human rights, and they treat people as
objects. I think it's the way they're educated from childhood _
they're cold and selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a harsh sentiment that is mirrored by some on the mainland.
Taiwanese businessmen have a reputation here as disdainful bosses
who overwork and underpay their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwanese think they're superior to us in every way _
business, fashion, music, political system,'' said a 35-year-old
Shanghai businessman who said he was afraid to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call Chen the `president,' he said, ``but according to
international law, he cannot be a president because Taiwan is not a
real country. They think that little place can fight with a country
of 1.3 billion people. . . . How can they think they are higher
than us?''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``People themselves are no different,'' said Fan Zigen, 58, a
ship factory worker. ``The problem is between the governments.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it looks unlikely that either government will bow to
the other on reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all think there will eventually be reunion, but most people
want the status quo for now, and leave the solution for the next
generation,'' said Charlie Chou, 50, a Taiwanese computer executive
visiting Shanghai. ``It will take new leaders to solve this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
This article was reported in Shanghai and Taipei.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
