<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0341 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-NETWORKS-SPI &LR;      05-19 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NETWORKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS NEED A LESSON IN COURTESY TO CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Mrs. Wiseman? Say it ain't so, Jeremy.
</P>
<P>
   The annual exercise in self-congratulation over the fabulous
fall schedules the networks have assembled inevitably leaves behind
a pile of detritus they don't even bother to sweep up.
</P>
<P>
   This heap of canceled shows doesn't warrant so much as a
hasta-la-bye-bye from the networks as they trip over one another in
the rush to trumpet what's new. And so fans of CBS's charming ``Now
and Again'' will have to get along without the sweet strength of a
character like Lisa Wiseman. Hope springs eternal for fans of
``Sports Night,'' which reportedly will be picked up by HBO. But as
we await rescue by the cable cabal, which probably wouldn't resume
production until January or February, our memory of the boyish and
brilliant Jeremy Goodwin starts to fade.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Colin, who made me wish Mrs. Wiseman lived next door,
and Joshua Malina, who made me wish I worked with Jeremy, are
terrific actors who will survive the brutality of network whimsy.
But it doesn't excuse the awful manners the networks display each
spring.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when TV writers get phone calls from
incredulous readers who don't believe it when they read that their
favorite show has been canceled. ``How could this happen?'' they
demand to know. ``How will they resolve last week's cliffhanger?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is that they won't, because network
executives have a disdain for viewers that makes the Soup Nazi look
like the customer's best friend. The only people they like less are
maitre d's who don't have their favorite tables ready. (Speaking of
service providers, in this age of satisfying the customer _ of
Nordstrom and amazon.com and L.L. Bean _ ever wonder why the
networks never tell us how to get in touch with them? Even their
Web sites don't make it easy.)
</P>
<P>
   When the Post-Intelligencer ran a ``Winners &AMP; Losers'' box with
each story about the fall prime-time lineups, readers would
invariably call to say we must have been mistaken, that ``The
Pretender'' or ``Early Edition'' or ``Wasteland'' couldn't possibly
have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they were, but the networks never mention it. If a person
isn't reading this column or TV Guide or some other source when the
cancellation occurs, whether it's at the end of the season or three
weeks into it, he has no clue that a show has been dispatched to
the Dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it considered foolish to ask that a network tell us when
a show is no longer in stock? When we call to order something from
a catalog, we're told immediately if the item is available. If it's
not, we might be peeved, we might even say we'll never buy from
that catalog again, but at least we have information that allows us
to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when we tune in on a certain night at a certain hour to see
a familiar show, something else comes on in its place and there
isn't a clue from the network. Why can't they put a note at the
bottom of the screen? It could be terse: ```Sports Night' is no
longer on ABC's schedule.'' Or it could be warm and fuzzy: ``If you
tuned in to watch `Now and Again,' we're sorry to say it is no
longer on our schedule. We hope you enjoy what we've put in its
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's serving the customer. Such a radical concept!
Sure, it's going to get some people bent out of shape, but that's
going to happen no matter how we find out about the cancellation.
Wouldn't it build credibility and good will if the networks were up
front about it?
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the events at which the networks unveil their new
fall lineups to the advertising community are called ``up-fronts.''
They are a springtime ritual that allows the networks to obtain
up-front commitments from advertisers, who in turn get lower rates
by signing on early.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking hundreds of millions of dollars per network, and
the response of the advertisers is used to gauge how the fall
lineup will play in homes across America.
</P>
<P>
   If only our frustration spoke as eloquently as hard currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
