<SLUG> BC-BKN-POWER-SHIFT0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gloves coming off in Lakers-Blazers
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This time, it's personal.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Conference finals, viewed by many as the ``real''
NBA championship series, has taken on a heated flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers and Portland Trail Blazers have not
reached New York-Miami proportions yet, but they don't like each
other. That much is clear from the words and actions on the court
from both sides, starting with today's Game 1 in the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The teams split four regular-season games, but Portland's wins
did not impress league MVP Shaquille O'Neal. ``They beat us, but
they didn't beat us,'' O'Neal said. ``They won the games, but they
didn't beat us. We just have to be ready. The whole team is going
to be pumped up, the city is going to be pumped up, everybody is
going to be pumped up, and we will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Trail Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy seems ready. He complained all
week about O'Neal's physical style, trying to plant seeds in the
minds of the referees. And he didn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy said he was ``shocked at how (the Lakers) were able to
get (illegal defense) calls on Sacramento by talking about it in
the newspaper. On a couple of them, I don't even think Sacramento
was illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers ``had a lot of nerve even complaining about it, the
way Shaq just stands in the middle all the time,'' Dunleavy said.
</P>
<P>
   And the talk was just beginning. Los Angeles coach Phil Jackson
did a Lenny Wilkens, saying Portland is a team that is struggling
with leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think that if Scottie (Pippen) doesn't lead this
team and take them by the horns, they're not going to get by us,''
said Jackson, who teamed with Pippen and Michael Jordan to win six
NBA titles with the Chicago Bulls. ``I don't know who else can lead
them. I don't see another leader on that basketball club, someone
who can get things done at critical times and make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson was not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Portland underachieved this year,'' he said. ``I
thought we would have to win 65 games to beat them. But after we
beat them (90-87 in Portland on Feb. 29), they fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, the Blazers fizzled after the Lakers' significant
win, finishing the regular season 14-12. But they have played some
of their best ball in the playoffs. ``We have our confidence
back,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
