<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-RAC-FUSAICHI-PEGASUS-     05-19 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FUSAICHI-PEGASUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RACING SEES A SAVIOR IN FUSAICHI PAGASUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Preakness is only the second leg, but a lot of
people whose livelihood depends on thoroughbred racing already have
visions of a Triple Crown dancing in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus will be the savior that racing executives and
fans have been awaiting for 22 years if he can get out of this town
unscathed in the Preakness Saturday and then win the Belmont Stakes
on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility of a Triple Crown is very good for business,''
said Chip Tuttle, a vice president with the National Thoroughbred
Racing Association, a coalition that promotes the sport. ``Just the
possibility means three or four (television) ratings points for the
Belmont Stakes, additional column inches of newspaper and magazine
coverage, greater TV exposure. It's three weeks of additional
mainstream coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   That possibility existed in each of the past three years, when
colts won the first two legs of the crown, only to be sideswiped by
the grim reaper of racing, the Belmont Stakes. The difference is
that Fusaichi Pegasus has a much greater aura than any of the
previous three.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally different than in the case of Real Quiet,
Silver Charm and Charismatic,'' said New York Racing Association
executive Bill Nader. ``This time I think people will come to see a
coronation as opposed to hoping to see a Triple Crown winner. This
time they come expecting to see it, and maybe seeing one of the
all-time great horses, a horse they may be comparing to Affirmed,
Seattle Slew or Secretariat.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's the small matter of beating seven other
horses Saturday afternoon going 1 3/16 miles in the 10th race at
Pimlico before one can even consider such a leap of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're dying to have a media horse, we're dying to have
a Triple Crown horse,'' said trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who trained
Charismatic, last year's Derby and Preakness winner. ``It's out
there possibly, but right now it's still a Derby horse going for
the second leg. Nothing more, nothing less at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   But the presence of a first-class colt like Fusaichi Pegasus,
who sold for $4 million and could be worth 10 times that with a
Triple Crown on his resume, makes this quest seem more realistic
than the other bids of recent vintage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has been waiting for an outstanding racehorse
with a regal pedigree,'' author Andrew Beyer said in the Daily
Racing Form. ``The best American champions in recent years _ Cigar,
Holy Bull, Skip Away and Silver Charm _ have all been the products
of moderate pedigrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, conversely, is a son of the great cornerstone
sire Mr. Prospector, and has the look and bearing of a potential
superstar stallion himself.
</P>
<P>
   Should he become the first horse since Affirmed (1978) to sweep
the Derby, Preakness and Belmont Stakes, the residual effects on
what is perceived to be a struggling industry could be monumental.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good for the sport right now,'' said trainer Bob Baffert,
who had two healthy whiffs of Triple Crown perfume with Silver
Charm in 1997 and Real Quiet in '98. ``When they were coming down
the stretch and I thought I was going to win the Triple Crown, man,
it was a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Three horses won Triple Crown winners in the 1970s, but the
magic has been missing since. Spectacular Bid, Pleasant Colony,
Alysheba and Sunday Silence also won the first two legs before
failing in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would help the sport like a Michael Jordan helped
basketball,'' said the NTRA's Tuttle, who remains bullish on
racing. ``Handle was up in North America last year for the fifth
straight year. Sales at public auctions topped $1 billion for the
first time ever. Purses exceeded $1 billion for the first time. All
this crap about a dying industry should be gone whether he wins it
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the immediate impact on the Belmont Stakes can't be
denied, and the folks at NYRA will have fingers crossed on both
hands on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that in the last three years, when we went from
70,000 to 82,000 to 85,000 (fans), the people have left with a
positive experience,'' Nader said. ``But if it is a non-Triple
Crown Belmont, the expectations are much lower. We're looking at a
crowd more in the neighborhood of 50,000. It's a big swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects are even more far-reaching in terms of Belmont
Stakes wagering if Fusaichi Pegasus has the betting public's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we handled nearly $75 million on Belmont Stakes
Day,'' Nader said. ``Without a Triple Crown on the line, we can't
even come close to that. The whole day of racing is great, so if we
have a Triple Crown opportunity and it gets everybody to focus on
Belmont Stakes Day, it carries over to our supporting races.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle said the NTRA already is feeling the effects of Pegasus
mania, having been contacted by prestigious magazines for stories
about the game's rising star.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility of a Triple Crown would mean additional
national and regional promotion for racing,'' he said. ``It means
people spending national advertising revenue. The media impact is
worth millions of dollars, and that's only if the possibility
exists.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Pegasus should actually win all three races? It's an
appealing thought for horse racing boosters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that if there is a Triple Crown winner, that
racing gets the cover of Sports Illustrated,'' Nader said. ``Racing
gets the front page of some major newspapers, not the front page of
sports or the back page of sports, but the front page of the
newspaper. We need to get over that hurdle and see how much we can
capitalize on that opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
