<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has move the following
entertainment/arts, Financial, Travel and Style articles this week
for release Sunday, May 21, 2000. Articles from the Week in Review
section will move Saturday morning:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COVER STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-THEATER (Undated) _ On the eve of the annual awards, Robin
Pogrebin assesses what's wrong (and right) with the Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROSIE-O'DONNELL-THEATER (Undated) _ If Broadway were a religion,
Rosie O'Donnell would most certainly make the short list for
beatification. Her daytime talk show on ABC is a virtual worship
service for the theater. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS-OPINIONS (Undated) _ The annual ritual of asking what is
right and wrong with the Tony Awards has arrived. Last year, some
of the wrongs concerned the show: Radio City Music Hall was not
available for the ceremonies; Rosie O'Donnell pulled out as the
host, and the ratings and general telecast quality plummeted. This
year, O'Donnell will be at her post _ at Radio City Music Hall _on
June 4. But concerns remain about the awards in general. Jesse
McKinley gets some opinions from people working in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN-STROMAN-THEATER (Undated) _ They are images as American,
and crusty, as apple pie _ cowboys on the prairie, lovers in a
small town, dancers in a smoky club _ scenes endlessly romanticized
in everything from the detective chic of Dashiell Hammett to the
purple prose of ``The Bridges of Madison County.'' For Susan
Stroman, whose notable talent seems to involve creating lively
steps against quintessential American backdrops, it seems only
natural that theater might be the medium to shake some dust off
those stereotypes. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THANDIE-NEWTON-MOVIES (Beverly Hills) _ An interview with
Thandie Newton, the British actress who will be seen on screen
under John Woo's direction inflaming the passions of a trio of
chiseled-jawed men (including Tom Cruise) when ``M: I-2'' opens May
24. By Ariel Swartley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEATNIK-ROCK-MUSIC (Undated) _ When Allen Ginsberg, the last
surviving member of the Beat trinity that included Jack Kerouac and
William Burroughs, died three years ago, it was entirely
appropriate that Lou Reed and Patti Smith be prominent among those
participating in the ceremonies honoring Walt Whitman's greatest
poetic descendant. The shock waves of Ginsberg's ``Howl,''
Kerouac's ``On the Road,'' and Burroughs' ``Naked Lunch'' radiated
far beyond the academy. It's clear today that as much as the Beats
helped loosen the academic strait jacket constricting American
literature, they had a far more profound impact on rock culture. By
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   VIENNA-ORCHESTRA-MUSIC (Vienna) _ When the Vienna Philharmonic
performed Beethoven's Ninth Symphony recently in a former Nazi
concentration camp in Mauthausen, Austria, it was knowingly wading
into deep waters of memory and repression, meaning and association,
hope and delusion. And all of that is to reckon without the
late-breaking international fracas over Joerg Haider and the
Freedom Party, as the orchestra did through most of its four years
of planning. The event was intended as a Janus-headed look
backward, with remorse and a hope for healing, and forward, with
resolve and a hope for renewal. By James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   ARTIE-SHAW-MUSIC (Undated) _ H.L. Mencken once suggested that in
a well-run universe, everybody would have two lives: ``one for
observing and studying the world, and the other for formulating and
setting down his conclusions about it.'' This is more or less the
way that the clarinetist Artie Shaw, who turns 90 on May 23, has
contrived to arrange things. By Terry Teachout.
</P>
<P>
   TURAY-TUCKER-MUSIC (Undated) _ ``I was basically a product of
the pop generation,'' says the lyric tenor Gregory Turay, 27,
latest winner of the Richard Tucker Award, the fanciest American
prize a American classical singer can win. Back in his days as a
teen rocker with his father's band Time Trax, he would bring the
house down with Billy Idol's ``Mony Mony.'' An interview. By
Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   METALLICA-NAPSTER (Undated) _ Metallica is suing Napster with
the stated intention of shutting down piracy, not harassing the
music lovers who legitimately trade music through it. But by
gathering the names of users and asking that they be banned from
the service, the band arguably resorted to privacy invasion. The
band's approach has so angered fans that they are organizing
boycotts and merchandise burnings, and establishing anti-Metallica
Web sites and bulletin boards. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARLEM-DANCE (New York) _ Dance Theater of Harlem celebrates its
30th anniversary this year. The classical-ballet company was
founded by Arthur Mitchell, a leading dancer with the New York City
Ballet, in response to the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr.
George Balanchine and Lincoln Kirstein, the founders of City
Ballet, encouraged Mitchell to start the troupe. City Ballet will
pay tribute to the company in three shared programs on May 25, 26
and 28 at the New York State Theater at Lincoln Center. Jennifer
Dunning talks with the directors.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ANASTACIA-DANCE (New York) _ Until now, the only ballets titled
``Anastasia'' have been about the Russian Grand Duchess who
legendarily survived the murder of the entire Imperial family by
Bolshevik forces in 1918. On Tuesday, however, an Afro-Brazilian
Anastacia will arrive at the Joyce Theater in New York as the
heroine of a new ballet by DanceBrazil. Nobody knows who Anastacia
actually was, but one thing is sure: she was no Grand Duchess. By
Shayna Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART/PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARDER-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ Twenty years ago, Malerie Marder
was snooping in her father's dresser drawers and found a snapshot
of a naked woman. It was no big deal, her mother assured her, but
warned her never to pose like the woman in the picture. She didn't
listen. To put it mildly. For the last year, Marder, 28, has
photographed family members and friends nude, including her mother
and ex-boyfriend posing together, in either upscale California
homes or pay-by-the-hour motels. At a time when sexually explicit
display rarely elicits more than a yawn, Marder has managed to
raise eyebrows with her voyeuristic images that challenge the taboo
against incest. By Elizabeth Hayt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLOONEY-TV (Undated) _ What hath George Clooney wrought? Six
weeks after Clooney used his star clout to get the drama ``Fail
Safe'' broadcast live _ in black and white on national television _
entertainment-industry trade publications have already reported
plans for two other live dramas. One is on CBS with Julie Andrews
as the star; the other is on HBO with Glenn Close as co-executive
producer. Optimists see this as the glimmer of a possible second
golden age of television. More likely it's just the latest in
reality programming. By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
