   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-ECONOMY (Amman, Jordan) _ Jordan, poor but ambitious, has
opened its doors wide to trade and investment under a new king. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-RATES RATE (Undated) _ While it often seems that nobody
invests for income these days - mania for capital gains has driven
stock prices so high that the average dividend of companies in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is barely 1 percent - the Federal Reserve's
drive to prevent an inflation surge is causing increased
interest-rate temptation. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-KODAK (Undated) _ It may be the quintessential
company-in-transition. Over the last several years, Eastman Kodak
has jettisoned the legacies of failed diversification efforts, cut
$1.2 billion in overhead and embarked on a series of digital
photography initiatives intended to catapult the company into the
New Economy. But given the lackluster results shareholders have
endured, many wonder if Kodak really is on the verge of such a
transformation. By Joanne Legomsky.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-GRASSROOTS (Undated) _ Andrew Segal, the king of `B' office
space, is in the catbird seat now that everybody wants funky
business-casual space, not fancy-schmancy lobbies and amenities. By
Joel Kotkin.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-TEQUILA (Undated) _ An American tries to launch his own
brand of premium tequila, and discovers how hard it is to break
into a cliquish, insular business. By Alice Feiring.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-FINANCE-DISASTERS (Undated) _ With the Los Alamos fire
as a peg, a look at ways to carry on your personal business when
disaster strikes. It's tough, even if you were diligent: your files
have burned, your backup floppies have melted, you have no mailbox
in which to receive your visa bill, no home phone number to leave
for return calls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-DISCLOSURE (Undated) _ Who gets a heads-up from his or
her mutual fund company about its portfolio moves? Until recently,
nobody. But in the last year or two, such detailed disclosure has
become, if not yet the norm, then a growing trend in the fund
industry as it adapts to the Internet age. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-STRATEGIES (Las Vegas) _ The kernel of truth embedded in
contrarian analysis is that the market rarely follows forecasts
that are very widely held. Bull markets typically end once everyone
becomes convinced that the market has nowhere to go but up. That is
the origin of the old saw about bull markets liking to climb a wall
of worry, and it explains why having a bootblack tell you about the
latest stock tips is considered the quintessential sign of a top.
Similarly, bear markets generally come to an end when everyone has
thrown in the towel and turned bearish. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-DIGEST (Undated) _ Mutual funds, investment notes and
news.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-PROFILE-BARSKY (Undated) _ Investing discussion with
hedge funders Neil Barsky and the folks at Midtown Research. By
Alex Berenson.
</P>
