   &UR; BUSINESS COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ETHICS-COLUMN (Undated) _ When to tell the truth is to deceive.
By Jeffrey L. Seglin.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Say what you will about capitalism;
you must admit it has a marvelous way of turning even the most
violent and earthshaking upheavals into safe, salable kitsch. By
Tom Redburn.
</P>
<P>
   PRELUDES-COLUMN (Undated) _ When you're newly successful,
everybody wants to be your long-lost friend. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-LOWRIDERS (Tampa) _ Lowriding emerged in the '50s in
the barrios of California, as Chicano youths _ in what may have
been a reaction to the hot-rod culture dominated by whites _
transformed their cars into shiny, fantastical, ground-hugging
showboats. ``Go low and go slow'' were the watchwords. From the
beginning, lowriding was as much about ethnic identity as about
machinery. In the 1980s, lowriding began to break out of its
traditionally Latino stronghold. By Dan Neil.
</P>
