<HEADLINE>
INVESTING NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sun., May 21)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH: Industry Is Cool to Frequent Disclosure
</P>
<P>
   The Investment Co. Institute, the main trade group for the
mutual fund industry, reacted coolly last week to a call for it to
back more frequent mandatory disclosure of fund portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Investment companies are now required to disclose their holdings
twice a year under Securities and Exchange Commission regulations _
a rule that has not changed in more than 60 years. A few funds
voluntarily report more often.
</P>
<P>
   A letter to Matthew Fink, president of the institute, calling
for a committee to study the issue and advocate new rules was
signed by John Rekenthaler, research director of Morningstar Inc.,
the fund data company; Thomas O'Hara, chairman of the National
Association of Investment Clubs; and Donald Luskin and H. Davis
Nadig, co-founders of MetaMarkets.com, whose OpenFund reports its
portfolio and trades live over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue has generated discussion for many years, and the
institute has considered it with many members on several
occasions,'' Fink told Dow Jones News. ``The current requirement to
disclose portfolio information semiannually remains appropriate.''
Even so, Fink said he would put the issue on the agenda for a
meeting of the institute's rules committee on June 20.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement on Kemper Ads
</P>
<P>
   Kemper Distributors was censured and assessed a penalty of
$100,000 by the National Association of Securities Dealers last
week because of what the NASD described as inaccuracies in mutual
fund advertisements that continued to appear even after the company
had been asked to stop them. In settling the case, Kemper
Distributors, the sales arm of Kemper Funds, neither admitted nor
denied the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Eight advertisements that appeared The Wall Street Journal,
Barron's and other publications between April and September 1997
overstated the return on a hypothetical $10,000 investment made at
the 1988 inception of the firm's Kemper-Dreman High Return Equity
fund, according to an NASD report. A graph in one of the ads
suggested that such an investment would have been worth $23,000 at
the end of 1991 and $29,000 by the end of 1994; the correct figures
would have been $17,000 in 1991 and $22,000 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Kemper called the errors ``technical
infractions'' and said it had implemented new policies to ensure
that they did not recur.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper was also accused of violating NASD rules in a March 1997
ad that showed a straight line sloping up, with the low end labeled
``you are here'' and the high end marked ``your future is here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The straight upwardly sloping line did not convey the risks of
fluctuating prices inherent in investing,'' the NASD statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next six months, Kemper has agreed to submit all graphs,
bar charts or pie charts in its advertising to the NASD for review
before use.
</P>
<P>
   DIARY: Britain's Dot-Com Cash Crunch
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the collapse last week of Boo.com, a high-profile
European Internet retailer, a study by PricewaterhouseCoopers
warned that seven of Britain's 28 publicly traded Internet
companies could run out of cash in the next six months, while fewer
than half had enough cash to last through the next 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The study calculated the companies' ``burn rate'' based on their
latest reported balance-sheet cash, gross profits and cash
expenses, and factored in 130 percent annual growth, described as
typical for Internet commerce. No link was found between a
company's burn rate and the performance of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
