<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELIEFS: NEW REPORT OPTIMISTIC ABOUT PROTESTANT DENOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death of distinct Protestant denominations has been, it
appears, greatly exaggerated. For some while, the very notion of
denomination _ Baptists, Methodists, Presbyterians, Episcopalians,
Lutherans and so on _ has been viewed as theologically fuzzy and
sociologically doomed.
</P>
<P>
   A denomination, with its own distinctive doctrinal emphases,
modes of worship and forms of organization, does not claim to be
the only legitimate expression of Christianity, although it may
claim to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the United States, the denominational society par
excellence, Christian denominations have lived side by side without
aspiring to encompass all believers in a territory, as Roman
Catholic, Orthodox or many established national churches have
historically done. And unlike small, intense sectarian movements,
denominations do not consider friendly cooperation with one another
a betrayal of doctrinal purity.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds cozy, maybe too cozy. The boundaries separating
denominations have long grown blurry for many Protestants, who say
that being Methodist or Presbyterian or Baptist does not really
matter to them or, indeed, that they are not sure what it means.
</P>
<P>
   This decline of denominationalism is not really surprising.
Denominations were based, after all, on distinctions of social
class, region, ethnicity and race, along with _ and perhaps more
than _ distinctions of doctrine, practice and polity.
</P>
<P>
   There were unmistakable denominational cultures. Think of
Garrison Keillor's endless reminders of the Lake Wobegon Lutheran
proclivity for the tuna-and-noodle hot dish. Or the stock
portrayals of East Coast Episcopalians, Midwest Methodists or
Southern Baptists in any number of short stories and novels.
</P>
<P>
   Mobility, education, intermarriage and the common, media-borne
culture of entertainment and advertising have all taken their toll
on these differences. From one point of view, this is a good thing.
Denominations were often crucial rungs on the ladder of class and
status. Going from the Baptist Church to the Presbyterian or
Episcopal Church was a sign of upward mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in 1929, a young theologian, H. Richard Niebuhr, made
his reputation with ``The Social Sources of Denominationalism,'' a
landmark study in American religion. For Niebuhr, denominational
divisions represented nothing less than a ``moral failure of
Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   So should the disappearance of denominations be counted a moral
success? While no one regrets the fading of denominational
snobbishness, the eclipse of differences that were deeply rooted in
history and theology has often appeared to be less a triumph of
Christian unity than a general ``dumbing down'' of belief and
practice.
</P>
<P>
   That is why a report by Nancy T. Ammerman, a distinguished
sociologist of religion who teaches at Hartford Seminary in
Connecticut, will be considered good news. The glass of
denominationalism is at least half full, she wrote two months ago
in the liberal Protestant weekly The Christian Century.
</P>
<P>
   A study of a wide range of Protestant congregations, she
reported, found that 55 percent of them, ``slightly more among
conservatives, slightly less among liberals,'' considered
themselves ``strong standard-bearers of their denominational
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a striking finding. Denominational identity is generally
related, as one might expect, to the proportion of a congregation's
members who grew up in its tradition, compared with the proportion
who, in the language of sociology of religion, are ``switchers.''
Yet ``Nearly three-quarters of the white Protestant congregations
we studied,'' Ammerman wrote, ``reported that half or more of their
members grew up in another denomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But not even high percentages of switchers have discouraged
congregations that really want to maintain their denominational
identity, Ammerman said. They seemed to be going about it very
consciously, deliberately emphasizing denominational doctrines in
their preaching and religious education, especially for new
members.
</P>
<P>
   A Lutheran pastor near Seattle spoke of an ``unabashedly
Lutheran'' stress on God's grace in his congregation's preaching
and teaching. A Presbyterian pastor did play down ``John Calvin's
doctrine of special providence and _ horror of horrors _ his
doctrine of predestination.'' To stop exploring predestination and
other specifically Calvinist teachings, he said, would amount to no
longer ``understanding what it means to be Presbyterian.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, it was not so much specific doctrines as specific
traditions of worship that were the vehicles for carrying
denominational identity. This was particularly true of
Episcopalians and their attachment to the ritual found in the Book
of Common Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   It was also true of the evangelical congregations associated
with the recent Vineyard movement, whose pastors display a nearly
de rigueur informality in attire and whose worship is permeated
with its distinctive ``praise music.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual congregations feel free to reconfigure their
denominational identities in ways that might not have been accepted
formerly, Ammerman and her fellow researchers found, but ``for
about half the Protestant congregations, an intentional retrieval
and construction of tradition'' was alive and well, with
denominational identity ``no longer taken for granted, but now
chosen; no longer a matter of enclave and birth, but now a matter
of faith and practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those congregations in which distinct denominational
identities are being chosen and nurtured do not seem to be the
worse for it,'' Ammerman wrote. ``Most are vital and growing, and
few, if any, are isolated or hostile to the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the denominationalism Niebuhr feared, they are building
distinctions based more on ritual and doctrine than on social
divisions,'' she concluded. ``Theirs is an experiment in blending
tradition and openness that bears watching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
