<SLUG> BC-EURO-TOURISM-ART-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING ON THE WINGS OF THE DOLLAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before his wedding in 1985, Mark Lesser priced a honeymoon
in Paris. Even though the dollar was stronger than at any time
since the early 1970s, the trip was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, Lesser, 37, will celebrate his 15th anniversary
with his wife, Stacy, in Paris and Nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw how much further the dollar would go,'' said Lesser, now
the sales director of an Internet software company and a resident
of Manalapan, N.J. Fifteen years ago, he said, ``Our income was a
quarter of what it is now, so now is just a good time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now seems to be a good time for other U.S. travelers, too. Many
are reveling not only in their increased income, but also in their
incredible buying power abroad. The value of the dollar has surged
recently against most of the world's currencies, but especially
against the euro, which 11 European nations introduced as their
common currency in 1999. As the dollar rises, the costs of hotel
rooms, restaurants and related items generally decline for
Americans, making foreign trips enticing.
</P>
<P>
   The European Travel Commission, based in Brussels, expects 12
million Americans to visit Europe this year, a 3.5 percent increase
from last year and the seventh consecutive annual increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen it quite as heavy as this year,'' said Iris
Citron, the president of Creative Travel in Springfield, N.J., and
Lesser's travel agent. There is an ``enormous amount of travel to
Europe by people who in the past would go on inexpensive cruises or
cheaper trips to the Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, low air fares and individual feelings of wealth are
driving summer travel plans more than the currency's strength, some
travel agents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very big year for Italy, and Paris is packed,''
said Jackie Rush, vice president at Waters Travel in Washington.
``It's only because we are so affluent here; we are so rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Though travel agents say many of their clients do not realize
what a bargain Europe is, some tourists go on spending sprees when
they see how far their dollars will go. Savvy travelers wait to pay
for hotels until they arrive when they can more easily take
advantage of rates quoted in the local currency instead of buying
travel packages in dollars, said Ralph Ferrara, president of
Schneider Travel, a small agency in Butler, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar generally peaked in 1985, but it has surpassed or
reached the same levels against a few of the 11 currencies that the
euro is replacing. So far this year, the dollar has gained 12.2
percent against the euro. And it is up 16.5 percent since last
summer, making a significant dent in prices in Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   (Until January 2002, when euro bills and coins will begin to
circulate, the individual European currencies are being used for
most purchases, although credit card charges and electronic
payments are calculated in euros.)
</P>
<P>
   Against the Portuguese escudo, the dollar has eclipsed its 1985
level. It is virtually at its 1985 level against the Italian lira
and just below its 1985 peak against the Spanish peseta. And it has
climbed to levels not seen since the summer of 1986 against the
German mark, the French franc and the Dutch guilder.
</P>
<P>
   The euro ended Friday at 89.71 cents, just a bit above its
record low, making the dollar worth 2,158 lire, 185.45 pesetas,
223.45 escudos, 2.18 marks, 7.31 francs and 2.46 guilders.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar is moving higher against other major currencies, too,
though the rally has been smaller. It has risen 11.2 percent
against the British pound since January and is now the strongest
there since the spring of 1994. Against the Canadian dollar, the
U.S. dollar is moving back toward its record high of the summer of
1998. Even against the Japanese yen, it has eked out a small gain
recently, though it remains 27 percent below its most recent high
in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Though the rise of the dollar against the pound has been enough
to cut vacation costs in Britain by 7 percent since last summer, a
trip to Canada will still cost about 1 percent more than last
summer. And a trip to Japan will be a lot more expensive, with the
dollar down more than 9 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of a stronger dollar, of course, is that it
becomes more expensive for others to travel to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, Europeans have not cut back significantly on
U.S. travel. According to the latest available data from the U.S.
Commerce Department, tourism from Western Europe grew 5.6 percent
in 1999. It was up 11.9 percent from Spain, 7.5 percent from the
Netherlands, 4.5 percent from France, 4.4 percent from Germany and
2.5 percent from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   And the Commerce Department predicted this week that the growth
would continue as the economic revival in Europe helps offset the
decline in purchasing power from weaker currencies. For this year,
the government forecasts that the number of visitors from the
Netherlands will increase 6.8 percent from a year ago; Spain, 6.6
percent; France, 5.6 percent; Germany, 4.4 percent; and Italy, 3.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though final figures on U.S. travel for last year are not yet
available, the Commerce Department says the number of Americans
traveling by air to Western Europe jumped 7.4 percent in the first
three months of 1999 from the comparable period a year earlier.
Travel by Americans to all other countries rose 7.7 percent over
that period. Preliminary data for the entire year show that 24.6
million Americans traveled overseas by air, excluding trips to
Mexico and Canada, for a 6.5 percent increase over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   People simply have more money in their pockets, said G. Anna
Schoeman, an agent with Polk Travel in Denver. Only about 20
percent of her clients mention the dollar's power as a factor in
their travel decisions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredibly inexpensive air fares are more of a motivation than
the strength of the dollar,'' she said. ``When you can go from
Denver to London for $450 or Denver to Paris for $500, the strength
of the dollar might come up after they purchase their ticket, and
maybe even after they arrive in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Laird G. Newman, an analyst with Andersen Consulting, said he
was pleasantly surprised after he arranged an April trip to Italy
through Schoeman. ``We did find that the dollar was at the exchange
rate of 2-1, and we thought, `That's great,''' he said. ``We ended
up doing a lot and spending a lot and thinking how great the dollar
was.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Americans spot bargains in foreign goods, U.S.-made products
are becoming more costly to Europeans and others. And some analysts
suspect that the strength of the dollar may be cutting into U.S.
exports. In 1999, total U.S. goods sold to countries in the
European Union rose 1.9 percent, down from gains of 5.9 percent in
1998 and 10.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Given that much of the world is still rebounding from financial
crises in 1997 and 1998, ``The most plausible reason for the
decline is the appreciation of the dollar,'' said Gordon
Richardson, an economist at the National Association of
Manufacturers in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But it is too early to see a clear pattern, in part because the
pickup in economies around the world may be hiding the dollar's
effect. Trade data released Friday showed that U.S. exports rose to
record levels in March.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in short-term interest rates this week by the
Federal Reserve has given the dollar yet more support. And the
strength of the U.S. economy is attracting foreign investment,
which also helps bolster the value of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But the Federal Reserve is intent on slowing the torrid pace of
growth of the U.S. economy. Once signs of slowing appear, the
dollar should begin slipping. That will cut into the buying power
of U.S. travelers. But it may take a real economic slowdown and not
just a slip in the currency to stem the tide abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Rush, the travel agent in Washington, said, ``I don't believe
for one second that the euro going up will slow the flow of
Americans going to Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
