<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WEB-GASOLINE-NYT &LR;      05-19 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-GASOLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES OFFER CHEAPER GAS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELINE MAYNARD  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet has changed the ways that people order new cars and
bid on old ones. Now Web entrepreneurs are out to change the way
you fill your gas tank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several Web sites are offering services aimed at trimming the
cost of a fill-up _ and just in time, too, since motorists face the
prospect of entering the peak summer travel season with prices 35
cents a gallon higher than they were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet broker Priceline.com, known for offering discount
airline tickets and hotel rooms, is opening a gasoline-buying
service that will try to help consumers cut deals for cheaper fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Carclub.com, a Web site operated by J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, the
automotive and consumer-product marketing company, is giving
members a 10 percent discount on gasoline through the rest of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies offer discounts to frequent purchasers or
operate Web sites that help consumers find stations in their area
that are selling the cheapest gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the price of a gallon of unleaded gasoline last week
stood at $1.492 a gallon, up 7.2 cents in just the last two weeks.
(In metropolitan New York, the price of a gallon of self-service
unleaded gasoline was $1.60, according to the most recent survey
conducted April 19 by the Automobile Club of New York.) Last year
at this time, the national average was $1.14 a gallon.
Historically, gasoline prices rise in spring and early summer, as
millions of motorists make vacation trips.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Priceline.com will begin mailing blue Gas Cards to
the 1 million people who have already registered on its Web site.
The program is modeled after Priceline.com's WebHouse Club
grocery-buying service, started in November, which lets consumers
name their price for food and dry goods, prepay for the order, then
purchase their selections at a participating supermarket using a
green WebHouse Club card.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline sales will start June 20, said Robert Padgett, a
spokesman for Priceline.com. Gas Card participants will go to
Priceline.com's site and enter a per-gallon bid for unleaded
gasoline in one of three grades: regular, midgrade or premium.
Priceline.com tells consumers to expect discounts of 10 to 20 cents
a gallon off local prices, though an occasional dealer may agree to
a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   Once the bid is accepted, customers can prepay for up to 50
gallons of gasoline. They will purchase the fuel with their Gas
Card, either directly at the pump or inside the service station.
The card can be used only at self-service bays. If pump prices fall
below the prepaid level, Priceline.com will give club members a
credit for the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Padgett said merchants would be paid the full pump price.
Price-line.com is making up the difference by selling advertising
space on its gas site, the first time it has done so on one of its
sites. The service will be offered free for the first 90 days.
After that, Gas Card members will pay a $3 monthly handling charge.
Padgett could not estimate how many gas stations were participating
in the nationwide service.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power's Carclub.com is also using stored-value cards. Its
Gas MasterCard is sent to each customer who pays a $5.99 monthly
fee. This covers the gas discount and other services, including a
payment of up to $500 for a member's insurance deductible in case
of an accident, advice from a mechanics' hot line and free
directions from its ``Help, I'm Lost'' 24-hour customer assistance
center.
</P>
<P>
   Carclub.com expects 250,000 members by year's end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
