<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEST BY WATER FOR THE FLYING HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The horse of the moment, Fusaichi Pegasus, was
snugged down in his barn at Pimlico Race Course on Friday on the
eve of the Preakness, but one unexpected complication fell on him
and his seven rivals: rain.
</P>
<P>
   The rain was heavy at times, and it was supposed to linger, with
showers predicted on Saturday morning followed by clouds all day
and the temperature on the cool side, in the mid to upper 60s. But
rain or shine, the ``flying horse'' remained the 3-5 favorite to
win the Preakness and to advance to the Belmont Stakes in New York
on June 10 with a chance to win the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness will be run at 5:27 p.m. on Saturday with a purse
of $1 million at a distance of a mile and three-sixteenths.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Drysdale, who trains Fusaichi Pegasus, remembered that his
star won the Wood Memorial in New York last month on a rainy track
that was listed as ``wet-fast.'' But his five other races were all
run on fast tracks, and the Pimlico track was fast early Friday
morning when the colt went galloping for Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The workout went faster,'' Drysdale said, ``because his
stablemate and workmate went off a little quick. But it was all
right. He came out of it fine.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the eight horses in the Preakness have had much exposure
to rain, although Captain Steve won the Breeders' Futurity at
Keeneland last October on a sloppy track. In the Kentucky Derby,
Captain Steve poked his head in front as the 19 horses headed for
home, but he was bumped by Wheelaway and finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really want to see,'' said Bob Baffert, his trainer,
``is for the real Captain Steve to show up and run like I know he
can. I think he moves up on a wet track. He's had only the one race
in the slop, and he won that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Rose, the 88-year-old owner and trainer of Hal's Hope,
who ran 16th in the Kentucky Derby after winning the Florida Derby,
said that his horse was fit and that rain would be welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cut he suffered on his right front leg when he stumbled
coming out of the starting gate in the Kentucky Derby is completely
healed,'' Rose said. ``I wouldn't mind if we had rain. He's never
run on an off-track. But he's worked fine in the slop, and his
pedigree says he can handle a wet track.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert visualized four speed horses leading the field around
the track, with four closers stalking them for the critical run
down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the horses will run in two tiers,'' he said, ``with
Hugh Hefner, Hal's Hope, High Yield and Snuck In all up close to
the lead. We'll be in the second tier. A lot depends on the track
condition. But I want my rider, Robby Albarado, to put Captain
Steve where he's comfortable. I'd like him to sit and relax, and
make one run.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said that he wants Fusaichi Pegasus to show more speed
in the Preakness than he did in the Derby, when he went from 15th
place on the first turn to take the lead in the homestretch. Once
the speed horses begin to fade, the closers should be moving up,
led by Fusaichi Pegasus, Red Bullet and Impeachment, who are widely
expected to be involved in a late showdown with High Yield.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, the trainer of High Yield, has won the Kentucky
Derby four times, the Preakness five times and the Belmont Stakes
three times. ``I don't think horsemen and some of the public are as
ready to concede the Preakness to Fusaichi Pegasus,'' he said.
``You've got to remember that he has to run in these races. That's
why the Triple Crown is here, and it's so tough. You win one or two
and you think, or hope, that you can go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, and added from long experience, ``But that's why they
run these races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
