A0427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ANTI-STRIKE-AD-NYT &LR;      05-19 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-STRIKE-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTORS APOLOGIZE FOR AD THAT ACTORS CALL RACIST AND SEXIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ridley Scott, the director of ``Gladiator,'' the No. 1 movie at
the box office, has apologized for a trade publication
advertisement that has heightened tensions in a three-week-old
actors' strike. The advertisement depicted the bare breasts of a
black woman.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in Shoot, a weekly magazine of the advertising
industry, the advertisement stated that Marcus Nispel, a prominent
director of commercials, was setting up a temporary office in South
Africa _ out of reach of the striking Screen Actors Guild. Nispel
works for RSA U.S.A., a commercial production agency owned by Scott
and his brother, Tony Scott, the director of the movie ``Top Gun''
and the current film ``Where the Money Is.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike against the advertising industry by members of the
Screen Actors Guild, known as SAG, and the American Federation of
Television and Radio Artists began on May 1. Some 135,000 actors
belong to the unions.
</P>
<P>
   In the advertisement, under the picture of an aging woman's
pendulous breasts, the text read: ``In South Africa, this is what
SAG means.''
</P>
<P>
   Outrage over the advertisement prompted actors and
representatives of the NAACP to protest in front of RSA's offices
in West Hollywood on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Anne-Marie Johnson, a television and film actor who chairs the
equal employment opportunity committee for the screen actors, said
the advertisement showed ``the lengths that certain companies will
go to attract nonunion work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This company felt very comfortable using racism, ageism, and
sexism to promote business and to attract advertisers,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the protest, the Scott brothers apologized for a ``huge
mistake'' by their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew absolutely nothing about this advertisement,'' they
said in a statement, ``and are as upset, sickened and appalled by
this situation as anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson pointed out that the Scotts had waited three days
after the advertisement had appeared to express their regret. ``I
think they apologized too late,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of National Advertisers and the American
Association of Advertising Agencies disavowed the advertisement,
saying it did not represent the industry's views.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Independent Commercial Producers, the largest
trade organization for the television commercial production
industry, blamed the tensions caused by the strike for the
advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the association, Matt Miller, said:
``Commercial producers are in a position where they need to work.
We're in a time right now where emotions are running very high.''
</P>
<P>
   The central issue in the strike is how to pay actors for their
work in commercials. The actors want to be paid each time a
commercial is shown on network television and want to extend that
practice to cable television. Advertisers want to replace ``pay for
play'' with a flat one-time-only fee for both network and cable
spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0281 </DOCNO>
