<SLUG> BC-RAC-BEST-BETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHERE TO INVEST IN A RUNAWAY MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ So you think one of these Kentucky Derby also-rans
or one of these over-hyped newcomers can shoot the winged horse out
of the sky? That's certainly the way to bet, because you can't do
much with a 2-5 shot, but is it the right mentality?
</P>
<P>
   In other words, do you bet against the best horse just because
he's a poor investment? A lot of people do, and a lot of people
will Saturday in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the previous three Kentucky Derby winners was nearly
as talented as Fusaichi Pegasus, yet all went on to win the second
leg of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   However, none went off as the betting favorite, and Charismatic
became the longest-priced Kentucky Derby winner ever to take the
Preakness, returning a staggering $18.80 on a $2 win ticket.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we got to the Belmont Stakes, the doubting Thomases,
including yours truly, believed. Charismatic tragically broke down,
but still managed to finish a courageous third as the 8-5 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   We also should pay some attention to recent history, which tells
us the last non-Derby starter to win the Preakness was Deputed
Testamony, way back in 1983. That's a tough nut to crack for the
likes of Red Bullet, Snuck In, and Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an occasional intrusion in the exotic wagers by
Preakness horses who skipped the Derby. Badge, for instance, ran
third at 58-1 last year, and Classic Cat was third at 12-1 the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   But the three years before Classic Cat, the top three finishers
all were Kentucky Derby runners, including 1996, when Louis
Quatorze scored a rare wire-to-wire victory in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it appears that the only thing that can beat
Fusaichi Pegasus is the unfamiliar and possibly wet track at
Pimlico, or the scant two weeks since his Derby coup.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly expect a good performance by Captain Steve, who was
wiped out by Wheelaway in Kentucky, and High Yield, who simply
hates Churchill Downs. Impeachment benefited from a crazy pace in
Kentucky and passed tired and underbred colts there. Hal's Hope
would be an unlikely turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Of the newcomers, Red Bullet certainly merits serious
consideration, especially with Jerry Bailey riding. His speed
ratings have been climbing steadily, he's had five weeks off, and
he is a son of Unbridled. But let's not forget that Pegasus buried
him in the Wood by 4 1/4 on a wet track _ and we may have a wet
track Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Snuck In and Hugh Hefner are a cut below the rest of the field,
and don't appear to have the speed or staying power to pose a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   We don't expect to match the $66 exacta or the $435 trifecta we
got in the Derby, but what the heck. The picks: Fusaichi Pegasus,
Captain Steve, Red Bullet, High Yield.
</P>
</TEXT>
