   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Washington) _ Little-known Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y.,
jumps into the race against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton for a
Senate seat from New York, quickly filling a political vacuum
created by the withdrawal of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from
the showcase contest. By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Paducah, Ky.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
campaigning in Kentucky, urges older Americans to volunteer as
after-school tutors in the nation's schools. The Republican
presidential candidate also defends his plans to change Social
Security. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-DEFICIT-CHINA (Washington) _ Democratic Reps. David Bonior
of Michigan and Dennis Kucinich of Ohio say granting permanent
normal trade relations to Beijing would heighten the U.S.-China
trade deficit that reached $5.1 billion in March. Proponents of the
permanent trade measure argue that the deficits will decrease as
barriers to imports into China are dropped. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-SPLIT (Washington) _ As the China trade bill nears a
pivotal House vote next week, the contentious split over the issue
is reflected in the firmly contrasting positions of two Michigan
congressmen _ Republican Dave Camp and Democrat James A. Barcia.
Camp is strongly for the bill; Barcia, strongly against. By JUDY
HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAILWAY-KILLER (Houston) _ Prosecutors provide a stream of
witnesses who talk about Angel Maturino Resendiz's threat to
society. Relatives of some of the nine people he has confessed
killing also testify as jurors weigh a sentence for the Mexican
drifter in the rape and murder of a Houston physician. The
convicted murderer continues to say he would prefer execution to
life in prison. By RAD SALLEE.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ The shuttle Atlantis and
seven astronauts head for a rendezvous with the international space
station, where the crew will make repairs. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BEARS-DNA (Glacier National Park, Mont.) _ Clever scientists
have come up with a new grizzly bear census in Glacier National
Park by using DNA in bear hairs. Based on the new technique, the
bear counters estimate that there are 332 grizzlies in the park,
located in Northwestern Montana. By comparison, a 1970 census based
on bear sightings came up with an estimate of 200 bears in the
park. By The Hearst Newspapers. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-PREAKNESS (Baltimore) _ One of the great sensory experiences
of racing is turning for home in the Kentucky Derby with the wind
in your face and the wall of sound rolling like thunder from the
throats of 150,000 fanatics. Kent Desormeaux, the jockey who will
ride Fusaichi Pegasus in the Preakness on Saturday, lives for the
moment. By JIM DENT. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-FUSAICHI-PEGASUS (Baltimore) _ Three horses won Triple Crown
winners in the 1970s, but the magic has been missing since.
Fusaichi Pegasus will be the savior that racing executives and fans
have been awaiting for 22 years if he can get out of Baltimore
unscathed in the Preakness and then win the Belmont Stakes. By MATT
GRAVES. (Already filed.)
</P>
