<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MINISTERS-WIVES0520-C     05-19 2692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINISTERS-WIVES0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Pastor's wife
 &HT;    By Kim Folstad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is a gleam in Andrea Gardner's blue
eyes _ a glow to her whole face, really _ when she talks about her
husband's recent call to become a clergyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that moment,'' she says. ``I just said. . . wow. I
had to let it sink in for a little while. But I was definitely
supportive of that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, she expects her passion may be subdued at certain
stages along the way. ``I know there are going to be
disappointments, trials,'' Andrea, 35, says. She and her husband
are, after all, very new to this. Boynton Beach Baptist Church just
opened in September, and there's no telling when the pastorate will
become Ron Gardner's full-time job. He was and is a teacher. So is
Andrea.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, she says, they've really been preparing for this
ministry all their lives _ albeit unknowingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord will lead. This is his idea, not ours,'' Andrea says
and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He equips the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Esther Ilnisky smiles, too, when she talks about life as a
pastor's wife. But she'll speak plainly about the pressures as well
as the pleasures of the job.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Bill, has been a minister since before they were
married 46 years ago. They have been at Lighthouse Christian Center
International in West Palm Beach for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for a second'' has she regretted her decision to share his
life's work. ``I've wondered. I've questioned,'' Esther says. ``But
I've never doubted.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are other jobs that aren't so life-altering or
time-consuming. The pay isn't great and the boss is awfully
demanding. And there are always those fawning female fans with whom
men of the cloth _ and their wives _ must contend.
</P>
<P>
   But William Ilnisky promised her an adventure, and she got it.
And she made the best of the situation, developing her interests
within the church and outside of it. She found her own place _
founded her own ministry, in fact, with The Esther Network
International and Children's Global Prayer Movement. She has her
own office at the church, a new book (''Let the Children Pray,''
Regal Books), even a new Web site (www.cgpm.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a personal calling myself to be in God's service,''
Esther says. ``I've complemented my husband's work while at the
same time, he has released me to do what I want, to follow my
dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed, and the role of the reverend's wife has
evolved. Thank goodness, says Mami Hampton-Kisner.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, is wise to the wishes of church congregations. But
during the four-plus years her husband, Gerald Kisner, has been
pastor of Tabernacle Missionary Baptist Church in West Palm Beach,
Mami has managed to find a way to keep everybody pretty happy.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in the church; her godfather was a preacher. ``I had
seen the commitment pastors' wives make,'' she says. So she knew
what she was getting herself into when Gerald told her that he had
decided to give up his career as a successful attorney to become a
minister. When he gave her some time to consider whether she still
wanted to join him in life's journey, she took more than a month to
rethink his marriage proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, finally, was yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `OK, Lord, if this is the path, let's go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The path.
</P>
<P>
   It has its share of bumps, says Dale Wolery, a California pastor
and executive director of the Clergy Recovery Network. Wolery and
his wife travel the country offering workshops to clergy couples
who must deal daily with loneliness, stress, low pay and the
pressure to live up to others' high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The main complaint? The pastor is still seen by many as a sort
of superhero _ the collared crusader, if you will. And, too often,
his wife assumes the role of the superhero's unknown assistant,
working diligently to make sure he looks good, the house looks
good, the church runs smoothly and the children behave.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the phone rings, the right reverend flies off to the
rescue _ always with a purpose, usually to great praise. Meanwhile,
his steaming spouse must stand in line behind everybody else vying
for her husband's attention. And unlike other jobs, it's tough to
ask him to say no when the hours get out of hand, Wolery says.
``It's hard to say, `I really need you,' when your husband is
serving God and building a church.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger and resentment boil below the surface in many ministers'
marriages, he says. And it takes a toll: The divorce rate for U.S.
pastors has risen 65 percent in the past 25 years, while the
overall divorce rate in the United States has been declining since
1981.
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 survey taken by the Christian journal Leadership found
that 94 percent of ministers feel pressured to have an ideal
family, and 77 percent of their spouses felt pressured to be an
``ideal role model for the Christian family.'' Although more wives
are declaring their independence _ dealing with and delegating
church duties on their own terms _ many still allow themselves to
be overworked and marginalized, Wolery says.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the role of the pastor's spouse is
so often ill-defined, he adds. ``The pastor gets a job description.
His wife doesn't. The pastor goes to his board. Where does the wife
go? Wives don't even have a forum for discussing expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolery agrees with a 1997 survey by the Episcopal Church, which
found that clergy wives who are employed outside the home were
better able to set and maintain boundaries between home and church
than those who aren't. According to the study, working wives still
volunteered in their husband's church activities, but they enjoyed
it more. ``They get a sense of self,'' Wolery says. ``And that
identity helps them navigate the tricky workings of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many churches continue to expect a two-for-one deal: When
they hire a pastor, they count on his wife to serve as music
director or secretary or nursery school supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing if she chooses the job,'' Wolery says. ``It's
another if she feels it's been forced on her.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to imagine Esther Ilnisky ever chilling in
someone else's shadow. Now in her 60s, she is a petite and pretty
free spirit, a nationally known force in the growing movement
empowering women of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ilnisky says it's his wife's charisma _ and her
unconventionality _ that makes her so popular with his
congregation. Forget the image of the matronly minister's wife with
her white shoes, white gloves, white hair and pursed lips. Esther
is warm and worldly, she speaks her mind and she loves her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They enjoy it when she's (in church),'' Bill says. ``When she
disagrees with something I say, she lets everybody know it. People
watch for her reaction. She adds some spice to the service in that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the two agree, it wasn't always so. When they were at a
rural church in Indiana, many years ago, Esther struggled with the
expectations of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd have interviewed my wife then, you wouldn't find the
same woman you see now,'' Bill says. ``She would go ballistic.
Sociologically, it was more than she was capable of dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Life was easier for Esther when they were missionaries in
Jamaica and Beirut, where there weren't as many preconceptions
about what she should or shouldn't do. When they came back to the
United States, she says, ``I didn't know what the rules were for
being a pastor's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, she didn't own a proper dress. And though she was
interested in her husband's church, she wasn't prepared to take on
a set of preordained hostessing duties just to keep the members
satisfied. ``I just loved the people. But that wasn't enough for
some,'' Esther says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the missionary mind-set, a broader view. I wasn't
totally engrossed in the congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   It took time, but Esther learned to deal with all those watchful
eyes. And, along the way, she and her husband became determined to
make the most of living life in a fishbowl. Instead of trying to
hide Esther's individuality or their need for time together _
particularly when their daughter was small _ the Ilniskys decided
to set an example with a lifestyle that put family first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for some of the women whose husbands are really dug
into their work,'' Esther says. But it's a mistake, she adds, to
expect him to change, and whining only makes things worse. Sure,
she's been known to lose her patience, particularly when the same
person calls again and again, then doesn't heed the counsel her
husband offers. But she understands it's his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a pastor's heart,'' she says, ``He's a coddler, I'm a
pusher.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of feminism. Not from Gardner or Ilnisky or
even the hyphenated Hampton-Kisner. But they all speak about
knowing independence, using their own gifts, and making the role of
pastor's wife fit them instead of trying to squeeze into some dated
two-dimensional image. If they aren't torchbearers for the cause,
they have at least benefited from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, people played fake roles,'' Mami says. ``They
were somber, bland, they wore old clothes. And if that's who you
are, that's fine. But. . . ''
</P>
<P>
   It definitely is not who Mami Hampton-Kisner is. A public
relations and marketing expert, she is outgoing, sophisticated and
busy with her own causes, which range from raising money for
nonprofit organizations such as Hope House to running political
campaigns. Standing on the steps of her husband's church on Eighth
Street, she points to the surrounding neighborhood and talks about
her hopes for the future of the community. This is her outreach.
</P>
<P>
   Loneliness? Resentment? ``He gets home before me, sometimes,''
the fortysomething Mami says and grins. ``I don't sit idle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be allowed to do what they have a passion for,''
Gerald Kisner says. And that goes for both the pastor and his wife.
``We've made it clear that Mrs. Kisner will do what Mrs. Kisner
wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, she's the pastor's wife. But she's also a member of the
congregation,'' he says. And she shouldn't be expected to do
anything more or anything less than others in the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding something she enjoys and making it her contribution to
the church _ that may be the key to happiness as a minister's
spouse, says Janice Hildreth, editor of the online newsletter ``The
Pastors Wife'' (www.pastorswife.com). If she follows her heart,
she's less likely to burn out, Hildreth stresses. And in the long
run, she's going to be of much more help to her husband and his
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The role of a pastor and his wife is to lead the church and to
teach, she says, and, ``If you're doing everything, no one's
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Ilniskys and the Kisners have found members who are
willing to take on the duties traditionally assumed by or assigned
to the pastor's wife. Esther plays the piano and works with the
``praise team'' that performs at each service, but she is not the
star of the show. She's not even the co-star. And when she's away
on business with her own ministry, she says, they certainly can go
on without her.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Mami. Instead of choosing just one church job
_ or trying to do all of them herself _ she says she spreads
herself around, doing a little something with each group. She also
makes a point of sitting in a different pew every Sunday, so she
can get to know all the members. ``My talent is people,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She will not, she maintains, take an assigned role just because
``that's what man expects you should do.'' Her concern is what God
wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never seek a way to be a pastor's wife,'' Mami says. ``The
Lord helps me do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, her husband's congregation is established, and there
are plenty of people to share the work. It's not nearly so simple
at a smaller church, and, Hildreth says, the majority of pastors'
wives are dealing with congregations with fewer than 150 members.
Churches such as Boynton Beach Baptist, which had 25 to 30 regulars
at last count, have different needs. ``In a small church, everyone
has to work,'' Hildreth says.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone notices who's not working _ particularly if it's
the pastor's wife.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, ``Miss Andrea'' bids farewell to ``Pastor Gardner''
and takes her three children _ 8-year-old Austin, 5-year-old Amanda
and 2-year-old Avery _ along with the other little ones in the
congregation to children's church.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Gardner used to teach English and drama at Berean
Christian School. Now, she's a full-time mom and she home-schools
Austin and Amanda. Putting together a Sunday school lesson each
week is time-consuming, but she says she doesn't worry about taking
time away from her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave a lot of thought to the kids,'' Andrea says,
acknowledging the pressure that will come with being the pastor's
children. ``God has called them as well as us. They're excited
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she also helps her husband set up every week in the
cafeteria at Crystal Lakes Elementary School _ where the
congregation sits on folding chairs and the sound system must be
tweaked before each sermon _ Andrea spends most of her time with
the children, making crafts and teaching Bible verses.
</P>
<P>
   This is her ``main ministry,'' and one part of being a pastor's
wife for which Andrea believes she is especially well prepared. As
the congregation grows, the politics of pleasing everyone will get
more complicated, she knows. But she intends to stick with what
works for her.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she will play hostess. Of course, she will be her
husband's ``helpmate.'' But, she says, she plans to capitalize on
her God-given talents as she takes on those new duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is not to say, `Oh, I hope I said the right thing to
this woman this week,' '' she says. ``My motive is to please the
Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Andrea plans to be a friend to the women who join the
church, and not the overworked martyr or the wrist-rapping
headmistress of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   That's a positive trend many churches are seeing, Hildreth says.
Next to dealing with the expectations they assume the membership
has for them, she's found the most common complaint among
ministers' wives is loneliness and isolation.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be a sort of an unwritten rule, passed down from one
pastor's wife to the next, that they weren't to get too close to
other women in the congregation, she says. Clergy spouses were to
ignore the inevitable church gossip, avoid any signs of favoritism
and hold themselves up as a worthy representation of godliness.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, the first ladies of the church are learning
that spending time with women with the same interests and
commitment to God is good for them. By getting close and, on
occasion, showing their warts, Hildreth says, they're able to
``show how grace saves.'' And the blessing of never being put on a
pedestal is that you can't fall _ or be pushed _ off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're accepting of everyone, they're accepting of
us,'' Esther says.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it's about finding balance, the pastors and their wives
agree. Yes, the minister's spouse does have to be aware of her
position, and she has to be able to develop a sensitivity to the
people in the pews, Gerald Kisner says. ``There's a certain
graciousness people expect from a pastor's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   But you also have to give the members of the congregation a
little credit, his wife adds. ``They realize how it is. They have
careers too.''
</P>
<P>
   And for every negative, there are is this positive: ``You're
constantly around someone who tries to walk with Jesus,'' Mami
says.
</P>
<P>
   That the walk turned out to be a lifelong mission has been more
blessing than burden, these ministers' wives say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a Sunday morning thing,'' Andrea says. ``This
is not just a job and it happens to be in the `religion' category.
This is our whole life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He equips the call,'' she repeats and beams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't resent it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
