<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0454 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ALA-CHURCH-BOMBING-11     05-19 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-CHURCH-BOMBING-1180(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS TRACE LIVES OF SUSPECTS IN CHURCH BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Thomas E. Blanton Jr. should not get
claustrophobic in his cell in the Jefferson County jail. At 8 feet
by 10 feet, it is roomier than the ramshackle 5-foot-by-10-foot
trailer in nearby Fultondale where he lived before surrendering
Wednesday on murder charges related to the 1963 bombing of
Birmingham's 16th Street Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred and fifty miles away, near Payne Springs, Texas,
Bobby Frank Cherry's own trailer, substantially larger and neater
than Blanton's, now sits empty as its former occupant also has
taken up residence in an isolated cell here. Nearby homeowners
cannot fathom how their good-natured neighbor, an avid fisherman
who was always willing to lend a hand with a project, could have
been involved in one of the most heinous crimes of the civil rights
era.
</P>
<P>
   For 37 years, Blanton and Cherry have lived their lives, perhaps
always looking over their shoulders but only rarely concerned that
they would ever be charged with the murders of the four black girls
who died on Sept. 15, 1963. They have been suspects almost since
the beginning, and they have been interviewed and trailed and
reinterviewed over the years as investigators dusted off their
files and made another run.
</P>
<P>
   But until this week, the authorities never seemed to pose much
of a threat to the two old Ku Klux Klansmen, and so they carried
on. They saw the South change around them, or at least much of it.
And they had little choice but to sit and watch as eager young
prosecutors and investigators responded to pressure from black
leaders just as their predecessors had responded to white
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton, a 61-year-old loner, filled his time with a series of
jobs as a security guard in the Birmingham area, one of them at an
upscale subdivision known as Liberty Park. He lost several jobs,
sometimes when word of a new investigation would hit the papers,
and he would grumble that the publicity had cost him a paycheck,
said Wyman S. Lee, himself a former Klansman and a longtime friend
of both men.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton earned a juris doctor degree in 1980 from the
unaccredited Birmingham School of Law, but never passed the bar
exam, blaming that failure on the influence of civil rights figures
in the state bar association, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he was charged, Blanton had been working for three
years as a sales associate for a Wal-Mart store in suburban Hoover,
just south of Birmingham. A Wal-Mart spokesman said he worked in
sporting goods, where the shelves are stocked with shotguns,
hunting knives and fishing lures. This week he was suspended
without pay.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry, 69, who now has heart disease and diabetes, moved to
Texas in the 1970s shortly after Bill Baxley, Alabama's attorney
general at the time, reopened the investigation into the church
bombing. That inquiry resulted in the murder conviction of Robert
Chambliss, the presumed ringleader and the only man previously
charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the trail ran dry and Baxley left office before he could
pursue indictments against Blanton, Cherry and Herman Cash, the
three other men named as suspects in early FBI files. Cash died in
1994, and Chambliss died in prison in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry has worked as a welder, carpet cleaner and truck driver.
He reportedly has married five times and fathered 15 children, and
his estrangement from some members of his family is at least partly
responsible for his current problems. Several relatives and former
relatives, including an ex-wife and a granddaughter, have said they
told a grand jury that Cherry had boasted about playing a role in
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember him bragging about it once or twice,'' said
Teresa Stacy, Cherry's 24-year-old granddaughter, who spoke in a
telephone interview on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Willadean Brogdon, who was married to Cherry from 1970 to 1972,
said that Cherry pointed out the church to her once. ``He said that
was the place he had bombed,'' she said, also in a telephone
interview on Thursday. As their marriage deteriorated, Brogdon
said, Cherry would threaten her: ``He used to tell me if I ever
talked, the same thing would happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of Brogdon and Stacy echoes that of Chambliss'
wife and niece, both of whom played a role in providing information
to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss' niece, Elizabeth Cobbs, testified at his 1977 trial
that on the day before the explosion he had pointed to a newspaper
story about school desegregation and said: ``You just wait until
after Sunday morning and they will beg us to let them segregate.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanton and Cherry were indicted on Tuesday by a state grand
jury after a nearly four-year reinvestigation, conducted primarily
by the FBI and the U.S. attorney's office here. They turned
themselves in to authorities on Wednesday and are now in jail
without bond. Through their lawyers, both have proclaimed their
innocence, as they have since first being identified as suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton has long been suspected of using his two-tone 1957
Chevrolet, with a Confederate flag flying from the antenna, to
drive the three other men to the church, where they planted the
bomb on the night before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here on Wednesday, Doug Jones, the U.S.
attorney, and David Barber, the Jefferson County district attorney,
declined to discuss what roles they believe the two men played and
what evidence they would present.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, all four suspects in the bombing were
members of Eastview Klavern No. 13 of the United Klans of America.
Neither Blanton nor Cherry had ever been prosecuted for any
race-related crime. But FBI files from the original investigations,
which are now archived at Birmingham's public library, characterize
both as rabid racists of the head-knocking variety.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton is the son of Thomas Blanton Sr., known as ``Pops,'' one
of Birmingham's most notorious white racists. The FBI files state
that he was born in Washington, had a 10th-grade education, and
served as an aircraft mechanic in the Navy from 1956 to 1959. He is
divorced and has one daughter, according to Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The files include an account of an interview with a woman who
said she was riding with Blanton in the early 1960s when he veered
toward a black man who was crossing the street. The man dived out
of the way and narrowly missed being hit, the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Eddy, a former state investigator who spent years on the
bombing case, said in an interview that Blanton would go into
grocery-store parking lots and put some sort of acid on the seats
of black people's cars so it would burn their skin when they sat
down.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry grew up in Mineral Springs, Ala., had an eighth-grade
education, and served in the Marine Corps from 1957 to 1959,
according to the FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   While Blanton's voice is rarely heard in the files, Cherry comes
off as vociferously unrepentant. One report states that he
``admitted to agents firing his rifle at Negroes outside his house
within the past two months.'' When investigators asked him about
the Aug. 20, 1963, bombing of a black civil rights leader's house,
he ``recalled saying to himself, `I hope it killed him.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Baxley, the former attorney general, said in an interview that
Cherry was ``a bully and a total liar.'' Blanton, he said, was ``a
little bit different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His dad was so bad,'' Baxley said. ``The worst racist in this
city was Chambliss, but the runner-up was Pops Blanton.'' Baxley
said he felt ``a twinge of sympathy'' for the younger Blanton,
because with the racism he learned from his father, ``how else are
you going to turn out?''
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Blanton asked Lee if he could put his tiny
trailer on Lee's one-acre plot behind a cement plant in Fultondale.
Lee, who lives in his own trailer on the land, is a plumber, and
the lot is strewn with junk cars and broken toilets. Lee said that
Blanton's trailer has no running water or plumbing. Blanton stores
belongings in a decrepit Dodge station wagon parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Though they live only yards from each other, Lee said he does
not see Blanton often. ``He comes and goes,'' Lee said, adding that
Blanton sometimes stays with his daughter. ``He stays to hisself,
pretty quiet, and never makes any trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry had been living with his latest wife, Myrtle, amid
winding roads and thickly forested hills in Esquire Estates, a
rambling collection of mobile homes just outside Payne Springs,
Texas. Their large blue trailer, with a wooden porch and a few
attached outbuildings, is neatly kept with potted plants hanging
from the porch rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors described Cherry as helpful and friendly. ``When I got
sick with cancer, he and his grandson came over and replaced all
the carpet in my living room,'' said William K. Turner, who has
lived next door for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The two men enjoyed drinking coffee together on the porch in the
mornings. ``In all that time I never heard him talk about racial
stuff or politics,'' Turner said. ``He said one time that he used
to be involved in politics, but that was all he said.'' He added:
``I don't know if I'll ever see him again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
