<HEADER>
A0466 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS &LR;      05-19 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE ATLANTIS BEGINS MISSION TO SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ After a dawn liftoff Friday, the shuttle
Atlantis sped toward the uninhabited international space station,
finally successful in a fourth attempt to begin an urgent repair
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Thundering from NASA's Kennedy Space Center, Atlantis climbed
steeply into a moonlit Florida sky, kicking off a two-day pursuit
of the orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The seven astronauts were on course to rendezvous with the
station late Saturday, and were to dock just before midnight CDT.
</P>
<P>
   High winds at the shuttle's emergency runways in Florida, Spain
and Morocco thwarted three attempts to begin the planned 10-day
mission late last month. Wind problems for another rocket earlier
this week bumped the fourth attempt by the shuttle another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our way,'' cheered Atlantis commander Jim Halsell as
the mission's fortunes finally changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew plans to deliver more than a ton of supplies
and equipment to the station, including four large storage
batteries for the faltering Russian power system; electronic gear
to repair a wavering American communications system; and enough
fuel to gently boost the altitude of the slowly sinking outpost by
nearly 27 miles with the shuttle's steering jets.
</P>
<P>
   All of the work is intended to prepare the orbital facility for
the overdue arrival of the Russian crew module in July and of the
first resident crew of astronauts and cosmonauts in November.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Halsell are pilot Scott ``Doc'' Horowitz, mission
specialists Jeff Williams, Jim Voss, Mary Ellen Weber, Susan Helms
and Yuri Usachev, a Russian cosmonaut.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a 42-year-old Army officer and the crew's only rookie,
is scheduled to join Voss, a 51-year-old former Army aviator, late
Sunday for a near seven-hour spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   During the excursion, the two men plan to re-secure a wobbly
American cargo crane on the exterior of the station and continue
the assembly of a similar Russian cargo transport device.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and Russian space agencies started what was to be a
six-year orbital assembly effort for the station in late 1998 by
coupling a Russian-built power, propulsion and guidance module
called Zarya with Unity, an American-made hub equipped to receive
future components.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two compartments form a 77-foot-long passageway
intended to interconnect future crew quarters, life-support
systems, laboratory modules for scientific research and solar-power
generation equipment.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the first pair of modules were joined, Russia's crew
module was to follow in seven months.
</P>
<P>
   That appointment came and went as a new roadblock arose. Russia
experienced back-to-back failures of its normally reliable Proton,
the rocket that is to launch the crew module into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the two coupled components have been inactive since
June. At that time, a shuttle crew dropped off hundreds of pounds
of supplies for future resident astronauts and cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   As the delay in the crew module grew, the Zarya module's
half-dozen power storage batteries began to falter.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a temporary increase in solar activity has caused
wisps of the Earth's atmosphere to balloon higher in altitude. The
frictional drag of the blooming atmosphere is causing the orbital
outpost to descend between one and two miles each week.
</P>
<P>
   Both the impaired power system and the loss of altitude are of
concern to NASA, which serves as the managing partner for the
16-nation station assembly project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battery situation has the priority. Reboost is important,
but we are at a point where we want to get the electrical system
totally up and running,'' said NASA's Robert Cabana, the station
program's manager of international operations.
</P>
<P>
   A minimum of three batteries must function to ensure a crew
module linkup.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial boost in altitude from the shuttle will also
conserve fuel aboard the station.
</P>
<P>
   While inside the station, the shuttle crew will also install new
fire extinguishers, replace 10 smoke detectors and install new air
circulation fans in the Russian segment. They will leave exercise
and computer equipment, clothing and water for future resident
crews.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, six U.S. and Russian station construction missions
are scheduled through December, a doubling of all previous
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The project's global backers envision the fully assembled
station as a state-of-the art orbiting science laboratory for
cooperative research in a range of scientific disciplines,
including physics, biology and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the Atlantis crew into orbit on Friday was a
replica of the Olympic torch. The symbolic torch and a flag to
commemorate the competition will be delivered to Sydney, Australia,
site of the 2000 Summer Games, after the shuttle returns to Earth. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
