<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 230.
WASHINGTON, May 19 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: GUNS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday passed, 50 to 49, a non-binding
resolution that commends the efforts of last week's Million Mom
March and calls for further action on stalled gun control
legislation by Memorial day. That gun control legislation, which
would require background checks for all gun-show sales, child safty
devices for handguns and a ban on high capacity ammunition
magazines, was passed in the Senate last year but has not been
delivered to the House. Supporters said that in the wake of the
massacre at Columbine High School, the new gun laws are long
overdue. Opponents said the gun control advocates were trying to
force a vote on a divisive issue in an election year. A ``yes''
vote supports the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 53 to 47, a measure to remove a
provision from military spending bill that would set a deadline for
withdrawing American troops from Kosovo. Supporters said setting a
date for removing troops from the area would put them at greater
risk and give Yogoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic the victory
he seeks. Opponents said the U.S. was mired in an endless conflict
and that President Clinton had recklessly placed troops there
without congressional approval in the first place. A ``yes'' vote
favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) N N
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) N N
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday rejected, 250-166, a measure to streamline
the congressional budget approval process by restricting emergency
spending, reviewing entitlement programs, and giving the president
a stronger role in writing spending bills. Supporters said it would
prevent government shut downs and last minute negotiations that
often end up favoring the president's spending priorities.
Opponents said it gave too much power to the president and would
end up creating more problems. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 264-153, a measure that would
require U.S. troops in Kosovo to begin withdrawing by next April
unless NATO allies start taking on a larger share of military
responsibility in the region. Supporters said NATO allies should be
providing more military and financial support for peace-keeping
operations. Opponents said the measure could imperil the peace
process at a critical time. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: GUNS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved a provision to a larger Defense
authorization that allows the government to purchase guns from all
gunmakers, not just those that adopt new safety measures. The
authorization passed 353 to 63. Supporters said they wanted to
prevent the president from circumventing Congress by enacting the
policy. Opponents said eliminating the policy would mean gun makers
have no incentive to make safer guns. A ``yes'' vote favors the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
