<HEADER>
A0492 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-REPUBS-NY     05-19 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS, DEMOCRATS PREPARE FOR GIULIANI'S REPLACEMENT IN SENATE
RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York state Republicans rushed Friday to ensure
that the party could still mount a serious challenge to Hillary
Rodham Clinton following New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
protracted exit from the Senate contest, rallying around the
candidacy of a little-known Long Island representative as they
contemplated a race whose every dynamic was altered in the space of
a single afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Gov. George Pataki, party leaders in New York and
Washington embraced the candidacy of Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island, proclaiming him an articulate and telegenic challenger to
Clinton. Lazio declared his candidacy in an e-mail to news
organizations as soon as Giuliani announced his withdrawal, and
moved to assemble a campaign staff, led by Michael Murphy, the
media consultant to John McCain's presidential campaign. And Pataki
said in an interview that he would personally assist Lazio in the
formidable task of raising money for his contest with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a political atmosphere that verged from carnival to chaos
throughout the day, there were sharply different assessments from
Republicans and Democrats about how Lazio (assuming that he wins
his party's support at the convention on May 30) would fare in a
contest against Clinton. But it was undisputed that this second-act
cast change would produce a profoundly different kind of race than
would have been presented by Clinton and Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a battle between two celebrities _ candidates
about whom almost every New Yorker had fixed and often intense
opinions _ is now shaping up as a contest between a famous first
lady and a congressman who is barely known outside Suffolk County.
And what had been a competition between two people with fairly
similar views on issues that tend to be determinative in New York,
among them abortion and gun control, is now between two candidates
who occupy starkly different places on the ideological spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans like Pataki, who was never particularly happy
with Giuliani in the first place, Lazio, he said, represented a
fresh and unencumbered challenger to Clinton. Pataki described
Lazio as a four-term member of Congress whose record could appeal
to moderate New Yorkers, an attractive television presence, and a
valuable base smack in the heart of the New York suburbs. Perhaps
even more significant, Lazio is not the polarizing figure that
Giuliani was, robbing Clinton of one of the advantages she enjoyed
in her contest with the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki _ who was once an unknown state senator from Peekskill,
bringing what many people viewed in 1994 as a far-fetched challenge
to Mario Cuomo _ chuckled at the notion that Lazio would be hurt by
his obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be a very strong candidate,'' Pataki said in the
interview. ``We will have a very good philosophical debate on
issues, with two candidates with competing philosophies. There are
no questions in my mind that the overwhelming majority of New
Yorkers will agree with Rick Lazio and not with Mrs. Clinton. Not
to mention that Rick Lazio is a New Yorker. He is one of us. He
doesn't have to learn what it is to be a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, Lazio was an untested and barely known candidate
with a conservative voting record, faced with the formidable task
of getting a full-fledged campaign organization financed and
running, and getting himself known to New Yorkers. And Clinton's
aides moved to define Lazio to New Yorkers before he could. They
noted that he favored a ban on late-term abortion and voted for
much of the Contract With America as they invoked his affiliation
with Newt Gingrich, the departed House speaker, and reprised a
tried and trued line of attack in New York, most recently in
Charles Schumer's successful challenge to Alfonse D'Amato in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani, for whatever vulnerabilities he had, did present a
problem for us in terms of having a relatively good record on
issues like abortion, gun control and the environment,'' Sen.
Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, the chairman of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, said in an interview. ``Now New
Yorkers will have a very clear distinction. He is a genuinely
conservative candidate. It's a fundamentally different race.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Rick Lazio is a clean slate that remains to be
written on. Hillary Clinton has the resources to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
