<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GIULIANI-SENATE0520-C     05-19 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-SENATE0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giuliani ends his senate race
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Dream Political Match-Up succumbed to cold, hard
reality Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ending weeks of speculation, New York City's embattled Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani announced he was dropping out of the U.S. Senate
race against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, aides and supporters packed into a
conference room at City Hall, Giuliani settled the question of his
immediate political future, although much about his personal and
professional life clearly remains in flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the right time for me to run for public office,''
said Giuliani, who seemed uncharacteristically reflective and even
gentle at times, occasionally ``shooshing'' overeager reporters
like a bemused parent. ``It's not . . . the right priority for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics isn't as important as I thought it was,'' continued
Giuliani, who had been under increasing pressure to make a decision
to give the Republican Party a fighting chance against the
well-known, well-financed first lady. ``I used to make many of my
decisions in the last 10 years around politics and I'm going to
make them differently in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The past three weeks had been uncharacteristically unsettling
for the often hardnosed mayor, known for vanquishing real and
perceived enemies ranging from Times Square porn purveyors to
thoughtless jaywalkers. Just days after revealing late last month
that he had been diagnosed with prostate cancer, the mayor stunned
reporters by announcing he was seeking a legal separation from his
second wife _ apparently without telling her first. That followed
soon after his admission of a relationship with a ``very good''
female friend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Giuliani said his public agonizing over whether to
stay in the super-stakes, high-profile race against Mrs. Clinton,
and his decision to back out, was almost completely due to his
health. Namely, it was his indecision over how best to fight the
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself unable to really make the treatment decision
yet, even though I've been over and over it,'' said Giuliani. ``The
decision on whether to run had me almost in the same position,
which has never really happened to me. I've always been able to
make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   No such hesitancy plagued Republican congressman Rick Lazio, who
immediately issued a short statement announcing his intention of
entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   Another New York congressman, Peter King, also had signaled his
desire to run if Giuliani dropped out, although Lazio appears to be
the choice of Gov. George Pataki and other leading Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state Republican convention will be May 30 in
Buffalo and the influential Pataki reportedly will endorse Lazio as
early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after Giuliani's announcement, Mrs. Clinton paused
briefly during a campaign appearance, telling reporters she had
already telephoned Giuliani to wish him well. She refused to
speculate about possible replacement opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty of time to talk about the issues and to
compare and contrast the issues between me and anyone else,'' said
Mrs. Clinton, who was nominated as the Democrats' candidate at
their state convention Tuesday. ``I think today we all ought to
just wish the mayor the best and let him know the people of the
city are behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent poll of New York voters conducted by Quinnipiac
College, Mrs. Clinton led Lazio by nearly 20 points in what was
then a hypothetical match-up. A 42-year-old fourth-term congressman
from suburban Sussex County, Lazio trails the first lady in name
recognition and, perhaps more importantly, in money.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have estimated it will take each party's candidate about
$25 million to compete for the seat being relinquished by retiring
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has raised more than $12 million, while Lazio had
only raised about $3.5 million before Pataki persuaded him last
August to defer the Republican nomination to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   And while the mayor had raised more than $19 million for his run
against Mrs. Clinton, only $2,000 of it could go to Lazio under
federal campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio carries little of Giuliani's political baggage,
particularly among women and minorities in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of voters in New York City who hate Rudy
Giuliani,'' New York magazine political columnist Michael Tomasky
told CNN. ``I can't think of any voters in New York City who hate
Rick Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the married, Catholic, suburban congressman may be in a
position to exploit Mrs. Clinton's perceived weaknesses in ways
Giuliani couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to say, `I'm a New Yorker. I was born here and I
live here. I'm one of you,' '' said CNN political analyst Bill
Schneider. ``That's going to be the Lazio message.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that was Lazio's message when he spoke briefly to
reporters a few hours after Giuliani's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been my lifelong home,'' Lazio said, adding that he
would have ``much more'' to say about his campaign in the next few
days. ``This is the state I've represented in the House of
Representatives for eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was first elected to Congress in 1994 as part of the
controversial freshman class that was fiercely loyal to then-House
speaker Newt Gingrich. Many political observers predicted Friday
that the first lady's campaign would attempt to paint him as a
right-wing extremist, in contrast to the more liberal Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of New Yorkers don't like the Republican Congress,''
said CNN's Schneider, pointing out that Lazio voted to impeach
President Clinton, something that might prove particularly damaging
to him in the New York metropolitan area. ``You can bet the first
thing the Clinton campaign will do is paint Rick Lazio as a loyal
lieutenant in the Gingrich Congress that went after her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
