u a BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-NYT &LR;      05-19 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HALF OF $363 MILLION LOTTERY IS CLAIMED  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A brewer and his family collected their half of the
$363 million Big Game lottery jackpot here Friday, after waiting
nearly two weeks to identify themselves as one of two winners of
the largest lottery prize ever awarded in America.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kainz, 64, and his wife, Sue, 62, of Tower Lakes, a
northwest suburb of Chicago, accepted their winnings Friday with
their three sons and daughter-in-law. The other winner, the owner
of a swimming pool company from suburban Detroit, stepped forward
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Kainz family owns and operates a small brewery and a medical
supply company in the Chicago suburbs. The Kainzes, along with
their sons, Michael, 34, Patrick, 29, and John, 26, and Michael's
wife, Jennifer, 29, had pooled money to buy 50 $1 tickets for the
May 9 drawing. They opted to take their money in a lump sum, worth
about $61 million after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Kainz, a regular lottery player, had purchased the tickets while
stopping by a service station in the nearby suburb of Mount
Prospect, to buy gas. The winning number was on the third line of
the fifth ticket he matched against the numbers printed in a
newspaper on the day after the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stomach retreated to the lower portion of my body,'' he
said, when he realized that he had won. He and his wife immediately
locked the ticket in a safe deposit box at a bank.
</P>
<P>
   Kainz Friday compared his family to that of the other prize
winner, Larry Ross, 47, whose children also work for the family
business. Ross also took his prize in a lump sum payment of about
$61 million, after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine weeks leading up to the winning drawing, 565 million
tickets were sold in Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts,
Michigan, New Jersey and Virginia the seven states that participate
in the Big Game.
</P>
<P>
   Kainz said he and his wife had no intention of retiring, but
instead would use some of their money to improve their businesses,
including the Wild Onion Brewing Co., which Kainz said is on
schedule to ``just break even'' this year. They will also replace
the leaky roof on their home and travel to Ireland and France, and
they said they planned to give away a lot of the money to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win something of this size _ I mean this is sheer
luck, any one of you could have won this,'' Kainz said, ``you've
got an obligation. Certainly we will be considering the many, many
things we can do for humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members said they had had difficulty keeping their win a
secret, especially once officials revealed that the ticket had been
sold locally. Kainz had a particularly difficult time when, on a
visit to her dentist, he jokingly asked if ``she had picked up her
lottery winnings yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I nearly bit off his hand,'' Kainz said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple went to Sweeney's Oil the day after the drawing, when
it was announced that the ticket had been sold there. They were
even approached by a television reporter, but declined to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have known they were winners all along, and have enjoyed
watching what has been going on,'' said Lori Montana, an Illinois
Lottery official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean to put any of you through any anguish,'' Kainz
told reporters, adding that he was trying to protect his family's
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Kainz was also standing in the crowd when lottery officials
awarded a $1.8 million commission check to John Sweeney, owner of
the station that sold the winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick and John Kainz, who are both single, joked that they
would probably be hearing from many of their old girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   But John Kainz had this message for them: ``Too bad, suckers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
