u a BC-FLA-RETIREES-SCHOOLS-     05-19 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-RETIREES-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA COURT RULES AGAINST IMPACT FEES FOR RETIREMENT
COMMUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Fla.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The Florida Supreme Court has ruled that the
developer of a retirement community does not have to pay fees
imposed by the county to defray the cost of school construction.
</P>
<P>
   Many communities across the country have imposed such one-time
assessments, called impact fees, so that developments help pay for
the additional services they require.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen Florida counties use the fees to raise about $71.4
million a year for new schools, according to the state's School
Finance Construction Commission. State officials estimate that
about $3 billion is needed annually for school construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Supreme Court ruled on Thursday that Aberdeen, a
mobile home community in Ormond Beach, 40 miles north of Orlando,
that prohibits children and requires residents to be 55 or older,
did not have to pay the fees because it would not require any more
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Volusia School District, of which Aberdeen is a part, must
now pay back $90,000 in fees and interest to the retirement
community. Aberdeen sued the school district in 1997, and a lower
court judge ruled earlier this year that Aberdeen residents did not
have to pay the fees.
</P>
<P>
   The case has generated interest nationally among home builders,
who have objected to impact fees for schools, utilities, roads and
other services. In Florida, those fees add $4,000 to $5,000 to the
cost of a new home, and Keith Hetrick, a lawyer representing the
Florida Home Builders Association, said that ``prices people out of
the market.''.
</P>
<P>
   California has the highest impact fees. In the Silicon Valley,
they can add as much as $30,000 to the cost of a new home, Hetrick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Shackford, a spokesman for the National Association of Home
Builders in Washington, said impact fees are an ``unfair burden''
for first-time buyers because they pay for services and facilities
that benefit the entire community.
</P>
<P>
   Shackford said many states no longer impose such school
construction fees on housing for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling will have a critical financial impact on school
districts that currently impose school impact fees,'' said Dick
Graham, a lawyer representing the Volusia School District, ``and
all other counties and school districts that may find the need to
impose a school impact fee as a means of raising funds for new
school construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Blanton, executive director of the Florida School Boards
Association, said counties have had doubts about the reliability of
the fees for several years. This case may lead to eliminating them
altogether, he said. ``For counties, they are going to have to look
at every project that goes up in the future,'' Blanton said, ``and
gauge whether it genuinely generates students.''
</P>
<P>
   Hetrick said Aberdeen residents would still have to pay property
taxes to the school district. ``People would like to think that
impact fees are not taxes, but they are,'' Hetrick said. ``They
have been sold to the public that these fees will solve our
problems, but they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hall, superintendent of the school district, said the
ruling separates the community. ``It allows a community of adults,
basically, not to have anything to do with children,'' Hall said.
``That's potentially disastrous in this democratic society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
