<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0519 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      05-19 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TELLS OF PLAN TO BOOST SENIOR CITIZEN VOLUNTEERISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PADUCAH, Ky. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush on Friday unveiled a
$290 million federal plan to boost senior citizen volunteerism by
paying more of their expenses and rewarding some of the most devout
volunteers with $1,000 trust funds for their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In the McCracken County Senior Center, where 350 elderly
citizens donate about 70,000 hours a year to help others, Bush said
he would target low-income seniors with his initiative. Many have
time and wisdom to share and more of them will be available to
volunteer as the baby boom generation ages, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Over five years, Bush's plan would add $240 million to existing
senior volunteer programs and $50 million to a new initiative. Bush
said a lack of money for training leaves many would-be volunteers
idle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's older Americans are the healthiest, the most energetic
and best educated generation of seniors in our nation's history,''
Bush told his bipartisan audience. ``You all are daily blessings to
this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also offered assurances that his plans to make fundamental
changes in Social Security were no threat to seniors. Vice
President Al Gore has assailed Bush's plans as too risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make this clear to everybody in this room that when
I become the president, nobody is going to mess with your benefits
in Social Security. This Social Security system will be safe, will
be strong and will be secure, and in this campaign, I'm not going
to let any Washington, D.C., politician scare you into thinking
otherwise,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   To promote volunteerism, Bush said he would ask Congress to
boost funding for the federal Senior Corps, a 27-year-old
public-private partnership that includes programs for foster
grandparents, senior companions for the homebound and mentoring of
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals as president will be to increase the
opportunities for seniors to volunteer, to tap that reservoir of
good will and experience and wisdom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, my administration will seek more funds for Senior
Corps, from $183 million to $250 million over a five-year period of
time. This increase of funding will allow for an additional 250,000
senior Americans to serve as volunteers under Senior Corps
programs,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many senior centers like this one in Paducah will be able to
expand their activities,'' he said. The remark drew the biggest
applause of the day for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also disclosed his intention to create ``Silver
Scholarships'' to spur volunteerism by older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A low-income senior who volunteers 500 hours will be eligible
for a $1,000 scholarship, which they can deposit into an education
savings account for their own children or grandchildren or another
needy child in their neighborhood,'' Bush explained.
</P>
<P>
   In his one-day swing through Western Kentucky in a tour bus,
Bush also dropped in on the lunch crowd at the busy Woodshed Pit
Bar-B-Que Restaurant in Hopkinsville, where Gore supporters greeted
him with signs saying ``Hands Off Social Security'' and ``Bush,
you've got a gambling problem.''
</P>
<P>
   They were reacting to Bush's proposal to modify Social Security
rules to allow workers to invest part of their payroll taxes in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Later he visited the Chevy Corvette assembly plant in Bowling
Green, where he greeted unionized workers and plant managers and
drove a car about 50 feet off the end of the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   In a new wrinkle to his grinding travel regimen, Bush's charter
jet dropped him off in Waco, Texas, so he could go straight to his
ranch in nearby Crawford. His jet and entourage continued to
Austin, the state capital. Bush returns to the campaign trail
Monday through Wednesday, traveling to Washington, D.C., Ohio and
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
