<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-VIRUS COMPANIES WARN OF NEW ROGUE PROGRAM'S DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anti-virus software companies on Friday warned of potential
damage from a new computer program circulating on the Internet,
similar to but more malicious than the one that disrupted computer
systems around the world earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the new program's ability to evade most of the
current anti-virus software, there were no confirmed reports of
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-virus companies said they had received reports of the
program from the United States, Europe and Israel after it emerged
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Computer Emergency Response Team Coordination Center at
Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh said late Friday afternoon
that it had received no independent confirmation of infections by
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Several anti-virus companies downgraded the threat of the new
program Friday afternoon after warning that it was a high risk
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said Friday morning that the FBI had
opened an investigation into ``a new, more destructive variant'' of
the rogue program that circulated worldwide early this month.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Vatis, director of the National Infrastructure
Protection Center of the FBI, said at the same briefing his agency
had received reports suggesting that more than 1,000 computers had
been infected. He did not cite the source of the information.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-virus software experts said that despite the similarities
between the new program and the earlier one _ which was borne as an
attachment to e-mail with the heading ``I Love You'' _ the new one
appeared to have been written by a more experienced professional
programmer and had been designed to thwart detection by anti-virus
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is this was written by an English-speaking
programmer, because of some of the variable naming conventions
inside the program,'' said Roger Thompson, technical director of
ICSA Labs, a research firm based in Reston, Va. The new program,
which researchers have named VBS/NewLove.A Worm, exploits the
Microsoft Outlook e-mail program to send itself to each person in
the program's address book.
</P>
<P>
   The program does several things to avoid automatic detection,
Thompson said. This capability has led researchers to define the
new program as polymorphic _ a type of software designed to escape
detection by popular anti-virus programs.
</P>
<P>
   The NewLove program searches the Windows operating system to
find the name of a recent document and then takes the name of that
document. It also places the phrase ``FW:'' and the document name
in the subject heading of the electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the program constantly changes its length by altering
the number of lines of code it is made up of, an effort to escape
discovery by anti-virus software that uses file size as a detection
signature. In all cases, the program, written in the Visual Basic
language, appends the extension .vbs to each document name.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, many corporate computer managers took precautions to
stop the transmission of the program by simply closing their
networks to electronic mail with Visual Basic attachments.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is more destructive than the earlier one,
Thompson said, because after mailing itself from a victim's
computer, it systematically overwrites files not in use on all of
the disk drives attached to the target computer.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, data on an infected computer and attached network disk
drives will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Several computer security experts said the new program
highlighted the shortcomings of much of the industry's commercial
anti-virus software.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the technology used to guard against viruses was
developed for a pre-Internet computer world where malicious
programs were largely spread via floppy disks at a much slower
rate. Today instantaneous communication via the Net has meant that
the virus detection software is quickly outraced by malicious worm
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call for people,'' said David Kroll, a
director at Finjan Software Inc., a computer security firm in San
Jose, Calif. ``The reactive database models of the anti-virus
software industry can never keep up with these new worms.''
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers said that operating systems vendors like
Microsoft should shoulder more of the responsibility for protecting
users against malicious software code. Last week, after many
computer users complained about their system's vulnerability,
Microsoft modified some security features of its Outlook program to
make it more difficult for computer users to be victimized by such
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly some and perhaps the majority of responsibility lies
with the operating system vendor,'' said Eugene Spafford, a
computer scientist at Purdue University. ``Why do we have operating
system vendors saying its a user problem and trying to absolve
themselves of the responsibility?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
