<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-ENVISIONING GRADUATE EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 21, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Graduation day! Bachelors of arts and of science have begun
streaming out into the world to find their place in it. In terms of
our shared economic future, however, the graduates who are most
interesting are those completing, not their 16th year of formal
education, but their 21st, 22nd, 23d year in school _ in other
words, the PhDs.
</P>
<P>
   In this high-tech age, to a greater extent than ever before,
PhDs have become the people who make the future, inasmuch as they
create the new knowledge upon which economic growth depends. Now
the system that makes the PhDs is changing faster than ever, too,
thanks to technology.
</P>
<P>
   What could be done to improve it?
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends on who you ask. After all, graduate education
is an industry of remarkable complexity.
</P>
<P>
   There are the research intensive universities; the rest of the
higher education system, including liberal arts and community
colleges; and the K-12 schools that prepare the young. There are
the doctoral students themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There are government agencies that subsidize the students,
businesses, and agencies that recruit them; the disciplinary
societies and educational associations (the American Chemical
Society, for example) that exist to strengthen professional
cohesion among them; and the foundations, which foment change.
</P>
<P>
   That is why 150 high-powered educators and technocrats
representing these eight core constituencies gathered in Seattle
last month at the invitation of the Pew Charitable Trusts and the
University of Washington for a conference on ``Re-envisioning the
PhD.''
</P>
<P>
   After three days of hashing over the matter in ways designed to
produce the greatest possible consensus, Jody Nyquist, director of
the university's Center for Instructional Development and Research
and the principal organizer of the conference, said, ``It's a good
start. There's a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, almost everyone realizes that competition is at the
heart of the success of the US system of doctoral education. The
creation of the land-grant universities in 1862 ranks as one of the
most inspired acts of public policy in US history. The monopoly of
the old schools and the East Coast was broken; soon the Ivy League
was running hard to remain on top.
</P>
<P>
   But laissez-faire is not necessarily an all-or-nothing
proposition. Robert Weisbuch, president of the Woodrow Wilson
National Fellowship Foundation, told the gathering in Seattle, ``It
isn't about tearing down this loose structure but about making it
stronger, most particularly through asking it to see and understand
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   If the conference identified a single overarching problem, it
had to do with the lack of information in the system. Lots of
students go to graduate school without even knowing how long it
will take, never mind their job prospects when they are done. Their
choice many be informed by nothing more substantial than the latest
ranking of graduate departments in US News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Freeman, a Harvard economics professor, told the meeting
that when he assigned a graduate student to apply to the leading
programs in science and engineering, he found that information
about the distribution of salaries of graduates was virtually
impossible to obtain. Business schools and law schools routinely
furnish the information on first or second request but PhD programs
profess ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   This will change. Charlotte Kuh, executive director of the
Office of Scientific and Engineering Personnel of the National
Research Council, told the meeting that the new NRC rankings of
university departments, due in 2005, would weigh factors other than
research dollars and reputations. By eliciting information about
the satisfaction and success of recent graduates, the NRC ranking
would give a much clearer picture of differences among graduate
departments.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Web-based bulletin boards, such as Tomorrow's
Professor, maintained by Stanford University's learning laboratory,
The Next Wave (for scientists), at PhDs.org (for engineers), help
fill in the blanks.
</P>
<P>
   Better information may also increase the pressure on
universities to come up with a shorter, more intensive PhD. Perhaps
the most successful curriculum reform was to standardize medical
training as a four-year postgraduate degree, with specialty
training to follow. Why not try to compress the learning required
to master physics, chemistry, biology, mathematics, or computer
science to four or five years _ with postdocs specializing in
research, teaching, or industrial work, according to their
interests?
</P>
<P>
   No suggestion was heard more frequently than that the pattern of
funding graduate students be changed to give more money to students
in the form of portable scholarships. Currently professors control
most of the federal subsidies to higher education through their
administration of large research grants. Student must focus on the
topics the professors want to cover. The result: newly minted PhDs
with exceedingly narrow research interests who, according to
industrial research managers, require immediate retraining before
they're ready to work.
</P>
<P>
   Another gripe: New scientists are ill-prepared to talk to those
outside their immediate fields. Chemists are at ease only with
other chemists, not with molecular biologists or process engineers.
A taste for interdisciplinary work needs to be built into graduate
work. So does a taste for diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Professionals talk about the reform of graduate education the
way the rest of us talk about the weather. Not so the
techno-politically-connected ``re-envisioning'' caucus. Their next
step is to seek a national task force to review opportunities for
reform in the Age of the Web. Look for the drumbeat to grow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-19 1608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVORING PEDRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have seen a lot more than we have, and their collective
advice is to sit back and enjoy. Hurricane Pedro is something
special to be savored. To get a better idea of the greatness of
Pedro Martinez, we spoke with a group of former players and
managers who span the last 50 years of Major League Baseball, in
both the American and National Leagues. Carl Yastrzemski, Jim
Lonborg, Dick Radatz, Joe Morgan, and Sam Mele have seen the best
of the best in the last half-century, and they feel Martinez is at
the top of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzemski: ``Pedro has as many ways to get a hitter out as any
pitcher I've ever seen. I thought (Bob) Gibson, (Sandy) Koufax,
(Ron) Guidry, (Denny) McLain were the best I've faced. Koufax had
the fastball, curveball. Gibson had the fastball, slider. Pedro has
five different pitches. Gibson and Koufax were power pitchers.
Everything was hard. Pedro has the power, but has the off-speed
stuff they didn't have. Gibson and Koufax came right at you. Pedro
can do that, and then get you out with finesse. He's a tremendous
finesse pitcher. The most important thing about pitching is
control. The thing that makes the greatest difference in pitching
is the ability to throw with all of that power to great spots. When
Guidry was going good for the Yankees, he had terrific control. He
could set you up with pitches to tough spots and then get you out
with a rising fastball just out of the strike zone. McLain never
missed a spot. Of the guys I have mentioned, McLain is the most
like Pedro. He had power, he had finesse. It would be impossible to
be better than Pedro is right know. The hitters don't have much of
a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonborg: ``I was thinking the other day . . . Have I seen anyone
better than what Pedro has been the last couple of years? I thought
about what (Orel) Hershiser did when he threw all of those
scoreless innings. That was the epitomy of consistency, throwing
all those innings, shutout after shutout. What Pedro is doing now
is phenomenal. I love the fire he pitches with. That incident (in
Cleveland for which he was suspended) didn't bother him. He came
back pumped, with fire in his heart. I like his aggressiveness. He
goes right after the hitters. Koufax was the best pitcher I ever
saw. He was dominant when he was at his best. I couldn't believe
Gibson could throw as hard as he did with such great control. With
Pedro, a hitter can never feel comfortable. He can work all parts
of the plate. In and out. Up and down with such great command of
his pitches, that it is impossible to feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sox manager Morgan: ``Right now, Pedro is as good as
anyone who has ever pitched. He's got the speed, the stuff, and the
best straight change I have ever seen. If you are lucky enough to
get your bat on the changeup, you just run down to first base and
take a right turn. Pedro is a lot like Juan Marichal. They both had
many ways to get a hitter out. Marichal threw five different
pitches from five different angles. You never knew what to expect.
You couldn't guess with him. Most guys just have two pitches, so
you could guess what was coming and get lucky once in awhile. You
couldn't do that with Marichal, and you can't do that with Pedro.
Gibson was the most intimidating pitcher I've ever seen. He was
devastating. I loved two lefthanders, (Warren) Spahn and Johnny
Podres. Spahn had unbelievable control. He didn't throw that hard,
but he had a great screwball, and that's the one he would set you
up for. I swear he would throw two fastballs and make sure they
were balls, and then when you thought he had to come with another
one, he threw that screwball and he had you on a ground ball.
Podres was very underrated. Great fastball. Great straight change.
I loved the straight change. It's a dynamite pitch. I don't know
why more guys don't use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mele: ``Pedro has it all, and I like the way he pitches with
such great flair. He is sort of like Gibson in that way. They both
would look at you after they struck you out as if to say `You
really didn't think you were going to hit me, did you?' I don't
care what you have for stuff, you have to have control to be a
great pitcher. The thing that separates most of the great ones from
the rest of the pack is the great fastball, with movement and
control. When I played in the American League there was a pitcher
on Detroit, Virgil Trucks, who could throw as hard as anyone, but
he couldn't win. His fastball was straight. No movement. But after
awhile he learned to cut it, and get it to move, and he started to
win. These kinds of pitchers, with the fastball and control, set
you up, and then get you to chase the high fastball out of the
strike zone. They know how to use that `out' pitch to their
advantage. Pedro is fun to watch. He's really something when he is
in trouble, and works his way out of it. Koufax was the toughest I
ever hit against. I got a double off him once down the left-field
line, early in his career. Years later I was managing Minnesota and
we played against the Dodgers in the World Series. Sandy wouldn't
pitch the first game due to a Jewish holiday. But he won two games
in the Series and beat us, 2-0, in the seventh game. I've always
said, if I had another Jewish holiday in the right place, we would
have beat them that year. After the final game, I walked under the
stands and Sandy was standing in the doorway. He looks at me and
says: `10 years ago, in Ebbets Field, you hit a double off me down
the left-field line.' I couldn't believe he could ever remember
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz: ``Outside of Marichal, he's the only guy I've ever seen
who can get you out with more than two pitches. Pedro has fastball,
curve, and the best change I've ever seen, and the ability to throw
them at any point in the count. It doesn't matter if he's ahead of
the batter or behind, he'll throw any pitch he has at any time, to
a spot where he wants to throw it. And when a pitcher is like that,
he is impossible to hit. The toughest pitcher I ever faced was
Koufax. I remember one time playing against him in a spring game in
Arizona. I came up to the plate and John Roseboro the catcher says
to me, `We're going to give you two fastballs, and a curve, and
then you sit down. I was a pretty good bunter, so I decided I was
going to bunt. I tried to bunt the first pitch and it almost
knocked the bat out of my hand. On the third pitch, I swear I heard
it break. Roseboro says to me, `Have a nice summer.' We should all
enjoy what we have in Pedro. Someone like this doesn't come along
often.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins sent an old knee brace worn by Ray Bourque to Denver
this week for him to wear in Friday night's playoff game with
Dallas. Bourque suffered a knee injury two weeks ago, in the same
spot he was hit 12 years ago by the Rangers' Michel Petit. Bourque
missed 20 games then and wore the brace from time to time for
protection. There has been speculation in the Bruins ranks that if
Bourque has stayed out of the lineup the last two weeks, he must
need surgery. However, Bruins president Harry Sinden, who had the
brace shipped to his former star, doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player has a serious knee injury, you don't send him out
to practice in full pads,'' Sinden said. ``Ray has been working in
full pads. My guess is that he took a good hit on the knee,
probably extended it, but that it is nothing serious.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bourque left Boston, he said he didn't know if this would
be his final year. Apparently, it is not. Bourque recently told
someone close to him that he is going to play next year and wants
to play for Colorado. Ray will be a free agent at the end of the
season. However, he wants to stay with Colorado and there is
already an understanding that he and his agent, Steve Freyer, will
talk contract with the Avalanche at the end of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have a slim chance of getting into the top three
when the NBA's annual draft lottery takes place Sunday, and most
likely will end up in the No. 11 slot. At this point, general
manager Chris Wallace thinks the team could be looking at one of
the following players as a possible pick: Jerome Moiso, 6 feet 10
inches, UCLA; deMarr Johnson, 6-9, Cincinnati; Morris Peterson,
6-7, Michigan State; Mike Miller, 6-8, Florida; Erick Barkley, 6-1,
St. John's; or a 7-2 center from Greece, Tsakalides Iakovas . . .
When Joe Bellino out of Winchester was winning the Heisman Trophy
at the Naval Academy 40 years ago as the best college football
player in the land, he was idolized by the son of one of the
coaches at the school. At graduation, Bellino autographed his hat,
to be worn and thrown in the air at graduation, and gave it to the
kid when the day was over. Bill Belichick still has the hat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I still think the best deal Dan Duquette has made is Heathcliff
Slocumb to Seattle for Derek Lowe and Jason Varitek. But think
about this one. Mo Vaughn for Brian Daubach. When Vaughn opted for
$13 million a year with the Angels, becoming at that point Mo
Money, the Sox signed Daubach as a free agent. Since the start of
1999, here are the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Name ! Avg. ! HRs ! RBIs ! Salary &QL; 
Money ! .286 ! 46 ! 145 ! $13 million &QL; 
Daubach ! .305 ! 29 ! 103 ! $390,000 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the money he saved on Money, Duquette could sign Jose
Offerman, Carl Everett, and Daubach for less than the Sox would
have paid to keep Mo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
