<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0556 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-PERSONAL-     05-19 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-PERSONAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A CHANGE IN GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rudolph Giuliani has often been called operatic, but
little in his past prepared the audience for Friday's performance.
It was a new character on stage: vulnerable, affectionate,
introspective, indecisive, apologetic to his enemies, more
concerned with being ``a better person'' than winning a political
fight.
</P>
<P>
   His enemies may doubt his conversion. One of his promises
Friday, to reach out to disaffected New Yorkers, was reminiscent of
the overtures he made to minority voters in his second inaugural
speech.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever he does the rest of his term, there was no
mistaking the change in Giuliani Friday. He started off sounding a
bit like Lou Gehrig in ``The Pride of the Yankees.'' ``I'm a very
fortunate man,'' Giuliani said in response to the applause that
greeted him. ``The reason I'm such a fortunate man is that I have
people that love me and I love them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there would not be ``a new Rudy,'' but then he promptly
talked about about becoming ``somebody who grows from the fact you
confront your limits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I understand myself a lot better,'' he said. ``I think
I understand what is important to me better. Maybe I'm not
completely there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't surprising to hear that intimations of mortality made
Giuliani reassess his life. But it was a shock to hear him confess
to a new sensation. For the first time, he had met a decision he
was having trouble making. For a moment he sounded almost like that
classic Hamlet on the Hudson, Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself unable to make, really make the treatment
decision yet,'' he said referring to his prostate cancer. ``And
about the decision to run, I was almost in the same position, not
being able to make it, which has never really happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his background as a prosecutor, Giuliani was
accustomed to making difficult decisions based on imperfect
information. Prosecutors, unlike politicians, are used to making
people unhappy. Giuliani prided himself on acting quickly and not
looking back.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked near the end of his second year in office to
name any mistakes he'd made, he could barely come up with anything.
He refused even to apologize for his endorsement of Mario Cuomo,
which left him politically isolated and unable to carry out some of
the most important reforms he had planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never revisit it,'' he said in October of 1995, a year after
the endorsement. ``You don't get the benefit when you make a
decision to know what you're going to know a year later. I made the
right decision based on the things that I knew at the time. I'm
actually proud of the decision, because it was an ability to take a
risk for what I thought was the good of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday he was having second thoughts about lots of things. He
promised to try to overcome ``the barriers that maybe I placed''
between himself and New Yorkers who didn't feel a part of the
city's good times. ``I'm going to dedicate myself to trying to
figure out how we can get them to feel that, too, including maybe
changes I have to make in the way I approach it, the way I look at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   How will the mayor's new persona go over with the public? The
reaction was mixed among an unscientific sample of people
interviewed on the streets of Brooklyn. Ken DiPreta, a writer out
walking his dog in in Cadman Park, was not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really pretty self-absorbed of him,'' DiPreta said, ``to
suddenly realize, `Gee, maybe I haven't exactly been nice to people
as mayor.' All of us knew that he was like that. So to hear him
discovering normal human kindness like it was some great new
invention seems a little strange.''
</P>
<P>
   But others were willing to cut the mayor a break. ``He suddenly
became human,'' said Quentin Arthur, a law student standing outside
U.S. District Court in Brooklyn. ``It's like tragedy had to strike
before he could see what he was like. I don't think it's an act. I
think he really probably does want to be a better person.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's new priorities have been obvious to city officials.
``There's been a lot of self-examination,'' Nicholas Scoppetta, the
commissioner of the Administration for Children's Services, said.
``What's quite remarkable is that he has done a good deal of this
in public, and his declarations of where he finds himself have been
public, too. I find it all very moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for him,'' Scoppetta said. ``He is going through an
extremely difficult time and doing it with the whole city watching
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's aides and friends have always said there's a softer
and gentler Rudy that the public never sees, and journalists have
always known that he can be charming when he sits down to dinner
with a glass of Chianti. But even at his most relaxed, even when he
was rhapsodizing about opera, he was not what you could call a
touchy-feely guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What moves me about opera is that you can express emotions in
a way that you can't when you just speak,'' he said one evening
five years ago after watching ``Tosca,'' but the emotions that
concerned him seemed to be mainly political. ``Tosca'' was one of
his favorite operas because it featured a struggle against
political evil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
