<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN BATTLING ON CENSUS RESURFACES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Partisan vitriol dominated a House hearing on the
census Friday, with Republicans suggesting that the Clinton
administration was trying to manipulate the count to benefit
Democrats, and Democrats insinuating that Republicans did not want
to count members of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations, at a hearing of the House Government Reform
Committee's Subcommittee on the Census, were not fresh. But the
testy exchanges came as the Census Bureau was poised to begin the
procedure that has most sharply divided the two parties:
statistical sampling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the pressure factor,'' said Chip Walker,
communications director for the subcommittee's Republican majority.
``We're right in the middle of the census, and crucial activities
are going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Kenneth Prewitt, the Census Bureau's normally reserved
director, got into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Republicans on the subcommittee made public a
memorandum from a midlevel Census Bureau manager telling
subordinates that daily progress reports ``must and cannot be
shared'' with investigators from the General Accounting Office. The
Republicans said this indicated that there were people in
``influential'' positions at the bureau who were trying to hide
what it was doing, and so were ``dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Prewitt angrily demanded an explanation Friday from
the subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla. Prewitt would
not relent even after the hearing had adjourned, instead
confronting Walker, the communications director. ``I want to know
who these influential people are and what is the evidence that they
are dangerous,'' Prewitt demanded.
</P>
<P>
   When Walker tried to offer an explanation, Prewitt responded
with an epithet.
</P>
<P>
   The feuding enlivened a dry, technical presentation of the
current status of the census and the bureau's plans to use
statistical sampling as a way to check to accuracy of the head
count and adjust the final totals.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials plan to collect data from a sample of 314,000
randomly selected households, and use that data to adjust
population totals for geographic areas as small as a city block.
The adjustment will increase the numbers of minority residents _
principally inner-city blacks and rural Hispanics, who are often
missed by traditional census methods. Democrats support the plan,
and Republicans oppose it, primarily because both sides believe it
will give Democrats an advantage during the process of redrawing
congressional districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
