<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0576 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-19 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ MUST TEMPER HIS TEMPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like ants or an eccentric aunt, the Portland Trail
Blazers will descend upon Shaquille O'Neal's crib today. They're at
Staples Center for two games against the Los Angeles Lakers and
O'Neal suspects they'll try to overstay their welcome.
</P>
<P>
   If he isn't extra vigilant, the Trail Blazers will end up taking
over the place, he just knows it. The gall of them! I mean, it's
not like he ever promised them a Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   How O'Neal wishes the Trail Blazers would get his hints about
when he has had his fill of them. Don't they ever wonder why his
elbows keep connecting with their chests?
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is not ribbing them, he's reminding them that they're
being a complete nuisance. Duh. How dense can they be?
</P>
<P>
   Why, if he could, O'Neal would plaster the players' entrance at
Staples Center with bumper stickers that are takeoffs of ones
showing up on the backs of Volvos everywhere in greater Portland:
``Welcome to Southern California. Now Go Home.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ask the Lakers' 7-foot center, the Trail Blazers might as
well be Tonya Harding. The way they beat him up, O'Neal wishes he
could obtain a restraining order to prevent them from coming within
500 yards of Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine O'Neal is the worst. Just because he shares Shaquille's
surname, he evidently has gotten it into his head that he can plant
himself in O'Neal's favorite spot, around the basket.
</P>
<P>
   When Shaquille already is there.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if he thinks Shaquille's personal space is his to share,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Neals nearly came to blows the first time they were
together in the ring, er, on the court, in November. The game was
in Portland and Shaquille got so tired of carrying his 330 pounds
around and Jermaine's, too_ my lord, you would have thought the
latter was a 226-pound backpack _ he dispensed with subtleties and
tried to tattoo the basketball onto Jermaine's chest.
</P>
<P>
   That earned Shaquille an early night. Since it was his second
technical foul in less than a minute _ he had shoved Jermaine over
another invasion of his personal space _ the Lakers' eighth-year
player and team captain was ejected. The Lakers, down by seven
points at the time, proceeded to lose by 15.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine played five minutes and picked up five fouls. Obviously
he wasn't in there to show Shaquille his jumper.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's numbers that night weren't as horrible as his mood. He
finished with 21 points. That was right around his four-game,
regular-season average against the Trail Blazers (20.5) but well
below his season average (30.1) against everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question, Jermaine O'Neal and his fellow forwards
Aryvdas Sabonis and Brian Grant can act on Shaquille's
concentration like a stiff breeze on a pile of raked leaves.
Goodness knows O'Neal's focus clearly was scattered in November
when he drew the two technical fouls and again in January when he
missed three foul shots out of four attempts in a four-point loss
to the Trail Blazers at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a coincidence that O'Neal averaged 2.5 fouls and shot
51.9 percent from the foul line in the Lakers' two victories in the
regular-season series. When he's tuned into the game, the Lakers
all are able to get on the same frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, when the Trail Blazers and Lakers meet today in
Game 1 of the Western Conference Finals, John Salley, the Lakers'
backup center, will help out O'Neal by screaming, ``Focus!'' until
he's hoarse if he has to.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal kids Salley that his voice is as grating as fingernails
on a chalkboard, but he takes Salley's message seriously. O'Neal
seconds what Jackson said of Jermaine O'Neal and Co. in November :
``They're not playing ball, all they're trying to do is knock
(O'Neal) out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy being the host with the most; the most bulk, the
most press clippings, the Most Valuable Player in the NBA trophy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal long ago stopped jawing at the officials for letting
opponents mug him in the paint with impunity. ``I'd rather save my
energy,'' O'Neal explained Friday after practice.
</P>
<P>
   The most he'll say, after a hack goes unpunished, is ``And
one.'' That's Shaq shorthand for ``the shot ought to have been a
three-point play.''
</P>
<P>
   A teammate said he once talked to the officials on O'Neal's
behalf. ``You can see Shaq's being hacked,'' the player recalled
saying. ``Why aren't you calling anything?''
</P>
<P>
   The official's reply was something along the lines of, ``Shaq's
so much bigger than everybody else, he ought to be able to handle
those fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions O'Neal has fed every frustration into a
flame that rages within. It provided the fuel for his MVP season.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers first-year coach Phil Jackson was the one who counseled
O'Neal to bury his emotions, the better to bury his opponents.
Indeed, O'Neal started referring to himself as ``The Big
Impervious'' after one of Jackson's lectures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Imperious,'' anyone? Jackson now wonders if it
wouldn't be better for O'Neal to set off a controlled burn every
once in a while in the hopes of avoiding a raging wildfire
somewhere down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He piles on (all the frustration) and loads up on it (and) it
wears him down,'' said Jackson, who doesn't want O'Neal saying or
doing anything dumb.
</P>
<P>
   He merely wishes he'd play his assigned role of prima donna with
a tad more conviction. You know, call the illegal defenses when he
sees them. Speak his mind on the worst of the uncalled fouls (but
never stop smiling). Let everybody know the Lakers are back, not
laid-back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see everybody of his stature going to the referees
constantly,'' Jackson said. ``He's one of the only guys in the
league at his level who leaves the referees alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Salley says O'Neal can afford to pipe up now because he has the
clout, after his play this season, to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make a difference when Shaq talks,'' Salley said,
``because he is who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is the league's MVP. As long as he remembers that's not
the Most Victimized Player, that's not the Most Volatile Player,
his house should be safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
