<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-RETAILER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SPORTING-GOODS STORE PROVES IT'S A KEEPER  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On a recent Saturday afternoon in San Rafael,
Calif., fly-fishing instructor Floyd Dean was expertly casting and
reeling, bending and swiveling at the edge of a 40-foot
demonstration pool.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty or so a-fish-ionados lined the pool, following his every
move. It is a rite of spring in this Marin County parking lot _ the
annual Fly-Fishing Fair staged by Western Sport Shop, just across
the street.
</P>
<P>
   First, Dean demonstrated the ``Wyoming cowboy,'' twirling his
rod in a lassolike motion above his head. ``This'n 'll get your
ear,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the classic ``willow cast,'' featured in the movie,
``A River Runs Through It.'' Twenty rapt heads followed every move
as the line plopped down gently at the end of the long pool.
</P>
<P>
   The fair, which includes fly-tying demonstrations and booths
with the latest fishing paraphernalia, is more than a sales
opportunity for Western. Special events like this differentiate the
53-year-old retailer from discount chains and other rivals. In this
era of intense retail competition, they help the independent shop
stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small market, so any new competitor who makes a serious
run at it will take some business,'' said Jim Edgar, who has owned
Western for the past 13 years with his wife, Judy. ``Their margins
will hurt and our margins will hurt. That's happened several times,
but then they go out of business and we survive.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to retail rivals, Western faces the challenge of
declining interest in fishing and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans who fished at least once in 1999 was 7
percent lower than in 1987, while hunting was down 33.4 percent,
according to the Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association. By
contrast, mountain-biking participation rose more than 400 percent,
and snowboarding jumped 124 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To counteract the downturn, Western offers frequent classes and
seminars on topics like bay fishing and fly-tying. (Flies are the
insectlike lures, typically made from animal hair and feathers,
that fly-fishers use instead of bait). For its lectures, Western
hires some of the biggest names in the esoteric world of
fly-fishing, like Lefty Kreh and Dave Whitlock.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Western's annual Waterfowl Day, featuring decoys,
shotguns, duck calls and other equipment, attracts flocks of bird
hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Mounted Heads, Bait and Soda
</P>
<P>
   The store itself, with its high ceilings and timbered paneling,
is a relic of the past. A piece of paper scrawled with the words
``Bait &AMP; Soda'' is taped to a refrigerator in the back. Mounted
heads of elk, deer and other game, many of them decades old, line
every wall.
</P>
<P>
   The heads ``are too big for most people to keep in their
homes,'' so customers store them at Western, said Judy Edgar.
``Sometimes customers come in to visit their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Western ``is not a slick place'' and that's not the goal, said
Jim Edgar. ``We like to provide a unique shopping experience in an
age when there aren't many.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its quaint decor, Western's merchandise selection is
considered one of the broadest and most up-to-date in the area. In
addition to equipment, it stocks more than 5,000 titles of new and
used outdoor books with titles like ``In Praise of Wild Trout'' and
``Lunker!'' (a type of bass).
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably four shops in California that are really
good and this is one of the best,'' said Robert Louis Stephens, a
fishing guide who manned a booth at the Fly-Fishing Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Western's customer service is old-fashioned, too, shoppers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are helpful,'' said Darren Hesse, who attended the
Fly-Fishing Fair. ``They tell you where the hot fishing spots are,
and their information is always good.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Western's employees receive commissions or any kind of
incentive pay tied to sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we think that's counter to the nature of the service
we're trying to deliver,'' Jim Edgar said. `It motivates people to
sell stuff customers don't need, and that's just not the kind of
store we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Western does give every employee Christmas bonuses, and managers
receive annual bonuses based on subjective performance measures,
but not sales, Edgar said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales on the Upswing
</P>
<P>
   Western, which occupies 5,000 square feet, has been riding high
for the past couple of years. Sales rose 13 percent in 1998 and 18
percent in 1999. Bay Area residents are flush with cash, and some
are now dropping $1,000 or more to get completely outfitted for,
say, a bone-fishing trip to the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Business hasn't always been so good. When the Edgars bought
Western in 1987, the store had been in decline for several years.
The fact that it still exists is a testament to the Edgars' love of
minding the store, rather than to its financial rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Western's founder, Gene Thompson, started the business in 1947.
It rapidly became a mecca for local outdoorsmen. He moved it to its
current space on Third Street from its original Hayes Street
location in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's daughter, Antioch resident Sandy Gangwer, remembers
that her father greeted every customer by name. A meticulous
merchant, he insisted that she arrange bait fish in perfectly
straight rows.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, Thompson sold Western to two longtime
employees. In the mid-'80s it was purchased by a
construction-company executive, Al Perini, who soon decided that
retailing wasn't his sport. By that point, the store had very
little inventory, its prices were a bit steep and it was losing
money.
</P>
<P>
   Perini mentioned his plan to sell the store to a fishing buddy,
Jim Edgar, a lifelong management consultant with no background in
retailing. The two were fishing for salmon at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar bit. ``I'll buy it,'' he told his friend. Today he notes,
``It was a decision of the heart, not the wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Edgars installed their son, Jim Edgar Jr., who had been
manager of a camera store, as Western's manager. Judy Edgar began
organizing events and publicity. Jim Edgar Sr. kept his eye on
finances without leaving his consulting business, Edgar Dunn &AMP; Co.,
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Phasing Out Hunting Gear
</P>
<P>
   The Edgars made significant changes in the first few years,
including reorganizing the floor plan, restocking depleted
inventories, hiring more staff and putting more emphasis on
fly-fishing. In its earlier incarnations, the store had focused
mostly on hunting, a sport that has been declining in popularity in
the Bay Area for years.
</P>
<P>
   When their son left Western in 1995 for another retail job, Judy
and Jim Edgar considered selling the store. But they were hooked.
They resolved to keep going and asked a longtime employee, Gene
Fassi, to manage day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues, which had doubled under Jim Edgar Jr., have risen
another 50 percent under Fassi. Fly-fishing is the fastest-growing
category; both hunting and other types of fishing are on the
decline.
</P>
<P>
   The Edgars' persistance has been rewarded with black ink for the
past three or four years, although profit margins remain thin,
under 5 percent. (They also own a fly-fishing specialty store in
Santa Rosa, Western Angler, which is profitable).
</P>
<P>
   Four-Day Weeks for Full-Timers
</P>
<P>
   Today, Western's biggest challenge is to find knowledgeable
employees with good people skills who are willing to work for a
retail wage, said Jim Edgar.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive, Western lets full-timers work 10-hour days,
four days a week _ a schedule that allows staff to spend three days
a week hunting and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Many new hires are high school students who work after school
and retirees looking for something to do a couple of days a week,
Edgar said. These folks don't demand high wages and the old-timers
have extraordinary stores of knowledge about local hunting and
fishing spots, Edgar said.
</P>
<P>
   Another looming challenge for Western is a 12-screen cinema in
the works for downtown San Rafael. The theater would surround
Western on two sides and engulf an adjacent parking garage used by
Western customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parking is already difficult in San Rafael,'' said Jim Edgar.
He expects Western to survive if the theater is built, but business
may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
