<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-NASDAQ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NASDAQ TAKES ANOTHER BEATING  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ That hissing sound you hear is the Nasdaq
composite index continuing to lose air.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-heavy Nasdaq fell 148.31 points, or 4 percent, Friday
to finish the week at 3,390.40 _ its first close below the 3,400
level since May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts are predicting that the Nasdaq could lose another
500 points _ or more _ before hitting bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, meanwhile, shed 150.43 points,
dropping to 10,626.85, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
dropped 30.26, to 1,406.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nasdaq has hit its high for the year,'' said Rao
Chalasani, chief investment strategist at First Union Securities in
Chicago. ``The market is unsupportable for technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wall Street's initial reaction to this week's
half-percentage-point increase in short-term interest rates was one
of relief that the bloody deed at last had been done, investors are
now fretting over what comes next.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve all but guaranteed that rates will go up
even more if the risk of inflation persists. Market watchers are
resigned to the almost certain prospect of another increase when
the Fed's policy-making committee meets again on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the consensus is that Greenspan &AMP; Co. are looking
to boost interest rates by another quarter-point. But some analysts
believe the Fed is ready to experiment with stronger medicine and
could jack up rates by as much as a full percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is very possible,'' said Douglas Cliggott, chief
investment strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities in New York. ``What
we've seen so far has done virtually nothing to slow things down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech and telecom stocks led the selling yesterday. Cisco Systems
was the most active Nasdaq stock, falling $1.94, to $53.44. Intel
Corp. also took it on the chin, declining $6.06, to $117.88, while
Hewlett-Packard Co. slid $5.50, to $126.19.
</P>
<P>
   In an example of that old saw about buying the rumor and selling
the news, telecom equipment-maker Ciena Corp. plunged more than 15
percent to $116.50 after reporting better-than-expected quarterly
earnings of $18.4 million (12 cents per share).
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the market to remain in the doldrums, rising a
bit here, tumbling again there, until next month's Fed meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sentiment on a day-to-day basis will keep swinging back
and forth,'' said Al Kugel, senior investment strategist at Stein
Roe &AMP; Farnham in Chicago. ``All this uncertainty is going to take a
couple of months at best to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   While he thinks most tech stocks remain overpriced, Kugel is
pointing clients toward financial services firms, which he said are
now trading at bargain levels.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan's Cliggott is adopting a more recession-ready
posture, focusing on companies that produce foods, beverages and
pharmaceuticals _ ``Things people will buy whether or not they have
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   One trend all analysts are taking note of is the absence of
investors spilling into the market in search of fire-sale
discounts. In the past, so-called buying on the dip was a hallmark
of the market and kept share prices from ever sinking too low.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like the only investor buying on the dip this week was
Prince Alwaleed bin Talal, the Saudi billionaire with a penchant
for U.S. tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   The prince said he had invested $1 billion in 15 U.S. companies,
including six Internet firms and two telecom ventures.
</P>
<P>
   These included separate $50 million investments he made in
bookseller Amazon.com, auctioneer eBay, investment firm Internet
Capital Group, discount reservation provider Priceline.com, content
producer InfoSpace.com and ad agency DoubleClick.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old prince, a nephew of Saudi King Fahd, also said
he has his eye on a number of other Net outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Does he know something that other investors don't?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say the party is over, but tech stocks won't see
the same kind of run-ups that we saw in '99,'' said John
Scarborough, a partner with the San Francisco investment firm of
Bingham, Osborn &AMP; Scarborough.
</P>
<P>
   His advice for investors is to maintain the long view and,
despite short-term market turbulence, to take solace that even the
beleaguered Nasdaq will likely be higher five years from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a huge mistake to bail out at this point,''
Scarborough said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
