<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURGENT IN PERU CALLS FOR ELECTION BOYCOTT
</HEADLINE>
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ A day after withdrawing from the Peruvian
presidential contest, Alejandro Toledo on Friday called for
peaceful demonstrations against the government to discredit the
vote scheduled for May 28.
</P>
<P>
   He also asked people to abstain from voting as a protest in
light of allegations of fraud that have tainted the initial round
of voting in April. Aides to Toledo, who has run a surprisingly
strong insurgent campaign, said his call would be the beginning of
a permanent civil disobedience effort he hoped would isolate and
discredit the government of President Alberto K. Fujimori, who is
seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   In Peru, voting is obligatory, and failure to cast a ballot
carries a fine equivalent to $35 _ a large sum in this poor country
_ though it has rarely been collected.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a 54-year-old, American-educated business professor,
announced his withdrawal from the May 28 election late Thursday
because he said he believed that the vote would be a fraud. On
Friday he conceded in another news conference that he has left the
path open for Fujimori to claim a new five-year term. But he also
suggested that his strategy was aimed at forcing Fujimori to hold a
clean election or risk becoming an international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to unleash the democratic forces of Peru,'' he
said. ``President Fujimori can declare himself the winner, but his
government will lack credibility and legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's aides said the campaign to discredit the election and
the government would include peaceful marches this weekend in Lima
and in provincial capitals around the country. Supporters set
bonfires at midday in the central plaza of Chimbote, a northern
port city where Fujimori was expected as he continued his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has refused to postpone the election, as Toledo
demanded after the publication of a report on Thursday by the
Organization of American States saying that it could not guarantee
a fair and clean vote on May 28 because there was insufficient time
to test a new computer program designed to count ballots. It also
asked that the May 28 vote be delayed for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he would not get back into the race unless the
election was postponed to June 18, and his campaign was given equal
time on all television channels and new poll-watchers were
selected.
</P>
<P>
   The April balloting was marred by charges of vote tampering and
campaign dirty tricks directed by Fujimori's intelligence agency.
The report by the Organization of American States questioned why
ballots and tally sheets disappeared for hours at a time after the
April vote, making it impossible for its monitoring group to
validate the results.
</P>
<P>
   If Fujimori continues to refuse to the postpone the May 28 vote,
advisers to Toledo said, the opposition forces will try to follow
the ``people power'' tactics that brought down the government of
Ferdinand E. Marcos in the Philippines in 1986. Those tactics
included strikes by trade unions as well as business leaders and
marches by students and peasants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make peaceful demonstrations, pacific resistance,''
Toledo said at the news conference, ``until there is a transparent,
clean election.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar campaign had begun immediately following the April
balloting, with thousands of university students and other
protesters filling city squares across the country protesting
allegations of fraud. The demonstrations stopped after three days,
when the government announced that Fujimori had fallen just short
of an outright majority and that a second round would be required
to decide the election.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign election observers say privately that the internal and
international pressures probably stopped the government from
declaring a first-round victory for the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
