<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      05-19 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GIULIANI STAYS AT CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, may 20:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's announcement Friday that he is bowing
out of the U.S. Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton marked a
decision that, once revealed, feels both correct and inevitable.
But no one could have predicted as recently as a few weeks ago the
degree to which the mayor who asks and gives no quarter would turn
his withdrawal press conference into an existential meditation on
life, love, mortality and priorities. It was, in its way, as
extraordinary a political moment as the Bryant Park press
conference of May 10, when Giuliani acknowledged the emotional
impact of his cancer diagnosis and surprised the city, and his
wife, by announcing the end of his 16-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   From the medical standpoint, Giuliani was right to allow himself
more time to choose between surgical and radiation therapies for
his prostate cancer. From the standpoint of party loyalty, he acted
unselfishly in saying he did not want to disappoint fellow
Republicans by finding in September that he could not sustain a
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the introspective, self-analytic quality of
Giuliani's remarks that was most striking. The press conference was
peppered with references to love, mortality, shaken confidence, an
unaccustomed difficulty in making decisions. Giuliani is not the
first middle-aged man to discover, under the shock of a threatening
diagnosis, that ``you're not a superman and you're just a human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is a middle-aged man with 19 months to serve as mayor of
New York City. While he dismissed talk of a ``new Rudy'' as silly,
he seemed to be taking a fresh look at his relations with the
city's minority communities and perhaps at the polarizing effect of
some of his statements on law enforcement. He spoke of overcoming
``barriers that maybe I placed there'' to making every New Yorker
share in the city's new spirit of optimism and prosperity. The
mayor even included a very un-Giuliani-like pledge to consider
``changes I have to make in the way I approach'' some issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics will say that by showing a softer side, Giuliani was
looking to prepare himself for future campaigns and to limit the
damage from his public romance with a single woman, Judith Nathan,
and his impending legal separation from his wife, Donna Hanover.
But the content of Giuliani's remarks should be taken on the
merits. He has made New York City safer and more efficient. If he
can spend the final months of his term healing racial tensions and
behaving in a less authoritarian way, that would give real depth to
his declaration of ``love for the people of this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's departure from the Senate race upends what seemed
destined to be a battle of political titans. But Clinton, the
Democratic nominee, would make a mistake to assume that her new
rival will not be competitive. For one thing, the campaign dynamic,
shifting from two strong characters to one, will make Clinton
herself a central issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Republican leaders seem to be rallying behind
Rep. Rick Lazio, who will bring energy to the task. Indeed, he
barely managed to muzzle his ambitions while Giuliani was the
party's favored contender. With his suburban base and conservative
views on social issues like abortion rights, he may win more votes
upstate than Giuliani. But with the mayor out, Clinton can aim for
an even bigger vote in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, for his part, has done everyone a service by making a
timely exit from a contest for which he no longer had an appetite.
Even his detractors will have to concede, too, that he gave New
York three weeks of political drama that no one is likely to
forget. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
