<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-NADAS-NYT &LR;      05-19 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NADAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER S. NADAS, TEACHER OF PEDIATRIC CARDIOLOGISTS, DIES AT
86 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Alexander Sandor Nadas, who trained generations of pediatric
cardiologists at Children's Hospital in Boston and at Harvard
Medical School, died on Tuesday at his home in Needham, Mass. He
was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Nadas, a longtime former resident of Wellesley, Mass., retired
in 1982 as chairman emeritus of the hospital's department of
cardiology and in 1984 as professor emeritus of pediatrics at the
medical school. He had been associated with Children's Hospital
since 1949 and was credited with helping build the department's
national and international renown for the care of children with
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Medical School and Children's Hospital honored Nadas in
1989 by establishing a professorship in his name. Just days before
he died, the American Heart Association gave him its Paul Dudley
White Award for his work as a pediatric cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   Nadas' research centered on cardiovascular physiology and the
physiology of congenital heart disease in children. He was the
author of hundreds of clinical research papers, and wrote four
editions of a textbook for medical students, Pediatric Cardiology,
first published in 1957 by W.B. Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   He was a past member of the editorial boards of Circulation, The
American Journal of Cardiology and the Yearbook of Cardiology. He
was active in various professional associations, and was president
of the American Pediatric Society in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Nadas was born in Budapest and graduated from Budapest
Medical School in 1937. He emigrated to the United States in 1938
to pursue his medical career, and trained in New York, Cleveland,
Boston and Detroit, where he received his medical degree from Wayne
State University in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Nadas then spent four years in private practice in Greenfield,
Mass. In 1949 he joined the staff of Children's Hospital. His
association with Harvard Medical School dated to 1950, when he was
appointed an instructor in pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Nadas' wife of 53 years, Elizabeth McClearen Nadas, died in
1994. He is survived by two daughters, Trudi Murch of Phoenix and
Betsy Seamans of Pittsburgh; a son, John A., of Wellesley, and
three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
