<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0629 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     05-19 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS HOPE SATURATION DEFENSE WILL CONTAIN O'NEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ What a daunting task: contending with all
that size, that muscle, the athleticism and the quickness. The
ability to fill the lane, deny access to the rim, contest every
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Some people would say it's a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Shaquille O'Neal certainly could have a rough time against
the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, the league MVP, is the biggest, strongest weapon in the
NBA and the Los Angeles Lakers' greatest asset, but he faces
perhaps his greatest challenge in the Western Conference Finals
that open today at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal gets not one huge body to fight through but two or three.
And Portland can reload with a frequency that no other opponent can
match: From Arvydas Sabonis and Rasheed Wallace to Brian Grant and
Jermaine O'Neal, the Trail Blazers can always send strength and
size in pairs.
</P>
<P>
   A daunting task indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got that size,'' said Lakers teammate Ron Harper. ``I
mean, they've got guys the same size as him, almost.''
</P>
<P>
   It has always been the teams that can double-team with two big
men (San Antonio, Sacramento) that fluster O'Neal, and Portland
might have done it best this season. In four games, he averaged
just 20.5 points _ his lowest output against any team that made the
Western Conference playoffs, and nine points below his season
average.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are skewed a bit by O'Neal's fourth-quarter ejection
when the teams met Nov. 6 at the Rose Garden, but even in the other
three games, he scored only 21, 17 and 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   That's no way to beat the NBA's deepest team. One way or
another, the Lakers know they will need O'Neal to score closer to
the 29.8 points he's averaged in playoff series victories over
Sacramento and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq will get more points this series,'' Harper said. ``I'm
sure about that. He knows we need him. And we're going to keep on
going to Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland knows it. And the Blazers are built to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense starts with the 7-foot-3, 292-pound Sabonis, who
is beefy enough to hold his position on the low post. Then comes
the help. The 6-11, 230-pound Wallace is one of the most agile
power forwards in the league and he's got a nice, long wingspan to
crowd O'Neal's sightlines and passing lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have a lot of big bodies and they do get away with
more banging than usual,'' O'Neal said, ``but we just have to play
through that and keep playing. . . . This is not a Shaq vs. Sabonis
thing. They have a deep team, they have a very talented team, so
it's vital that we take care of the ball, take high-percentage
shots and just play together. If we do that, we'll be fine. We
match up pretty well with this team and it's going to be an
exciting series.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sabonis gets in foul trouble, and he always does, the
Blazers turn to Grant, a mere 6-9 and 260 pounds but strong and
fearless. Jermaine O'Neal isn't the strongest of defenders, but
he's young, spry and 6-11, 248 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, Sabonis and the activity of some of the other guys
can cause him problems,'' said the Lakers' Derek Fisher. ``but I
think . . . we played them all four times so early in the season
that until that last time we defeated them (Feb. 29), we really
hadn't started to reach our peak as a team and develop our ability
to, when a team is taking certain things away or we're struggling
in a particular area, being able to adjust and still take advantage
of it. So I think we're a little smarter team now, where he might
not score 35 or 40 points, but we'll still figure out ways to make
sure that he's an effective part of our basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland has not only denied O'Neal points, it has taken away
opportunities. On average this season, he made 12 of 21 attempts
per game. But against Portland he averaged just 16 attempts and
eight made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've just got to stay with trying to get the ball
inside, be a little more patient on the offensive end,'' Glen Rice
said. ``I think Shaq is going to move a little bit more in the
paint so he can keep them off balance a little bit. . . . If he
struggles, we definitely have to be there to take up the slack. In
the past when he struggles, we tend to not do the things that we're
capable of doing. But rest assured, we'll be able to do it in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   But again, the burden will be on O'Neal to find his open
teammates. Adjusting and countering opposing defenses has become
one of O'Neal's strengths, much more so now than when these teams
last met two-and-a-half months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing a better job,'' coach Phill Jackson said.
``He's in and out. Against Phoenix, he had some real good reads and
did a real good job and other times, the last game he got a couple
passes blocked and they ran out (on fast breaks).''
</P>
<P>
   But can the Lakers beat the Blazers if O'Neal is held to 20.5
points a game? ``What did he get in Portland, 23 in a ballgame and
we won?'' Jackson said, referring to the Lakers' 90-87 victory Feb.
29. ``We'll find a way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
