<DOCNO> NYT20000519.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0635 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-REPUBS-1S     05-19 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-REPUBS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS, DEMOCRATS PREPARE FOR GIULIANI'S REPLACEMENT IN SENATE
RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (ADDS 600-word optional 2nd take, photo note)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT-18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York state Republicans rushed Friday to ensure
that the party could still mount a serious challenge to Hillary
Rodham Clinton following New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
protracted exit from the Senate contest, rallying around the
candidacy of a little-known Long Island representative as they
contemplated a race whose every dynamic was altered in the space of
a single afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Gov. George Pataki, party leaders in New York and
Washington embraced the candidacy of Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island, proclaiming him an articulate and telegenic challenger to
Clinton. Lazio declared his candidacy in an e-mail to news
organizations as soon as Giuliani announced his withdrawal, and
moved to assemble a campaign staff, led by Michael Murphy, the
media consultant to John McCain's presidential campaign. And Pataki
said in an interview that he would personally assist Lazio in the
formidable task of raising money for his contest with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a political atmosphere that verged from carnival to chaos
throughout the day, there were sharply different assessments from
Republicans and Democrats about how Lazio (assuming that he wins
his party's support at the convention on May 30) would fare in a
contest against Clinton. But it was undisputed that this second-act
cast change would produce a profoundly different kind of race than
would have been presented by Clinton and Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a battle between two celebrities _ candidates
about whom almost every New Yorker had fixed and often intense
opinions _ is now shaping up as a contest between a famous first
lady and a congressman who is barely known outside Suffolk County.
And what had been a competition between two people with fairly
similar views on issues that tend to be determinative in New York,
among them abortion and gun control, is now between two candidates
who occupy starkly different places on the ideological spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans like Pataki, who was never particularly happy
with Giuliani in the first place, Lazio, he said, represented a
fresh and unencumbered challenger to Clinton. Pataki described
Lazio as a four-term member of Congress whose record could appeal
to moderate New Yorkers, an attractive television presence, and a
valuable base smack in the heart of the New York suburbs. Perhaps
even more significant, Lazio is not the polarizing figure that
Giuliani was, robbing Clinton of one of the advantages she enjoyed
in her contest with the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki _ who was once an unknown state senator from Peekskill,
bringing what many people viewed in 1994 as a far-fetched challenge
to Mario Cuomo _ chuckled at the notion that Lazio would be hurt by
his obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be a very strong candidate,'' Pataki said in the
interview. ``We will have a very good philosophical debate on
issues, with two candidates with competing philosophies. There are
no questions in my mind that the overwhelming majority of New
Yorkers will agree with Rick Lazio and not with Clinton. Not to
mention that Rick Lazio is a New Yorker. He is one of us. He
doesn't have to learn what it is to be a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, Lazio was an untested and barely known candidate
with a conservative voting record, faced with the formidable task
of getting a full-fledged campaign organization financed and
running, and getting himself known to New Yorkers. And Clinton's
aides moved to define Lazio to New Yorkers before he could. They
noted that he favored a ban on late-term abortion and voted for
much of the Contract With America as they invoked his affiliation
with Newt Gingrich, the departed House speaker, and reprised a
tried and trued line of attack in New York, most recently in
Charles Schumer's successful challenge to Alfonse D'Amato in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani, for whatever vulnerabilities he had, did present a
problem for us in terms of having a relatively good record on
issues like abortion, gun control and the environment,'' Sen.
Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, the chairman of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, said in an interview. ``Now New
Yorkers will have a very clear distinction. He is a genuinely
conservative candidate. It's a fundamentally different race.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Rick Lazio is a clean slate that remains to be
written on. Hillary Clinton has the resources to do it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans across the state, who had waited with increasing
consternation for Giuliani to act, it was a day of relief, anxiety
about the future and occasional displays of irritation at the way
Giuliani had handled these last few weeks. In that time, he had
announced that he had prostate cancer; was involved with another
woman, an Upper East Side consultant for a pharmaceutical firm; and
was seeking a separation from his wife, Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been viewed with suspicion among Republicans since
he campaigned with Cuomo against Pataki in 1994. Giuliani's
announcement came so late that the Republican Party had already
printed thousands of ``Rudy'' placards for the convention at the
end of May, a point several Republicans noted acidly Friday. What
is more, Lazio is giving up a congressional seat that Democrats
could well capture in November.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the mayor has any interest in running for office in the
future is an open question, he said Friday. Giuliani's aides have
suggested that the mayor might want to run for governor in 2002.
They acknowledged that he has as much riding on Lazio's winning
this race as Lazio does himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot depends on what plays out,'' said Stephen Minarik, the
Republican Party chairman in Monroe County, discussing Giuliani's
future status. ``He is on tenuous ground with some Republicans
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's advisers Friday described Lazio's candidacy as
uphill, in no small part because of his late start. ``It's going to
be a very difficult campaign,'' a Giuliani adviser said. ``The
Clinton campaign has had a year's head start.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Clinton have each spent nearly a year setting up
the basic instruments of a campaign. Lazio needs to set up an
office, hire staff, and raise money; he has $3.5 million now,
compared with $9 million for Clinton. Presumably, Giuliani could
help in that regard, since he has $9.2 million on hand that could
be funneled through the Republican Party. The mayor said Friday he
wanted to help as much as possible, but would have to study the
financial and legal possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio does not have one of the main advantages that Giuliani
brought into the race against Clinton: the ability to draw votes in
New York City. He also has a long history of votes in Congress,
which Clinton's campaign has been cataloging for weeks now to use
in speeches and advertisements that will seek to portray him as ``a
foot soldier of Newt Gingrich,'' as one Clinton's aides put it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, running for Senate is entirely different than from
running for the House. Clinton has spent much of the past year
traveling the state, and the results of that are clearly apparent
in her increasing command of New York issues and ease on the
campaign trail, in contrast with her difficult start.
</P>
<P>
   This is Lazio's first statewide race for office, and he is not
going to have the luxury of time to learn the task, several
Democrats noted. And because he is the choice being offered by
Pataki and the state Republican chairman, William Powers, he is
vulnerable to portrayal by Democrats as the party machine
candidate, an attack that Cuomo sought to use against Pataki, who
was elected to a second term in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that, Lazio clearly comes into this with several
advantages, a point that many Republicans made throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in many ways, this is certainly not insurmountable,
and I think it presents Hillary Clinton with a whole new set of
problems,'' said Rep. John Sweeney, whose district stretches from
the Hudson Valley to the Adirondacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
