<P>
   (NYT18) OAKDALE, N.Y. -- May 19, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-REPUBS --
Congressman Rick Lazio, likely to assume his party's mantel in the
heavyweight Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton, wants the
job badly, but he wasn't anxious to talk about it. ``This is an
exceedingly difficult time for the mayor,'' Lazio said of Rudolph
Giuliani's announcement on Friday afternoon that he's bowing out of
the contest because of prostate cancer. Lazio and his wife,
Patricia, before a cancer forum in Oakdale, N.Y., Friday. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- May 19, 2000 -- PEACEKEEPING-U.S. --
Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., has singlehandedly blocked the United
States from paying $368 million that it owes the United Nations for
four of its most difficult peacekeeping operations, infuriating the
Clinton administration and some of its allies. Gregg during a
campaign rally for Gov. George W. Bush earlier this year. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SPRINGFIELD, N.J. -- May 19, 2000 -- EURO-TOURISM --
Iris Citron, president of Creative Travel, goes over a travel
itinerary with client Mark Lesser who is taking his wife on a trip
to France this August in celebration of their 15th wedding
anniversary. Like other American travelers, the Lessers are
reveling not only in their increased income, but also in their
incredible buying power abroad. (Nancy Wegard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 19, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS-5 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announces his decision to drop out of the
race for U.S. Senate, Friday. Giuliani, his political ambitions
derailed by prostate cancer and a split with his wife, abandoned
his Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton. (Frances
Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 19, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS-4 --
As Mayor Rudolph Giuliani stunned New Yorkers by dropping out of
the nation's most-watched Senate race, Hillary Rodham Clinton
wished him a quick recovery from prostate cancer and said his
withdrawal would not change her campaign tactics. Clinton during
her news conference Friday following Giuliani's official
announcement. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 19, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS-3 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announces his decision to drop out of the
race for U.S. Senate, Friday. Giuliani, his political ambitions
derailed by prostate cancer and a split with his wife, abandoned
his Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 19, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 21 --
SCANDINAVIAN-CHIC -- A fashion show featuring Swedish designers
last week which was part of a three-day exhibition of fashion, food
and design conceived by a magazine called Stockholm New. (Barbara
Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- May 19, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 21 --
SMALL-HANDBAGS-FASHION -- Designers have pounced on a new trend.
M.Z. Wallace and Burberry are among a number of companies that have
recently introduced or plan to introduce matched sets of handbags
meant for the woman who must have two. Burberry, left, has designed
a see-through tote that holds a smaller bag with its signature
tartan while M.Z. Wallace has added a pouch. (Tony Cenicola/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 19, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 21 --
SMALL-HANDBAGS-FASHION -- Designers have pounced on a new trend.
Tod's, Lambertson Truex and Burberry are among a number of
companies that have recently introduced or plan to introduce
matched sets of handbags, meant for the woman who must have two.
Frances Beatty Adler, an art dealer, lugs two bags to work, but
once in a while she stashes the tote. ``Sometimes I feel it's my
right not to be burdened,'' she said. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 19, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS-2 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has decided to drop out of the race for U.S.
Senate, and will call a news conference later Friday to detail his
decision, two aides to the mayor said. Republican leaders fretted
over who would take up the banner. Without Gov. George Pataki, who
is the strongest possible candidate, Republican leaders have given
the most attention to Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island. Clockwise
from foreground, President Clinton, Giuliani, Pataki and Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the Democratic nominee for the Senate, during
funeral services for Cardinal John O'Connor earlier this month.
(Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CONCORD, Mass. -- May 19, 2000 --
REFUGEE-SCHOLARSHIPS-BOS -- Few of the sons and daughters of Asian
immigrants who will pick up $1,000 scholarships in a ceremony at
the University of Massachusetts in Boston this weekend any idea
where the money is coming from, or why. Fumio Robert Naka was one
of the many Japanese-Americans held in camps in the United States
during World War II. (Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- May 19, 2000 -- AUTOS-CRUISER-BOS -- They seem
to appear by the decade: cars that capture American drivers and
their current lifestyles. Now comes the Chrysler PT Cruiser, part
truck, part minivan, part Beetle. Pedestrians in Boston get an
eyeful of the new vehicle. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEWFANE, Vt. -- May 19, 2000 -- NONCOMPETE-BOS --
Ex-Omega Optical Inc. workers who launched rival Chroma Technology
Corp. won a lawsuit alleging unfair competition filed by their
former employer. Front, from left: Lee Madden, attorney Heidi
Harvey, and Vim Auer. Rear: Paul Millman, Carolyn Fulford, Wendy
Cross, and Frank Kabbel. The suit, which sought an estimated $15
million in damages, argued trade secrets were used to launch the
rival firm. The case is being appealed. (Janet Knott/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 19, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-WITHDRAWS-1 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has decided to drop out of the race for U.S.
Senate, and will call a news conference later Friday to detail his
decision, two aides to the mayor said. Republican leaders fretted
over who would take up the banner. Without Pataki, who is the
strongest possible candidate, Republican leaders have given the
most attention to Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island. (Vic Delucia/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) RAMALLAH, West Bank -- May 19, 2000 --
MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-2 -- Palestinian police officers try in vain
