<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AARP0520-COX     05-19 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AARP0520-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AARP seeks diversity in its membership and its mission
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ They say the times they are a-changing for the
largest association of older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   This week the AARP held its 15th and likely last ever national
convention. Next week Bob Dylan turns 59 and the AARP embarks on a
mission to capture his generation _ one more interested in hip
topics than hip replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Like a divorcee bent on a new life, first to go was the name.
The American Association of Retired Persons recently became nothing
more than its acronym as the organization realized that almost half
of its membership was not retired and a good percentage wasn't
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are over the hill, we certainly have picked up steam
going downhill,'' said Horace Deets, the former Catholic
priest-turned-executive director of the 34 million-member AARP. He
delivered his address from the group's national convention this
week at the Orange County Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to the top of the hill for the organization is
storied, somewhat sordid history.
</P>
<P>
   AARP was founded in 1958 when a retiree named Ethel Percy Andrus
discovered that insurance companies discriminated against older
people, including friends from her own California Retired Teachers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Andrus soon found Palm Beach insurance magnate Leonard Davis,
who offered $50,000 in seed money that established Colonial Penn
Insurance Co. Millions signed up for the insurance with the
endorsement of the American Association of Retired Persons, and the
non-profit organization reaped benefits in the form of a royalty
that was then poured back into programs for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1978, a ``60 Minutes'' television report painted AARP as
a front for the insurance corporation and an outraged membership
subsequently dropped Colonial Penn for Prudential Insurance Co.
More recently, the organization has aligned itself with United
Health Care Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors are still drawn to insurance packages and discounts on
cruises and hotels but the organization acknowledges such ``member
services'' are no longer enough.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech before the convention last week, Deets noted that
AARP's potential membership base is expanding at the edges _ there
are ever-more people 50-plus on the horizon and more people are
living beyond age 85 every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge of the 21st Century is: What do we do with this
longevity bonus?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   About 18,000 seniors Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday used part
of theirs attending the convention _ billed as ``AARP Celebrates
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Most came to wander an exhibition hall largely filled with the
type of do-dads and giveaways that litter any corporate convention
hall. There were travel and insurance come-ons common of old-style
AARP gatherings. And salesmen hawked recreational vehicles, foot
massagers and vitamin caplets aimed at an aging population.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also a curious blend of new-age sights clearly
aimed at the 50-something market.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner, yoga instructor Ronni Diamond stood on one foot
to demonstrate how serenity can improve your golf swing. About 50
polo-shirted men and women hung on every word.
</P>
<P>
   Across the hall, acupuncturists competed for attention with
universities, each hoping to capture members' attention.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneous educational workshops included a ``baby boomer
track'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Social responsibility in a diverse world,'' with entertainer
Harry Belafonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making time for fun and frolic,'' with Dr. Ruth Westheimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discovering your entrepreneurial spirit,'' with ice cream
icons Ben Cohen and Jerry Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a misconception that this is a seniors
organization,'' said attendee Theresa Contino. ``We want to attract
younger people.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, most of the conventioneers appeared to be in their
60s and 70s. That may be because working men and women in their 50s
would have a hard time getting away for a three-day mid-week
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The organization not only wants to be younger, but also more
diverse. A number of high-profile presenters last week represented
ethnic minority groups, including poet Maya Angelou and Raul
Yzaguirre, president of the Hispanic National Council of La Raza.
Some say the effort has worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could count the blacks at the last two conventions,'' said
Sheryl Clayton, a black woman from East St. Louis, Ill. ``This is
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   There are currently 23 state offices but there will be one in
every state by the end of the year, according to AARP spokeswoman
Kathy Marma.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will change, too, Marma said. AARP hasn't yet set
a date or place for the next national convention, and Marma said it
likely will be replaced by a set of regional gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
