<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRADE BILL EDGES CLOSER TO APPROVAL IN HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mo., Mich., Calif., Colo., N.Y., Ohio, Mass., Ill., Fla.,
Ky.)  By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opponents of a decisive China trade bill refused to
admit defeat on Friday and vowed to step up their lobbying over the
weekend. But growing signs indicated that barring an unforeseen
shift in votes or provocation by Beijing against Taiwan, the
measure was edging toward victory.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders expressed confidence that the
legislation to grant China permanent normal trading privileges was
on track for passage, and they scheduled a vote for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for approval increased Friday as supporters outlined
details of a bipartisan agreement to monitor Beijing's human rights
record, and agreed to fold the monitoring provisions into a single
package with the upgraded trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the agreement should attract at least six
Republicans and 10 to 15 Democrats who otherwise would have voted
against the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal is a hard-fought compromise that should help us
in the House pass permanent trade relations with China,'' Speaker
J. Dennis Hastert said in giving the House Republican leadership's
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said publicly that they were still a
few votes shy of the 218 needed for passage, but privately they
expressed confidence that the goal was well within reach. President
Clinton and members of his Cabinet, including Commerce Secretary
William M. Daley, will continue to make calls to wavering lawmakers
this weekend, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Friday night that it was canceling a
short, prime-time television address on China that Clinton was to
give on Sunday night. White House officials said Democrats who
supported the measure or were undecided had told them a speech now
would come too late to influence any lawmakers and would only put
additional strains on House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the 211 House Democrats are expected to oppose the
bill, leaving its passage in the hands of Republicans, who are
expected to deliver about 150 votes in favor.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton had delivered his speech on Sunday, it would have put
overwhelming pressure on the House Democratic leader, Richard A.
Gephardt, to deliver a rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gephardt announced his opposition a month ago, he has
studiously played a behind-the-scenes role, leaving the public
lobbying job to the No. 2 House Democrat, David E. Bonior of
Michigan. ``It's a division of labor that's worked,'' said Peggy
Taylor, the AFL-CIO's chief Washington lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt fears that taking a more aggressive stance would worsen
tensions among Democrats, and threaten his goal of reclaiming the
House this fall and becoming speaker.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, Gephardt has quietly stepped up his
activity, in part because more members are seeking him out before
the vote next week. Gephardt said Friday on National Public Radio,
``I'm going to talk to everybody I can.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Gephardt was breaking his pledge not to lobby
actively against the measure, Rep. Robert T. Matsui of California,
a Democratic vote-counter in favor of the bill, said, ``No, not
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But a prime-time speech by Clinton would have pushed Gephardt
dangerously close to crossing that line, Democratic aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say passage would allow American companies to benefit
fully from a market-opening agreement connected with China's bid to
enter the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions, some religious leaders, environmental groups and
veterans' organizations oppose the bill because of China's record
on human rights and labor standards, and fears of job losses in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of the undecided diminished on Friday. Supporters
picked up Diana L. DeGette of Colorado, John J. LaFalce of New
York, Thomas C. Sawyer of Ohio and Martin T. Meehan of
Massachusetts, all Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents won over Robert E. Andrews of New Jersey, Rod R.
Blagojevich of Illinois, Karen McCarthy of Missouri, Peter Deutsch
of Florida and Edward J. Markey of Massachusetts, all Democrats;
and Harold Rogers of Kentucky and Steven C. LaTourette of Ohio,
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, most opponents were putting on a brave face on Friday.
``I don't think either side has a majority, but at this point we're
in the lead,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But other foes were more fatalistic, especially as business
groups promised to ratchet up their advertising campaigns. Rep.
Gene Taylor, a conservative Democrat from Mississippi who opposes
the measure, said, ``Have you ever seen big money lose?''
</P>
</TEXT>
