<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILWAY-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS PUSH FOR DEATH PENALTY IN RAILWAY KILLER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RAD SALLEE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Prosecutors used gruesome pictures and emotional
testimony Friday to drive home the message to jurors that, mentally
ill or not, multiple killer Angel Maturino Resendiz is too
dangerous to live and deserves to die.
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors cast stony glances at the defendant, who sat
attentively and expressionless through it all, turning occasionally
to speak to his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the seven-woman, five-man jury convicted Maturino
Resendiz, 41, of capital murder in the Dec. 17, 1998, bludgeoning
of Dr. Claudia Benton in her West University Place home near
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz had confessed to killing Benton and eight
others, but pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity. Defense
psychiatrists described him as a paranoid schizophrenic who
believes that he is half-angel, half-man who kills at God's
direction.
</P>
<P>
   After being convicted, Maturino Resendiz said in court that he
would rather die than be imprisoned for life, and asked his lawyers
not to cross-examine witnesses or argue on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Allen Tanner objected to the most gruesome
photos but otherwise mounted no defense.
</P>
<P>
   To sentence Maturino Resendiz to death, the jury must find him a
continuing threat to society, with no mitigating circumstances to
justify a life sentence, the only alternative under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Before convicting him, jurors were told about his eight other
victims but saw only detailed evidence from the Benton case.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Dominguez, 29, of Phoenix described how he searched the
southeast Houston duplex of his sister, Noemi, 26, when she failed
to join him in Dallas for an animated cartoon convention in June
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms were in disarray, with big piles of clothes and
bedding on the floor, and her car was gone. Finding no sign of his
sister, he realized he should look under the pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lifted the quilt that my mother had made for her, and a few
articles of clothing. I saw my sister,'' he said. ``I jumped back
and I think I shrieked.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez, a Rice University graduate and schoolteacher, was
face down and partly nude, her head mangled. The pattern was
repeated in photos of some of Maturino Resendiz's other victims.
All lived near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   After Maturino Resendiz's arrest, items of Noemi Dominguez's
jewelry, including a cross, a ``Return of the Jedi'' pin and a
spider ring, were found in Maturino Resendiz's home in Rodeo,
Mexico. Alex Dominguez identified the items in court.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Vacek of Schulenburg, Texas, wept as she testified about
finding the body of her mother, Josephine Konvicka, 73, under the
covers in her bed.
</P>
<P>
   A photo showed a garden tool embedded in her forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Experts later testified that they found Dominguez's blood on the
blade, indicating that Maturino Resendiz had carried the
pickax-like ``grubbing hoe'' with him from Houston to Schulenburg.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Neely of Weimar, Texas, a few miles from Schulenberg, told
how he waited on Sunday, May 7, 1999, for Pastor Norman ``Skip''
Sirnic and his wife, Karen, to show up for church.
</P>
<P>
   On duty as a ``greeter'' at the church door, Neely said, he knew
that Sirnic always preached an 8:30 a.m. sermon at a nearby church,
then drove hurriedly to the 9:30 service at Weimar United Church of
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   When he did not appear, the service went on while Neely searched
the parsonage next door.
</P>
<P>
   A police videotape shows the Sirnics' nude bodies lying side by
side in bed, their faces crushed with a sledgehammer Maturino
Resendiz found in a utility room.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's truck turned up in San Antonio, and some of their
jewelry was found at Maturino Resendiz's home.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's last testimony, Randy Kennedy, police chief of
Hughes Springs, Texas, near Texarkana, described finding the body
of his neighbor, Leafie Mason, 87.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he went to check when Mason did not show up at the
local nursing home to visit her retarded sister, Birdie, whom she
had lived with and cared for as long as she could.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's body was under a pile of blankets on the floor. An
antique flatiron, its handle broken off, is thought to be the
murder weapon, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz was tied to the crime by a palm print Kennedy
noticed on a windowpane. Seeing a storm coming that could wash away
the print, he called a lumber company and had them cut out the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, prosecutors Ted Wilson and Devon Anderson expect to
call their last witnesses, including the girlfriend of Christopher
Maier, a college student beaten to death in Lexington, Ky., in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The girlfriend was beaten and raped, and will be the only
eyewitness against Maturino Resendiz.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Bill Harmon advised jurors to bring their
overnight bags Monday, because they may be sequestered to
deliberate punishment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
