<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-19 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE NOT KEY INGREDIENT IN RECIPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ His Los Angeles Lakers teammates trotted
out a couple of new variations on the Glen Rice theme Friday, as
practice broke up on the eve of the playoff showdown with the
Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   This was from Shaquille O'Neal: ``It's going to be our job to
get Glen more involved.'' And this was from Ron Harper: ``Glen?
It's not about him, it's about us. We've got to get him more
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Haven't we heard this before?
</P>
<P>
   On the court, in the 14 months since the 6-foot-8 jump shooter
joined the Lakers in a trade, his teammates haven't seemed to know
what to do with the vague concept of getting Rice ``involved.'' In
the locker room, though, they've always known what to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   It's always something along the lines of: ``Involving Glen is a
priority if we want to win.'' Or: ``We're working on promoting the
involvement of Glen.'' Or: ``Glen? Involved? A capital idea!''
</P>
<P>
   More than a year now and they haven't figured out how to do it.
Now you doubt they ever will.
</P>
<P>
   If you're nostalgic, watch Rice closely in the games ahead. He
is eligible for free agency this summer. These could be his last
13.9 points as a Laker.
</P>
<P>
   His shot is off target, his chances to shoot have declined, and
as a necessary result his playoff scoring is way down _ after his
regular-season scoring hit a 10-year low at 15.9 a game.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, he doesn't complain, and to their credit, neither
do the Lakers. This is no time for a member of a potential champion
to talk about his individual disappointments, and no time for the
front office to talk about a disappointing individual.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice can't be happy about his time in Los Angeles, where the
ex-All-Star and one-time 26-points-a-game scorer is a distant third
option behind O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can the Lakers believe they got what they expected when they
sent Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to the Charlotte Hornets to get
J.R. Reid and a certain outside-shooting threat in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the Lakers' playoff media guide is adorned with a
posed photo of (left to right) O'Neal, Bryant and Rice. Move Rice a
little more to the right (off the page) and you get the real
picture.
</P>
<P>
   As reticent as Rice has been on the subject of his contentment
and future, he did reveal a little Friday afternoon when he was
asked if his 1999-2000 season has been different than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   Rice emitted a quick laugh, ran his right hand over the stubble
on his scalp, and said: ``It has been different. But at the same
time, if you look at where we are as a team, I'm satisfied with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He had said earlier that his reduced role didn't diminish his
enjoyment of the longest playoff run of a 10-year NBA career with
Miami, Charlotte and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think team first,'' said Rice, who will be playing in his
first conference championship series. ``It's not an individual
thing. If we win a championship, good things will come to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If they win the championship, Rice will own an NBA ring to go
with the NCAA-title jewelry he earned with Michigan. Then he might
correctly ask himself if it's worth sticking around.
</P>
<P>
   He's known as a proud fellow, and he must have been insulted
last summer when the Lakers merely picked up the $7 million option
on his contract and didn't address his wish for $14 million a year.
Even though the Lakers will have the salary-cap freedom to raise
his salary, Rice might get closer to his eight-figure request with
another team.
</P>
<P>
   He's a shooter by nature _ the Big Ten's all-time leading scorer
at the time he left Michigan, the NBA's third-most-prolific 3-point
shooter. If he wants to get back to that, he'll have to get out of
Shaq's and Kobe's shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Name another ``vital cog'' whose team went 16-3 when he scored
10 or fewer points this season.
</P>
<P>
   None of this appears to be Rice's fault or his teammates'. He
wants to score more. They'd love him to score more. But sometimes
these things just don't work out.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something changes fast _ in this series, or in the next,
if there is a next _ the next time we see him, Rice will be
involved with another team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
