<HEADER>
A0660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ARAB-ORGAN-DONORS-NYT     05-19 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAB-ORGAN-DONORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE TO AN ISLAMIC MYTH ON ORGAN TRANSPLANTS AS AILMENTS RISE
</HEADLINE>
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Even now, six months after her decision, Najah
Bazzy's family is still upset with her. Her 14-year-old daughter
pleads with her to reconsider. Older relatives fear that she has
offended God.
</P>
<P>
   But Bazzy is resolute. When she dies, her heart, liver, kidney
and lungs will be donated. While thousands of other people have
made the decision to sign organ donor cards or become live donors,
Bazzy's declaration is controversial. As an Arab-American Muslim,
she is part of a community that ardently believes it is forbidden
for Muslims to donate organs, even to a relative. To see Heaven,
they say, their bodies must return to God in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   These days, that notion is being challenged as increasing
numbers of Arab-Americans here in what is perhaps their largest and
most influential community in the United States, as well as their
relatives back home, are found to have liver and kidney disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a saying in Islam: He who saves a life saves
humanity,'' said Bazzy, a 40-year-old Lebanese transcultural nurse
who is spearheading an initiative to include in Islamic wills a
section for organ donations. ``Why are we so eager to take our
organs with us and give up the opportunity to save a life? How do I
know I'm not depriving the world of a genius?''
</P>
<P>
   That is why religious leaders are rallying with doctors and
community outreach workers to dispel a decades-old myth that the
Koran forbids organ donation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the International Association for Organ
Donation, a year-old nonprofit organization founded by a former
marketing executive whose teen-age son was battling kidney disease,
has started an education campaign. By introducing reluctant donors
to Arab-American patients waiting for transplants and by holding
dinners, distributing posters, bumper stickers and T-shirts, the
group hopes to sign up thousands of the more than 275,000 Arabs
here and in parts of Detroit. Doctors say organ transplants between
relatives or people of the same ethnicity have a higher rate of
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Islamic taboo banning the donation of organs,''
said Imam Hassan Qzawani, who heads the Islamic Center of America,
which has more than 8,000 members and is one Detroit's largest
mosques. ``People have reservations because it was not practiced in
the old countries and because of Islam's strict guidelines about
disfiguring the body. But as long as you're not giving your eyes or
an organ that is needed for one's own survival, we have the right
to help save someone's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Hammoud, 29, tried desperately last year to persuade her
father to accept a kidney from his son. But he opted for a cadaver
donation, which later failed. ``He would have waited another eight
years rather than take it from my brother,'' Hammoud said.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, about 20 people are waiting for either a kidney or
liver transplant, said the Gift of Life Transplant Society of
Michigan, which only last year started studying Arabs as a separate
group. In the last six years, only one Arab-American donated an
organ in Michigan, though at least a dozen have received
transplants, doctors and organ donation researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 69,399 patients waiting for organ transplants in the
United States, it is unclear how many are Arabs. The United Network
for Organ Sharing, in Richmond, Va., which oversees transplants in
the United States, traditionally counts Arabs as Caucasian, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joanna El Hajj, a health care coordinator at the Arab
Community Center for Economics and Social Service, said she only
needed to pick up her telephone to know that the numbers were
growing. The calls come with frightening frequency, El Hajj says.
Almost every day she is talking to someone, or the relative of
someone, waiting for a kidney, liver or bone marrow transplant. The
center routinely sponsors fund-raisers to help patients across the
country pay medical bills and bring sick relatives to the United
States for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, I would get maybe one call, two calls,'' said
El Hajj, who recently decided to become a donor. ``Now, every day
there is a new case. I get calls from Tulsa, from Boston, Maryland,
Jordan, Iraq. We can't continue to ignore what is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   El Hajj, who received a heart tissue transplant 26 years ago in
London, has a theory about the increase in need. ``We're seeing the
aftereffects of war, I believe. A lot of the people who are coming,
they lived through the chemical pollution of the civil wars in Iraq
and Lebanon. It's like in Vietnam when they sprayed the gases, you
only see the effects over a period.''
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that the Arab population is merely in the midst
of growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have an immigrant community this large, eventually
they will develop the same disease as the larger population,'' said
Marwan Aboujould, director of transplant surgery at the Henry Ford
Hospital in Detroit. ``The problem is that medical technology and
the population have surpassed the community's education. That can
be as hard to overcome as issues of culture and faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
