<SLUG> BC-NRA-TIMESSQUARE-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA PLANS TIMES SQUARE RESTAURANT AND ARCADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With GUNS-NRA) 
By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The National Rifle Association plans to open a theme
restaurant and a game arcade in Times Square, a move that has
outraged gun-control advocates and astonished redevelopment
officials.
</P>
<P>
   At its national convention Friday in Charlotte, N.C., the NRA
said it was negotiating to open a restaurant called NRASports
Grille, featuring ``a wild game menu and fresh mineral waters from
around the world.'' The group said it also planned an adjacent
electronic-game arcade and gift store called NRASports Blast, which
it described as ``an exciting total shooting sports and sporting
goods experience.''
</P>
<P>
   William Powers, the NRA's director of public affairs, was not
specific about the plans, but said in a telephone interview that
the Times Square project would ``open sooner rather than later.''
He said the project would be ``big, very big.'' He compared it to
similar ventures by the World Wrestling Federation, which has a
Times Square restaurant and gift store, and Planet Hollywood, the
pop-culture theme restaurant on West 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said the gift store would not sell guns.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's plans quickly drew criticism. ``This is ludicrous,''
said Kimberly Mariani, a spokeswoman for Handgun Control, a
lobbying group in Washington. ``The very New Yorkers who have
worked to reduce their crime rate don't want the NRA coming into
Times Square and glorifying the gun culture. Now, not only their
policies will leave a bad taste in your mouth, but their food as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Sexton, president of the Times Square Business
Improvement District, which provides business consulting, security
and other services to businesses in Times Square, said he was
surprised by the NRA's plans, which were first reported Friday by
the Daily News, and expressed mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're entitled to be in Times Square and it's my job to
treat them as a neighbor,'' Sexton said. ``But symbolically and
philosophically, it's very hard to look on a business whose focus
is shooting and feel that this is a happy development.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Real estate brokers familiar with Times Square who said they
were not involved in the negotiations said the NRA has been looking
for space for more than a year and that its interest has focused on
1530 Broadway, near 45th Street, the site of the Criterion movie
theater and Sbarro, an Italian-food cafeteria. That block of
Broadway also has some of Times Square's most prominent billboards,
including Liz Claiborne and Jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Moss, Jr., an owner of B.S. Moss Enterprises, the
landlord of 1530 Broadway, denied that he was negotiating with the
NRA. ``I've never spoken to them and I would not be interested in
speaking to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A broker who is said to be familiar with the negotiations
described the NRA as seeking 45,000 to 55,000 square feet on at
least two floors, one of them at street level.
</P>
<P>
   Rents for that area run $275 to $300 per square foot on street
level and $50 a foot for basement or second-floor space. At those
rates, that broker said, the NRA might pay annual rent of more than
$7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, the NRA spokesman, would not confirm that the group was
looking at 1530 Broadway, but said that the figure of $7 million
was not daunting and that the NRA was determined to develop the
project, with partners if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent like that didn't stop the WWF or Planet Hollywood and it
won't stop us,'' Powers said. The NRA has 3.6 million members and
an annual operating budget of $150 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
