<SLUG> BC-TV-CABLE-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COURT UPHOLDS LIMITS ON SIZE OF CABLE OPERATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court Friday upheld the
constitutionality of a law that sets limits on the size of a cable
company. The ruling strengthens the hand of the government as it
completes its review of the largest merger in the cable television
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals here reversed a lower
court opinion that had found the law violated the First Amendment.
The lower court decision had cast a cloud over the pending review
by regulators of AT&AMP;T's proposed merger of MediaOne, which, when
completed, will catapult the company to the top of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The rules by the Federal Communications Commission limit cable
ownership to 30 percent of the market, and by some estimates, the
combined company would control about 40 percent or more of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision written by Judge Douglas Ginsburg, the court said
that in writing the law, Congress ``drew reasonable inferences,
based upon substantial evidence, that increases in the
concentration of cable operators threatened diversity and
competition in the cable industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the FCC said they would be completing the
examination of the AT&AMP;T deal shortly. The agency immediately lifted
a stay it had imposed on the enforcement of its cable concentration
rules. The commission is expected to approve the deal soon,
although AT&AMP;T has been lobbying hard to get as much time as
possible to complete any divestitures. The Justice Department is
also examining the deal to see if it violates any provisions of
federal antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the appeals court also upheld the
constitutionality of a law that gives regulators the authority to
limit the number of channels that a cable system has a financial
interest in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
