<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WIZARDS-JARVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARVIS HEADS SOUTH AS WIZARD TALKS STALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis will board a plane Saturday for Florida and the Big
East Conference coaching meetings. For now, he remains the
basketball coach of St. John's and not the new head coach of the
Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said his agent, Robert Ades, was gathering information
about whether Michael Jordan wanted to offer Jarvis a job with the
Wizards, giving him an opportunity to return to the city where he
coached George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ades nor Jarvis had heard from Jordan as of early Friday
night as the talks seemed to be losing momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis reiterated that he was not sure if he was the top choice
of the Wizards, adding that if he did receive an offer it would not
be a foregone conclusion that he would accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely nothing to report,'' Jarvis said. ``I
haven't talked to Michael Jordan today. I have people who work for
me gathering information.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis would not say whether compensation was impeding the
progress of the negotiations, but one Eastern Conference team
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he heard the
two sides were far apart over salary and contract structure.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers were far below the $3 million a year that Michigan
State coach Tom Izzo recently turned down from the Atlanta Hawks,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said he met with his assistant coaches Friday morning. He
said the Wizards' interest in him had not disrupted his program's
preparations for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said he had kept Ed Manetta Jr., St. John's athletic
director, informed of his contact with the Wizards and indicated
that nothing would be resolved over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, however, had said he wanted a coach in place before
Sunday's NBA lottery drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fortunate to work at a place that is understanding enough
to allow me to look, listen and learn,'' Jarvis said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
