<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAATEN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD AND GEORGIA ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Those peep holes on the ends of tennis courts
work two ways. In addition to the fans getting a closer look, the
players can look beyond their court and sense the match's overall
mood.
</P>
<P>
   It was somber for the USC and UCLA women's teams, who suffered
one-sided defeats in the NCAA quarterfinals at Pepperdine. The
Trojans lost 5-1 to third-ranked Georgia, and No. 1 Stanford shut
out UCLA 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches don't like me to say that,'' UCLA's Elizabeth Schmidt
said, ``but I can feel there wasn't as much cheering. You can tell
when people are up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Down was the operative word Friday. Although the 12th-ranked
Trojans(18-9) took almost an hour longer to lose than No. 9 UCLA
(17-9), not much went right for either team.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA, the Bruins didn't win a set in losing in about 90
minutes. Schmidt came the closest, losing 7-5 and trailing 3-2 to
Jennifer Heiser at No. 5 singles when the Cardinal (29-0) had won
the necessary five matches.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else won more than three games in any set. After the
first sets were complete, UCLA had won just 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't let us into it,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   For USC, not much more went right.
</P>
<P>
   __ No. 1 singles Kara Warkentin, a slow starter of late, started
about as slowly as possible, losing 6-0 to fifth-ranked Aarthi
Venkatesan. Then Warkentin lost 6-3 and the match was over in less
than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   __ No. 4 and No. 5 singles Jacqui Boyd and Anita Loyola lost in
an hour. Boyd lost the first set 6-4 when Lori Grey broke her at
love, then fell 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her serve is not one of her strengths, shall we say,'' USC
coach Richard Gallien said.
</P>
<P>
   Loyola said she didn't let herself get patient and lost 6-2, 6-2
to Kelly Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   __ Veronika Safarova won the first set 6-4 over Esther Knox, but
then her right shoulder started acting up, and Knox won the next
two sets 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It threw my game off completely,'' Safarova said. ``I can't
play as relaxed as I like.''
</P>
<P>
   __ And Tiffany Brymer, at No. 6 singles, played a grueling two
hour, 28-minute match before losing in three to Anne Nguyen. Brymer
won the first set 7-5 and had all of the momentum before losing 6-2
in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   USC's lone bright spot: Freshman Jewel Peterson, ranked 17th
nationally, earned USC's lone point with a 7-5, 6-4 win over
Marissa Catlin at No. 3 singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look for things that go wrong, you're going to find
them,''Gallien said. ``The trick is to drive yourself through. If
you don't, it demoralizes you. The tough teams keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Stanford, which faces fourth-ranked Wake Forest in
a semifinal today at 2 p.m. Florida and Georgia meet at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal is so deep that when Teryn Ashley suffered back
spasms and couldn't play at No. 3 singles, coach Frank Brennan
moved everyone up one and put Keiko Tokuda at No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   In case any player had doubts, top singles player Marissa Irvin
suggested to look at this not as moving up a step but as facing a
new opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Tokuda beat Catherine Hawley 6-1, 6-3. Normal fourth singles
Lauren Kalavaria beat Amanda Basica 6-1, 6-3 and Gabriela Lastra
knocked off Abigail Spears 6-1, 6-2 in fourth doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, shuffling the deck is nothing new for Stanford.
Irvin, from Harvard-Westlake High, played in just her 22nd match
Friday because she has been preparing to turn pro after the NCAAs.
Ashley has been hurt before, as has freshman Laura Granville at No.
2 singles.
</P>
<P>
   They're healthy now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every NCAAs, they come out at their best,'' said Annica
Cooper, who lost 6-0, 6-3 to Granville, ``and it's tough to go
against that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
