<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-SIXER-PACERS-NYT &LR;      05-19 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SIXER-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF MILLER FORCES OUT THE 76ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The return of Reggie Miller marked the end of the
Philadelphia 76ers' season.
</P>
<P>
   Miller returned from a one-game suspension and scored 25 points
to lead the Indiana Pacers to the Eastern Conference finals with a
106-90 victory over the Philadelphia Sixers on Friday night in Game
6. By winning the four-of-seven-game conference semifinal series,
4-2, Indiana will make its third consecutive trip to the conference
finals against the winner of the New York Knicks-Miami Heat series.
</P>
<P>
   Showing their experience and poise in front of a noisy, partisan
Philadelphia crowd at the First Union Center, the Pacers never
trailed after the first few minutes and held off every rally by the
76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who sat out Game 5 after throwing a punch at Matt Geiger
in Game 4, got a measure of revenge by making jumper after jumper,
shooting 10 for 18 from the field, pushing the Pacers into the next
round and sending the Sixers on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   After leading by three points at halftime, Indiana took control
by dominating the third quarter, 29-16. That gave the Pacers an
85-69 lead heading into the final period, and Philadelphia never
cut Indiana's lead to single digits thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers had hoped to become the first team in NBA history to
rally from a 3-0 deficit to win a series, but as Friday night's
game progressed, they finally succumbed to an opponent that had
more depth and more experience.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose, who had been quiet in the previous two games, added
21 points for the Pacers, giving Indiana a one-two punch that the
Sixers never contained.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Pacers did a superb defensive job on Allen
Iverson, Philadelphia's All-Star guard, who was held to 18 points
on 7-for-20 shooting. When Iverson does not have a huge game,
particularly against a team as strong as the Pacers, the Sixers are
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana ran two or three defenders at Iverson, forcing him to
give up the ball or to take difficult shots. With Iverson in check
and none of his teammates able to step up, the Sixers simply did
not have enough offense to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Taking control in the third quarter, the Pacers took an 85-69
lead into the final 12 minutes. Miller was relentless, making key
shots that kept the Sixers reeling. With Rose on one side of the
floor and Miller on the other, Indiana spread Philadelphia's
defense and constantly found the open man.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pacers making baskets and controlling the tempo, the
Sixers never got a chance to get their running game going, and the
Pacers methodically took control of the game. By the fourth
quarter, it was clear Philadelphia was in deep trouble, and Indiana
never lost control in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers looked tired and they knew the end was near. By the
end of the game, Miller was smiling on the Indiana bench, looking
forward to the next series.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana led at halftime, 56-53, but the Sixers rallied from a
14-point deficit in the second quarter. Running an offensive clinic
early, the Pacers madenine of their first 10 shots and built an
early lead. Indiana forced Philadelphia to scramble defensively,
and the Pacers moved the ball crisply and found open men all over
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Miller looked sharp, making his first four shots and had 13
point in the first quarter. Each time Miller made a shot, he turned
and stared at the fans in the front row as he ran down the court.
</P>
<P>
   It was Miller at his best, making key shots, and relishing his
role as a villain. And as the Pacers gradually increased their lead
to 39-25, it appeared the Sixers were in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But at that point, Philadelphia went on a 16-3 run to change the
game's momentum. It was no coincidence that most of Philadelphia's
run occurred with Miller resting on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Without Miller to spread the defense, the Sixers began making
stops, and that ignited their offense.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc made a huge impact, coming off the bench to score 10
first-half points for the Sixers. And instead of watching Iverson
carry the offense, the Sixers got a strong first half from George
Lynch and Aaron McKie, who combined for 19 points in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson had 11 first-half points on 4-for-11 shooting, but he
took good shots and got his teammates involved offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Holding Miller scoreless in the second quarter, the Sixers tied
the game, 45-45, as the crowd at the First Union Center went wild.
But the Pacers never lost their poise, and they nursed a
three-point lead into the locker room. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
