<HEADLINE>
AMGEN ANEMIA DRUG GETS GOOD TEST RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ Amgen's upcoming anemia drug lasts as
long in cancer patients as it does in patients with renal failure,
according to the results of a study to be presented today.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by Dr. John Glaspy of the UCLA School of
Medicine, is being presented to the American Society of Clinical
Oncology annual meeting in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, NESP, already has been submitted for approval by the
Food and Drug Administration for use in chronic renal failure
patients. It is considered a successor to Epogen, Amgen's $1.76
billion-selling anemia drug.
</P>
<P>
   NESP, as a successor to Amgen's largest-selling drug, has the
potential to be a huge seller in its own right, in part because the
company is unrestricted in the markets it can seek.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen only holds the rights to market Epogen to kidney patients
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen is testing NESP's effectiveness in cancer patients, who
become anemic during chemotherapy when the treatments wipe out the
bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   NESP, or novel Erythropoiesis stimulating protein, is not a
replacement for Epogen, but a different formula that allows
patients to go longer between doses, said Amgen spokesman David
Kaye.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said the research compared the length of time it takes for
the drug to work its way through the systems of patients undergoing
chemotherapy and those with chronic renal failure.
</P>
<P>
   More research is needed into the safety and efficacy of the drug
before the third phase of studies can begin.
</P>
<P>
   Anemia drugs are proving to be valuable where it was once
believed they weren't necessary, Glaspy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugs that raise red (blood cell) counts are extremely
important drugs, and we're just finding out in the last few years
their effect on disability and low quality of life,'' Glaspy said.
``Fatigue we thought was due to the cancer, we've found out was due
to the anemia.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer patients are a new market for Amgen, which only sells
Epogen to people with kidney failure because of a marketing
agreement it has with Johnson and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Johnson and Johnson has the U.S. rights to
market the drug - which it sells as Procrit - to all U.S. markets
other than patients with renal failure.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen faces a court challenge to its patents for Epogen. A
federal trial is ongoing in Boston to determine whether Cambridge,
Mass.-based Transkaryotic Therapies Inc. infringed on Amgen's
patents for its top-selling drug.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen also is scheduled to present the results of phase three
studies of a prostate cancer drug, Abarelix, which it developed
along with Praecis Pharmaceuticals. Those study results will be
presented Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
