<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FTC Seeks Authority to Protect Privacy Online
</P>
<P>
   Concluding that companies on the Internet have not properly
protected the privacy of consumers, the Federal Trade Commission
has decided to ask Congress for authority to impose tough consumer
privacy safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC approved a staff recommendation in an unannounced vote
to seek legislation giving it such authority. The action comes as
the agency has stepped up investigations of several major Internet
companies over their use of consumer data. It marks a sharp
departure from the agency's previous policy of relying almost
entirely on the industry to police itself. Democratic lawmakers in
both the House and Senate, however, said this week that the
prospects for final passage of any privacy measure were not strong.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Reports $6.3 Billion Loss
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor said its loss widened to 684.4 billion yen on a
consolidated basis, or $6.3 billion at current exchange rates, in
the fiscal year ended March 31, as it erased outstanding pension
liabilities, adopted new accounting practices and moved to cut
employees.
</P>
<P>
   China Trade Bill Edges Near Victory
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of a decisive China trade bill refused to admit defeat
and vowed to step up their lobbying over the weekend. But growing
signs indicated that barring an unforeseen shift in votes or
provocation by Beijing against Taiwan, the measure was edging
toward victory. House Republican leaders scheduled a vote for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals Court Upholds Cable Law
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court upheld the constitutionality of a law
that sets limits on the size of a cable company. The ruling
strengthens the hand of the government as it reviews AT&AMP;T's pending
merger with MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Revises Earnings Down 1 Cent
</P>
<P>
   Intel said that it had revised its first-quarter per-share
earnings down by a penny and had lowered sales by $28 million,
disclosing the initial financial hit it would take for circuit
boards found earlier this month to have a defective component.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Deficit Widens
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit widened to a record in March as surging
demand for oil, automobiles and other imports overpowered a second
consecutive monthly increase in exports, Commerce Department
figures showed. The deficit in goods and services grew to $30.2
billion in March from $28.7 billion in February. Economists had
expected a $29.5 billion deficit. Although the U.S. shortfall with
China narrowed, record imports from Japan, Canada and Western
Europe caused the trade gaps with those regions to widen.
</P>
<P>
   Korean Traders Plan Monday Strike
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-thousand members of South Korea's securities industry
union are planning to strike during their lunch hour Monday, when
the stock exchange plans to continue trading during what has
historically been a midday break. The change, approved by the South
Korean government, makes this country the first in Asia to keep its
stock exchange open during the lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank Doubles Profit Forecast
</P>
<P>
   Softbank, Japan's largest Internet investor, more than doubled
its forecast for its annual earnings, partly because of a rise in
the value of its stake in a computer network design company and an
improved profit outlook for its finance unit. The company said it
expected net income of 8.5 billion yen ($78.2 million) for the year
that ended on March 31, up from its previous forecast of 3.5
billion yen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
