<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-19 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0783 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-1STLD-WRI     05-19 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-815(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI WITHDRAWS FROM SENATE RACE, CITING HEALTH REASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Rewrites, expands and updates earlier story and changes
byline.) 
(ART ADV: Photos, NYT5, 13 and 15, are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani withdrew from the most
celebrated Senate race in the nation on Friday, saying that his
health and his still-undecided treatment for prostate cancer were
more important to him than his campaign against Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional, riveting news conference, which he began in an
uncharacteristically nervous voice, Giuliani said that he wanted to
devote his remaining 18 months in office to becoming a better mayor
_ one who reaches out to minorities _ as well as becoming a better
person. He took his listeners along on a psychological journey,
holding out the possibility that his illness had changed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think the core of me was in politics, probably,''
Giuliani said during in his half-hour of remarks in the City Hall
Public Hearing Room, which was crowded with more than 35 television
cameras from around the world as well as hundreds of supporters,
teary campaign aides, members of his administration, reporters and
friends. ``It isn't. When you feel your mortality and your humanity
you realize that, that the core of you is first of all being able
to take care of your health.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, he said that confronting his ``limits'' had
allowed him to see himself differently: ``You realize you're not a
superman and you're just a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``This is not the right time for me to run for office.
If it were six months ago or it were a year from now or the timing
were a little different, maybe it would be different. But it isn't
different, and that's the way life is.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Republican Party reacted with sympathy, but
immediately pledged support for Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, the
choice to replace the mayor. Party leaders said they were worried
about the race but nonetheless relieved that Giuliani had made a
decision after weeks of reviewing his options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand and respect his decision to put his health
first,'' said Gov. George Pataki. Pataki had much preferred Lazio
as the candidate to oppose Clinton. He supported Giuliani a few
months ago only because of a growing consensus among state
Republican Party leaders that Giuliani would be Clinton's strongest
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki described Lazio as a worthy candidate with a politically
appealing record in Congress on issues like tax cuts and smaller
government.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also tried to cut off speculation that he might enter the
race himself, saying that he was happy to remain in his current job
and support whoever became the Republican Party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   When Lazio began mulling over a bid for the U.S. Senate last
year, his biggest drawback was perceived as his lack of name
recognition in a race that was fast becoming defined by celebrity
and star quality.
</P>
<P>
   Now his supporters are hoping to turn that seeming weakness into
his biggest strength. Lazio may be a virtual unknown, their line of
reasoning goes, but at least he does not arouse the strong
antipathy inspired in certain quarters by both the man he hopes to
succeed, Giuliani, and the Democrat he hopes to challenge, Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a moderate Republican, he's telegenic,'' said Howard
DeMartini, who was the chairman of the Suffolk County Republican
Party when Lazio was first elected to Congress here in 1992. ``He
will be able to turn the focus of the campaign back onto the first
lady. Over the last few months, Hillary has been able to shift the
focus away from herself and onto the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said that Giuliani ``had the best interests of New Yorkers
in mind,'' and added that he was ready to run. ``I'm looking
forward to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's pending entry and Giuliani's withdrawal instantly
changed what had been an overheated, entertaining race of national
interest into a more traditional campaign. City Hall, which in
recent weeks has been a jangling nerve center, settled into a new
calm when the mayor left shortly after 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Giuliani said that he had wavered in
recent days on whether to stay in the race, and had been up much of
Thursday night agonizing over his decision. But he said he finally
reached it Friday morning after speaking to a few close friends.
Earlier on Thursday night, he had appeared at a nationally
televised town hall meeting at the 92nd Street Y in Manhattan,
where he gave no indication of his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went in last night to the town hall meeting and I saw
the people outside saying `Run, Rudy, run, Rudy, run Rudy,' I had,
you know, half the time last night I felt like I wanted to run,''
Giuliani said. ``And half the time I felt like I shouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed up last night going back and forth about what's the
right decision and what isn't the right decision. I believe this is
the right decision. And I think somehow, somewhere, some way, this
is all for the best.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's life has been in a near-constant state of turmoil in
the last three weeks, much of it recorded by a persistent and
expanding press corps.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, the mayor announced that he had prostate cancer. On
May 3, he said that he had a ``very good'' friend, Judith Nathan.
On May 10, he announced that he was seeking a separation from his
wife, Donna Hanover. Hanover, who was surprised by the
announcement, responded the same day by announcing that the
couple's troubles had begun years before because of a relationship
between her husband and a member of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover's press secretary identified the staff member as
Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas, Giuliani's former director of
communications, and said that Hanover believed that the
relationship had been intimate. Both the mayor and
Lategano-Nicholas have denied that the relationship was sexual.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani has been holding increasingly personal news
conferences, in which he has ruminated openly about his life,
Friday's announcement reached a new level of introspection. ``I
also believe that, you know, things happen in life for reasons that
sometimes you only figure out afterwards,'' Giuliani said. ``And
there is something good that comes out of this. A lot of good
things come out of it. I think I understand myself a lot better. I
think I understand what's important to me better.''
</P>
<P>
   But that ``doesn't mean there's going to be a new Rudy,'' the
mayor said, making light of his frequently combative personality.
``I think that's silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also sought to redefine the remaining months of his
mayoralty, promising that he would try to embrace the minority
groups he has alienated in the past. His administration, he said,
would try to make sure that it ``accomplishes the goal of, you
know, reaching every person that we can reach and making sure that
every New Yorker feels that I'm dedicated to them, that I want to
protect them, that I want to help them, and that I want my time as
mayor to count for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said that he wanted to figure out how he had placed a
``barrier'' between his administration and the city's minority
voters. He also said, abruptly, that he wanted to increase the
number of people covered by health insurance, because of what he
has been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that I felt from the beginning of this and
continue to feel is a tremendous sense of compassion for the people
that have to make decisions like this alone,'' he said. ``One of
the things maybe that I can do is figure out how we accelerate
making sure that people are covered _ I mean, there are a lot of
things that I think I can accomplish that I haven't accomplished
before.''
</P>
<P>
   C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president who has been
a frequent critic of the mayor, said that she was ``very hopeful
that he will, indeed, work to overcome the many barriers that face
too many New Yorkers.'' The Rev. Al Sharpton, one of Giuliani's
most vociferous critics, said that he wished Giuliani well, but
that he did not see his withdrawal from the race ``as a political
loss for the people of the state.'' Sharpton also said that he was
now more inclined to run for mayor in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani had repeatedly said in the days after
announcing his illness that he would first make a decision on his
cancer treatment and then decide on the race, he said Friday that
his thinking had been flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't organize this,'' he said. ``I mean, I didn't
understand the impact of this. It was, what I thought at first was,
OK, I'll take a week or two, or three, whatever it takes, to figure
out what the treatment is. I will then decide on the treatment,
I'll then look at the treatment and I'll figure out, does that mean
I can run or I can't run.'' Giuliani added, ``I know it sounds
silly, but I thought of it like a budget decision or a legal
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said the decision, which was between surgery and
radiation, had turned out to be far more difficult than he ever
imagined _ in part, he said on Thursday, because of possible side
effects. Although surgery is the choice of most men of Giuliani's
age _ which is 55 _ and has a high cure rate, it also causes
impotence and incontinence in many patients. Doctors say that
radiation, particularly in the form of ``seeds'' inserted into the
prostate, has less effect on sexual function, but its long-term
cure rates are not known.
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors said that Giuliani would have been physically
able to continue in the race no matter what treatment he chose _ if
he was willing to campaign part time over the summer _ Giuliani
said Friday that he did not want to run a race when he was not
operating at 100 percent of his capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concentration isn't going to be there,'' he said. He added:
``Nobody can tell you in percentages what the side effects are
going to be. You can be fine, you can be terrific, or you can have
problems and then you won't be able to carry out your commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that he would continue to mull over his treatment
options in the coming weeks, and that his decision would not be ``a
political matter'' but a personal one. He said again, as he has
repeatedly, that his decision not to run was based on his health,
not on his unraveling marriage or personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Joannie Danielides, Hanover's press secretary, said that the
mayor telephoned his wife and informed her of his decision shortly
before he made his announcement. Both Hanover and Giuliani are
living at Gracie Mansion while they work out a separation
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked briefly,'' Danielides said. ``She's concerned for
his health and will try to help him with that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close of Giuliani's announcement, a reporter asked the
mayor if he felt closer to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's closer to me,'' the mayor replied.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, who telephoned the mayor shortly after his
announcement, said afterward, ``I certainly hope and pray, as I
know all New Yorkers do, that he will have a full and speedy
recovery.'' Asked if she would miss the mayor as an opponent,
Clinton replied, ``Well, I think we should just wish him well as a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides acknowledge that her campaign had long ago begun
studying the voting records and political backgrounds of each of
the men who were considering replacing Giuliani on the Republican
ticket. In the case of Lazio, Clinton's campaign had already begun
to compile information on the congressman's voting record, with an
eye toward portraying him as a conservative ideologue who is less
than supportive of abortion rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
