<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WAKE UP IN SIXTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Adversity, taken in small, manageable doses,
isn't such a negative thing for the UCLA softball team.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State pushed UCLA for the better part of five innings
Friday, but the Bruins used a five-run sixth inning to earn a 10-4
victory and eliminate the 49ers on the second day of the NCAA
Tournament regional at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the girls that I think a game like this is good for
us,'' said UCLA coach Sue Enquist, whose team advanced to face
(Florida State or Iowa) today at 10 a.m. and is one victory away
from the regional championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, ranked No. 1 in the region, looked powerful and
frail at times against the No. 3 49ers. They held a tenuous 5-4
lead after four innings and needed two-run singles from Julie Adams
and Lyndsey Klein to break the game open in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the way we won in a tough situation,''
said Enquist, whose team had breezed through a five-inning 8-0
victory over Canisius on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA totaled 11 hits, but the difference was on the mound.
Amanda Freed, who pitched a complete game against Canisius, was
called upon to get the Bruins out of a jam in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State had already scored twice to cut UCLA's lead to
5-4, and had the bases loaded with two outs. Freed relieved starter
Courtney Dale and struck out No. 3 hitter Elizabeth Sanches to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ultimate compliment a coach can pay a pitcher, to
put her in the game in a situation like that,'' Enquist said of
Freed. ``I was very pleased with her effort and it's great for her
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Freed (23-7) shut down the 49ers over the next three innings.
She allowed two hits and one walk and struck out five. Dale's
statistics (3 innings, five hits, four runs) weren't overwhelming,
except that she shouldn't even be on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Dale was diagnosed with a torn labrum in her pitching shoulder
in February but delayed surgery so she could keep pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a competitor,'' Enquist said. ``A lot of kids
wouldn't be able to handle what she is doing, with this kind of
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were able to break through against 49ers starter
Kristi Fox (Newbury Park High), a senior who had thrown a complete
game in Thursday's loss to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   After a shaky start, which included a two-run home run by Crissy
Buck in the third inning, Fox (24-10) settled down and retired
seven of the next eight Bruins she faced but was hit hard in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA loaded the bases on singles by Buck and Natasha Watley and
a walk to Lupe Brambila, and Adams and Klein followed with two-run
singles to chase Fox from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of a bad last game to end on,'' Fox said, ``but
if I'm going to lose to somebody, it might as well be UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins win this morning, they will advance directly to
Sunday's championship game. A loss would put the Bruins in today's
3 p.m. game, against the loser of the 12:30 p.m. Canisius vs.
(Florida State or Iowa) game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
