<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. ASSEMBLY INSURGENT FALTERS IN BID TO REPLACE SPEAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The daring attempt to depose the Democratic
speaker of the state Assembly sputtered Friday as the man who
orchestrated it acknowledged that his base of support had seriously
eroded.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the insurrection, Assemblyman Michael Bragman, who
represents the Syracuse area, said that the ``rock solid'' backing
he once had in his bid to replace the speaker, Sheldon Silver of
Manhattan, had dwindled in the face of threats and retaliation by
Silver and his powerful allies.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Bragman vowed to press ahead with his
campaign to oust Silver, who he said had an autocratic and
secretive style that had alienated many of the 98 Democrats who
make up the majority party in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he believed that there was enough dissatisfaction
with the speaker to topple him. ``Am I still in a position to win?
I don't know,'' he said. ``But you know what? There is going to be
change here. Sheldon Silver must go as the speaker of the New York
state Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman also ruled out the possibility that he would seek
support from Assembly Republicans to become speaker, a prospect
that would have thrown the chamber into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman needs the support of at least 50 Democrats to oust
Silver. But even if he cannot muster that many votes, he can still
create huge headaches for the speaker. Silver needs a sizable
majority to control legislation as tightly as he does now, and a
faction of Democrats led by Bragman might make that difficult, if
not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman made his comments two days after he threw the chamber
into turmoil with his announcement that he would try to overthrow
Silver in a showdown vote on Monday. Silver immediately stripped
Bragman of his position as majority leader, cut his $34,500-a-year
stipend and even had him locked out of his office here in the State
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, who has been in the Assembly since 1981, represents a
huge threat to Silver. Bragman is a formidable fund-raiser with
broad support among moderates, conservatives and liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has not taken the threat lightly, using all the powers at
his disposal to beat back the insurrection. He has punished
rebellious lawmakers and secured the help of powerful union
officials and influential party leaders to solidify his support.
</P>
<P>
   He demoted two high-ranking lawmakers who pledged their loyalty
to Bragman and then cut their annual pay by $12,500 each. The raw
display of power immediately placed other lawmakers on notice that
they would meet the same fate if they crossed Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's furious maneuvering over the last 48 hours seems to be
paying off. He has won the backing of key Assembly Democrats from
New York City whose support is crucial if he is to maintain power.
</P>
<P>
   The Silver loyalists include Herman D. Farrell Jr., the
Democratic leader in Manhattan; Clarence Norman Jr., the Democratic
leader in Brooklyn; and Roberto Ramirez, the Democratic leader in
the Bronx. The borough delegations that these men lead represent
more than 40 members of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Silver was trying to negotiate today with Thomas Manton, the
Queens Democratic leader, to secure the support of all 16 Assembly
members from that borough. Manton has had a continuing feud with
Silver, and he recently offered to deliver most of the borough's
Assembly members to Bragman provided Bragman moved quickly to
depose Silver.
</P>
<P>
   The ouster of a speaker is an uncommon occurrence _ the last
attempt in the Assembly was in the 1960s _ and Bragman's comments
Friday were widely interpreted as an admission of defeat. But he
may have achieved something that is almost as extraordinary as
toppling a legislative leader: he may have seriously wounded
Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman seemed to be hinting at such a prospect Friday. ``I
think something extraordinarily positive has already come out of
this,'' he told reporters, noting that he had the support of at
least 40 Democrats who were frustrated with Silver. ``It is my
intention to go in on Monday and let the members speak up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman also sharply criticized the tactics Silver used in the
last few days to crush the uprising, saying they were typical of
the authoritarian rule Silver had imposed over the house since he
took power in 1994. ``The speaker has demonstrated to the public in
the last couple of days what he is all about,'' Bragman said.
``This is a one-man operation. The members are not participating.
They are not being treated with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   A speaker is traditionally chosen by the majority party's
members in an election held behind closed doors at the start of a
newly elected Legislature's two-year term. When a candidate emerges
with a majority, the full Assembly is convened and the members of
the majority party unite behind that candidate in a formal vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
