<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT STONE, 81, ACTOR AND TEACHER  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert W. Stone, an actor and teacher, died on May 11
in New York. He was 81 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, who was professionally known as Robinson Stone, appeared
on Broadway in ``Othello'' with Paul Robeson, ``Cyrano de
Bergerac'' with Jose Ferrer, ``Macbeth'' with Michael Redgrave,
``20th Century'' with Gloria Swanson and ``Mamba's Daughters'' with
Ethel Waters. His best-known film role was that of Joey, the mute,
in Billy Wilder's screen adaptation of ``Stalag 17,'' about a World
War II German camp for Allied prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a talent coordinator for David Garroway's ``Today''
show on NBC and as a casting director for the producer David
Merrick. He was a professor of English at Fordham University, where
his students included the actors Denzel Washington and Dylan
McDermott.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-19-00 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
